<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLDRAFT-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS USUAL, KINGS WILL PICK ATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ hen the Los Angeles Kings traded with the New
York Islanders for star forward Ziggy Palffy six days ago, they set
themselves up for one of their typical draft days.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if your interest in the draft is focused on the
Kings, drag out your rocking chair, put your feet up and drift in
and out of consciousness today when the action begins in Boston.
Today, for the 22nd time in the 33 drafts in which the Kings have
participated, they will be without their first-round selection.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' first pick won't come until the second round, 43rd
overall, a compensatory selection awarded them when they chose not
to sign forward Matt Zultek, a player they chose in the first round
two years ago. Theoretically, the Kings could select Zultek again
today, if he's still available when their turn arrives.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' other nine selections in the nine-round draft will be
74th, 76th, 92nd, 104th, 125th, 133rd, 193rd, 222nd and 250th. If
the Kings are to find a budding Gretzky today, they will have to do
so the old-fashioned way: by unearthing him.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Mighty Ducks, on the other hand, still have their
first-round selection, the 15th pick. The Ducks also will choose
48th, 83rd, 105th, 141st, 173rd, 201st, 230th and 258th.
</P>
<P>
   This draft will have a decidedly European flavor, with roughly
half of the first 20 players chosen expected to be non-North
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay, which selected center Vincent Lecavalier first
overall last year, once again has the opening selection.
</P>
<P>
   Under ordinary circumstances, Long Beach Ice Dogs center Patrik
Stefan probably would be the automatic first choice, but his
concussions have clouded the issue. The Lightning could choose
Stefan, but right wing Pavel Brendl, a native of the Czech
Republic, might be a safer bet. Brendl had 134 points in 68 games
playing junior hockey in Calgary, scoring 73 goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest with you,'' Lightning scout Don Murdoch
recently told the Toronto Sun. ``We have a list of four players,
and they are Brendl, the Sedin twins (Daniel and Henrik, of
Sweden), and Patrik Stefan. We already have Vincent Lecavalier, who
is a hell of a playmaker, so could you imagine Brendl playing with
him? But nothing is etched in stone, and we probably won't make our
decision until (this morning).''
</P>
<P>
   Next will come the expansion Atlanta Thrashers, followed by the
Vancouver Canucks. If Stefan doesn't wind up with the Lightning, it
is very likely he will be chosen by one of these teams.
</P>
<P>
   One rumor has the Thrashers completing a trade with the Canucks
and Chicago Blackhawks that would enable them to select both Sedins
_ left wing Daniel and center Henrik. The Sedins have hinted it's
possible they will hold out if they don't both wind up with the
same team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
