<SLUG> BC-POPPER-JOURNAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAYAKER'S ORDEAL ON COLORADO'S SOUTH FORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Two weeks ago, on June 12, as Paul Bratton
and six friends put their kayaks in Colorado's South Fork River,
one hour north of Denver, Bratton suddenly felt a peculiar
reluctance to continue.
</P>
<P>
   It was just after noon, and it was chilly. Heavy clouds hung low
in a darkening sky. Sleet was falling.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I won't do it today, thought Bratton, 31, a former
emergency medical technician with Metropolitan Ambulance Services
Trust and now an emergency-room nurse at Baptist Medical Center in
Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   But he shrugged off the feeling as irrational.
</P>
<P>
   And so he headed downstream, one of seven kayakers, each paying
careful attention to the water, knowing if he didn't, he could be
up against it.
</P>
<P>
   Bratton loves that part of kayaking, a sport he took up in 1993.
He enjoys the respect demanded by a fast river, the teeth-gritting
rush of adrenaline that comes with facing white water and steep
drops.
</P>
<P>
   And that exhilaration has been matched by a growing love of the
wilderness, a desire to see and feel things he can't experience
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   That morning's run promised to be fairly easy, just a few hidden
rocks, he thought. But it would be beautiful, real wilderness, no
dams, no roads, no paths, no exit for 12.4 miles.
</P>
<P>
   And he soon grew comfortable in his kayak, relaxing, loosening
his muscles, enjoying the power of the racing water pushing him
along.
</P>
<P>
   Be cautious, he thought. Don't relax too much. Watch for fallen
pines. Be alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Know fear,'' he and his buddies say to each other. ``Because
the river can kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   After two hours they ``eddied out,'' clustering together in a
fairly calm pool on the downstream side of a large rock. There they
exchanged information about the river ahead.
</P>
<P>
   When they pushed off again, Bratton was last in line.
Trapped
</P>
<P>
   Fifty feet downstream from the eddy pool, the river made a turn.
Within seconds, Bratton's friends were out of sight. He was alone.
</P>
<P>
   A moment later he felt his kayak scrape a submerged rock.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, man, I boofed that one, he thought, using a kayaker's term.
</P>
<P>
   The rock jarred his boat sideways. He boofed another invisible
rock, lost control, then came to a sudden, jarring halt against ...
something.
</P>
<P>
   He was broached, turned sideways against the water.
</P>
<P>
   Almost reflexively he leaned downstream, tipping his kayak away
from the oncoming current.
</P>
<P>
   If I lean upstream the river will flood my boat, he thought.
</P>
<P>
   He felt the obstacle with his right hand, realized it was a
large, submerged tree branch with two limbs at the end.
</P>
<P>
   He was pressed against both limbs, the upper grabbing at the lip
of his boat's cockpit, the lower grasping at his kayak from below.
</P>
<P>
   He was in the tines of a huge wooden fork, held there by the
force of the water, pinned like a beetle on a cork.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't move. And he knew the river could push him under at
any moment, batter him, drown him.
</P>
<P>
   He felt the leading edge of panic, recognized it, fought it
down.
</P>
<P>
   No, he said to himself, think of how to get out.
</P>
<P>
   It was nearly instinctive, that thought, part of his training,
not only as a kayaker but as an emergency medical technician and a
nurse.
</P>
<P>
   In any emergency he was trained to think sequentially: What do I
do now? What do I do next?
</P>
<P>
   He felt his kayak sinking, and he was trapped in it, couldn't
get free. The upper limb had punctured the spray skirt over his
cockpit. Water was pouring in.
</P>
<P>
   He grabbed that limb with his right arm, hooked it with bicep
and forearm, held himself up, felt the terrible power of the racing
water strain his muscles.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to shimmy out, rocking with his hips, seeking to unlock
the tree's hold.
</P>
<P>
   Now he was moving sideways. Worse. The river smashed against his
side, pinning him harder against the log.
</P>
<P>
   He felt the frigid water race across his legs, numbing him,
slowing him.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his paddle, saw it sweep downstream.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, God, he thought, this is like a routine ambulance run that
turns into a nightmare. You expect to find someone with a minor cut
and instead find bodies scattered everywhere. Your thinking's
scrambled, and if you don't fine-tune, you lose it all.
Sense of helplessness
</P>
<P>
   Within 10 minutes, he was submerged to his armpits in freezing
water, his legs pinned, his right arm aching from just hanging on.
</P>
<P>
   He feared hypothermia, feared losing his ability to think
quickly, rationally.
</P>
<P>
   He searched for an analogy, some way to make sense of what was
happening.
</P>
<P>
   It's like being in a happy relationship, he thought, and all of
a sudden your lover says goodbye, won't talk to you, won't explain.
</P>
<P>
   And that's it. That's the end. Bam, like that. Everything I took
for granted is over, and I can't do a thing about it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to drown here. I'm going to drown slowly.
</P>
<P>
   What will it be like? What will I feel? How long will it take?
Should I just take a huge gulp of water?
</P>
<P>
   No, he thought. Think about what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   What if I just push under, all the way under. Maybe I'll wash
free. No, too risky, not until there's nothing else to do. Save
that for the end.
</P>
<P>
   His hands were numb. He wiggled his feet to get circulation.
</P>
<P>
   He felt the pulse of the water on his head and back, the
tremendous power washing over him, the surging current strangely
lulling, peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   No! Don't lose it. Keep thinking. Keep doing everything I can to
get out.
</P>
<P>
   He tried straightening his kayak again, tried dislodging it,
pushing off, breaking the limb with his hands. Nothing worked.
</P>
<P>
   He screamed for help, heard the echoes of his own voice off the
canyon walls.
</P>
<P>
   Man, that's feeble, he thought, and almost laughed.
</P>
<P>
   He thought about what it is to drown, the physiology of it,
remembered everything he knew from training.
</P>
<P>
   He hoped he'd have a laryngeal spasm, that his airway would
simply shut off. And then ... then a few moments of burning panic
followed by a moment of euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, God, just make it quick, he thought.
</P>
<P>
   He began saying Hail Marys, Our Fathers. He prayed for peace,
for calm.
</P>
<P>
   He struggled to recall other words he wanted to say, remembered
them.
</P>
<P>
   From dust thou art, unto dust thou shalt ...
Rescuers
</P>
<P>
   His paddle saved him.
</P>
<P>
   It washed a quarter-mile downriver, and two of his friends, Dan
Miller and Rob Nix, both from Columbia, Mo., saw it and knew
something was very wrong.
</P>
<P>
   At first they figured Bratton would walk down, that he'd lost
his boat, gone swimming.
</P>
<P>
   But when he didn't appear, they started walking back upriver on
the banks, deeply worried, breaking through heavy brush, climbing
cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   It took them 30 minutes to reach him.
</P>
<P>
   Bratton saw them in the distance, saw a yellow dot bobbing in
the woods, Nix's bright flotation vest. He began to scream, to
wave.
</P>
<P>
   Nix threw him a tow rope. Miller went into the water, hopped
from eddy to eddy, dived across four feet of rapids, helped free
Bratton's boat.
</P>
<P>
   Back on land, Bratton stumbled at first, hypothermic, giddy,
uncoordinated. His friends dried him, got him into warm clothes,
fed him, got him up and walking.
</P>
<P>
   He made his way downstream, he got back into his boat. He didn't
want to, not at all, but there was no choice, no other way out.
</P>
<P>
   That night they all made it into the calmer water of the Cache
La Poudre River and found their campsite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I have to put you two on my Christmas-card list,''
Bratton said to Nix and Miller.
</P>
<P>
   He said little more. He couldn't talk about what had happened,
was too tired, confused.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning he woke to the smell of breakfast, the beauty of
snow-capped mountains, the sight of tumbling, shifting clouds
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, just think, you might not have seen this,'' said a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Bratton shrugged, said, ``Yeah,'' and then wandered away to be
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Kansas City, Mo., he returned to work.
</P>
<P>
   For two weeks he has kept the experience inside. He thinks
constantly about what happened, senses it holds some great meaning
for him, ponders new thoughts about respect and kindness,
uncertainty and faith.
</P>
<P>
   He knows that his deepest feelings are shifting, changing, but
he doesn't understand the process yet, and still can't talk about
it.
</P>
<P>
   It's just too much to explain, he thinks. And so, for now, he
plays the stoic river rat.
</P>
<P>
   Last week an old friend from Metropolitan Ambulance Services
Trust brought a patient to the Baptist emergency room while Bratton
was on duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I heard you almost lost it on some Colorado river,'' his
friend said.
</P>
<P>
   Bratton smiled, shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``What river?'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
