<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-ABUSE-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Lawyers file $2.2 million settlement offer for inmates abused in
Texas prison  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Lawyers Friday filed a proposed $2.2 million
settlement offer for Missouri inmates abused in a Texas prison.
</P>
<P>
   Almost $1 million would be divided among six groups of lawyers
who represent the prisoners, with the remainder split among up to
2,100 inmates. Lawyers say it would be the nation's largest
prison-abuse settlement.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Nanette Laughrey froze action on pending
prisoner lawsuits while she considers whether to approve the
proposed class-action settlement, filed in federal court in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   Judges in many of about 30 other lawsuits filed by more than 700
inmates also froze their cases this week, lawyers said. The
settlement proposal does not allow for inmates to sue outside of
the class action.
</P>
<P>
   Because of prison crowding, up to 2,100 Missouri prisoners were
housed in Texas from January 1995 to December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A September 1996 training video showed attack dogs biting
Missouri prisoners while a jailer dragged men down a hallway. An
inmate with a broken ankle slowed down, the tape showed, and a
guard shocked him with a stun gun.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance company for the private jail-management firm,
Capital Correctional Resources, and Brazoria County in Texas would
pay the $2.2 million without admitting any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners had claimed that Missouri officials knew about the
abuse and did not investigate. Missouri would pay nothing under the
proposed settlement but pledges not to take settlement money
inmates receive, which it could do to cover incarceration costs.
</P>
<P>
   The state also would review all discipline infractions prisoners
received in Texas -- infractions that could delay their parole. And
Missouri pledges not to send any of the prisoners back to Texas
jails before June 15, 2004.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
