<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-COACH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASEY GETS NOD TO COACH NETS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New Jersey Nets' long and somewhat peculiar trek toward
naming a head coach ended Friday when the team announced that Don
Casey would continue in the job. The decision ended a seven-week
search that never truly seemed to include more than two candidates:
Phil Jackson and Casey, who served as their interim coach over the
second half of last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who will present Casey as their coach at a news
conference on Monday, released a statement saying that Casey, 62,
would receive a multiyear deal.
</P>
<P>
   A person with knowledge of the contract said that the deal was
worth about $1.4 million during the first year and that the Nets
had an option to terminate the contract before the 2000-1 season.
</P>
<P>
   Casey has yet to sign the contract, which will be completed over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Casey nor the team's top officials were available for
comment, but a person close to Casey described his mood as
``ecstatic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased that Coach Casey will return to lead the
Nets next season,'' Michael Rowe, the team's president, said in the
statement. ``He's a veteran coach with a great deal of NBA
experience who did an outstanding job last year, especially when
you consider the rash of injuries that decimated the front line.''
</P>
<P>
   After John Calipari was dismissed March 15, Casey took over the
Nets' coaching duties with the team in shambles. The club's record
was 3-17, largely because the players had rebelled against
Calipari's domineering personality. Casey's laid-back and humorous
approach immediately won over the players and they began calling
him King Casey.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing six players to season-ending injuries, including
starters Jayson Williams and Keith Van Horn, the Nets compiled a
13-17 record under Casey. After the season, even though it was well
known that the Nets' ownership would make a bid for Jackson, nearly
all of the team's stars endorsed Casey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casey was the right man for the job,'' Williams said Friday.
``The players respect him and his coaching staff. I think he'll do
the same job that Phil Jackson would have done and probably better
because the players really care for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets began their very public courtship of Jackson and made
him an offer of $21 million over three years. He turned down the
deal and last week accepted a five-year deal worth a reported $30
million to coach the Los Angeles Lakers. After that, it appeared
that the hiring of Casey was a mere formality for the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   But the longer the Nets remained silent about their coaching
situation, the more it prompted speculation that perhaps they were
interested in Jeff Van Gundy, the Knicks' coach.
</P>
<P>
   With Van Gundy's announcement on Thursday that he would remain
as the coach of the Knicks next season, the timing of Friday's
announcement by the Nets could be taken as a sign that Casey might
have been their third choice. But there was no hint of that Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players responded very positively to Coach Casey and his
staff,'' said John Nash, the team's general manager. ``We feel that
the new attitude that he and his staff have brought to the team
bodes well for the future of the Nets.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey's staff of assistants _ Jim Lynam, Eddie Jordan and Mike
O'Koren _ is an integral part of the equation. Lynam and Jordan
have head coaching experience and handled much of the team's
preparation through the final 29 games. Lynam coached the offense
and Jordan the defense, while Casey oversaw the entire operation.
</P>
<P>
   Many people within the organization believed that Casey would be
hired only if Lynam and Jordan returned, and while that is likely,
neither has committed to rejoining the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   Casey, who coached Temple University to a 151-94 record from
1973 to 1981, joined the NBA as an assistant with Chicago in 1982.
He was also an assistant for the Los Angeles Clippers and the
Boston Celtics. He served as the Clippers' interim head coach for
the second half of the 1989 season and became the Nets' first
assistant before the 1996-97 season, Calipari's first with the
club.
</P>
</TEXT>
