<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-SPRINT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Johnson pulls out with injury
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ ``Making history.'' It's a phrase Michael Johnson
casually drops when the conversation turns to what makes him run.
Understandably, so. This is the man who wore the golden slippers in
the Atlanta Olympics, rewriting track history with his 200/400
meter gold-medal double and world record 19.32 in the 200.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Johnson has to wonder if his best running days aren't
history.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is injured again, this time pulling out of what was to
be the signature event of the USA Track and Field Championships _ a
showdown over 200 meters against a talented field featuring
recently crowned 100-meter world record-holder Maurice Greene.
Johnson's career has been marred by injuries since capturing
headlines at the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   During a speed workout Thursday, Johnson felt a twinge in his
right quadriceps. He decided to withdraw from the championships
after he felt the injury warming up Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's disappointed, for sure,'' said Brad Hunt, his longtime
agent. ``If it was a do-or-die situation, he'd strap it up and go.
But his goal is to run fast this summer, and there's no reason to
risk it.''
</P>
<P>
   By scratching from the 200, Johnson won't have the opportunity
to qualify for the World Championships in the sprint. Hunt said
that he still plans to run the 400 at the Worlds, where he won gold
in 1997 and thus enjoys an automatic bid.
</P>
<P>
   The news was a letdown for Greene, who had been itching to get a
shot at Johnson and his mind-boggling record of 19.32. This was to
be the race for anyone with a short attention span. Greene, 24,
fresh from clocking a world-record 9.79 over 100 meters, had hoped
to race Johnson to the finish line _ a possible world record in the
balance.
</P>
<P>
   This would have been the World's Fastest Man vs. the World's
Greatest Sprinter. Now, it's Greene running to pad his credentials,
though Florida freshman sensation John Capel might test him in the
nationally televised final Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be the World's Greatest Sprinter, you have to show
versatility,'' said Greene, plotting for a year to step up in
distance for a showdown opposite Johnson. ``You have to run more
than one race.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene finds himself playing catch-up for a lackluster
performance at the 1996 Olympic Trials in Atlanta, where he failed
to make the U.S. team. So he'd angled to knock Johnson off his
lofty perch and, while at it, take a piece out of his 19.32 _ a
mark some thought might last for ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I capable of running it right now?'' Greene said.
``Possibly. Do I believe I can run that fast? Yes. Can I do it this
weekend? Possibly.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Johnson, married last fall to Dallas TV reporter
Kerry Doyen, to ponder his future in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know if your best years are to come or if they're in
the past,'' said Johnson, 31.
</P>
<P>
   The most lasting memory of Johnson since the Atlanta Olympics is
of him pulling up lame in his match race against Donovan Bailey.
That was in the spring of 1997, and since then Johnson has spent
most of his time nursing an assortment of hip and leg injuries. To
save his legs, his racing has been restricted largely to the 400
meters. He hasn't run under 20 seconds since Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not being able to run the 200 the last two years, I haven't
been able to be the athlete I was in '92 through '96,'' Johnson
said. ``Because of injuries, I've been forced to be a 400-meter
runner.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson plans to stay around through next summer, likely
attempting another 200/400 double in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
