<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0316 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-CHAMPIONSHIPS26-C     06-26 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-CHAMPIONSHIPS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurdles fiasco has Adkins thinking retirement
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ While training partner Angelo Taylor eyes a gold
medal tonight in the 400-meter hurdles, Olympic champion Derrick
Adkins is left to ponder retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins stumbled coming off the sixth hurdle in the semifinals
Friday night, finishing a distant seventh (52.28 seconds) in his
semifinal heat. Taylor won the earlier heat and posted the fastest
qualifying time of 49.09.
</P>
<P>
   For Adkins it was an end to his season _ possibly his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``In September, I'll decide if I want to train for next year or
give it up,'' said Adkins, dejected. ``I don't know if I have it.''
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken Adkins has been slowed by injuries since the
Atlanta Olympics, and never regained the stamina that made him the
world's best hurdler. Friday night, he lacked the strength to
maintain his normal pattern of 13 strides between hurdles and
stumbled badly coming off the sixth barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins credited Georgia Tech coach Grover Hinsdale with Taylor's
development. Taylor, though, also acknowledges the help and advice
provided him by Adkins. Most afternoons, Taylor works out with
Adkins and fellow Tech grad, 400-meter runner Derek Mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like training with those guys, because they're on the same
level,'' said Taylor, a Southwest DeKalb graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Century club
</P>
<P>
   With marquee 100-meter sprinters Maurice Greene (200 meters) and
Marion Jones (200 and long jump) sitting out to focus on other
events, the men's and women's titles went to Dennis Mitchell and
Inger Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, a veteran of three Olympics, closed over the final 10
meters to win in 9.97 seconds _ well off Greene's recent
world-record clocking of 9.79.
</P>
<P>
   In the women's race, Miller, who trains in Los Angeles with a
sprint group that includes Greene, took the final in 10.96. Second
was two-time defending Olympic champion Gail Devers in 10.97.
Devers recently moved to Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   Around the track
</P>
<P>
   In the surprise of the meet, Marion Jones was beaten by Dawn
Burrell in the long jump. Jones failed to improve on her opening
effort of 22-3, and Burrell passed her on her next-to-last jump of
22-10 _ a career-best and sixth-best ever by an American. The top
three finishers advance to the World Championships, so Jones' goal
of four gold medals is still a possibility. ... It was a rough
night for the Atlanta contingent in the men's 400. Derek Mills,
Jonas Motiejunas and Milton Campbell all failed to advance from the
semifinals. ... Atlanta Olympic gold medalist Charles Austin won
the high jump with a clearance of 7-5 3/4. ... Connie Price-Smith
claimed an eighth straight shot put title.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
