A0318 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NURSING-STUDENTS-KAN &LR;      06-26 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-STUDENTS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN WOMAN BENEFITS FROM KINDNESSES IN KC AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STACY DOWNS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Two weeks ago Delia Noselo was living in a
cardboard shack in Mexico with her mother, her seven nieces and
nephews, and a mess of chickens.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old woman, who has not been able to use her legs
since she fell off the back of a truck eight years ago, had to drag
herself on her arms across the dirt floor.
</P>
<P>
   Now, thanks to nursing students and faculty from Johnson County
(Kan.) Community College, Noselo lives in Kansas at Delmar Gardens
of Overland Park -- a nursing home with carpeting, a piano in the
front hallway and a window view of woods and a pond. She has a room
she shares with one other person. But most important, she is
getting the medical care she needs.
</P>
<P>
   Noselo on Friday completed her first session of physical
therapy. Through a translator, she talked in Spanish about how her
legs hurt, how she wants to learn English, how she enjoys the food
and how she doesn't miss anything from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hasn't had much love,'' said Mary Smith, an associate
professor of nursing. Smith led students on a 10-day trip earlier
this month to practice community health care in Las Pintas, a rural
area 30 miles east of Guadalajara, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Smith met Noselo last year on a previous visit. What she saw
troubled her deeply.
</P>
<P>
   Noselo hadn't been bathed in weeks, her hair was matted, and she
weighed 80 pounds. She used a broken wheelchair that later
completely gave out, forcing her to crawl with her arms.
</P>
<P>
   She lived with her mother, who was busy raising her other
daughter's seven children and working as a cleaner in a butcher
shop. They had no electricity or plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   And there was no one to care for Noselo.
</P>
<P>
   Smith talked to local doctors, who said Noselo couldn't receive
government aid for medical care because she is a U.S. citizen. She
was born in Brownsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Smith suspects Noselo had polio as a child. She had been married
for a short time, but her husband abandoned her, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like Delia is a victim,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   So when Smith returned with 11 students and other faculty
members this year, she had a plan to bring Noselo back.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an easy decision. It meant taking Noselo out of her
culture, where she knew the language, was familiar with
surroundings and had a family. But when Smith saw her again, she
knew it was the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted to leave,'' Smith said. ``She wanted to get better.
She wanted to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   For the plane trip to the United States, Noselo sent for her
original birth certificate, and a Mexican official wrote a letter
and included a photo of her as her identification. The students
used $450 left over from their medical supplies fund for her
airfare.
</P>
<P>
   Smith knew Noselo needed full-time care, but didn't know what
nursing center would be the best. At first Noselo stayed in Smith's
home. Smith soon called a friend, Pam Davidson, who recently had
become nursing director of Delmar Gardens near the college. The
center accepted Noselo without any assurance it would be paid for
her care. She has applied for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   One of Noselo's greatest needs is an electric wheelchair that
would cost $4,000. Medicaid wouldn't cover that expense, Davidson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wouldn't be dependent -- it would open a whole new
world,'' Davidson said. ``She could go to church and the grocery
store to pick out her own food -- she's never had that
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said the goal was for Noselo to live in a group home,
where she could live independently, share her language and her
culture.
</P>
<P>
   A Delmar nurse assistant from Argentina regularly visits with
Noselo. She gave her a book of puzzles and games in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Smith would like college Spanish students to help teach Noselo
English. In turn, Noselo would help them with Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing students and faculty, some of whom speak Spanish, visit
Noselo each day. One of the students, Kitsy Gough, 21, of Overland
Park, said Noselo lights up when she sees people she knows.
</P>
<P>
   But Gough knows that although Noselo's life has greatly
improved, living here will be a difficult adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people ask her how she is doing, she always uses the
Spanish expression `It's going to be a battle,' '' Gough said.
</P>
</TEXT>
