<HEADER>
A0323 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRE-DELAY-KAN &LR;      06-26 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-DELAY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPATCHER'S ROLE QUESTIONED IN FIRE DEPARTMENT'S FAILURE TO
RESPOND TO MEDICAL CALLS DURING FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE PENN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- A Kansas City fire dispatcher is being
investigated for his role in the Fire Department's failure to
respond to emergency medical calls across the city while a
four-alarm fire was under way in late May.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, fire units were battling a blaze that destroyed a
two-block-long abandoned warehouse in the West Bottoms. About 75
firefighters -- out of about 200 usually on duty during a typical
shift -- spent two hours bringing the fire under control. More than
100 people were evacuated from neighboring buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Department records contend that the dispatcher, a Fire
Department employee, failed to send fire units to respond to seven
emergency medical calls relayed by the Metropolitan Ambulance
Services Trust in a 26-minute period.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious call was a cardiac arrest in midtown. The
patient was dead when a MAST ambulance crew arrived, but MAST's
incident report stated that the patient had been dead for some time
and that a quicker response would not have made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six other calls, according to MAST, four patients were
taken to hospitals, where they were treated and released; the two
others did not require treatment.
</P>
<P>
   MAST did not disclose the names of any of the patients, citing
patient confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Fire Department disciplinary report obtained by
The Kansas City Star, the dispatcher told his superiors that he
thought the department was too busy fighting the fire to respond to
all but the most pressing medical calls.
</P>
<P>
   In the city's emergency medical system, Fire Department units
function as ``first responders.'' Emergency medical calls are
relayed from MAST to the Fire Department because fire stations are
more numerous than MAST ambulances and are placed strategically
throughout the city. The idea is for firefighters to reach the
scene of an emergency first and provide initial care until an
ambulance can get there.
</P>
<P>
   The union representing Kansas City firefighters is campaigning
for the department to take over ambulance service in the city. A
committee has been formed to study the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The dispatcher refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Chief Rick Brisbin said he had not seen the disciplinary
report, but he confirmed that the incident occurred and was being
investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look into it,'' Brisbin said. ``We take those kinds of
things very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Fire Department regulations, dispatchers are required to
respond to any request for service that comes to them by their
computer link to MAST.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Gratton, the Health Department physician who leads the
city's emergency medical system, said he was concerned about the
incident but wanted to know more about the case before commenting.
</P>
<P>
   Brisbin said officials think they know what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand what went on over there,'' Brisbin said. ``But
it still prompts an investigation. We understand what it's like to
expend resources as fast as you can find them. But it's pretty
serious to get caught up in the flow of things like that.
Professional dispatchers shouldn't miss something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the disciplinary report, a supervisor ordered the
dispatcher to contact MAST officials to tell them that firefighters
were responding to emergency medical calls but had to repeat the
order ``two or three times'' before the dispatcher acted on it.
</P>
<P>
   The disciplinary report included a transcript of a
``fact-finding session'' in which the dispatcher was questioned by
his supervisor, acting Deputy Chief Paul Berardi.
</P>
<P>
   The report quotes the dispatcher as saying: ``Three EMS calls
popped up on the MAST link that did not seem to be
life-threatening....I called MAST and told them this thing would
probably escalate and asked if they could handle the EMS calls.''
</P>
<P>
   In explaining why he decided to ask MAST to handle the medical
calls, the dispatcher was quoted in the report as saying, ``I was
trained to take care of FD (Fire Department) first.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire Department dispatchers are trained to juggle many
emergencies at one time, Brisbin said. However, he said he expected
the volume of calls the dispatcher was handling at the time to be
an issue raised in the dispatcher's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to deal with lots of emergencies,'' Brisbin said.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Department officials said a disciplinary hearing would be
held before punishment, if any, was rendered.
</P>
<P>
   Berardi, listed as the author of the disciplinary report,
refused to discuss it, calling it a private personnel document.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, the dispatcher was told by a Fire
Department supervisor that despite the demands the West Bottoms
fire placed on the department, the department was still available
to respond to emergency medical calls.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the disciplinary report, the dispatcher is
accused of failing to send fire units on seven such calls received
between 1:01:37 p.m. and 1:27:37 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the cardiac arrest, the other calls involved
reports of a traffic accident in Westport, someone suffering chest
pains in the 6400 block of Prospect Avenue, someone suffering from
shortness of breath near Interstate 435 and Interstate 29, and
another person experiencing difficulty breathing near the
intersection of 20th Street and Hardesty Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Two other calls involved reports of unconscious persons, one in
the 3900 block of Monroe Street, the other in the 6700 block of
Prospect Avenue. MAST units responded to the incidents. MAST
declined to release the names of the ambulance crew members who
responded to those calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 0018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
