<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0324 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYUN-TRACK-KAN &LR;      06-26 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYUN-TRACK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JIM RYUN AND TEEN WHO BROKE HIS RECORD SAVOR MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- What becomes a legend most? Perhaps it's the grace
in which he relinquishes his hold on a piece of immortality.
</P>
<P>
   When Jim Ryun, the legendary miler who now runs in search of
votes, not medals, heard recently that a high school sophomore had
broken the first major record he ever set, he was surprised, and a
bit disappointed, too.
</P>
<P>
   Not because his record, the fastest mile by a high school
sophomore, had fallen. But because it had taken so long for
somebody to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six years. A full generation. Countless runners had come
and gone, and his record had weathered them all. But it should have
been eclipsed years ago, Ryun said. That's the ``natural
progression'' of sports.
</P>
<P>
   So when the three-time Olympian, who's now a second-term
Republican congressman from Kansas, met Alan Webb, the 16-year-old
schoolboy from Reston, Va., who dethroned him, he eagerly went
straight for the details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me a little about the race,'' Ryun asked Webb on the
front steps of the Capitol last week during a ceremony with past
and present Olympians. ``I want to hear about the pace of it.
Describe it for me. What was your last 400 meters?''
</P>
<P>
   And Webb, looking about as nervous as someone suddenly coming
face-to-face with an idol has every right to be, said, ``I went the
last quarter in 59 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' said Ryun, recalling all too well the toll the final
400 takes on the lungs and legs.
</P>
<P>
   And the wide-eyed Webb smiled the smile of youth aglow with an
elder's approval. But not just any elder's. Ryun is arguably the
greatest American miler of all time. He was still in high school
when he went to the Tokyo Olympics in 1964. He had just handed Webb
a moment perhaps more lasting than any gold medal he might someday
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations,'' the athlete-turned-politician said before
heading back to the ceremony. ``Just keep your focus and keep
going. You've got great talent. I'll be watching with eager
expectation. God bless you.''
</P>
<P>
   In his prime, Jim Ryun was running. It was long before jogging,
long before shoes came in a zillion shapes and colors. He won five
national collegiate titles and became a world-record holder in the
mile, the 1,500 meters and the 880 yards. He won a silver medal in
the 1968 Olympics, even as he was suffering mononucleosis and
running in the thin air of Mexico City. On the wall of his
congressional office are eight Sports Illustrated covers with his
picture.
</P>
<P>
   There were frustrations, too, like falling in the 1,500 meter
qualifying round at the Munich Olympics in 1972. He never made the
finals. But Ryun, whose religious faith imbues every aspect of his
life, said the experience strengthened him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a great deal of success as an athlete,'' he said.
``This gave me an opportunity through a very high-profile situation
to come to grips with that it's not always going to go your way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't wish it on anybody,'' he quickly added.
</P>
<P>
   Ryun was a student at Wichita (Kan.) East High School when he
took up running, pretty much out of desperation. He had been cut
from his church baseball team and the junior high basketball team,
and he wasn't big enough for football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what cross-country was all about, but one of my
first goals was to make the team,'' Ryun said. ``And if you make
the team, then you get a letter jacket, and since I was not one of
the more popular students in school, I assumed that maybe I could
get a girlfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Got the jacket,'' Ryun said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   His career was jump-started on a humid day in Houston, in June
1963, when he was 16 and racing in the shadows of older, wiser
runners at the U.S. Track and Field Federation National
Championships. He ran the mile in 4:07.08, a mark that stood for
nearly four decades. Until two weeks ago. That's when Webb, on a
cool night on a Raleigh, N.C., track, ran the same distance in
4:06.94.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he was a legendary high school distance runner,'' said
Webb, who can tick off Ryun's stats the way other kids can recite
the minutiae of ``Star Wars.'' ``It feels really, really good. It
feels great, actually. When I first did it, it took me a little
while for it to sink in. That night, I was sort of like -- wow!''
</P>
<P>
   Ryun still owns other high school titles. He became the first
high-schooler to break the four-minute mile, running 3:59 when he
was a junior at Wichita East. As a senior, he ran a 3:55.3, still
the American high school record.
</P>
<P>
   But Alan Webb is closing in, and Ryun couldn't be happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am thrilled that he broke the record,'' he said. ``The
junior record and senior record, those are still there. It seems
like Alan might be the next possibility, and I wish him well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
