u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     06-26 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG ROAD FOR A SHORT, WILD SEASON
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They said that this lockout-shortened season would be
a blessing, a five-month sprint instead of a seven- or eight-month
marathon. In fact, this has been the longest short season in
National Basketball Association history. And for the Knicks, the
wildest.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 78-77 loss Friday night, New York's Miracle Knicks
learned how to roar this season.
</P>
<P>
   The deep, dark circles under coach Jeff Van Gundy's eyes are the
signature of a dramatic season where there was no rest for the
weary. ``There was no time from the start to the end to ever gather
yourself,'' Van Gundy said Friday. ``We had one four-day break.
Other than that, it was just game after game after game. If you
were hurt at any point in the year you had no chance to get back to
feeling better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The games were much more bunched together. In that way it was
a very long season; that makes it more of a mental challenge as
well. A lot of times you might play back-to-back games, then you
have two days off. Here it was back-to-back, a day off, then
back-to-back-to-back. The regular season is always a mental
challenge, but this one, to me, was harder.'' Friday night, for the
first time, the Knicks looked tired.
</P>
<P>
   There was something more grueling, more intense about watching
the Knicks this season. Something deeply personal and intimate made
this season more riveting, more excruciating than ever. The Knicks
became a nonstop, day-to-day epic that began at this time last year
when they underwent the equivalent of root canal work: they traded
the venerable Charles Oakley for an untested and unproven Marcus
Camby.
</P>
<P>
   That trade created a deep wound in the team, and it hurt Oakley
and a loyal contingent of Oakley supporters, Van Gundy being first
among them. Then a wisdom tooth was ripped out in January when the
popular John Starks was traded for Latrell Sprewell, an
All-Star-caliber player who made headlines with Golden State for
attacking his coach.
</P>
<P>
   From Day 1 until Day 170, the Knicks have been a laboratory of
race and politics, a kaleidoscope of the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy: Leaves Yale to play Division III basketball. Some say
that was an early sign of poor judgment; others call it a valiant
concession to passion. As King Edward VIII gave up the throne of
Britain to wed the love of his life, Van Gundy left the citadel of
education for the sport he loved. Goes on to be head coach of the
Knicks and comes within three games of an NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   Camby: Repays money that his college lost because of a
recruiting violation he was involved in. Goes from Knicks pariah to
crowd favorite to starter.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell: In the most dramatic turnabout of all, goes from
recalcitrant to the rebellious hero who teaches his team to roar.
Now Disney is talking about including him in a project. And Friday
night, he tried to resurrect the Knicks, just when it appeared they
were done. With 8 minutes 57 seconds left in the game, his
3-pointer gave the Knicks a 3-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   This season has seemed long because the Knicks have been
relentless. As recently as Thursday, Larry Johnson introduced yet
another multilayered theme, the theme of Knicks as rebellious
slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, Johnson took his lumps. Mostly the criticism
centered on the incongruity of money and bondage: how can someone
who makes $84 million call himself a slave?
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell came to his friend's defense. Compensation that
athletes receive often adds up to hush money, an incentive to
behave, to buy homes and cars, to go off and be quiet. ``Some guys,
like Larry and myself, don't see that money when we're put in that
position,'' Sprewell said. ``Somebody else, concerned about the
money to the point of saying, `I like this hush money, I'm going to
hush up.' Not saying I should have done what I did, but they're not
going to let it go that far.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People asked me, `How could you do this and do that if you
make $8 million a year?''' Sprewell added. ``I'm saying it's not
about the money, it's about me as an individual, my personal
manhood and you speaking to me as a man. Money wasn't even a factor
at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks learned to roar this season; the noise could
reverberate for a few seasons to come. Anyone who followed the team
from beginning to end feels the way you feel at the end of a great
book: exhausted, invigorated, stimulated. Sorry the story ended
this way, a 1-point loss, but glad that it's over.
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember when a short season seemed so long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
