<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0330 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-1STLD     06-26 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINK TO SUSPECTED CON MAN TURNS PRIESTS INTO PARIAHS IN VATICAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: CORRECTS spelling of baptized in graph beginning `Jacobs was
born...,' and of affidavit in last graph. Also changes `holiday' to
`vacation' in graph beginning `In August...') (rm) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ As priests, they make an unlikely pair. One is an
affable, worldly American bon vivant who zooms around Trastevere on
a raffish blue motorbike and defied his New York archbishop in the
1980s by running a trendy Manhattan restaurant to raise money for
the poor. The other is an owlish Italian canon law scholar who
serves as an emeritus judge on the Roman Rota, the court of appeals
of the Holy See.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the Rev. Peter Jacobs, 73, and Monsignor Emilio
Colagiovanni, 79, provided a clerical cloak of respectability for a
Greenwich, Conn., money manager who authorities suspect embezzled
more than $300 million from a web of insurance companies across the
United States. Both men insist they were badly duped by Martin R.
Frankel, who disappeared last month and is wanted by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The priests say they knew Frankel as David Rosse, a middle-aged
tycoon who claimed descent from the biblical King David and said he
was eager to give at least $50 million to the Roman Catholic
Church.
</P>
<P>
   They supported the St. Francis of Assisi Foundation, a charity
Frankel set up and then attempted to use to buy several insurance
companies in the United States. He named Jacobs as the president of
that foundation. Colagiovanni, who had his own foundation, said he
went a step further, giving Jacobs' charity power to move funds in
and out of his foundation's Vatican bank account.
</P>
<P>
   With federal investigators in the United States scouring the
records of Frankel's intricate financial transactions, those
actions have left both priests exposed and vulnerable. And it has
turned both of them into virtual pariahs inside the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Valls, said there was no
link whatsoever between The Vatican and Frankel. He also denied any
connection between Colagiovanni's Monitor Ecclesiasticus Foundation
and the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Yet before the scandal erupted, senior Vatican officials were
also intrigued by Frankel's professed desire to shower riches on
church charities. At least two senior Vatican officials met with
Frankel's American lawyer, Thomas A. Bolan, and tried to help his
client set up a charitable foundation that would be part of the
Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   Bolan, a former law partner of Roy Cohn and an active figure in
Catholic charity circles in the United States, met in Rome to
discuss the foundation with Bishop Francesco Salerio Salerno, and
Monsignor Gianfranco Piovano, top Vatican officials, according to
his lawyer, Maurice R. Nessen, and the two priests. Reading from
his notes of what Bolan recollects, Nessen said Friday that the
meetings in Rome centered on how an outside philanthropist could
channel money through the Vatican to support religious causes.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Church officials are highly sensitive to any hint of a banking
scandal ever since the 1980s, when the Vatican bank was badly
tainted by its ties to the Banco Ambrosiana, which collapsed in the
wake of a huge financial scandal and the mysterious death of a
mafia-linked banker, Roberto Calvi in 1982. The pope later ordered
a clean-up of the bank that eventually led to the Vatican producing
its first healthy profits in 1993 after decades of budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Salerno is now secretary of the Apostolic Signatura, the Supreme
Court of the Church. At the time of the meeting with Bolan, he was
secretary of the Prefecture for the Economic Affairs of the Holy
See. In an interview Friday, Salerno said he denied ever discussing
the foundation with Bolan, though he said he did so with
Colagiovanni. ``I could not refuse Monsignor Colagiovanni, he is a
judge on the Roman Rota,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Salerno said he told other Vatican officials that
``hypothetically'' nothing would legally prevent an American
financier from opening a charitable foundation in the Vatican.
``The Vatican is a sovereign state, anything can be done, but the
question is will it be authorized,'' Salerno said.
</P>
<P>
   Nessen, Bolan's attorney, said that his client had a later
meeting with Piovano, an assistant Vatican secretary of state, who
disagreed with Salerno, pointing out that Frankel could not be
allowed to control a Vatican foundation's assets, especially since
Frankel also wished to invest in insurance companies in America.
Eventually, however, the two sides worked out a compromise: the
Monitor Ecclesiasticus Foundation, Colagiovanni's cultural and
charitable organization, could act as ``founder'' _ in legal terms
as ``settlor'' _ of a new, independent foundation controlled by
Frankel. According to Nessen, the new foundation would be named
after St. Francis of Assisi and could claim links to the Vatican,
as Frankel desired. Nessen said that Salerno was aware of and
approved this arrangement in advance. Asked in writing to respond,
Salerno did not reply.
</P>
<P>
   But after Frankel's suspected embezzlement schemes came to
light, the Vatican sought to distance itself from the American's
associates in the church.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro-Valls described Colagiovanni, who as president of the
Monitor Ecclesiasticus edits a Vatican-approved canonical law
quarterly and also runs its charitable arm, as a ``pensioner.''
Navarro-Valls said he knew nothing about Jacobs, but volunteered
that he was an ``ex-Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Salerno also pointed out Jacobs' Jewish roots after the scandal
surfaced. Neither he nor Navarro-Valls nor others mentioned the
fact that Jacobs was formally rebuked by the Catholic Church in
1983, after he ignored an archbishop's order to cease operating his
New York restaurant, The Palantine. Jacobs' right to perform
priestly duties was suspended at that time because he violated
church rules about business transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, who continued to serve Mass and perform weddings, said
in an interview that he believed his suspension was reversed in
1987 after he gave up the business. According to his archdiocese in
Washington, however, the suspension was reversed, but not the ban
on giving sacraments.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Priestly faculties are like a medical license, and Father
Jacobs' were never restored,'' William E. Lori, auxiliary bishop of
the Archdiocese of Washington, D.C, explained on Thursday. ``The
sacraments he performed since 1983 are not valid.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs was born in New Hampshire, the son of a Jewish father and
an Irish Catholic mother. Jacobs was baptized as a Catholic, but he
only began practicing his faith while serving in the Navy during
World war II. He was ordained in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   In his long, colorful and highly unorthodox career as a priest,
he has made interfaith marriages a specialty. It was, in fact, an
interfaith society wedding that brought Jacobs and Colagiovanni
together in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; They first met, Colagiovanni recalled in an interview, at the
Vatican Bank, known as the Instituto per Le Opere Religiose.
Colagiovanni's foundation has an account there. Jacobs said that he
was there visiting old friends who worked in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very social fellow,'' Colagiovanni said of Jacobs.
Soon after that meeting, Jacobs sought out Colagiovanni's expertise
in arranging a Catholic Church wedding for a divorced Jewish groom
and a Catholic bride. Colagiovanni said he had no idea at the time
he was helping one of America's wealthiest men, Edgar Bronfman Jr.,
president of Seagram Co., marry Clarissa Alcock, the daughter of an
oil executive, in Caracas, Venezuela. Jacobs said he officiated at
the service, alongside a local priest and a rabbi, over the
objections of the local cardinal. An associate of the Bronfman
family said that this was untrue, and that the local priest had
officiated, with Jacobs serving as a ``greeter.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, who has worked in the slums of New York and Washington,
D.C., also hobnobs with European aristocrats and counts the late
Princess Grace of Monaco, Walter Cronkite, Arrigo Cipriani, the
owner of Harry's Bar, among his many well-heeled friends. Another
one was Bolan.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, Colagiovanni said he got another call from
Jacobs when he was on vacation in Cleveland. ``He told me there was
a Jewish millionaire who wanted to do good things for the church
and the poor,'' Colagiovanno recalled.
</P>
<P>
   He flew at Frankel's expense to New York, where he and Jacobs
and Bolan had dinner. Jacobs said he had known Bolan for 30 years
and had helped him through a variety of family crises.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the dinner, all three men drove to Greenwich, Conn.,
to meet the aspiring benefactor. Both priests said they were
surprised and impressed by Frankel's library, which was crammed
with books on Catholicism, ranging from papal encyclicals to
biographies of saints, including hundreds of tomes devoted to St.
Francis of Assisi. ``He had actually read the encyclicals,'' Jacobs
said. ``Even I haven't read them all.''
</P>
<P>
   But the priest also noticed Frankel's weird side, particularly
his obsessive fear of germs. ``He reminded me of the Jack Nicholson
character in `As Good as It Gets,' who kept washing his hands over
and over,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   Colagiovanni, like Jacobs, received from Frankel a 13-page
autobiographical sketch that laid out his financial credentials and
his piety. Colagiovanni said he was convinced of Frankel's good
intentions, but he said that when Frankel explained his desire to
give $50 million to Catholic charities by setting up his own
foundation at the Vatican, he told him that was impossible. ``I
explained no lay person could bank there,'' Colagiovanni said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he encouraged Frankel to start his own private
foundation. But Frankel was apparently so keen to bank at the
Vatican that he dispatched his lawyer, Bolan, to Rome by Concorde
to meet with Vatican officials.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides eventually settled on the compromise and founded
the St. Francis Foundation. Jacobs said that he learned that he was
appointed a trustee and president of the foundation after seeing
his name on a document.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel also ardently pursued celebrities to add legitimacy to
his organization, sometimes even after they declined to support
him. Lee Iacocca, the former Chrysler chairman, rejected Frankel's
overtures to serve on the St. Francis foundation board. But Frankel
did not readily accept no for an answer: He paid for Iacocca to fly
on a leased Gulfstream IV executive jet from Los Angeles to Milan,
Italy, where Iacocca attended to some personal and business
affairs, a spokeswoman for Iacocca said. She said that the retired
auto executive was not initially informed about how the trip was
paid for.
</P>
<P>
   And Frankel pressured Jacobs to use his own connections. Walter
Cronkite said that he had received and rejected a request from
Jacobs to serve on the advisory board. After that conversation,
Cronkite heard nothing more about the matter until early May, when
he got a voice mail at his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father Pete called and left a very cryptic message,'' Cronkite
said. ``He said, `The man who has given a billion dollars has
apparently absconded with the money, the whole thing is a mess. I'm
sorry I listed you as a member of the board of advisors. I hope it
doesn't cause you any problems.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That was the first time Cronkite heard that Jacobs had put his
name on the list of advisors. ``It was very much of a surprise,''
he said. ``I would not have thought that he would do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Colagiovanni said that he told Frankel he did not want to be
involved with collecting or investing money. He signed over to
Jacobs, president of the St. Francis Foundation, the right to use
the bank account of the Monitor Ecclesiaticus Foundation, which is
in the Vatican bank. But Frankel apparently never tapped that
source: both priests said that Frankel never sent any money to
either foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel instead used Colagiovanni's connections in a different
way, persuading the priest to sign a November 1998 affidavit that
stated that money contributed to the St. Francis Foundation came
from ``funds of the Holy See.'' Frankel's lawyers used that
document to support their claims that Frankel's charity and
business dealings had the approval of the Vatican. Colagiovanni now
says that the affidavit was misleading, and that he should not have
signed it. ``I trusted him,'' he explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
