<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0335 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEP-TRIAL-AZR &LR;      06-26 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEP-TRIAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND ATTACK KEY TO FIRST-DEGREE MURDER VERDICT IN SLEEPWALKING
TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER, RICHARD RUELAS   
 and VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ In the end, it wasn't the 44 stab wounds.
</P>
<P>
   It was Scott Falater's second attack on his wife _ when he held
her head under the water of their backyard pool _ that convinced a
jury Friday he was guilty of first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting defense claims that Falater was sleepwalking during
the bloody 1997 assault on his wife, Yarmila, the Maricopa County
Superior Court panel returned a guilty verdict after just eight
hours of deliberation.
</P>
<P>
   When asked at the news conference after the trial what message
the guilty verdict sent, one juror, Theresa Beaubien of Glenale
said, ``You can't get away with murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater didn't flinch as the court clerk read the verdict, which
ended a monthlong trial that attracted international attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he anticipated the verdict,'' defense attorney Michael
Kimerer said later Friday. ``We certainly knew that if the jury
came back that soon it was not going to be a good verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is despondent,'' Kimerer said. ``You've just been convicted
of first-degree murder and you don't understand how this crime
occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater based his bid for acquittal on the claim that his
conscious mind had remained asleep for 45 to 50 minutes as he
stabbed his wife 44 times, stashed the bloody clothes, then dragged
her into the backyard pool.
</P>
<P>
   But that second attack, jurors said after the trial, removed
their ``reasonable doubt'' about the prosecution's charge. They
said they reached agreement late Thursday, but when several members
wanted a night to sleep on it, they waited until Friday to take the
final vote.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:45 Friday morning, the jury informed Maricopa County
Superior Court Judge Ronald Reinstein that it had reached a
verdict. Less than an hour later, the packed courtroom heard the
announcement that could lead to Falater's execution.
</P>
<P>
   Falater, with the expressionless calm he showed during much of
the trial, turned to comfort his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay strong, mom,'' Falater said to Lois Wilcek, who sat
directly behind him, eyes red with tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could they do this?'' she asked her husband, stunned at
the fate of the oldest of her five children, a gifted former
Motorola engineer and self-proclaimed nerd who owns several patents
on electronics devices.
</P>
<P>
   Falater hugged Kimerer. A few minutes later, the dark-suited,
newly stamped convict was escorted by sheriff's deputies back to
the Madison Street Jail, where he has worn inmate's stripes ever
since that bloody night at the Phoenix home he shared with his wife
and two children.
</P>
<P>
   Several jurors then spoke with reporters about a complex and
gripping case that featured experts clashing over the emerging
science of sleep disorders, Falater friends and colleagues who
vouched for his character and the defendant himself, who sobbed on
the stand about killing the woman he called his soulmate and
confidant.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came off as an honest, law-abiding citizen, but I think
we're all capable of doing things,'' said juror Denise Aguirre, a
UPS driver from Phoenix. ``None of us know what happened there. We
don't know what triggered this.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Landrum, a Phoenix salesman, said he was not surprised
that witnesses for the prosecution could identify no serious rift
in the Falater marriage, no clear motive for a brutal murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no evidence of a motive,'' he acknowledged. But
then, speaking from the experience of his own failed marriage, he
added, ``If I'm having a relationship problem, there's only two
people that's going to know about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to find a motive, the jurors looked for a way to
understand the killing, which Kimerer portrayed as an involuntary,
senseless eruption in the peaceful domestic landscape of a happy
and prosperous family.
</P>
<P>
   Some jurors concluded that Falater may have been sleepwalking
when he first attacked his wife, stabbing her repeatedly next to
the pool pump.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of the stab wounds _ 44 _ suggested that he must
have awakened at some point, they said. The second attack at the
pool, which was witnessed by next-door neighbor, convinced them.
</P>
<P>
   Landrum said he formed two basic scenarios for the attack. In
one, Falater was ``fully conscious and wide awake.'' In the other,
Falater was sleepwalking when he stabbed Yarmila, then awoke and
``panicked and tried to cover it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Aguirre said she was one of four jurors who expressed
``reasonable doubt'' about the prosecution case when the panel
began deliberations Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But the eyewitness account of neighbor Greg Koons, who described
Falater's complex movements leading up to the grim incident at the
pool, persuaded her and others that the sleepwalking defense made
no sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deciding factors were that we did not think it was
probable or likely for the sequence of detailed events that took
place to have happened while the person was basically
unconscious,'' said Michael Riley, a manager at Intel and the jury
foreman.
</P>
<P>
   John Merrill, a supervisor at a Gila River Reservation casino,
agreed that Koons was vital to the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there had been no eyewitness, he probably would have gotten
away with it,'' Merril said. ``But Greg Koons' testimony was just
too damning.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill also thought Falater could have been sleepwalking when
he stabbed Yarmila.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when he dragged the body, I think he woke up. He could
have been sleepwalking and then he woke up and he saw, `Oh, look at
this. What have I done?' and I think he panicked and he dragged the
body over.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawna Wilkeyson said she thought Falater was wide awake during
the knife attack. She said the attack occurred too early that night
for Falater to have had time to fall into the deep sleep during
which sleepwalking occurs, according to expert testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some very heated discussions,'' said Riley, adding that
the panel took very seriously its responsibility in a
first-degree-murder case.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said the group weighed heavily the discrepancies between
defense and proseuction experts on sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, that's what made the deliberations so hard. We had
two groups of experts that were telling us the exact opposite
things. It came down to a choice of whose experts do you believe.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Aguirre said she found the experts to be of little
value. ``All the experts, they all have their own theory. . . .
They just confused me.''
</P>
<P>
   Several jurors said they were unimpressed by Falater's
expressions of grief on the witness stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too rehearsed,'' said Wilkeyson. ``One of the things we
talked about was (that) during questioning by the defense he looked
at the jury almost the whole time. When the state questioned him,
he didn't look at the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Beaubien, a Glendale housewife, said Falater's interview
with a homicide detective the night of Yarmila's death contradicted
his sleepwalking claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``He accepted the fact that his wife was dead too easily, and
the fact that he did it,'' she said. ``Wouldn't you be totally
astounded that you did it? Wouldn't you be incredibly remorseful
and crying and so upset?'' While defense attorney Kimerer declined
to speak after the verdict, prosecutor Juan Martinez expressed
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least for today, Yarmila's soul can perhaps get some
peace,'' he said, his eyes bloodshot with fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who has never lost a murder case, said he thought
about Yarmila each day of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a good mother,'' he said. ``She cared incredibly for
her kids. She assumed the role of wife. She participated in her
church. It's a shame it had to come to this.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he sympathizes most with the Falater's two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something they will carry with them for the rest of
their lives,'' Martinez said. ``It will affect them every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the trial started, he had filed his intention to seek the
death penalty. However, County Attorney Rick Romley said Friday
that his office will revisit that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Romley congratulated Martinez, the Phoenix police and the jury
for their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I think we need to sit back and kind of remember what
this was about, everybody,'' Romley said at a press conference.
``This was about a very, brutal senseless murder of a very good
woman.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
