<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN RETURNS; OTHERS CLOSE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mo Vaughn was back at first base on Friday
night and Todd Greene was fine with that.
</P>
<P>
   Who can blame him?
</P>
<P>
   The lineup change afforded Greene, a catcher, some time to rest
his knees. He had little time to prepare, though, as Anaheim Angels
manager Terry Collins made the decision just prior to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw that it was happening, when I looked at the lineup card
coming in,'' Greene said. ``I change like this depends on Mo, so he
must be up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several players currently on the disabled list made their
appearances in the Angels clubhouse before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was setup man Mike James, looking as if he just
rolled in from the beach. James, who dyes his hair blond, sported
some other unusual attire _ a diamond nose stud, and one in his
lower lip.
</P>
<P>
   No word on when he will be back in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Another injured Angel hanging around Friday was Tim Salmon. The
outfielder worked out his throwing arm while resting his injured
left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Collins noted most players have one of two reactions when they
see injured teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two fronts to it,'' he said. ``There are guys who
see Jimmy (Edmonds), Salmon and James and (Mike) Colangeo and Pep
Harris in there and it's a come down.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to some others these guys could also be a light at the end
of the tunnel _ `they are here, they are starting to work, so there
is hope.'''
</P>
<P>
   As for his thoughts, Collins was non-committal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say what I think about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tough times: While Thursday's win over Seattle was the Angels'
third in four games the team is still struggling. Coming into
Friday's game, Anaheim had won just six of its previous 18 games
and trailed 7-2 before rallying in the eighth for Thursday's 12-7
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Making their pitches: Thursday's game was a milestone for Scott
Schoenweis, who recorded his first big-league win. Mark Petkovsek
got credit for his first major-league save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
