<SLUG> BC-KALAKALA-FERRY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMED FERRY KALAKALA MAY HAVE BROUGHT WITH IT AN OIL-EATING
BACTERIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE BARBER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They knew the ferry Kalakala was historic.
</P>
<P>
   And they knew it had a lot of rust.
</P>
<P>
   What they didn't know was that the old boat rescued from the
Alaska mud last year was also a giant petri dish for what may be a
new strain of oil-spill eating bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   The microbe, found in bilge gunk shortly after its arrival at
Pier 66 on Seattle's waterfront last year, has been tentatively
named for the vessel: pseudomonas Kalakala 98.
</P>
<P>
   Now being studied by a local bio-tech firm, the life form could
take a bigger bite out of nasty oil spills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have been able to spray this in Prince William
Sound,'' damaged 10 years ago by the Exxon Valdez oil spill, said
Paul Norem, vice president of Martin Environmental Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   It's even created something of an international stir among
proponents of using microbial technology to clean up oil spills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an absolute, marvelous, 100 percent breakthrough,'' said
Terrie Trevillion, president of International Landmark
Environmental in British Columbia, which has been around since
1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these microbes are found in sweetwater, like lakes.
It's very rare that you find a microbe that lives in a saline
environment like this one does,'' she said. ``I'm really thrilled
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Trevillion's company does work with biodegradable oil spill
absorbants in Saudi Arabia, where she said the microbe might be
effective on the salty sands.
</P>
<P>
   The fragile, venerable Kalakala, built on the hull of a
burnt-out wreck in 1935, is an art-deco silver slug of a ferry
vessel. The Kalakala, now moored in Seattle's Lake Union awaiting
repairs, once featured dances and bands on its cross-Sound voyages.
In 1967 it became an Alaskan fish processor, mired in mud,
abandoned and rusting away on Kodiak Island when a Seattle man,
Peter Bevis, spearheaded a fight to bring it back to Seattle last
year and restore it.
</P>
<P>
   Before the harbormaster and Coast Guard would let it go to sea,
however, the bilge had to be cleaned last spring. Kalakala
officials asked MET to donate its ``bioremediation'' process, which
employs oil-eating bacteria to devour gunk.
</P>
<P>
   MET donated five gallons of its microbes concentrated in a
chemical, called a surfactant, that breaks hydrocarbons down into
smaller particles. Only water and carbon dioxide are left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``They followed the directions and they got a clean Kalakala,''
Norem said.
</P>
<P>
   Bevis said the ``super bugs'' cleaned the bilges in two weeks,
dining on a nasty, oily buildup left after three decades of
sedentary life.
</P>
<P>
   How the new ``Kalakala'' strain developed remains a mystery. It
may have already been living in the boat before MET's superbugs
dropped by for lunch. Or it may be a mutated form of those bugs or
... OK, let's not get carried
</P>
<P>
   away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like all the other pseudonomas, a huge genus of
bacteria, small round rods under the microscope,'' said Harry
Colvin, a microbiologist from Bainbridge Island near Seattle
working for MET partners John Martin and Norem.
</P>
<P>
   Colvin is culturing the bacteria in various environments to see
if it is stronger than other oil-eating bacteria that can withstand
saltwater, cold and the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Colvin said naming the bacteria for the Kalakala is so far
``only anecdotal.'' It must go through an official process to
determine if it is a new genus before it gets named for the place
where it was found.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the process of characterizing it and the next step is
to see if the ones isolated from that particular sample can be
grown for product,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Norem said hydrocarbon-eating bacteria already exist naturally
in the soil and water. MET, which has acquired microbes from
locations as diverse as Texas and Alaska's North Slope, simply
enhances, cultivates and concentrates the microbes. The rod-shaped
bacteria are then put in a nutrient, to stay alive, and a
``surfactant,'' a chemical that breaks down hydrocarbons, Norem
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives them something to sink their teeth into,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bevis, meanwhile, said he is trying to work out a few bugs of
another kind to restore the old ferry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry to say there are still some past-due bills and
snafus from the previous administration that didn't keep track of
some bills,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bevis, however, said the Kalakala foundation he oversees expects
to raise enough money to get the boat into dry dock by the end of
the year, so its hull can be examined and repairs estimated.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation hopes to acquire a $285,000 federal grant by fall
through the Interstate Transportation Enhancement Act. It first
must raise $195,000 on its own for the feds to match, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's confident it will happen, considering the level of support
for the old boat that's still out there. Visitors and the
all-volunteer staff celebrate weekly potlucks every Wednesday
beside the ferry. The most recent one commemorated the anniversary
of the Kalakala's refloating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still need big bucks for dry dock, but things are better
than they were a year ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago the boat was stuck in the mud, though millions of
tiny laborers were quietly working in its bilges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
