<HEADER>
A0338 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN     06-26 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE MULLING POSSIBLE CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the past week manager Davey Johnson and
general manager Kevin Malone have met a few times regarding the
direction of the Los Angeles Dodgers, and what they can do to turn
around the team's fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he won't make a move just for the sake of doing so.
But if the Dodgers continue their downward journey, Malone said he
won't stand still and watch the season end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not panic. There's no need for that,'' Malone said. ``But
we're not close to the top right now, and if that's the case we
have to make changes or modifications. If we get the offense
untracked, we'll get going.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't (make a move) unless it's the right thing to do. But
we're in fourth place. How much further down do we have to be to do
something?''
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers don't have favorable conditions to make a
blockbuster deal, since most of their marquee players are locked
into multiyear deals.
</P>
<P>
   Also, with the cost-cutting, early-season trade of Dave Mlicki
constantly haunting them, the Dodgers don't figure to move one of
their starting pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Lineup lingo: Johnson continued his lineup tweaking by switching
Eric Karros to the cleanup spot and moving Raul Mondesi down a slot
to fifth. Johnson said he did it for a night because the slumping
Mondesi, who's homered once in his past 81 at-bats, entered the
night with a .150 career average against Giants starter Shawn
Estes.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi had struck out nine times in 20 at-bats against Estes.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also started Trenidad Hubbard in center field and batted
him second, giving Devon White his second straight day off. Johnson
said he'll probably rest Eric Karros today against right-hander
Chris Brock and start left-handed hitter Todd Hollandsworth at
first.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, Perez return: Todd Hundley caught the last two innings
in Thursday's loss to San Diego, but that wasn't planned. However,
his start today against the Giants was set. After spending 11 days
in Camp Dempsey, Hundley gets his first start.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 10 games, Hundley has worked on his throwing
mechanics and built arm strength by throwing balls to second and
third base under the guidance of bullpen coach Rick Dempsey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be foolish to say Todd's going to go in there and throw
better than (Angel) Pena,'' Dempsey said. ``He's been able to work
and do what he hasn't been able to do for a long time. It was good,
and we made improvements. He's going to have to keep working at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Perez (2-8, 7.38 ERA) returns for at least one more
start. He last pitched June 16, getting pulled after allowing four
runs in 31/3 innings. But Johnson's been pleased with Perez's side
work, much of which focused on long-tossing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been able to loosen his shoulder,'' Johnson said. ``He's
been throwing from left field to home. That's the way you used to
test starting pitchers. If you couldn't throw from the left field
wall to home plate, you wouldn't start.''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna update: When Antonio Osuna underwent elbow surgery in May,
the Dodgers hoped he would be back between the All-Star break and
Aug.1. Before the game at 3Com, Osuna threw his second bullpen
session, after which Johnson said the right-handed reliever could
be ready to begin a rehab stint late next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have three good sessions, and preferably four,''
Johnson said. ``He's going to throw again Sunday. We'll see how it
feels on Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna threw fastballs and change-ups in his first two workouts.
He's slated to throw breaking pitches in Sunday's session. Johnson
acknowledged if things went well, Osuna could begin a rehab
assignment late in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Giants manager Dusty Baker said
outfielder Ellis Burks (right knee inflammation) would be activated
from the disabled list today.... Dodgers right-hander Kevin Brown
entered the night leading the National League with a 2.92 ERA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
