<HEADER>
A0339 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT     06-26 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS WIN A WILD ONE OVER ORIOLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ When the Yankees and Orioles face off in Camden
Yards, they do not play baseball. Rather, they produce the missing
link of sport, infinite contests of artless wonder.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Orioles combined for 29 hits in 3 hours 32
minutes Friday night, and ultimately, the Yankees prevailed, 9-8,
after Shane Spencer led off the ninth inning with a 415-foot home
run off Baltimore's Mike Timlin. The Yankees have won four straight
games and are 43-28; the Orioles (32-40) have lost three straight.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees blew a 7-4 lead, mostly due to Harold Baines'
three-run home run in the seventh inning, his second home run of
the game. But Tino Martinez tied the score, 8-8, in the eighth with
his fourth hit of the game.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later Timlin fell behind Spencer, two balls and no
strikes, before throwing a thigh-high fastball that Spencer crushed
into the back of the Orioles' bullpen beyond the left-center-field
fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every time we play them in this ball park, it's
one of these types of games'' Yankee manager Joe Torre said. ``To
win a ball game like that, especially late, it's a huge lift for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he got the sense that Spencer was going to do
something notable in that at-bat. ``Especially 2-and-0, just the
way he was standing up there looking relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees ended the game with Joe Girardi catching because
Jorge Posada left the game during his seventh-inning at-bat with a
mild contusion of his left thumb. He incurred the injury while
swinging, but he later said that he believed he would be able to
start on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, four couches in the middle of the Yankee
clubhouse were turned inward, forming a square. Before batting
practice, about half of the Yankees joined in an impromptu
discussion about the 50 greatest athletes of the century.
</P>
<P>
   The debate went on and on, Derek Jeter, Scott Brosius, Bernie
Williams and others arguing. The sight of that many players engaged
in any activity in a clubhouse is extraordinarily rare, and
telling.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was in the midst of the prattle, grinning, a little
tanner after three days in the Tampa Bay area. Martinez is from
Tampa, and the Yankees' trip there seemed to do good for his
batting average and peace of mind: he was 6 for 13 against the
Devil Rays with a double, triple, two home runs and six runs batted
in, and the confidence carried over into tonight's unprepossessing
triumph over the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   To win in claustrophobic Camden Yards, Torre was saying before
Friday night's game, you must be able to throw two types of pitches
effectively, to prevent opposing hitters from anticipating a
fastball and pumping long fly balls into the seats. Hideki Irabu
started for the Yankees Friday night and had a less than mediocre
fastball, an uncontrollable curveball and a hanging splitter. And
Irabu was the better of the starting pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's Scott Erickson needed 25 pitches in the first inning
and 27 in the third, a trend that lasted as long as he was on the
mound. The Yankees picked and pounded on him; two runs in the first
inning, another in the third, one apiece in the fourth and in the
fifth. Through five innings, Chuck Knoblauch had two hits and a
walk and an RBI, Paul O'Neill had hit the ball hard a couple of
times, and Martinez had two hits and a walk.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees led, 5-3, after 4 1/2 innings, but then Charles
Johnson ripped a home run off Irabu in the Orioles' fifth and it
was 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees closed out Erickson in the sixth inning, adding
two more runs _ the second on a two-out double by Martinez, his
third hit. Strangely, Baltimore manager Ray Miller had chosen to
leave Erickson in the game, rather than replace him with the
left-hander Doug Johns; left-handed batters were hitting just .184
against Johns this year.
</P>
<P>
   Posada's passed ball cost the Yankees a run in the Orioles'
sixth, however, and in the seventh, the left-handed Mike Stanton
allowed back-to-back singles to B.J. Surhoff and Albert Belle. The
Yankees still led by two runs, and Baines had not hit a home run
against a left-hander this year; Stanton had not permitted a home
run to anyone in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Baines rocketed a three-run home run to
straightaway center field. As Baines circled the bases with his
367th career home run and his 1,531st RBI, Stanton circled behind
the mound, removed his cap and yelled in frustration.
</P>
</TEXT>
