<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0347 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-ART-     06-26 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS EDGE KNICKS, 78-77, FOR NBA CROWN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Latrell Sprewell was bent down, grabbing his shorts
in exhaustion after his last shot of the night fell short of the
rim, and the San Antonio Spurs celebrated an NBA championship with
a 78-77 Game 5 victory Friday night at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The indefatigable Sprewell was not going to run out on the
Knicks in the game of their lives. He had hurt his team with his
mindless play early in the game, but embodying the spirit of a team
that would not let a setback foil their enchanted ride through the
playoffs, Sprewell made up for his indiscretions with 35 points. He
was just two short of another miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, who missed nine of his first 12 shots and was a
liability on defense until early in the third quarter, finished the
game 13-of-27 shooting with 14 points in the fourth quarter. He was
the perfect frenetic counter for the Spurs' quiet superstar, Tim
Duncan, who finished with 31 points.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Duncan's Spurs were too tall, too deep and too
healthy as they prevailed in the series, four games to one, and
captured their first league title.
</P>
<P>
   With Allan Houston by his side, Sprewell helped erase an
11-point third-quarter deficit and put the Knicks ahead, 66-63,
with nine minutes left in the game on only his fourth 3-pointer of
the playoffs. The game went back and forth from there. Avery
Johnson gave the Spurs a 78-77 lead with 47.6 seconds left on a
jumper from the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell missed a wild jumper with 27 second left. After a shot
by David Robinson did not hit the rim, he got his own rebound and
fired the ball to Johnson, who missed a 3-pointer as the clock
wound down. Sprewell had a chance to win it, but his fall-away
jumper at the buzzer fell way short.
</P>
<P>
   About three hours before the game, league officials were
choreographing the championship trophy ceremony, preparing
themselves for the Spurs' eventual victory. In the background,
coach Jeff Van Gundy leaned against a railing and watched.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks did not want the Spurs to celebrate on their court.
But they were not playing this just to save face; they were out
there to win. And then, well, you never know.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks looked to take fate in their own hands by doing the
little things to start the game. They were all over the Spurs'
pick-and-roll, disrupting the passing lanes that had been open in
Game 4. They were also driving the ball into the lane and not
flinching at the sight of Robinson and Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   That effort gave the Knicks a rousing 30-22 lead with eight
minutes left in the second quarter after a wild, driving layup by
Houston. The fans were up, the Knicks were high on their lead. But
the Spurs remained patient and methodical and seized the
opportunity when the Knicks suffered a series of mental lapses
before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sprewell energized the crowd with a flashy steal and a
vicious fast-break dunk with 1:36 left in the first half, he turned
right around and left Jaren Jackson open for a 3-pointer in the
closing seconds. Jackson's shot ended a 16-6 run that left the
Spurs ahead, 40-38, at the break. In the final seven minutes of the
half, the Knicks turned the ball over three times and helplessly
watched Duncan score six of his 16 first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks countered with Houston's scoring 10 points. Sprewell
was 3 for 11 from the field and was 4 for 6 from the free-throw to
add an inefficient 10 points. While disappointed by the finish to
the half, the Knicks were within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   They had to pay attention, though. The Spurs were experts at
turning up their game at the start of the third quarter. In Game 4,
they opened with a 9-0 run. Friday night, they started the third on
a 7-0 run as the Knicks turned the ball over three times and missed
their first four shots coming out of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes into the third quarter, the Spurs were ahead,
47-38. A livid Van Gundy, especially irritated at Sprewell's
defense, called a timeout and imparted a few harsh words. Whatever
he said, the Knicks got their act together. With the help of a
driving layup by Houston, followed by a jumper from him, the Knicks
pulled within four, 47-43. That led coach Gregg Popovich to call a
timeout with 7:14 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help. Sprewell began making amends for his rough
start. Charlie Ward stripped Johnson on a drive, then sent a pass
to Sprewell, who went up and over Jackson for an emphatic
two-handed dunk that drew a foul. After that 3-point play, he hit a
jumper to put the Knicks ahead, 48-47, with five minutes left in
the third.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dramatic turnaround led by the Knicks' most flamboyant
player. After hitting just three of his first 12 shots, he came
back with three scores in a row. The Knicks were ahead, 52-50, with
3:28 remaining in the third. Suddenly, the shot clock on the Spurs'
side of the court went out, and there was a delay of several
minutes while a portable clock was brought in and placed in the
left corner of the court.
</P>
<P>
   The play stoppage went on as Popovich argued that both teams
should have the same shot-clock position to create the same playing
conditions. He won his argument, and a clock was positioned at the
Knicks' end. But what would this cooling-off period do to the
Knicks' momentum?
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help. Duncan took over. He touched the ball every time
down the floor and either scored or drew a foul. In a compact
flurry, Duncan scored nine points in the last two minutes to give
the Spurs a 59-58 lead after the third.
</P>
<P>
   The night began well enough for the Knicks. Despite a miserable
series created by an injured knee and wounded pride from being
dominated by Duncan, Johnson worked inside the paint for a couple
of early layups to help get the Knicks off to a good start.
</P>
<P>
   And Houston was stopping at nothing. He was nailing the baseline
jumper, and he even slapped the floor in an uncommon display of
emotion when he leaned in and drew contact at the buzzer of the
first quarter. No foul was called, and Houston put his right hand
into the hardwood with the Knicks ahead, 23-20.
</P>
<P>
   The emotion was there, just as it has been for the Knicks the
entire finals. But the Knicks were also playing smart at this
point. They were taking away the lob passes to Robinson and Duncan,
holding off Johnson's penetration and keeping up on the boards.
They were giving themselves a chance to put the ball in Houston's
hands, and he gave them a 30-22 lead midway through the second
quarter on a twisting, driving layup.
</P>
<P>
   Houston then popped a nine-foot jumper that left the Knicks
ahead, 32-24, with 6:23 left in the second quarter. But then their
emotion got the best of them. After stripping a steal, Houston flew
out on a fast break and sent an alley-oop pass to Sprewell from 20
feet away. It was too much, and too high. Sprewell couldn't gather
it and a chance was blown with the Spurs down, 34-28, with four
minutes left in the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
