<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WITH A DRAMATIC FLAIR, BRING GRUNFELD BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Time To Say Goodbye.'' That's the song they played
in the Garden when the befuddled Rik Smits lumbered to the bench
with his sixth personal foul in the last game of the Indiana
series. (Surely you remember the Indiana series. Your short-term
memory can't be that shot.)
</P>
<P>
   It was a cute touch. The addled Dutchman trudging off the court,
with Andrea Bocelli serenading him in English, long distance, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time to Say Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what would transpire late in the network's prime-time
night, the men's basketball season was officially over in the land
of the knish and the calzone.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were unable to escape the coup de grace Friday night
in Seventh Avenue's Most Famous Arena, losing 78-77 to the Spurs,
who did not need to return to San Antonio to deliver the final
chop.
</P>
<P>
   So it was time to croon sweet nothings at Larry Johnson and the
rest of the Knicks. The next players on the court, the New York
Liberty, will not cuss anybody out the way L.J. did to a league
official the other day.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty on the court. Joy Fawcett and Carla Overbeck, the
soccer moms, in the World Cup. Steffi and Venus and Alexandra at
Wimbledon. The summer of the women. Not a moment too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time to Say Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Time for the fans to finally get some fresh air. Time for
everybody's minds and ears to recuperate from the witless blare of
the Garden sound system. The Knicks closed up shop at their home
court with the same swirl of confusion that has plagued the
organization since the lockout ended. Somehow this dysfunctional
group became the first eighth-seeded team to reach the NBA finals,
a fitting epitaph for this short, strange season.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, they must move forward. On Thursday, Jeff Van Gundy
said that he had been assured by Dave Checketts that the coaching
job was his for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's conciliatory tone made it seem fairly sure that he
was not going to put on his Johnny Paycheck tape and tell Checketts
just what he could do with the job, which would have been
interesting. As a result, the Nets have done the belated right
thing by hiring Don Casey, a basketball lifer, who restored calm in
the smoldering ashes of John Calipari's flameout.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Knicks are going to have to find a general manager. They
haven't had one since April, when Checketts took Grunfeld to dinner
and started to sing, ``Time to Say Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are going to need somebody to make trades, sign
players to long contracts, unless Checketts _ a basketball man,
essentially _ is going to revert to that role.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night would have really been the ideal time to do it. The
lights could have dimmed and an announcement could have been made
introducing the next general manager of the Knicks, and to the boom
of the sound system and the flash of the lights, out could have
come _ tah-dah! _ Ernie Grunfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? George Steinbrenner did it with Billy Martin. Fired
him, then trotted him out on Old-Timers' Day and introduced him as
the next Yankee manager. Totally nuts. Totally George.
</P>
<P>
   You could argue that Checketts is not Steinbrenner, and Grunfeld
is not Martin, and be correct on both counts. But, as Checketts
suggested when he hired Latrell Sprewell, where is it written that
a man cannot have a second chance? It was Grunfeld, after all, who
shipped Good Old John to Golden State for Sprewell. It was
Grunfeld, after all, who shipped Good Old Oak to Toronto for Marcus
Camby. So it took a little longer for the team to jell than the new
Garden owners wanted to wait. Tough.
</P>
<P>
   With Checketts' collaboration, Grunfeld had the wisdom to see
the need for new energy, in Sprewell and in Camby. When Checketts
was scuttling Ernie, he was also criticizing his own judgment. (He
didn't quite put it that way, of course.)
</P>
<P>
   All it would take is a dollop of flexibility. I don't recall
Steinbrenner's saying he was wrong in firing Martin. That was just
what George did on any particular day. He fired Billy. No big deal.
Admittedly, it got a little old, five Billy regimes. But what would
be the harm in a second chance for Grunfeld?
</P>
<P>
   Checketts would not have to apologize. Goodness, no. He would
just say this was the best thing for the organization at this time.
Your normal exec-speak. Then management could summon Van Gundy and
Grunfeld behind closed doors and bang their hard heads together,
and tell them to make nice this time.
</P>
<P>
   It's good enough for the merry king of the Bronx. It could be
good enough for the slick suits of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, no more foul tirades in the Garden. Not for
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time to Say Goodbye.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
