<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-TITLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS WIN NBA TITLE ON JOHNSON'S JUMP SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Finally, San Antonio has a reason to forget the
Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   Powered by Tim Duncan's 31 points and Avery Johnson's crucial
15-foot jumper in the final minute, the Spurs ended a 26-year wait
by clinching their first NBA championship with a thrilling 78-77
victory over the New York Knicks last night at Madison Square
Garden. The Spurs, who rose from the ashes of the old ABA Dallas
Chaparrals in 1973, won the NBA Finals, 4-1, and plan a fiesta on
the Riverwalk tomorrow afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me this is a journey that goes to show hard work and
persistence pays off,'' said center David Robinson, the backbone of
the franchise since 1989. ``It's a dream that I've been waiting to
come true for a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, who averaged 27 points and 14 rebounds in the series,
nailed down the Finals MVP by winning a memorable individual
shootout with New York's Latrell Sprewell (35 points).
</P>
<P>
   As they did throughout their dominant season the Spurs won with
defense, holding the Knicks without a point in the final 3:12.
</P>
<P>
   They took a 78-77 lead on Johnson's 15-foot baseline jumper with
47 seconds remaining. Sprewell then got the ball on the right wing,
but was forced into a rare miss on an 18-foot jumper when Duncan
double-teamed.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson then spun into the lane, but his shot failed to hit the
rim. The rebound was tapped to Johnson, who beat the shot clock
with a long heave that hit the rim, but New York's Larry Johnson
got the rebound in the corner with only 2.1 seconds remaining in
the game. The Knicks inbounded to Sprewell in the lane under the
basket, but he was trapped by Duncan and Sean Elliott and his
high-arching 15-footer over Duncan and Robinson came after the
buzzer and failed to hit the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get layup but I got too far under the basket and
they trapped me with those long arms,'' said Sprewell, who kept the
big-hearted, small-bodied Knicks in the game by hitting 13 of 27
shots. ``We didn't want them to celebrate on our court but they
deserved it. They are the best team.''
</P>
<P>
   Without raising their voice, raising the roof or even raising
interest in the NBA Finals, the Spurs can finally raise a
championship banner. By doing a Texas two-step in the heart of the
Big Apple, the bigger, better Spurs capped a season in which they
won 46 of their last 53 games and cruised to a 15-2 record in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible feeling,'' said Duncan, who pulled out a
video camera to record the celebration before the trophy
presentation. ``These guys just hung together all season and
tonight was no different. We won games like this all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan and Sprewell staged one of the more memorable one-on-one
shows in Finals history.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the fourth quarter, Duncan scored 15 of 16 Spurs
points and Sprewell scored 14 in a row for the Knicks. With
seemingly boundless energy, Sprewell got San Antonio's defense on
its heels with a couple of drives and then hit a variety of
jumpers, including a pull-up 3-pointer gave the Knicks a 66-63
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan answered Sprewell's free throws with one of his own to
pull the Spurs within 77-76 as the clock slipped under two minutes.
After a double-team on Sprewell forced a shot-clock violation,
Robinson missed a short left-handed hook as he was bumped without a
call. On New York's next possession, Larry Johnson clanged a long
3-pointer off the back rim to set up Johnson's baseline jumper.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio survived a shot-clock malfunction and an amazing
11-point performance by Sprewell to take a 59-58 lead into the
fourth quarter. With their shot clock having gone out and a
replacement fixated awkwardly in the corner on the floor instead of
on top of the backboard, the Spurs seemed un-nerved as the Knicks
rallied from a nine-point deficit to take a 54-50 lead. Duncan,
however, calmly responded by scoring the Spurs' last nine points on
two bank-shots, two free throws and a three-point play in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs tried to knock out the Knicks early in the third,
scoring the first seven points of the second half to continue a
13-0 run. While the Knicks didn't score on their first eight
possessions, Jackson filled in for an ineffective Elliott with a
fast-break layup and 25-foot 3-pointer that pushed San Antonio's
lead to 47-38.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, however, responded with a 10-0 sparked by the speed
and transition aggressiveness of Sprewell, who hit two jumpers and
brought the Garden to its feet with a three-point play dunk over
Jaren Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks led the entire first half until Jackson's left-wing
3-pointer with six seconds remaining allowed the Spurs to take a
40-38 lead into the locker room.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
