<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA SITS, BUT METS STILL OVERWHELM ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The question was inevitable and Bobby Valentine knew
it was coming. Is this, the New York Mets' manager was asked hours
before Friday night's game with first-place Atlanta, the first
meeting between the division rivals this season, a big series?
</P>
<P>
   Valentine was ready with his pat answer. ``It's the one we're
playing,'' he said after a pause. By game's end, the pause had to
come from Atlanta, which suffered a 10-2 loss to New York and saw
its lead in the National League East trimmed to two games.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine did allow that the weekend series had some meaning, if
only to give the Mets an opportunity to see what they would be up
against the rest of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know who the Braves are,'' Valentine said. ``Now, we're
going to play them and find out what they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Just who are the Braves, Valentine was asked?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the team in front of us,'' Valentine said.
``Perennial. Forever. And we get to see how we match up against
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the Mets matched up just fine, even if they had to
do so without their best player, Mike Piazza, who is still bothered
by a stiff neck.
</P>
<P>
   With Todd Pratt behind the plate in Piazza's place, Rick Reed
(6-3) turned in perhaps his strongest outing of the season,
limiting the Braves to one run on six hits in 6 1/3 solid innings.
Benny Agbayani, who has been playing the last two weeks with a
hyperextended left elbow that nearly kept him out of the lineup
Friday, homered to open the scoring. Reed helped his own cause with
a run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets won for the 15th time in 18 games and for the first
time in Atlanta since July 13, 1997, a span of nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Since halting their eight-game losing streak on June 6, the Mets
have gained four games on the Braves in the standing. Friday
night's victory was New York's fifth straight and ninth in the last
10 games. They have played 10 straight games without an error, a
club record. And Piazza is expected back for Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza awoke this morning and needed to turn his body in order
to turn his head. The symptoms from the mild concussion he suffered
Wednesday night had abated, Piazza said. But his stiff neck had
not.
</P>
<P>
   So Valentine decided he would keep Piazza out of the starting
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a short in the electrical system, a bank of lights at
Turner Field was blacked out for at least two hours before the game
while electricians worked on resolving the problem. The game began
45 minutes late before a sellout crowd of 48,292. And it began with
Piazza on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just stiff,'' Piazza said of his neck. ``But Bobby
totally made the call to have me rest it another day.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said one of the things that influenced his decision
was Piazza's inability to look up. ``It seems like you'd have to do
that if you catch,'' Valentine said, adding that he did not want
Piazza to do anything to aggravate the injury and keep him out of
the lineup longer.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about having to take on the Braves without his best
player, Valentine pointed out that Atlanta was without its
first-string catcher, too. Javy Lopez is on the disabled list with
a sprained right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez is no Piazza. But, as it turned out, the Mets got by
without Piazza's bat.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Atlanta's rookie left-hander, Odalis Perez, did not
make the Mets' hitters look bad at times. Perez struck out a
career-high nine in 51/3 innings, but the 21-year-old left
trailing, 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani opened the scoring when he led off the second inning
with a home run, the rookie outfielder's 11th this season in just
94 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, meanwhile, was mowing down the Braves. And when the Mets
parlayed five singles and two walks into three sixth-inning runs,
Reed had a 4-0 cushion. Reed even drove in the final run of the
inning with a line single to center.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves answered with a two-out run, when Jones walked, stole
second and scored on Randall Simon's single. But Eddie Perez,
Lopez's replacement, flew out to deep center to end the threat.
And, after the Mets added a run on Roger Cedeno's sacrifice fly in
the seventh, it was a 5-1 game and the National League East race
was getting as tight as Piazza's neck.
</P>
</TEXT>
