<HEADLINE>
ELDER STATESMAN PINCAY RIDES AWAY WITH JOCKEY TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEIDI PEDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Laffit Pincay may be in the twilight of
his riding career, but the 52-year-old proved he still has what it
takes to compete with the best.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay, the oldest rider competing, won the first race and
placed in two others last night to win the 1999 NTRA All-Star
Jockey Championship at Lone Star Park with 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   With his victory in the first race, he moved one victory closer
to Bill Shoemaker's record of 8,833. Pincay now has 8,757, second
behind Shoemaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really good about the whole thing. I'm very
emotional,'' said Pincay, who won with guest of honor Shoemaker
watching. ``I proved I can still ride with young riders and still
win races.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't unusual pressure for Pincay, who races almost every
day on the tough Southern California circuit. After three races
yesterday he had a three-point edge over Pat Day and defending
event champion Shane Sellers, who also had victories. It was
Pincay's third-place finish in the last race of the evening that
clinched the title and the $18,000 first prize.
</P>
<P>
   Youth also made a showing.
</P>
<P>
   Corey Lanerie, Lone Star Park's leading jockey this season _ and
at 24 the youngest rider in the All-Star field _ finished second
with 13 points. Kent Desormeaux, 29, was third with 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole competition was great,'' Lanerie said. ``I'm proud
to finish so well. I hope this could be my springboard for my
career. I know it can only help.''
</P>
<P>
   The third annual event showcases some of the country's best
riders, selected by a national panel of experts. Pincay was one of
four Hall of Famers present, along with Chris McCarron, Jerry
Bailey, and Day. Others competing were Alex Solis, Robby Albarado,
1999 Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner Chris Antley, Edgar Prado
and Eddie Martin Jr.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, Pincay has grown accustomed to riding
long shots, and he proved a bit of a long shot himself yesterday in
the All-Star wager, where fans bet on the jockeys instead of the
horses. Pincay paid $20.40 for a $2 bet, while the trifecta of
Pincay, Lanerie and Desormeaux paid a whopping $5,433.00, and the
exacta of Pincay-Lanerie $467.20.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay got off to a strong start, winning the first race by
taking advantage of another's misfortune. Solis fell off
second-favorite Daggett Peak after being bumped by Bailey's horse
out of the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Without a jockey, Daggett Peak ran near the front of the pack,
and Pincay, on Gold Nugget, followed the horse, then moved inside
of him on the far side to take the lead. Solis walked away from the
incident with a sore neck and rode in the remaining races.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay placed fourth in the third race, leaving the contest to
be decided in the fourth. His horse, Brave Pancho, made a late
inside bid to take the show spot, behind mounts ridden by
Desormeaux and Lanerie.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last race I was riding for my life to try to win the
championship,'' Pincay said. ``When we hit the wire, I was
desperate to know who was second. I knew Kent won the race, so I
was hoping whoever got second wasn't a guy close to me.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
