<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-SPREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL `IN THE ZONE' FOR A GAME OF A LIFETIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His head was rocking to and fro, his corn-rowed
braids flopping behind like a spoiler on a souped-up racer.
Ten-footer. Good. Three-pointer from the top of the arc. All net.
The building began to percolate with noise and adrenaline with each
made shot, and now even scaling San Antonio's mountain of 7-footers
seemed possible.
</P>
<P>
   In only the most important game of his life, Latrell Sprewell
was feeling it, that sensation you get on a basketball court when
you cannot miss from anywhere on the floor and it just does not
matter who is guarding you.
</P>
<P>
   In playground vernacular, this is called the zone, a dimension
far away from the elbows and forearms on the floor, a kind of
hermetically sealed booth with only two things inside: you and the
rim.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five points on 13-of-26 shooting. That the Knicks could
not take this contentious series back to San Antonio, that he
missed the last shot of the game with time running out and the
Knicks trailing by a point, almost did not seem to matter.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled his jersey off and walked back to the sideline in
disbelief as his teammates tried to console. Moments later, as the
Spurs celebrated their series-clinching 78-77 victory, the Madison
Square Garden crowd broke in to applause as the Knicks gathered at
midcourt for their post-game prayer. Sprewell took a few moments to
compose himself and join the gathering before doing his last
television interview of the season. He was more sympathetic in
defeat than he had ever been while leading the Knicks on their run
to the finals.
</P>
<P>
   With their season on the line, the Knicks turned to the most
unlikely hero in the post-Michael Jordan era, the player described
18 months ago as a selfish loner and a franchise killer, and he
somehow willed this team back into a game they looked out of early
in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he nearly won a shootout against the best player in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   It was early in the fourth quarter, and the Knicks were doing
everything imaginable to defend Tim Duncan. But he kept making
these impossible shots, off the backboard, straight on.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks needed someone to duke it out with Duncan, someone to
trade baskets and act like an All-Star _ even if Sprewell had not
been one for three seasons, even if he sat out all of last season
because he committed the most egregious act of disrespect for
authority in the league, choking his coach, an act for which he
will always be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   With 3 minutes 58 seconds left, though, he gave everyone
something else to remember. Rocking forward and stepping back for
that pretty jumper. Swish. Then he drew a foul on the other end of
the floor, after Mario Elie had delivered a 3-point dagger.
</P>
<P>
   For about 30 minutes Friday night, Sprewell transported himself
and he transported his team. Midway through the third quarter, the
Spurs and Knicks went back and forth like two kids trading blows in
a pillow fight _ with Sprewell and Duncan winding up and swinging
for the head.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was tearing down the court on the break, dunking on
Jaren Jackson and drawing a foul with less than five minutes left
to push New York in front.
</P>
<P>
   Elie, with all of the Garden screaming for him to miss, buried a
3-pointer a few steps in front of Spike Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sprewell again, dropping in two jumpers from the perimeter,
clutching his fist, scowling, feeling the rush of the crowd exhort
him on.
</P>
<P>
   On it went, the Game 5 pendulum swinging to and fro with each
huge basket.
</P>
<P>
   After a lengthy delay to install a new shot clock, Duncan
responded by softly banking shots off the glass, drawing fouls and
going to the line.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when it ended, Sprewell had hit hardest. His 11-point binge
in the quarter made San Antonio woozy heading into the fourth. The
9-point bulge the Spurs had built after halftime had shrunk to one,
and it was now a matter of pride and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell summoned both, filling it up from everywhere on the
floor. As the fourth quarter began, he dribbled twice and stepped
back on the left wing, launching a perfect swish. And the foul!
</P>
<P>
   The Garden went ballistic, hollering for this imperfect player
who in so many ways was playing the perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell played as well as I have seen anyone play in the
post-season the last five years _ a performance worthy of Jordan's
approval rating.
</P>
<P>
   After having been out of the NBA for more than a season,
Sprewell wanted the ball at the end of Game 5 of the finals.
Whether it was in vain or not, he earned a right to be considered
part of this franchise for some time to come.
</P>
<P>
   That's what getting in the zone can do for you, take you to not
only places you've never been before but also keep you there for a
while.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
