<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FILLING SCHOOL GAPS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that Chancellor Rudy Crew has removed so many administrators
from New York City's worst schools, he faces the far more difficult
task of replacing them. Finding good candidates to do these
thankless jobs will not be easy, which is why he has hired a
headhunting firm from Washington state to scout for replacements.
But the chancellor and his vocal critic, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
will now have to address the underlying problem _ the educator
brain drain, particularly to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Each year the city loses some of its best educators to softer
and better-paying jobs elsewhere, while the pool of replacements,
especially administrators, grows steadily smaller. There were only
about a dozen applicants for the top job at Manhattan's elite
Stuyvesant High School. At less prestigious schools, the number of
applicants can be as small as three or four. A major reason is that
the principals' union and the city have been bogged down in
contract negotiations for more than three years, despite a city
proposal that salaries would go up almost 30 percent if principals
gave up tenure. Educators who gamble on these high-wire managerial
positions do not need tenure, but they deserve a hefty salary
boost. If the union continues to balk, the state Legislature should
break this stalemate, ending principals' tenure with a law.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers, whose contract will expire next year, are also
increasingly hard to find. The rate of new teachers leaving after a
few years is almost twice what it is in other big cities. Moreover,
the city's classrooms are increasingly run by uncertified teachers
as many of the best educators are set to retire over the next four
to five years.
</P>
<P>
   With their annual pay at midcareer a dismal $41,000 a year in
comparison with almost $60,000 in richer suburbs, city teachers
still received some promising news this week. Crew and Randi
Weingarten, president of the United Federation of Teachers,
negotiated a package for extra pay and benefits to certified
teachers willing to tackle jobs in failing schools. This city-union
partnership, as well as Ms. Weingarten's willingness to be flexible
for this experiment, bodes well for these needy schools. The good
will generated by this agreement also raises hopes that teachers'
salaries will be substantially raised next year, at least enough to
keep the best from fleeing the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
