 EDITORIAL: THE SUPREME COURT TIGHTENS THE NOOSE  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The uproar over the Supreme Court's end-of-term decisions
reinforcing its preference for states' rights obscured another
distressing trend _ the court's increasing willingness to overlook
unfair procedures in death penalty cases. In two miserable
decisions shortly before it recessed, the court was so eager to
speed executions that it ignored serious flaws in trial and
sentencing proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   By a 7-2 margin, the court upheld a Virginia man's death
sentence despite the prosecution's suppression of important
evidence that the defense might have used to discredit the key
eyewitness. Writing for the majority, Justice John Paul Stevens
conceded that the outcome ``might have changed'' had the documents
been disclosed in a timely way to the defense. But that still fell
short, he said, of ``reasonable probability that the result of the
trial would have been different.'' That cavalier conclusion
provoked a scathing response from the two dissenters, Justices
David Souter and Anthony Kennedy. They noted that the death
sentence might well have been averted had just one juror harbored
doubts about the eyewitness' account.
</P>
<P>
   By a narrower, 5-4 margin, the court upheld the death sentence
of a Texas killer despite the trial judge's failure to give
complete instructions to the jury as to the options available to it
in case it deadlocked over the death penalty. One option was a life
sentence without parole. Because it was unaware of this
alternative, the defendant's lawyer argued, the jury felt its only
course was to impose the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas case marked the first application of the Federal Death
Penalty Act of 1994, which extended capital punishment to more than
40 federal crimes. Given the majority's casual approach to due
process, the case also marked another low moment for the nation's
highest court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
