</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS EDGE KNICKS, 78-77, FOR NBA CROWN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: CHANGES throughout)  (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Knicks' magic carpet fell to earth with a
disheartening thud Friday night when a potential game-winning shot
by the indefatigable Latrell Sprewell fell to the floor as time ran
out on Game 5 _ and their miracles expired.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, the San Antonio Spurs lifted their arms in
celebration at Madison Square Garden over their 78-77 victory and
danced on the Knicks' floor. Taller, deeper, healthier and, in the
end, just better than the Knicks, they had captured their first
National Basketball Association championship by winning the final
series, four games to one.
</P>
<P>
   Only when it was over, as the Spurs' shouts cut through the
sudden silence, did Sprewell grab his shorts and give in to
exhaustion. Only then did the Knicks give in to the ominous
elements that were against them in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   As the undermanned and physically drained Knicks filtered off
the floor, a chant grew for the home team in a crescendo from the
crowd while the Green Day song, ``Time of Your Life,'' played over
the speakers. It was quite a time.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a finish to an improbable and enchanting playoff
run for the Knicks. It ended with Sprewell scoring 35 points in an
effort to match the Spurs' superstar, Tim Duncan, who delivered 31
and was named the series' most valuable player. Smiling a wide
smile, Duncan held the trophy aloft with his fellow 7-footer, David
Robinson, a maligned superstar in seasons past who finally earned
validation for his career with a title.
</P>
<P>
   It came at the expense of a game Knicks team, especially
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all for nothing,'' said a dejected Sprewell, who finished
the game with 14 points in the fourth quarter and a 13-for-27
overall shooting effort after beginning the night 3 for 12. ``I
would rather have those last two points and have the victory. It's
disappointing once you know it's finally over, and the shot didn't
go in. The crowd was great. They've been great like that all year
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reason why I want to be here next year. It
was frustrating not to win it. Tim played well. He was on, and I
was on. It was back and forth, and no one wanted to lose. And I
think it showed. They deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   They earned it in the end. It wasn't just the 7-foot Duncan, but
also the pint-sized Avery Johnson who did the Knicks in. Johnson
gave the Spurs the 78-77 lead with an 18-foot jumper from the left
baseline with 1 minute 6 seconds remaining. The Knicks had their
chances, but Sprewell, who had hit five shots in a row, missed a
15-foot jumper. And then, with 2.1 seconds left in the game, the
Knicks set up for one last play.
</P>
<P>
   A lob by Charlie Ward went into the paint to Sprewell, who was
pinned too far under the basket by Sean Elliott and had to dribble
out into the open. He spun and fell away on a release from 6 feet
that came with one-tenth of a second on the clock. It would have
counted, but it fell a foot short of the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't score when we needed to down the stretch,'' coach
Jeff Van Gundy said. ``They're a great team. They really are.
</P>
<P>
   ``As disappointed as I am in the result for our guys because I
really was hopeful for them that it would work out. They stand for,
to me, a lot of things that should be taught about the NBA and team
basketball. When it was tough going, they didn't point fingers of
blame at each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The ending won't take away the magic of the journey the Knicks
took to make history as the only eighth seed ever to advance to the
finals. Two months ago, the Knicks were 21-21 and one nudge from
collapse. Van Gundy was nearly fired, the players were divided by
personal agendas and winning seemed less of a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the Knicks healed and pulled off an amazing run with
miracle shots sprinkled along the path like bread crumbs in a fairy
tale. There was Allan Houston's last-second runner that bounded off
the rim and fell into a net to save the Knicks from elimination in
the first round. And the star-aligned 4-point play by Larry Johnson
to save the Knicks from defeat in Game 3 of the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   There was a glass ceiling on their success, though. They
couldn't see it, but it was there in the form of Robinson and
Duncan. The two 7-footer were like wrecking balls to the Knicks'
dream. They dominated this series and combined for 21 rebounds and
46 points Friday night. They also led their team to the free-throw
line 17 of their 25 times. The Knicks went to the line just 16
times on the night.
</P>
<P>
   `'Size was the ultimate difference,'' Sprewell said. `'They made
it hard for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was ever easy for the Knicks this season. Everything
they went through was made harder once Patrick Ewing went down
after Game 2 of their Eastern Conference final against Indiana. He
had told the team to `'get me my ring.'' But the Knicks were one
7-footer short against San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was painful to watch,'' Ewing said, dressed in a suit for
the game. ``It was painful to see them celebrate on our floor, but
I was proud of this team. I remember all of the feelings from '94
when we lose and they all came back to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has been given an assurance by Checketts that he will
return. Checketts, sticking to his policy of not giving a
definitive answer publicly until he meets with the players and
coach this week, but he said, ``I'm certain things will work itself
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy when looking at the season as a whole said: ``I am
very proud of them, everything they accomplished. Hopefully when
the pain of this loss wears off they'll look back at the last two
and three months of the season and be very, very proud of not only
what they accomplished but how they went about accomplishing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks looked to take fate in their own hands by doing the
little things to start the game. They were all over the Spurs'
pick-and-roll, disrupting the passing lanes that had been open in
Game 4. They were also driving into the lane and not flinching at
the sight of Robinson and Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   That effort gave the Knicks a rousing 30-22 lead with eight
minutes left in the second quarter after a wild, driving layup by
Houston. The fans were up, the Knicks were high on their lead. But
the Spurs remained patient and methodical and seized the
opportunity when the Knicks suffered a series of mental lapses
before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sprewell energized the crowd with a flashy steal and a
vicious fast-break dunk with 1:36 left in the first half, he turned
right around and left Jaren Jackson open for a 3-pointer in the
closing seconds. Jackson's shot ended a 16-6 run that left the
Spurs ahead, 40-38, at the break. In the final seven minutes of the
half, the Knicks turned the ball over three times and helplessly
watched Duncan score six of his 16 first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   While disappointed by the finish to the half, the Knicks were
within striking distance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
