<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHING HELP MAY COME FROM WITHIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It may be a month before the Mariners can find
solutions to their bullpen problems through a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many teams that have to decide if they're in or
out of it, and it's too early to make that call,'' said vice
president for baseball administration Lee Pelekoudas. ``Some teams
have already established that they're out of it, but if they've got
quality, the longer they hang on to it, the better leverage they
have. No one's in a hurry to move pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's anyone's guess where the M's themselves will be
at the July 31 trading deadline. Much of it hinges, as usual, on
their relief, which has been suspect _ as usual.
</P>
<P>
   If the immediate answer to the Mariners' bullpen woes has to
come from within, they would seem to have several options.
</P>
<P>
   Their lone left-handed reliever is Allen Watson, who has
struggled since his trade from the New York Mets last week. But
there are three 24-year-old left-handed relievers t Class AAA
Tacoma, and each has had some success. If no trades are
forthcoming, one of those pitchers may be back in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to be prepared for that in case we don't seek
the alternative,'' said farm director Benny Looper. ``We're always
looking to find guys from our system to fill the need. The one
thing that we can't give them in triple-A is big-league experience,
but we're trying to prepare for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The three are Damaso Marte, Sean Spencer and Jordan Zimmerman,
the latter two having pitched briefly for the Mariners this season.
Spencer worked two games in May, allowing three earned runs in 12/3
innings. Zimmerman was sent down last weekend with a 6.75 ERA in 10
games.
</P>
<P>
   Marte has been developed as a starter, but the M's recently
converted him to relief, a role believed to suit him best. Marte
has had some good games but mainly has been inconsistent, with a
4.85 ERA and 30 walks, the most on the Rainiers. ``Right now, he's
walked too many to survive up here,'' Looper said.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer has been working on a two-seam fastball that can sink
away from right-handed hitters, which Mariners manager Lou Piniella
suggested he develop after sending him down May 10. The UW product
has a 2.67 ERA in 23 games and, Looper said, is showing signs of
re-gaining the arm strength he had last season.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, who was promoted to the M's from Class AA New Haven,
is getting his first Class AAA experience. He has thrown two
scoreless innings in two games, and Looper said he has increased
his velocity.
</P>
<P>
   Among starting pitchers, Brett Hinchliffe has made strides in
both velocity and location after struggling when he was sent down
in May. And 20-year-old Gil Meche (2-2, 3.38) continues to impress.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariners figure to be extra careful when considering
whether to promote Meche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want us to make the correct call on when is the time to
bring him up,'' Looper said. ``It could impact his career either
way.''
</P>
<P>
   PROJECT OVER: One prospect who won't be helping is Brien Taylor,
the former No. 1 overall pick who signed with Seattle this winter.
The Mariners thought they could help the left-hander turn around
his fractured career, but the club recently released him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His aptitude was just not very good,'' Looper said. ``We
hadn't been able to make enough progress to continue the
experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was headed for stardom after the New York Yankees drafted
him in 1991. But since ruining his shoulder in an off-season fight
in 1993, the 27-year-old has been buried in the low minors.
</P>
<P>
   He had too much experience to play at the Mariners' lowest
minor-league team, rookie-level Peoria, which is limited to players
with no more than two years in pro ball. When the Mariners
determined he was not ready for A-ball, they released him.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners tried to make Taylor into a relief specialist, and
worked on a sidearm delivery. But it never took.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put the ball in his hand, he never could do it,''
Looper said. ``He had a hard time picking up any adjustments. We
stayed with him a couple of months, but saw very little, if any,
improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL REPORT: Center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. spent yesterday's
pre-game resting on a table in the trainer's room. He did not dress
or participate in batting practice, but was on the lineup posted in
the Texas Rangers' clubhouse. Griffey, who left Thursday's game
with dizziness and a bad cold, did not start for just the second
time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Butch Henry is sticking to his goal of returning from a
torn labrum by August. Henry has been working out twice a day and
hopes to be given clearance to start throwing on Tuesday. ``That's
all tentative, but it can't come soon enough for me,'' Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Eric Weaver, who had surgery to remove bone chips from
his right elbow last month, threw for the third time yesterday and
is hoping to begin pitching for Tacoma by the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE HORN: By winning two of three games in Seattle this
week, the Angels finished with 78 all-time wins at the Kingdome,
the most of any visiting team. That's also more than the Mariners
have against any single opponent; Seattle's best mark in the Dome
is 75-61 against the Minnesota Twins. ... When the Mariners lost
three games earlier this month despite scoring 11 runs, they became
the first team to do that since at least 1951, according to STATS
Inc. ... The Mariners Wives are selling a set of all-occasion
greeting cards, featuring baseball artwork by children attending
The Hutch School. Proceeds from the cards, which are available by
calling 1-800-MY-MARINERS, will benefit the Fred Hutchinson Cancer
Research Center's Pediatric Oncology Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
