<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITLE GIVES ROBINSON HIS JUST REWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was supposed to be a coronation Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   David Robinson's Spurs won their first NBA title, beating the
Knicks and beating San Antonio's 26-year history.
</P>
<P>
   With a body chiseled out of obsidian, a soul filled with the
light of the Lord and a game that has been criticized as too soft
for too many years, Robinson got to that place all the great ones
dream about.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley is still dying for a championship ring. Patrick
Ewing makes no bones about it. Without a ring, the Knicks' injured
center says his NBA career feels a little empty, a little
unfinished.
</P>
<P>
   There is something forlorn about getting deeper and deeper into
a stellar career and not having that final affirmation _ not about
how good you are, but how hard you worked.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Robinson wanted and deserved his championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes a long ways toward fulfilling my dreams,'' Robinson
said, almost speechless in the wake of the Spurs' nerve-racking
Finals clincher, 78-77. ``Now I have to set new goals. But if this
was easy, it wouldn't be so sweet. You go through all those hard
times. You go through all those criticisms. That's what makes the
journey so special.''
</P>
<P>
   Now things are going to be a little different in Mr. Robinson's
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The Admiral will have a ring to match all the rest of the
hardware he was collected over the years as he established himself
as one of the greatest defensive players, scorers and stars of the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But the coronation of David Robinson turned out to be something
else. It was more of a reward. A just reward.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell made sure of that by taking some of the
spotlight and almost blowing up the series and the neat story line.
</P>
<P>
   How about that for contrast?
</P>
<P>
   David Robinson vs. Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Good vs. evil, if you want to reduce things to some simplistic
form.
</P>
<P>
   Soft vs. hard, if you want to hark upon the characterizations of
these two fine NBA players with vastly different temperments and
histories.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell _ a guy the Spurs persued hard after his coach-choking
debacle at Golden State _ showed why he wanted so badly to be set
free from the losing, overbearing surroundings with the Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell's energy, legs and relentless drive have been on
display almost the entire postseason.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night, when the Knicks could have easily folded in
the face of the Spurs' 3-1 series lead, Sprewell upped his game,
left behind any inclination he has toward recklessness.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sprewell nearly single-handedly pushed this series back
to San Antonio, trading basket after basket with Tim Duncan, the
other Twin Tower and the Finals MVP, as the game turned from Spurs'
mandate to a white-knuckler that the Knicks seemed determined to
steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spree was just awesome tonight,'' Spurs coach Gregg Popovich
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got one of those rolls. You just knew that the way
they were going, he and Tim were going to go back and forth. I
coached him for two years (at Golden State) and I know that when he
gets on a roll, he's unstoppable.''
</P>
<P>
   It should have been Ewing on the other side of court, battling
Robinson for the right to have some peace in retirement _ or at
least on the golf course, where the ribbing about who has a ring
and who doesn't can get awful nasty.
</P>
<P>
   But Ewing was sidelined. Robinson's fellow Dream Teamer and NBA
All-Star was out of action, leaving the stage wide open for someone
else to take up the Knicks' cause, to make it tough on Robinson to
get that final prize.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell served well. And because of his energy and effort,
Robinson's reward was all the sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made us earn this one,'' Robinson said. ``It's been a
long journey. I've got to give the Knicks so much credit. They
didn't give away anything. This city has a lot to be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the generosity of Robinson. That is why even though he
stepped aside to hand the scoring load over to Duncan this season,
Robinson is the one everyone wanted to see rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, everybody gets on David because they say he's not an
emotional person, he doesn't play with heart. But I think you have
seen this year that he really does,'' Spurs' backup center Will
Perdue said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of taken it as a personal challenge to show that he
really does. Everybody talks about what Tim's done during the
playoffs, but I think it's pretty important to notice what David's
done and the difference he's made.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Robinson's long-awaited championship thankfully puts an
end to any questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taken a lot of flak during his career,'' teammate Mario
Elie said. ``I said, `Dave, play hard and focused. You have a
chance to prove everyone wrong.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe David Robinson did not single-handedly prove everyone
wrong. He had help in making his championship come real. But that's
fine. Robinson is not selfish. He did it the perfect way.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
