<P>
   INTEL-REVAMP (Washington) _ Top officials at the FBI, CIA and
the Pentagon have met in recent days to discuss a revamping of the
country's counterintelligence apparatus. By David Cat Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   J.C.-PENNEY (Undated) _ Many former employees and other industry
experts think that Wall Street's optimism in J.C. Penney Co. is
premature. They believe that the core of the business _ the nearly
century-old retail chain, which accounts for roughly 50 percent of
annual revenues _ is as troubled as ever. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-JOINT-VENTURE (Undated) _ In yet another sign of the
pressure to merge that is reshaping the publishing industry, Time
Warner Books and Viacom's Simon &AMP; Schuster are in serious talks to
form a joint venture for their book operations, covering such
aspects as warehousing, marketing and sales. By Geraldine
Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHEED _ Lockheed Martin Corp., the nation's largest military
contractor, is considering selling assets valued at around $1
billion to winnow out noncore businesses and, perhaps, provide some
lift to a stock that has fallen more than 30 percent during the
last year. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-BLOCS (Rio de Janeiro) _ In an effort to bolster trade and
seek some sort of counterweight to American global economic
dominance, leaders of the world's second and third largest trading
blocs are to meet here this weekend and early next week in a
first-ever ``Latin American-European Summit'' that has already
proven divisive on several basic bread-and-butter issues. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ECON (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ In the financial subplot
of Indonesia's political transformation, few events have
demonstrated the progress and pitfalls as clearly as the agreement
this week between PT Astra International and its creditors on how
the company will pay back more than $1 billion in debt. By Wayne
Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN (Tokyo) _ For the first time ever, the Nissan Motor Co.
opened its shareholder meeting to the media, just one of the many
small signs that even the most traditional Japanese companies are
inching toward the greater disclosure and transparency demanded by
foreign investors. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
