<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT &LR;      06-26 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FIRED SUPERINTENDENT, SMALL SUCCESSES WERE NOT ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Walking through Public School 202 Friday, Robert E.
Riccobono saw programs taking seed that began under his
superintendency of District 19 in the East New York section of
Brooklyn. He watched elementary school pupils participating in a
literacy program devised at Johns Hopkins University. He spoke with
a former teacher who had become an assistant principal under a
program for training administrators.
</P>
<P>
   But he also saw a chart of the school's 1999 testing goals for
reading and math, goals that were not met. Like many other schools
in the city, P.S. 202's scores plummeted from a year ago, so when
Chancellor Rudy Crew announced a shake-up earlier in the week,
Riccobono's head was among those that rolled. He was one of five
superintendents who were removed; four others were placed on
probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was actually shocked,'' Riccobono said. ``I didn't expect
it. I felt we were making strides that were recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Crew's overhaul, the firing of Riccobono is
a telling reminder of the difficulty of improving the city's worst
school districts. He was regarded as a superintendent who had taken
steps to upgrade the curriculum and teacher training in his
district. For a time, he seemed to have the support of the
chancellor and the business community. But under pressure to take
action in the face of falling scores, Crew responded this week by
cleaning house, closing 13 schools and taking direct control of 43
others, including two in District 19.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Crew refused to specify why he removed the
superintendents, but he said he based his decisions on three
criteria: management skills, leadership and the achievement test
scores of their districts. On recent tests, fewer than a third of
students in District 19 were at grade level in reading and math.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy schools chancellor, Harry Spence, cited leadership
Friday as a factor in Crew's decision to dismiss Riccobono.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the challenge in District 19 as well as in other poorly
performing schools remains the same: what will work? Drawing its
students from East New York, one of the city's poorest areas,
District 19 is representative of the city's failing districts. It
has a long history of neglect, and critics say years of patronage
and cronyism are partly responsible for the dismal test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Riccobono's defenders say he took over only four years ago and
began making positive changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the chancellor has done the right thing in shaking
up the system, but this might be a case where the broom has swept a
little too widely,'' said Robert Berne, vice president of academic
affairs at New York University and a longtime observer of the
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Riccobono's removal was particularly notable because, in January
1998, the chancellor and the New York City Partnership and Chamber
of Commerce selected District 19 for a Breakthrough for Learning
program, in which teachers and administrators would receive bonuses
if student achievement improved. The program also included teacher
training and regular student assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, officials with the New York City Partnership declined
comment about Riccobono's dismissal, but a statement earlier in the
week from the business group hardly rose to his defense, saying
``there is scant evidence that performance has materially
improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Spence offered an optimistic assessment of the new initiatives
in District 19, saying they ``have begun, we believe, to bear
fruit, and we're excited about the possibilities for District 19's
future.''
</P>
<P>
   But asked about Riccobono, he said the Breakthrough program
includes ``a continual review, and ultimately a decision about the
leadership of the district and its potential for advancing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in that context that the chancellor made that decision
in District 19,'' Spence said.
</P>
<P>
   Randi Weingarten, president of the teachers union, said,
``Obviously, the chancellor lost confidence in him.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Riccobono said he understood that accountability
was part of the job. He was one of two superintendents dismissed;
one will be transferred to another job in the system, and two are
retiring. Riccobono, 53, said he might retire after 31 years in the
system.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed resigned to his situation, noting that he recently
removed 11 principals in his district. ``The principals that I let
go I'm sure felt I made the wrong decision,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
