<HEADER>
A0398 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-LA     06-26 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT GIANTS, END LOSING STREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kevin Brown was rocked by the San Francisco
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up two earned runs in 71/3 innings. It was his worst
outing of his career at 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers still persevered and won 4-2 Friday to
end a three-game losing streak and, for a day, remain a {-game
ahead of San Diego and out of last place in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe Brown wasn't knocked all over the yard by the Giants.
Two runs is a bit drastic. But for what the right-hander's done
against them, not to mention his accomplished in 3Com Park, giving
up one run is unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he gave up the two runs on five hits, his ERA
against the Giants still went up. So did his ERA at this ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Brown entered the night 6-0 with a 0.58 ERA in seven starts
against San Francisco. At 3Com, he had allowed one run in four
starts spanning 35 1/3 innings. His ERA went to 0.78 against the
Giants, 0.62 at 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   Not even a change in catchers disrupted Brown. Angel Pena left
the game with tightness in his right hamstring in the top of the
sixth. He was replaced by Todd Hundley, who wasn't due back into
the starting mix until today.
</P>
<P>
   Pena's status was day-to-day. Hundley was scheduled to start
today after sitting the last 11 days to work on his throwing
mechanics. It didn't hurt that Hundley hit his eighth homer of the
season -- a solo shot _ on a 2-2 pitch with one out in the ninth
off reliever John Johnstone. It gave the Dodgers a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The catching change didn't matter because Brown was nearly
impeccable _ until the Dodgers starting hurting him, too.
</P>
<P>
   Brown improved to 9-4, including 7-2 after a Dodgers loss.
Giants lefty Shawn Estes (4-5) took the loss after allowing three
runs on eight hits in a season-best eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   The first run Brown allowed came after a walk, but he got out of
further trouble with a double play. In fact, 10 of the first 18
outs he recorded came via the ground ball and in the first six
innings the Giants hit three balls out of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   But in the seventh inning right fielder Raul Mondesi misplayed
Jeff Kent's leadoff single into a triple, falling twice before
tracking the ball at the wall. Brown got J.T. Snow to pop to
shortstop, but Stan Javier's grounder to second scored Kent to pull
the Giants within 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's homer provided an insurance run.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Aurilia led off the bottom of the eighth with a single and
was sacrificed to second before Dodgers manager Davey Johnson took
the perilous walk to the mound to remove Brown and bring in lefty
Pedro Borbon, the Dodgers' best reliever to this point.
</P>
<P>
   Borbon, as his 1.33 ERA would suggest, did the job. He retired
pinch-hitter Charlie Hayes on a fly to right and struck out Bill
Mueller to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Shaw pitched the ninth for his 17th save but only his third
since June 5.
</P>
<P>
   It also why many people thought the game was over after the
Dodgers scored twice in the second inning to take a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros led off with a single to center, Mondesi flied to
right and Adrian Beltre walked. The runners moved up a base on
Estes' wild pitch and scored on Jose Vizcaino's single back through
the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants fought back with a run in the fourth inning, taking
advantage of one of Brown's few miscues. He walked Barry Bonds to
lead off the inning. Jeff Kent singled to move Bonds to third, and
the Giants' left fielder scored when J.T. Snow grounded into a
double play.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers grabbed their two-run lead back in the fifth inning
by having their table-setter do just that. Eric Young singled to
lead off and stole second and third, matching his stolen base total
since May 26. Young scored on Gary Sheffield's single to right to
put the Dodgers ahead 3-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
