<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0399 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-26 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND-GUESSERS SPARE JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Among the Los Angeles Dodgers fans, Dodgers
haters, letter writers, radio-show callers, sportswriters, talking
heads, second-guessers, soothsayers and sages who make up the great
``they,'' the scapegoat hunt is on, sparing nobody, just about.
</P>
<P>
   They blame the owners: The Fox people have been skewered for
everything from the Mike Piazza trade to the musical playlist at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   They blame the general manager: It's Kevin Malone's fault, some
in his own clubhouse seem to believe, for predicting a World Series
and ticking off the Dodgers' western division rivals, who've had
the nerve to play extra hard against them.
</P>
<P>
   They blame the players: Obviously.
</P>
<P>
   They blame the coaches: In fact, the coaches have been the only
ones to take the fall so far, with Charlie Hough (pitching) fired
and Rick Dempsey (third base) busted down to bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   They even blame the fans: It's !ital!your!off! fault, goes the
most counter-intuitive analysis of all. Dodger Stadium fans are too
LAid back, and that infects the players. There's the theory,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody else? Is there a secretary, parking attendant,
ticket-taker, peanut vendor, security guard or groundskeeper out
there who has escaped his/her share of the blame as the Dodgers
knock on the National League West cellar door?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, yes.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, when a team goes bad, the hammer of blame lands first
on the manager.
</P>
<P>
   It was this very week last year that Fox lowered the boom on
Bill Russell, along with GM Fred Claire. The Dodgers were two games
under .500 at the time, in third place, 12{ games out of first _ in
most respects better off than they are this morning.
</P>
<P>
   But the hammer hasn't grazed Davey Johnson. Not here. Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, a reader mentioned that he'd heard a couple of
talk-show hosts getting pretty emotional about Johnson. They
!ital!felt sorry!off! for Davey, saddled with as he is with a sack
of rocks for a ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of the hands-off-Davey approach to Dodgers
dissection: Bob Nightengale's 29-paragraph column about the Dodgers
in the current edition of Baseball Weekly mentions 21 current and
former members of the team's roster and managements _ but never
mentions Davey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you expect at least !ital!one!off! letter to the
editor, blaming Johnson for the team's supposed underachievement?
</P>
<P>
   We bring this up not to suggest Johnson is to blame for the
Dodgers being in the ravine they're in _ or to suggest the team
could be any worse without him. We bring this up because it's an
oddity that says a lot about the Dodgers and the men who are trying
to repair them.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here?
</P>
<P>
   What's going on is that the proven winners in the Dodgers front
office and clubhouse are escaping criticism _ and the only person
who meets that description is Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on is that Johnson is in the first year of a
three-year contract paying him a $1.5 million salary _ job security
that will render criticism moot for at least this season.
</P>
<P>
   And what's going on is that Johnson's reputation as a
high-maintenance employee has yet to catch up with him here _ he
has kept a remarkably low profile, overshadowed by the big-talking
GM, Malone.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't like this in New York, where Johnson managed the Mets
to the 1986 World Series title during six-plus seasons there, in
Cincinnati or in Baltimore. Johnson wasn't often under .500, but
when he was, he was a big target, and he caught flak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time we really lost was in '90 _ when he got
fired,'' said San Diego Padres first baseman Dave Magadan, who
played for Johnson's Mets from '86 to '90 as Keith Hernandez's
long-suffering understudy.
</P>
<P>
   ``After '89, when we didn't win it, that whole offseason it was
`Put up or shut up.' (Relief ace) John Franco signed that winter.
Davey was in a no-win situation. If we won, we were supposed to
win. If we didn't win, it was his fault, because we had talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were two games under .500 when Johnson was fired in May
1990, the loser in a feud with general manager Frank Cashen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, too many times, the manager gets the blame,''
Magadan said.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Reds and Orioles, respectively, were 26 and 34
games over .500 in the seasons before Johnson and those teams
parted ways, so it's not always about W's and L's.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a possible explanation for Johnson riding blame-free to
last place: L.A. fans have figured out, through hard experience
with the Dodgers, Lakers, Kings and never mind the Clippers,
there's only so much a manager or head coach can do.
</P>
<P>
   History says entrusting the lineup card to a ``proven'' winner
is a guarantee written on toilet tissue.
</P>
<P>
   By my count, 43 times in major-league baseball history a team
has hired a manager who'd already won a World Series with another
club (not counting Johnson and Colorado's Jim Leyland, hired this
season). How many times has that manager won a World Series with
his new team? Only three: Sparky Anderson (Cincinnati in the '70s,
Detroit in '84), and before him, Bucky Harris (Washington in '24,
Yankees in '47) and Bill McKechnie (Pittsburgh in '25, Cincinnati
in '40).
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA, the numbers are 25 hires and only one success: Alex
Hannum, who coached Bob Pettit's '58 St. Louis Hawks and Wilt
Chamberlain's '67 Philadelphia 76ers to championships _ not to
forget the '69 Oakland Oaks of the ABA.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL's Super Bowl era, six championship-winning coaches
have switched teams, and none has taken another call from the
President.
</P>
<P>
   All of which suggests another reason ``they'' have spared Davey
Johnson the hammer of blame.
</P>
<P>
   They're saving it for Phil Jackson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
