<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BEAT A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Gary DiSarcina came home Friday night and made
his presence felt at the plate in Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn, Troy Glaus and Jeff Huson did the rest of the work as
the Anaheim Angels put together another late rally and beat the
Oakland Athletics 4-3 before 29,911.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Angels' fourth victory in five games.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 3-1 in the eighth, the Angels tied the game on a
two-run single by Vaughn. With two outs in the ninth, Huson beat
out an infield single as Glaus scored the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, the Angels' shortstop who returned to the lineup
earlier in the week after breaking his arm in spring training,
scored Anaheim's first run.
</P>
<P>
   But Jason Giambi's solo home run in the sixth inning provided
the spark for a two-out, two-run Oakland rally that gave the A's a
2-1 lead. Oakland's other run came on a home run by John Jaha in
the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The game was the first in a six-game homestand against division
rivals Oakland and the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   How the Angels fare against both teams is vital and could have a
major impact on the rest of their season. The Angels entered
Friday's game last in the AL West. The team's 32-39 record left
them 8{ games behind Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Athletics, at the mid-point of a long, grueling
road trip, entered the game in second place with a 36-36 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things hinge on how we play the teams in our
division,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said before Friday's game.
``If we get playing well enough, we're right back in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got off to a rocky start on Friday night. Oakland's
leadoff batter Tony Phillips got aboard when starting pitcher Omar
Olivares bobbled a routine pop up but was not charged with an
error.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Miguel Tejada, grounded into a double play. Ben
Greive singled and Giambi doubled down the right-field line,
sending Greive to third.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares walked designated hitter Jaha to load the bases.
Olivares ended the threat by getting A's right-fielder Matt Stairs
to fly out to left.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's first at-bat also started out on a promising note when
Darin Erstad walked. He advanced to second, but got no farther.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares settled down in the second. Although leadoff batter
Eric Chavez reached on a single, A.J. Hinch struck out. Olivares
then picked Chavez off first base and Ryan Christenson grounded
out.
</P>
</TEXT>
