<HEADLINE>
MARION JONES COMES UP SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ Marion Jones' pursuit of five gold medals in the
2000 Olympics has been well chronicled. But her unprecedented
endeavor is far from a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   That was evident on Friday when Jones, 23, suffered her first
loss to an American in the long jump since 1997 in the USA Track
and Field Championships at Hayward Field. Dawn Burrell sailed a
career-best 22 feet, 10 inches to end Jones' two-year reign as
national champion.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, ranked No. 1 in the world in 1998 in the 100, 200 and
long jump was second at 22-3 and Shana Williams was third at 22-0\.
The top three finishers qualified for the World Championships in
Seville, Spain in August.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a nine-time state champion from Thousand Oaks High and
Rio Mesa High who became the first woman to win the 100 and 200
since 1948 in last year's championships, will attempt to bounce
back in the first round of the 200 today. She will not run the 100
in the four-day meet in Eugene, which concludes Sunday, after
having received an automatic berth as defending champion in the
World Championships by the IAAF.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hats off to Dawn, she had a wonderful performance,'' Jones
said. ``She deserved to win. I am going to be challenged and I am
going to have to face that for the rest of my career. I'm going to
have to pull it out at the end and today I didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the long jump competition on Friday, it did not look
as though Jones would need to take more than one jump. She took the
lead on her first round jump of 22-3. After fouling on her second
attempt, Jones, competing for the first time since spraining her
right knee in the Pontiac Grand Prix meet on June 12 in Raleigh,
N.C, passed on her third and fourth jumps to avoid putting
excessive pressure on the tender joint.
</P>
<P>
   When Burrell, the younger sister of former 100 world-record
holder Leroy Burrell, uncorked her 22-10 effort on her fifth jump
to move into sixth on the all-time U.S. list, Jones could only
respond with marks of 21-4{ and 21-7\ on her fifth and sixth jumps.
In the Pontiac Grand Prix, Jones rallied to win the competition at
23-0 on her last jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to put anything off on the knee. I felt
surprisingly good,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When meet day comes around, I'm ready to perform and jump.
Going undefeated the entire season is obviously not a big deal
anymore. Things happen. I'm going to have to move forward. There
are no excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Inger Miller and Dennis Mitchell were winners in the men's and
women's 100 in wind-aided marks of 10.96 and 9.97, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a USC athlete and a 1996 Olympic gold medalist in the
400 relay, edged two-time Olympic champion Gail Devers by
one-hundredth of a second. Angela Williams and Torri Edwards of USC
were third and fourth at 11.03 and 11.05.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, the 1992 Olympic bronze medalist, broke into tears
after winning his fourth national title. It was his first title
since having been reinstated after a two-year suspension for a high
level of testosterone. The suspension was overturned by the USATF
in December.
</P>
<P>
   Shelia Burrell, a UCLA graduate who trains at Cal State
Northridge under Matador assistant Jeff McAuley, won the heptathlon
with 6,101 points, posting top marks in the 200 on the first day at
24.04 and in the final event, the 800, in 2:11.82, to clinch the
victory over Tiffany Lott-Hogan (6,026).
</P>
<P>
   Burrell, the 1998 runner-up, was second going into the 800 in
the two-day, seven-event competition, 37 points behind Lott-Hogan _
but rocketed to the lead with a 59-second opening quarter to win
the event.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Haynes, the 1996 NCAA runner-up for USC, was third at
5,720 to earn her first top-three, U.S. national finish. Favored
DeDee Nathan, the world indoor pentathlon champion, finished eighth
at 5,318 after she no-heighted at 5-7\ and failed to score points
in the high jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``All week I kept saying to myself, `It's going to come down to
the 800.''' Burrell said. ``When it comes down to the 800, my
attitude is just do whatever it takes to get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
