<HEADLINE>
RANGERS POUND M'S TO OPEN SIX-GAME LEAD IN AL WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ We all knew this was The Last Domestand. The Mariners
are hoping it isn't the Last Stand, period.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a two-week stretch of division games, the
Mariners were humbled by the American League West-leading Texas
Rangers 14-4 before 30,490 fans Friday in the Kingdome's final
night game. It was the Mariners' sixth loss in their last seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wears on you a lot,'' shortstop Alex Rodriguez said. ``But
all you can do is come back tomorrow and give a good effort,
because we need to stop the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the bloodshed is seeping from the Mariners' bullpen. On
Thursday, Anaheim scored nine runs after the seventh inning for a
comeback win. Friday, the Rangers scored 13 runs after the fifth
inning for a comeback win of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' top two starters, Jamie Moyer and Freddy Garcia,
will close out this series. But as manager Lou Piniella has noted _
and his club has continually proven _ relief pitching is most
important.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' bullpen has a 3.46 earned run average, best in the
American League. The Mariners' bullpen ERA is 6.51.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nothing we can do,'' third baseman Russ Davis
said. ``The defense and the offense can't let it get to them. We
just have to continue to play our game and do our half, put runs on
the board and back those guys up. Hopefully things will pan out.''
</P>
<P>
   The last two nights, the Mariners' AL West rivals scored off
each of the six Seattle relievers, posting 20 runs in seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   And the problem is not so much how the relievers have pitched.
It's that they're the best the M's have.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you this: I don't have many options,'' Piniella
said. ``We'll leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas trailed 3-1 before pounding Frankie Rodriguez and Melvin
Bunch in a six-run sixth. The Rangers slugged three homers in the
inning, the first coming off starter Paul Abbott, who had allowed
only an Ivan Rodriguez solo homer through five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, making his first start of the season after tearing the
anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee during winter ball,
went five-plus innings, allowing three runs on five hits and three
walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased,'' Abbott said. ``I competed well, made some
good pitches and made some bad pitches. All in all, I was pleased
with it. It was fun to be out there against Texas, just being such
a big game. That part of it was great.''
</P>
<P>
   The sixth inning wasn't. Abbott said he suffered ``more of a
mental lapse'' than any kind of physical fatigue. He fell behind
leadoff hitter Juan Gonzalez 3-and-1, then allowed a 441-foot home
run. After a walk to Rafael Palmeiro, Abbott was replaced by
Frankie Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later, Rodriguez allowed a two-run homer to Lee
Stevens that gave the Rangers a 4-3 lead. The right-hander could
not finish the inning, issuing a two-out single and walk, and Bunch
was summoned to face Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   The catcher, who had nine runs batted in at the Kingdome April
13, popped his second homer of the night, a three-run shot that put
Texas up 7-3. He added a run-scoring sacrifice fly off Bunch in the
eighth, which was followed two batters later by a two-run homer
from Gonzalez that gave the Rangers a six-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Both Rodriguez and Gonzalez finished with five RBIs, and their
team now holds a six-game lead over Oakland and Seattle. The AL
West is often called a wide-open division, but only the
AL.Central-leading Cleveland Indians hold a bigger division lead
than Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have a chance to jump eight games ahead by the end
of the series. If they do, there may be another reason for fans to
get teary at the Kingdome finale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
