<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS CAPTURE NBA TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They were perceived as soft. It was not long ago
critics snickered and deemed the San Antonio Spurs the Pilsbury
Dough Boys of the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you can call them hardcore champions.
</P>
<P>
   Culminating perhaps the toughest run in modern day basketball,
the Spurs finished off the New York Knicks with a 78-77 Game 5
victory Friday night at Madison Square Garden to win their first
NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed in each other. That's what counts for us. What
happens in our little circle ... not what everybody else thinks,''
said Spurs center Tim Duncan, named the Finals most valuable
player.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs became the first former ABA team to win an NBA
championship. And by no means was this title ride easy.
</P>
<P>
   After a 6-8 start, San Antonio ran rough-shod through a grueling
50-game, 90-day schedule. The Spurs went 15-2 in the postseason,
beating Minnesota in the first round, then sweeping the Los Angeles
Lakers and Portland to reach the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it took a sledgehammer to take out the undermanned
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   But as the celebration ensued at midcourt, each Spur player
hugged one man just as tightly as they did the Larry O'Brien
Trophy. David Robinson finally earned a championship after 10 long,
hard seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was easy, though, it really wouldn't be worth the
journey,'' said Robinson, who went from winning the league's MVP in
1995 to having career-threatening back surgery two seasons later.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes it special. You go through the hard times,
you go through all the creases, then you're able to finally get it
done. And it's satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all happy for the big fella,'' Spurs forward Sean
Elliott said. ``He's been playing hard, he's been through so much
ridicule. But it means nothing now.''
</P>
<P>
   New York led 77-76 with 1:30 left in the fourth quarter. But
Spurs point guard Avery Johnson put in what was the game-winner
when he calmly sank a baseline jumper with 47 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   Known mostly as the little guy who couldn't, Johnson turned out
to be a big hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just unbelievable. My shots felt good the whole
playoffs,'' said Johnson, who played for the Sonics from 1988-1990.
``And the guys had a lot of confidence in getting me the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice the Knicks could have taken the lead in the final 30
seconds. But Latrell Sprewell, who punished the Spurs with 14 of
his game-high 35 points in the fourth quarter, missed his last two
shots.
</P>
<P>
   With the ball and 2.1 seconds left in the game, Sprewell's
fade-away jump shot from six feet fell short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather have two points and have the victory,''
Sprewell said. ``It's just disappointing once you know it's finally
over. ... Their size was the ultimate difference.''
</P>
<P>
   After combining for 42 points and 35 rebounds in the Spurs' Game
4 victory, Duncan and Robinson totaled 46 points and 21 rebounds
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Most impressive about the Spurs in the Finals and throughout the
playoffs was their mental toughness, which they displayed down the
stretch of games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a very strong team,'' New York's Allan Houston said.
``It's funny ... when you get to this point nobody wants to give
the other team credit. But the bottom line is they played better
than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of how hard-fought Game 5 was, there were 12 lead
changes and a dozen ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Knicks were scary and it's scary to see if they had a
healthy Larry Johnson and Patrick Ewing,'' the Spurs' Mario Elie
said. ``It probably would have been a different series.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie won his third ring after winning two with Houston in 1994
and 1995. Backup guard Steve Kerr walked away with his fourth
straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was obviously the common denominator,'' joked Kerr, who was
part of the three championship teams with the Chicago Bulls.
``Without me, I'm sure the Bulls don't win any. Without me coming
in here this year, the Spurs probably don't win.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the second half, Sprewell was nearly the spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   He took over in the third period when the Knicks erased the
Spurs' nine-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio's only retort was a big one: Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   He kept the Spurs afloat throughout the Knicks' surge. Duncan
scored nine of his team's last 10 points in the quarter, which
ended with the Spurs ahead 59-58.
</P>
<P>
   New York made trying to clinch a championship on their home
floor difficult from the start. Much like they did in winning Game
3, the Knicks jumped on the Spurs early.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio, though, never lost its poise before closing out its
fourth straight playoff series on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of stunning,'' Spurs coach Gregg Popovich said.
``You wonder if it's really true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 0253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
