<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT GIANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kevin Brown was rocked by the San Francisco
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up two earned runs in 71/3 innings. It was his worst
outing of his career at 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers still persevered and won 3-2 Friday to
end a three-game losing streak and, for a day, remain a {-game
ahead of San Diego and out of last place in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe Brown wasn't knocked all over the yard by the Giants.
Two runs is a bit drastic. But for what the right-hander has done
against them, not to mention his accomplishments in 3Com Park,
giving up one run is unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw that first pitch he threw was 97 mph, I knew it was
going to be a big game for him,'' said Dodgers shortstop Jose
Vizcaino, who played for the Giants in '97. ``I know they don't
like to face him. That's a plus. Every time he sees those uniforms,
he's big.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he gave up just the two runs on five hits, Brown's
ERA against the Giants still went up. So did his ERA at this
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Brown entered the night 6-0 with a 0.58 ERA in seven starts
against San Francisco. At 3Com, he had allowed one run in four
starts spanning 351/3 innings. His ERA went to 0.78 against the
Giants, 0.62 at 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an answer (for the success),'' said Brown, who
improved to 9-4 and is 7-2 after a Dodgers loss. ``You don't look
for reasons when things are going well. When things are going bad,
you look for a reason and try and change it. It's a double-edged
sword. It could be a good place to pitch, but they're usually a
good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown was pulled with one out in the eighth inning because of a
twinge on his left side, the result of reaching for Jeff Kent's
single in the fourth inning. He exited with a runner on second and
the Dodgers holding a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Borbon recorded the final two outs of the eighth and Jeff
Shaw pitched the ninth for his 17th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Brown) went back in for the eighth and let me know he wasn't
100 percent,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``I learned
before when he says something, to listen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, in typical fashion, dismissed the injury as being trivial
and said it wouldn't affect the status of his next start, which
happens to be in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   What can't be overlooked is the Dodgers gave Brown an early lead
on Vizcaino's two-run single in the second and from there it seemed
over.
</P>
<P>
   The first run Brown allowed came after a walk, but he got out of
further trouble with a double play. In fact, 10 of the first 18
outs he recorded came via the ground ball and in the first six
innings the Giants hit three balls out of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' second run came in the seventh when right fielder
Raul Mondesi misplayed Kent's leadoff single into a triple, falling
twice before tracking the ball at the wall. Brown got J.T. Snow to
pop to shortstop, but Stan Javier's grounder to second scored Kent
to pull the Giants within 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was smart enough I would have stopped pitching to have
them fix the mound,'' said Brown, who lowered his ERA to a NL-low
2.89. ``It would get me for a pitch or two. My spikes would get
caught in a hole, and then I'd get out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even a change in catchers disrupted Brown. Angel Pena left
the game with tightness in his right hamstring in the top of the
sixth. He was replaced by Todd Hundley, whose solo homer in the
ninth gave the Dodgers a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw the ball everywhere he wanted it to go,'' Pena said.
``He was unbelievable. Every situation he knew where to throw the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Pena said he expected to be ready to return Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
