<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BEAT ATHLETICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Gary DiSarcina came home Friday night and made
his presence felt at the plate in Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn, Troy Glaus and Jeff Huson did the rest of the work as
the Anaheim Angels put together another late rally and beat the
Oakland Athletics 4-3 in front of 29,911.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Angels' fourth victory in their past five games.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 3-1 in the eighth, the Angels tied the game on a
two-run single by Vaughn. Huson, who singled as a pinch-hitter for
DiSarcina, and Darin Erstad scored as Vaughn drove in his 48th and
49th runs of the season.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the ninth inning, Glaus doubled. He moved to
third on a groundout by Matt Walbeck and scored when Huson beat out
a groundball up the middle. Oakland shortstop Miguel Tejada ranged
far to left, but Jason Giambi was unable to scoop his throw out of
the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, the Angels' shortstop who returned to the lineup
earlier in the week after breaking his arm in spring training,
scored Anaheim's first run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those guys whose presence might make a difference
in a game,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said of DiSarcina, who
was playing just his fourth game of the year. ``It's certainly a
big piece of the puzzle, I just don't want to put a lot of pressure
on a guy who is just coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Giambi's solo home run sparked a two-out, two-run rally to give
the A's a 2-1 lead in the sixth. Oakland's other run came on a home
run by John Jaha in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The game was the first in a six-game homestand against division
rivals Oakland and the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things hinge on how we play the teams in our
division,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said before the game. ``If
we get playing well enough, we're right back in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the win, the Angels remain last in the AL West, 8{ games
behind Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to turn up the heat,'' said Vaughn, whose eight RBI
in the past two games give him 801 in his career. ``When we start
playing the division games you have to come out there with a
purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting the win was the biggest thing about tonight's game,''
he said. ``We got a win here, that was of the utmost importance.
That's the key.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Omar Olivares pitched seven strong innings,
allowing two earned runs. Scott Schoeneweis pitched the eighth and
closer Troy Percival (2-2) picked up the win after retiring the
side in order in the ninth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
