<SLUG> BC-RAC-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ENGINES HEAT UP, RACES LOSE COMPETITORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Drivers could not blame a full moon, so
maybe they can blame the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Or they can blame the start of summer for the heated exchanges
during the Street Stock race. Blame the heat for the proliferation
of blown engines. Certainly it wasn't Friday the 13th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mid-season, maybe some of the motors are a little
tired,'' Rod Johnson suggested after winning the Grand American
Modifieds main event before 2,493 at Irwindale Speedway Friday
night. ``People may need to go through them again.''
</P>
<P>
   In Late Model, Gerrit Cromsigt and Dusty McDonald are again tied
for the points lead after Cromsigt came from last to win the 30-lap
feature. Lee Ladd of Thousand Oaks won in Mini Stock and Alex Romo
of Covina won the Street Stocks race.
</P>
<P>
   There were five blown engines and two wrecks, taking out 10 cars
on a night when only 35 showed up.
</P>
<P>
   The most heat was generated in the Street Stock race.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Sallie tried to squeeze between Michael Pope and Luis Del
Real in Turn 3 of the first lap. But the space wasn't there. All
three touched and drew sparks. Pope pulled up on the outside of
turn 1, his car pointed toward the track. Sallie, from Tujunga,
pulled up directly across from Pope on the inside of the track.
They yelled at each other and then got out of the car and stomped
around for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could shoot through it,'' Sallie said. ``But they
got together. I felt like I had to get up there, it's only a 12-lap
race. I was trying to get up front.''
</P>
<P>
   Points leader Pope said he didn't see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was minding my own business and he tried to go between us,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only two cars finished the race, winner Romo and Del Real, from
Covina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard stuff, but I was trying to stay on my own line and
keep running my own race,'' Romo said after his first victory.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, it was a busy night for Haddock's Towing.
</P>
<P>
   Only six cars finished in Late Model. Todd Burns of Riverside
blew an engine during heat races and David Hessing of Canyon
Country lost his engine in the main event.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Porter of La Verne dropped out of the Mini Stock heat race
and failed to make the main event. John Rowe, involved in a head-on
crash with Kevin Bernhardt, failed to start in that race's main
event. In Grand American, Jim Fram of Irvine and Robert Rice of
Hawthorne tangled in turn 1, sending Fram along the turn 1 wall.
Roger Carufel Jr. of Saugus blew his Grand Am engine.
</P>
<P>
   Cromsigt, from Pine Mountain Club, took the lead from James
Weston, from Goleta, with six laps to go in Late Model. McDonald,
from Simi Valley, pushed his way past Weston to take second.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, from Canyon Country, took the lead on lap 3 of the
Grand American race and easily pulled away from others, even with a
caution with four laps to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had bad luck in the past, but everything was right this
time,'' he said. &UR; !dlim! &LR; !end!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
