</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WIN FROM DEEP IN TEXAS-SIZED HEARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So what's wrong with this picture? They've got rodeos
all over Queens and Texas is now the undisputed winter sports
champion of the American sports world.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Dallas Stars bring a Stanley Cup to the Lone Star
state. And now the San Antonio Spurs, who, for the record, began
life as the Dallas Chapparrals in the late, lamented American
Basketball Association, have brought an NBA championship to the
land of pickup trucks, sad Country ballads, and six-man football.
As far as excitement goes, this will just have to do until the
Cowboys come to camp.
</P>
<P>
   And what style! Yeah, yeah, yeah they did it with a thoroughly
modern 78-77 victory over the Knicks, but they did it by outdueling
the extraordinarily game Eastern Conference champs, who played this
entire series shorthanded, and who came within three minutes of
sending this series back to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The final hero was squeaky-voiced Avery Johnson, who created the
final score by swishing an open jump shot from the left corner with
47 seconds to play, and who then made a heads-up play by
recognizing that, because the 24-second clock was about to expire,
he had to get the ball up on the rim. New York grabbed the ensuing
rebound with 2.1 seconds left, but the additional two or three
seconds Johnson had obtained for his team looked pretty big when
Latrell Sprewell took Charlie Ward's in-bounds pass on the baseline
and found himself pretty well swallowed up by Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   In order to secure the game and the championship, the Spurs had
to find a way to overcome the heroic performance of the apparently
reformed Bad Boy of the NBA. What Latrell Sprewell did in the final
game of a completely bizarre New York season was play the kind of
game a Jerry West or Michael Jordan would be very proud to have
called his own. For encased inside his 35-point spree _ what else?
_ was one dazzling stretch in which he scored 14 consecutive
second-half New York points.
</P>
<P>
   At that juncture the game had, in fact, turned into an isolated
battle of one-upsmanship between Sprewell and the frightening Tim
Duncan, who, at age 23, is now officially the best player in the
history of the American Virgin Islands, the best player in the
history of Wake Forest, and the best current player in the World's
Greatest Basketball League.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan finished with 31 points on a rich assortment of
turnaround jumpers, jump hooks, and basic inside moves, and he did
his very best work when it was absolutely needed. That was in the
final two minutes of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had a 54-50 lead, having extricated themselves from a
47-38 deficit with a run of 10 straight and 14-3. The Madison
Square Garden crowd was frenzied. Sprewell was heating up. There
would have been no shame had the Spurs sort of relaxed and reasoned
that winning the title in the Alamodome wouldn't be so bad. Enter
Duncan, who had not yet scored in the second half following a solid
16-point first two periods. He banked in a 3-point play over two
men, hit another perimeter jumper, and then took one to the hoop
for a pair of free throws on the next three San Antonio
possessions. There is no way to exaggerate how much the Spurs
needed that lift, nor is there much doubt that they would have gone
under had somebody not stepped forward. That someone happened to be
Tim Duncan, whose 27 points and 14 rebounds per game in his first
NBA Finals only amplified the prior judgment of everyone from Jeff
Van Gundy to the mayor of San Antonio that he is already the best
player in the league.
</P>
<P>
   And if anyone doubts that luck plays a part in building sports
teams, consider that had a player of Duncan's magnitude not been
available in the draft the same year that a crippling back injury
kept David Robinson out of all but six games, the Spurs would not
be the new champions. There are years, such as the one we're in,
where there is no true No. 1 pick. And there are years when a
savior is sitting there. One of those years was 1997, and San
Antonio happens to be the grateful beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks gave them a tremendous battle in the face of very
daunting odds. Four weeks ago a bounce of the ball got them past
Miami, and since then they have accomplished something that is very
difficult _ they have managed to make New York City into a very
small town. To spend time in New York this week was to know that
the Knicks were on everyone's lips.
</P>
<P>
   But the real story now is San Antonio, and the happiest man on
the team is the noble David Robinson, who many believed was too
``soft,'' too passive, and just too damn gentlemanly to win an NBA
title. Now there is nothing left to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one big goal I had has been achieved,'' Robinson said.
``Now I need a new goal. And if this had been easy, it wouldn't
have been special.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy? Absolutely not. The outsized and outgunned Knicks squeezed
everything they could out of what they had to work with in a
circumstance when everyone in the basketball world knew who had the
better team. With three minutes remaining, they led, 77-75. They
never scored again. They had given it their all.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio Spurs, NBA champs. It may not be like winning the 5A
gridiron title, but it's close.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
