<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      06-26 1646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, June 27:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECTION (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Since Election Day on
June 7, the counting of the 112 million votes has slowed to a near
halt, bogged down in a morass of apparently unforeseen
difficulties. Remarkably, voters have not exploded in frustration.
By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Mexico City) _ The July 4 gubernatorial
elections in Mexico's most populous state, which surrounds Mexico
City, are being closely watched. The central campaign issue _ crime
and how to combat it _ is one that is likely to define the
presidential race. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   RADIOASTRONOMY-INTERFERENCE (Paris) _ Radioastronomers around
the world say they cannot escape the overhead ``pollution'' beamed
down nonstop from the growing fleet of communications satellites.
At observatories like Nancay Radioastronomy Station in France and
the famed Jodrell Bank in England, where pulsars were discovered,
astronomers complain that the enormously powerful signals emitted
by the low-orbit satellites are drowning out the faint whispers
coming from the universe. And these manmade constellations, they
complain, are increasingly invading the frequencies assigned to
radioastronomy. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-DRUG-MONEY (Bogota, Colombia) _ Taking a step that is
generating heated criticism in Washington, the Colombian government
has begun to include income earned from growing illegal drugs in
the way it calculates the size of the nation's economy. The move is
controversial but necessary, Colombian officials say, to take
account of the increasingly uncontrollable reality of the drug
trade, which by obviously imprecise assessments could amount to
between one one-quarter and one-third of Colombia's legal exports.
By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-BOOKS (Beijing) _ In the cramped basement offices of the
Alpha Book Company, two editors skirt a legion of rules and
regulations in order to bring out surprisingly provocative books in
a country where, officially, all publications are state owned and
controlled. Even though 1999 has been a chilly political period,
marked by sensitive anniversaries, dissident arrests and the
closing of several liberal publications, a growing stream of
adventurous books and magazines has been bubbling up from under the
ice, many courtesy of new private companies like Alpha Books. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ Senior White House officials were
informed that China might have stolen American nuclear secrets
nearly a year earlier than the Clinton administration originally
disclosed, according to current and former U.S. officials. By James
Risen and Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   HONG-KONG-CHINA (Hong Kong) _ In a move that has profound
implications for Hong Kong's legal system, China overturned a local
court ruling that granted residency here to more than a million
people. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AIRPORT (Slatina, Yugoslavia) _ Two weeks after the first
NATO peacekeepers arrived in Kosovo, the first military aircraft
landed at the province's main airport, which NATO commanders said
could soon open to regular flights. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLICE (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ People know that the U.N.
mission is to be the all-powerful civilian administration in
Kosovo, but its presence is barely felt. The most pressing need is
for an international police force to tackle the crime that has
flourished with the exit of the Serbian police and military forces
and many ethnic Serb civilians, the return of over 300,000 ethnic
Albanian refugees. The process of acquiring police officers from
donor countries is so time consuming that the 40 officers are
actually being borrowed from the UN mission in nearby Bosnia. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-YUGO-TV (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ On Yugoslavian
television, the evening news this week showed a tranquil Serbian
village in Kosovo where contented, secure farm families were
surrounded by lush crops, tidy haystacks and trustworthy British
soldiers, one of whom sweetly petted a village dog. That same
evening there was horrifying counterprogramming, but only for the
affluent sliver of the Serbian population that has access to CNN
and BBC on satellite television. Pictures of burning Serbian
villages in Kosovo, torched by vengeful Albanians, were broadcast
along with accounts of Serbs being shot to death and fleeing by the
tens of thousands from Kosovo. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DESTRUCTION (Pec, Yugoslavia) _ Even before NATO began
bombing on March 24, there was much destruction in Kosovo. But
there appeared to be a shift, in focus and intensity, since then:
Before, the destruction was almost always confined to rural areas,
where the Serbian military could argue that it was flushing out
rebels with the Kosovo Liberation Army. In March, though, with the
onset of NATO's bombing campaign, the Serbs took the destruction to
cities like Pec, Djakovica and Mitrovica in the north, where the
Kosovo Liberation Army may have had support, but was far less
visible. The nature of the destruction in Kosovo suggests a
campaign against the Albanian people and their property that went
beyond military tactics alone. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSPACE-BATTLEGROUND (Los Angeles) _ The struggle between the
nation's cable television operators and Internet service providers
over high-speed access to cyberspace has roiled city politics in
Los Angeles, where three commissioners have resigned during debate
on policy over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BANDWAGON (Miami) _ Two weeks have now passed since Gov.
George W. Bush first hit the campaign trail. And his poll numbers
just keep getting better, the crowds keep on coming, and the money
keeps on rolling in. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-DEPRIVATION (Mohansic, N.Y.) _ It is no secret that
Westchester County, golf oasis for the wealthy, is a golf desert
for everyone else. Though the county is peppered with 61 golf
courses, only five are open to the free-range duffer, that
particular golf subspecies who cannot afford even a mid-range
private club's $150,000 membership fee and $10,000 in annual dues.
The problem has become so bad in recent years that Westchester _
one of the most affluent counties in the nation _ is now among the
most golf-deprived, experts said. By Paul Zielbauer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton will try to
reconcile two seemingly contradictory goals next week when he
unveils a plan to cut the long-term cost of Medicare while
expanding the program to cover prescription drugs, administration
officials said. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-ROYALTIES (Washington) _ After Mobil Oil settled a lawsuit
last year charging that it had underpaid the government for
drilling rights, one of the public interest groups that filed the
suit shared its award with two federal employees. Since then, the
Interior Department has been trying to force the industry to pay
higher royalty fees to the government, but congressional critics
are now using questions about the unusual rewards to the federal
officials to delay any new regulations. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   MRS.CLINTON-BANKRUPTCY-LAW (Washington) _ For more than a year,
Hillary Rodham Clinton has been fiercely engaged behind the scenes
on a legislative issue _ consumer bankruptcy _ that could prove
politically tricky for other Democrats and for her own political
ambitions. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   VIRTUAL-DRUGGISTS (Washington) _ In the seamless realm of
cyberspace, pharmacies are shipping pills across state lines
without the requisite licenses. Doctors are writing prescriptions
for people they have never met, a practice the American Medical
Association says is unethical, but not illegal. And nobody _ not
Congress, nor the American Medical Association, or various federal
and state agencies _ knows quite how to stop it. A special report.
By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICIAN-NOVELIST (Washington) _ Rep. Peter King, R-N.Y., had
a certain merry smile this week when he returned to the House floor
fresh from a high-profile radio interview about his latest entry in
the political hopper: a novel, not a bill. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Fast cars and fast women. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ Bradley sees a longing for strict gun
control. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-SPORTS-BUDGET _ A rundown of sports stories will move by 2
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12 p.m.
</P>
