<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (lh) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Sunday, June 27. The N.Y. Times News Service supervisor is
Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton will try to
reconcile two seemingly contradictory goals next week when he
unveils a plan to cut the long-term cost of Medicare while
expanding the program to cover prescription drugs, administration
officials said. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 2 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   VIRTUAL-DRUGGISTS (Washington) _ In the seamless realm of
cyberspace, pharmacies are shipping pills across state lines
without the requisite licenses. Doctors are writing prescriptions
for people they have never met, a practice the American Medical
Association says is unethical, but not illegal. And nobody _ not
Congress, nor the American Medical Association, or various federal
and state agencies _ knows quite how to stop it. A special report.
By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DESTRUCTION (Pec, Yugoslavia) _ Even before NATO began
bombing on March 24, there was much destruction in Kosovo. But
there appeared to be a shift, in focus and intensity, since then:
Before, the destruction was almost always confined to rural areas,
where the Serbian military could argue that it was flushing out
rebels with the Kosovo Liberation Army. In March, though, with the
onset of NATO's bombing campaign, the Serbs took the destruction to
cities like Pec, Djakovica and Mitrovica in the north, where the
Kosovo Liberation Army may have had support, but was far less
visible. The nature of the destruction in Kosovo suggests a
campaign against the Albanian people and their property that went
beyond military tactics alone. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   MRS.CLINTON-BANKRUPTCY-LAW (Washington) _ For more than a year,
Hillary Rodham Clinton has been fiercely engaged behind the scenes
on a legislative issue _ consumer bankruptcy _ that could prove
politically tricky for other Democrats and for her own political
ambitions. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-DEPRIVATION (Mohansic, N.Y.) _ It is no secret that
Westchester County, golf oasis for the wealthy, is a golf desert
for everyone else. Though the county is peppered with 61 golf
courses, only five are open to the free-range duffer, that
particular golf subspecies who cannot afford even a mid-range
private club's $150,000 membership fee and $10,000 in annual dues.
The problem has become so bad in recent years that Westchester _
one of the most affluent counties in the nation _ is now among the
most golf-deprived, experts said. By Paul Zielbauer.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   3-graf refer:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-BOOKS (Beijing) _ In the cramped basement offices of the
Alpha Book Company, two editors skirt a legion of rules and
regulations in order to bring out surprisingly provocative books in
a country where, officially, all publications are state owned and
controlled. Even though 1999 has been a chilly political period,
marked by sensitive anniversaries, dissident arrests and the
closing of several liberal publications, a growing stream of
adventurous books and magazines has been bubbling up from under the
ice, many courtesy of new private companies like Alpha Books. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   2-graf refer:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ Senior White House officials were
informed that China might have stolen U.S. nuclear secrets nearly a
year earlier than the Clinton administration originally disclosed,
according to current and former U.S. officials. By James Risen and
Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
