<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, June 27, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-REVIEW (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rules. That was
the message of a term in which the court asserted its power over
every branch and level of government, few of which emerged
unchanged from the encounter. By Linda Greenhouse. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   STATE-POLITICS-REVIEW (Albany, N.Y.) _ Washington has been
transferring power to the states on matters like welfare, providing
lawmakers with more to wrangle over and drawing more interest
groups into the fray. State authority was further strengthened by
last week's Supreme Court decisions that placed curbs on Congress'
ability to make federal law binding on the states. By Clifford J.
Levy.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CONGRESS-REVIEW (Washington) _ When Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas made a triumphant visit to Capitol Hill last week,
congressional Republicans grabbed hold of him as if he were a life
raft that could sail them all to victory. But their clutch left
some in both parties predicting that Bush's Washington allies would
only weigh down his campaign. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-APOLOGY-REVIEW (Undated) _ Unlike being in love, being in
business sometimes means having to say you're sorry. Last week the
chairman and chief executive of Coca-Cola Co. issued one of the
more elaborate public apologies by an American business leader. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-LAWSUITS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Last week an independent
scientific panel reported that the courts had been wrong in saying
that breast implants caused serious disease. The battle over
implants, and similar cases in which courts appear to have reached
incorrect scientific conclusions, has meant that judges often
restrict the scientific evidence that can be presented to jurors.
By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCT-DESIGN-REVIEW (Undated) _ Age isn't the only thing
creeping up on the baby-boom generation. Consumer product design
and marketing are too, like wolves on cattle. By William L.
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   MAKEOVERS-REVIEW (Undated) _ If you are appearance-challenged,
you are hitting speed bumps on today's exciting but fiercely
competitive job superhighway, where Youth and Beauty are zooming
past in Ferraris. You are just the candidate for a Millennium
Makeover. By Joe Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   BALKAN-NATIONS (Rome) _ Nearly a decade after the old Yugoslavia
began to break up, President Clinton visited the thriving, peaceful
land of Slovenia a week ago, and then saw bedraggled Albanian
refugees waiting to return to Kosovo. The contrast could not have
been greater. A glance at the four newly independent lands _
Slovenia, Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Macedonia _
illustrates how differently they are faring now. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   EURO-FOOD-SCARES-REVIEW (Paris) _ Last month, researchers at
Cornell published findings that genetically altered corn, designed
to produce pollen toxic to pests, could also kill caterpillars of
the monarch butterflies, whose principal breeding range is the U.S.
corn belt. Americans heard this news with a momentary shrug of
disapproval. But in the European Union, environmental officials are
taking the news much more seriously. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   GERM-WARFARE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Ken Alibek was a military
physician in the Soviet Union. Like every doctor, he took an oath
to preserve life and guard against medical abuse. But after doing
so, he devoted himself for 17 years not to healing but to the
science of germ warfare _ devising new ways of harnessing deadly
microbes to maim and kill people. Among his killers were smallpox,
anthrax, tularemia and plague. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
