<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0441 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EURO-FOOD-SCARES-REVI     06-26 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-FOOD-SCARES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE LOSES ITS APPETITE FOR HIGH-TECH FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(dw) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The beating of a butterfly's wings in one hemisphere, it
turns out, really can cause a hurricane in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, researchers at Cornell published findings that
genetically altered corn, designed to produce pollen toxic to
pests, could also kill caterpillars of the monarch butterflies,
whose principal breeding range is the U.S. corn belt.
</P>
<P>
   Americans heard this news with a momentary shrug of disapproval.
But in the European Union, environmental officials are taking the
news much more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from consumers fed up with what British
newspapers call ``Frankenstein food,'' the union was tightening
regulations that have already limited the number of genetically
modified crops that can be marketed to 18. Now the
butterfly-killing corn seems likely to be barred under a tacit
moratorium on permitting any new items until the Europeans can
agree on new rules.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, where three-quarters of all genetically
modified crops are grown, consumers seem hardly to care whether
chemists have tinkered with the genes as long as the stuff looks
and tastes normal. In Europe, demonstrators in southern France this
month uprooted and burned part of a field of experimental modified
rapeseed.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Britain, which grows and exports such things, Sainsbury
supermarkets have had to pull everything made from genetically
modified organisms off the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   So why are the Europeans so much more nervous than Americans?
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is agricultural protectionism. Europe resents
the fact that many of the patents on genetically modified crops
with bred-in high yields and resistance to parasites are held by
American companies like Monsanto, DuPont and Dow.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a different attitude toward food in some places.
The French don't like what they call ``industrial'' tomatoes,
fruits and vegetables because they think these products just don't
taste very good.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest reason may be that Europeans are panicked these
days about food safety. Americans might be nervous too, if the Food
and Drug Administration had as dismal a record as Europe's
bureaucracies have racked up recently in insuring the safety of
food that comes to the table.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly had Europeans recovered from fears that mad cow disease
could infect people who ate infected beef when a new scandal in
Belgium last month caused fear that chicken, eggs, beef, pork, veal
and maybe even milk and cheese could be contaminated with
cancer-causing dioxin.
</P>
<P>
   At the root of both disasters was the same cause _ adulterated
animal feed. Five generations ago, most Europeans probably couldn't
afford to eat meat except for Sunday dinner. But things have
changed, and in the rush to produce more beef cheaply for modern
consumers, feed producers in Britain and elsewhere in the 1980s
took to enriching feed grain with ground-up offal and parts of
slaughtered sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Bossies were never meant to be carnivores, and after cattle
ingested bits of sheep brain that had been infected with a
nerve-degenerative disorder called scrapies, some cows in Britain
were seen staggering around, eventually succumbing to a
scrapieslike disease.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, fear spread that if cattle could get it from eating
sheep, people could get it from eating beef.
</P>
<P>
   Britain banned the adulterated feed in 1990, but pooh-poohed the
fears until 1996, when the authorities finally conceded that they
could not rule out a link between the disease showing up in cattle
and a horrifyingly similar malady that destroys the human brain,
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease.
</P>
<P>
   British beef was banned from continental markets for most of a
decade, and sales of beef produced in most other European countries
suffered as well.
</P>
<P>
   Did European food-safety regulation improve with this
experience?
</P>
<P>
   Not in Belgium, where last March veterinarians discovered that
chickens were getting sick and not laying eggs after eating feed
that had been enriched, this time with reprocessed animal fat. The
problem was that used motor oil had been dumped into the fat vats,
contaminating the whole food chain with dioxin.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Belgians until the end of May, though, to notify
consumers (or the authorities in neighboring countries) that there
was a problem with almost everything except vegetables. With little
they could trust to feed themselves with, Belgians threw out their
government in elections on June 13, just after another scare broke
_ this time over Coca-Cola; about 250 Belgian schoolchildren and
other people reported symptoms of nausea, intestinal pain and
headaches after drinking it.
</P>
<P>
   The company didn't admit liability but blamed shipping pallets
that had been treated, against European food regulations, with
toxic phenol or cresol.
</P>
<P>
   Not even wine seems safe. Last week, French inspectors seized
440 pounds of dried bull's blood that had been used, illegally, to
clarify cheap Cotes-du-Rhone and Cotes-de-Provence wines.
</P>
<P>
   All of that might seem to have little to do with genetic
engineering of vegetables, but there is a psychological connection;
a lack of confidence that the officials who are supposed to protect
Europeans from unseen dangers will do their job well, or even admit
there is a threat. In such an atmosphere, distrust of anything new
flourishes.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans also have one more reason to be wary about genetic
manipulation: Hitler had an interest in it. Nazi abuse of science
has left scars in the popular psyche that make European
environmentalist parties, especially in Germany, particularly
skeptical about the wisdom of toying with genes _ even in plants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0067 </DOCNO>
