<HEADER>
A0457 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CONGRESS-REVIEW-     06-26 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CONGRESS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 PULLING BUSH DOWN BY HIS COATTAILS  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089).  By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Gov. George W. Bush of Texas made a triumphant
visit to Capitol Hill last week, congressional Republicans grabbed
hold of him as if he were a life raft that could sail them all to
victory. But their clutch left some in both parties predicting that
Bush's Washington allies would only weigh down his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although he promised lawmakers that he would not ``bash members
of the Republican Congress,'' Bush, the son of the former
president, is in many ways already running against them. He decries
the partisan atmosphere in Washington that prevents the kind of
conciliation that leads to legislative compromise. He has sought to
soften the image of his party by calling himself a compassionate
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   But who has done more in recent years to make Republicans look
like hard-edged ideologues than the House Republican majority
brought to power by Newt Gingrich? From the government shutdown of
1995 to the impeachment of President Clinton in 1998, House
Republicans have been locked in bitter partisan clashes with
Clinton for years.
</P>
<P>
   Even now when their goal is to make no waves and let Bush become
their leader and spokesman, Republicans in the House cannot seem to
sidestep the kinds of controversies that could give pause to the
moderates and independent voters Bush will need to appeal to if he
becomes the party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Look what has taken place in the House this month alone. As the
peace settlement in Kosovo was being concluded and Clinton was
telling the nation it should be proud of driving back the forces of
Slobodan Milosevic, Republicans took to the floor to insist that
America had been defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is victory?'' asked Rep. William Goodling of
Pennsylvania. ``I call it a total disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Then within weeks the House was on to its debates over cultural
issues and gun control. Tom DeLay, the House majority whip, moved
to the fore with suggestions that day care and contraception were
causing youth violence. He called for creationism to be given equal
billing with evolution in schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Texan's jeremiad prompted George Will, a man of impeccable
conservative credentials, to ask DeLay on ABC's ``This Week With
Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts'' if he was a ``blaming America
first'' kind of Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Things are not expected to get prettier as the presidential race
moves ever nearer to the primary contests. Both political parties
expect a spectacular budget showdown over tax cuts and spending
this summer or fall, just the sort of confrontation Republicans
have shown a penchant for losing during the Clinton years.
Democrats are seeking to use Bush's many congressional endorsements
to tie him to the cuts in domestic programs that Republicans will
have to push through if they are to carry out their budget plan and
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush needs to speak out on this,'' said Roy Romer, the
general chairman of the Democratic National Committee. ``He cannot
sit idly by and let his allies in Congress rip apart programs for
families, and then say on the campaign trail that `I'm not going to
leave anybody behind.'''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Wittmann, a political analyst at the Heritage
Foundation, said Bush could also be hurt by a budget fight if his
congressional allies appear to give in to Clinton for a second year
in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a potentially serious mistake to embrace a
Congress that may ultimately frustrate the desires of the grass
roots of the Republican Party,'' Wittmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insists that his ties to Congress will not be a liability.
His persistently high poll ratings indicate that Congress is far
less of a drag on him than Clinton and the Lewinsky scandal are on
the leading Democratic contender, Vice President Al Gore. ``My job
is to talk about prosperity with a purpose, which I will do,'' Bush
said. ``I think attempts to tie me to DeLay and all that stuff, I
don't think it's going to hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Disillusioned voters could always elect Bush and then punish
Republicans in Congress by splitting their tickets and putting
Democrats in control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   It is also quite possible that Americans will not be as
alienated from Congress as Democrats hope. A survey conducted by Ed
Goeas, a Republican strategist, and Celinda Lake, a Democrat, found
that even though 52 percent of voters disapprove of the job
Republicans in Congress are doing, the electorate splits 39 percent
to 39 percent when voters are asked if they would prefer a Democrat
or a Republican for Congress. Twenty-two percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is hard to look like the embodiment of change when you
come to the Capitol and pose with the Washington establishment.
</P>
<P>
   William Kristol, editor of the conservative Weekly Standard,
predicted that Bush could eventually pay more for consorting with
the lobbyists who packed his Washington fund-raising reception on
Wednesday than for courting Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has said in the last two weeks that he's an opponent of
the status quo,'' Kristol said. ``Then he shows up at the Hilton
with 2,000 embodiments of the status quo and Washington insiders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
