<HEADER>
A0459 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALKAN-NATIONS-REVIEW     06-26 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKAN-NATIONS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR COUNTRIES ALIVE AND AILING IN THE BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(DW) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ A decade after the old Yugoslavia began to break up,
President Clinton paid a visit to the thriving, peaceful land of
Slovenia a week ago, followed quickly by a visit to bedraggled
Albanian refugees waiting to return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast could not have been greater, and the quick
succession of Balkan photo-ops hinted at how differently the
various parts of what once was Yugoslavia are faring these days.
</P>
<P>
   One lesson was hard to miss: The earlier these countries broke
off from Belgrade _ and the weaker the Serb claim to their land _
the better they are doing now.
</P>
<P>
   But comparisons among the republics that have broken away from
the Serb-dominated country that is still called Yugoslavia are more
complicated than that, because each of these lands had a different
role to play in the old Yugoslavia, and that role helped determine
its fate in the breakup.
</P>
<P>
   A quick glance at the four newly independent lands _ Slovenia,
Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina and Macedonia _ illustrates how
differently they are faring now.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenia, the old Yugoslavia's economic powerhouse, has been the
biggest winner.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did it break away first, with a war that was over in a
few days in 1991, but it always did have the best economic chance
to survive on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenia had strong, historic ties to its neighbors Italy and
Austria, and those ties lent realism to its ambitions to be part of
the new Europe. Today, they help account for the stability that
prompted Clinton to hold it aloft as a model for the rest of the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenians' purchasing power, at two-thirds the Western European
average, is close to that of Greeks, perhaps even equal.
</P>
<P>
   Slovenia also benefited from ethnic homogeneity; only a
smattering of Serbs and Croats live there alongside Slovenes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it qualified for consideration for future membership
in both the European Union and the NATO alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia was next to break away from Belgrade, in bitter fighting
in 1991 and 1992 that was followed by an ethnic cleansing campaign
in 1995 that evicted Serbs from Croatia and western Bosnia. The
Croats were the Serbs' major rivals in the old Yugoslavia, and
sizable numbers of Serbs lived within Croatia, so its secession was
traumatic.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia's leader, Franjo Tudjman, is a communist turned
nationalist, much like Milosevic; he too has cemented power under a
form of government that a British expert on the region, Timothy
Garton Ash, calls demokratura _ virtual dictatorship based on free
but not always fair elections and an authoritarian grip on power.
</P>
<P>
   In Serb-led Yugoslavia, the results of this style of rule are by
now well known. Milosevic has kept power during nearly a decade of
conflicts and international embargo, but the Serbian economy is in
ruins.
</P>
<P>
   In Croatia the picture is more mixed. Tudjman's brand of
nationalism has yielded some prosperity, but Croatians are
polarized politically, with Tudjman's Croatian Democratic Union
pitted against a harassed and divided opposition. Corruption is
widespread; heeding Western advice, Tudjman has sold off
nationalized industries, but the businesses have often gone to his
cronies. The banking system has been milked to fill his party's
coffers.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, the United States has supported the government in
Zagreb, and America is Croatia's biggest source of foreign
investment. Big construction contracts have gone to Enron Corp. and
Bechtel Corp. Recently the United States lifted an embargo on arms
sales and it has discussed drawing Zagreb closer to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   But the same human-rights advocates who have denounced Serb
atrocities against Bosnia's Muslims and Kosovo's Albanians are very
critical of Tudjman as well. His government's troops have been
accused of war crimes in the ethnic cleansing of Serbs in 1995, and
of not meeting all the commitments they made in signing the 1995
Dayton accords to pacify Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Kosovo has had a mixed effect. Croatian tourist
destinations are deserted but the ports have flourished.
</P>
<P>
   Tudjman was recently treated for cancer. Later this year Croatia
will hold elections, and the opposition is hoping to oust him. But
their divisions considerably reduce the chance of success.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia was hurt even more grievously in the breakup of
Yugoslavia, and the Kosovo war only complicates the picture.
Bosnian independence came at the price of a three-year war
characterized by Serb campaigns of ethnic cleansing, the siege of
Sarajevo and the division of the land, under NATO-led peacekeeping,
into a Serb-led republic and a Muslim-Croat federation. The war's
ferocity reflected the extent to which Croats, Serbs and Muslims
were intermixed.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, rampant inflation in what is left of Yugoslavia has
strengthened the marka, the new Bosnian currency, while it has
weakened the role of the Yugoslav currency, the dinar, in the
Bosnian Serb republic. But that region once did 70 percent of its
trade, mainly oil products and timber, with Yugoslavia, and in the
wake of the Kosovo war that business has withered.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a blow to Bosnia as a whole, whose economy now
relies almost entirely on international reconstruction money _ $5.1
billion over the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, a fragile political balance created by the Dayton
accords and enforced by NATO soldiers has held. This month, when a
Bosnian Croat, Ante Jelavic, assumed Bosnia's rotating presidency,
he pledged to accelerate Bosnian integration into the West. But
roughly 800,000 Bosnians remain displaced and only a few thousand
have returned to prewar homes in areas now controlled by other
ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, the southernmost of these lands, is the poorest; it
obtained independence in 1992 without a fight (it has deep ethnic
divisions but an insignificant Serb minority), and is often
portrayed as a contrast to its explosive neighbor, Kosovo. But
Macedonia also seems to be proving that a tolerant and enlightened
political leadership is no guarantee of economic progress.
</P>
<P>
   Last year elections produced a coalition government that united
the leaders of Macedonia's most polarized ethnic groups _ the
Macedonian Slavs (the majority) and the Albanians (about a quarter
of the population). The government inherited a stable but
dirt-poor, economy, with unemployment about 35 percent. Now the
Kosovo war has had a devastating effect. More than 250,000 Kosovar
Albanians poured in, taxing the economy and jeopardizing the ethnic
balance; lost trade and deals cost an estimated $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton arrived last week, the Kosovar Albanians he visited
were still waiting in Macedonia to go home, even as NATO used the
country as a route north for its peacekeepers. To the Macedonians
he pledged Western help to keep the country on the ``path of
prosperity, and even stronger democracy and freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonians, and others in the region, will be watching to see
how soon it arrives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
