<HEADER>
A0463 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DESTRUCTION-AR     06-26 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DESTRUCTION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVARS CONFRONT SYSTEMATIC RUIN IN THEIR COMMUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEC, Yugoslavia _ Rexhina Gashi, a 68-year-old Albanian woman
too stubborn to leave her block, says she stood on her balcony and
for two months watched the Serbs tear her city apart.
</P>
<P>
   First came the looting. On her street, a once-graceful row of
houses and shops with wooden roofs that runs from the main square
here to a white mosque, it was mostly soldiers and their
girlfriends. But some Serb civilians drove up with cars, she said,
cramming their trunks full.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the burning: Soldiers ignited bombs, she said, that
exploded into flames, quickly consuming the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Now this street, a market for half a millennium, is a heap of
bricks and metal, singed electrical wire looped around ash and
rubble. This work of destruction _ and it took a lot of work to
topple so much in so short a time _ was repeated across Kosovo,
often house to house, inflicting a vast amount of damage that has
barely begun to be tallied.
</P>
<P>
   Even before NATO began bombing on March 24, there was much
destruction in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But there appeared to be a shift, in focus and intensity, since
then: Before, the destruction was almost always confined to rural
areas, where the Yugoslav military could argue that it was flushing
out rebels with the Kosovo Liberation Army who lived, or could
hide, among Albanians there.
</P>
<P>
   In March, though, with the onset of NATO's bombing campaign, the
Yugoslavs took the destruction to cities like Pec and Djakovica in
the west and Mitrovica in the north, acting apparently out of pure
revenge, and a desire to drive the Albanians away for good.
</P>
<P>
   Werner Schellenberg, shelter coordinator in Kosovo for the U.N.
high commissioner for refugees, said he had seen more houses
destroyed fully: dynamited from the basement, set aflame
meticulously on every floor, and with roofs not merely damaged but
burned through.
</P>
<P>
   This suggests a campaign that went beyond military tactics. ``If
the KLA killed some police officers, in revenge the Serbs destroyed
an entire street,'' Mrs. Gashi said. ``When NATO attacked, they
burned everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mitrovica, virtually untouched before the NATO bombing, rows
of shops and houses downtown _ now patrolled by French peacekeepers
_ have been bulldozed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make a park?'' said Leon Ahmetovic, 26, a Kosovo Albanian
who returned to Mitrovica Friday, speculating on the motive. ``I
don't know. To exterminate Albanian people? They thought they could
stay here a long time? Maybe so. Maybe not.''
</P>
<P>
   He went down the street to see, for the first time since he fled
in early April, the mini-market that he and his family owned for
eight years. There were no windows. The ice-cream freezer was
burned and melted. All the goods were gone, some $5,000 worth.
Embers remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is supposed to be my shop,'' he said. Asked if he would
rebuild _ a question that collectively will determine the future of
Kosovo _ he said he was too discouraged to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this?'' he said. ``No. I have no money. It's too hard.
Maybe in a long time. But I don't think so. I have to start from
zero.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO troops arrived in Kosovo only two weeks ago, and so it is
too early for any but the most preliminary assessment of the damage
to property in Kosovo. But Schellenberg, whose organization must
cope with housing more than a million people displaced by the war,
has made an early survey, both by air around the province and by
foot here in Pec. And it is possible to compare the destruction
seen today to the damage from last year's fighting between Yugoslav
forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army that was chronicled in an
extensive study finished earlier this year by the U.N. refugee
agency.
</P>
<P>
   In that earlier survey of 89,998 houses in 625 villages _ areas
most damaged up to that point _ Schellenberg said 36 percent were
damaged to some extent, and 31 percent were considered
uninhabitable. That amounts to 27,672 uninhabitable houses, all in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   From his new preliminary survey almost two weeks ago, he said he
believed another 8,000 to 10,000 houses were now uninhabitable in
urban areas, mostly Pec, Djakovica and Mitrovica. In Pec, he said,
45 percent of the houses are uninhabitable, with some areas as much
as 90 percent destroyed. In Djakovica, he said, 30 percent of the
houses are uninhabitable. The capital city, Pristina, and Prizren,
in the south, did not suffer extensive damage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also estimates that another 2,000 to 3,000 houses have been
destroyed in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   This spring's destruction was all the more devastating, he
suggested, because he saw ``not a single'' house damaged in last
year's fighting and later repaired that had been left intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those houses which were temporarily repaired were
destroyed again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he saw interesting exceptions: Schools, Serb and
Albanian, were largely spared. As were big apartment buildings,
owned presumably by influential people. Most influential people
happened to be Serbs, regardless of who actually lived there.
``These were not damaged, which is good for the housing stock,''
Schellenberg said. ``But it's a clear indication there was a system
behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most of the damage was inflicted by the Yugoslavs, but there is
also damage from the NATO air campaign. In an observation supported
by two weeks of visits across Kosovo, Schellenberg said that most
of the bombs, in fact, seemed to hit specific targets like military
barracks and police stations.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition, several border villages were heavily damaged by
NATO bombs, as were bridges and houses near where the bombs fell.
</P>
<P>
   The war has hurt more than houses.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Bela Crkva in Kosovo's southwest, Isuf
Zheniqi, 39, returned to find his two buses, which provided half
his income, burned down to the frames. Here, villagers say 64
people were massacred, many of them the young men who were the
town's future.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, Safet Popaj, 60, looked over his burnt home and
announced: ``Kaput.'' In addition to the house, he said he lost
about 11,000 pounds of wheat, 6,600 pounds of corn and all seven of
his cows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had enough killing here,'' he said. ``But, you know,
economic casualties _ that's 100 percent of us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby village of Rogova, Rexhep Shala, 64, stood in his
own destroyed house but said it was not important on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``To survive we can just eat bread,'' he said. ``But to rebuild
_ now we are 20 years behind.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of hard-nosed practicalities, Schellenberg said he
believed the U.N. high commissioner for refugees would be able to
provide shelter for the returned refugees before winter. As in
Bosnia, the reconstruction in Kosovo will begin with efforts to
create one room in the house safe from weather. Then, by
mid-October, the plan is to make sure that room can withstand the
cold of winter.
</P>
<P>
   For that, he said, there are enough materials pledged by the
United Nations, the European Union, the United States and other
donors.
</P>
<P>
   But the long-term reconstruction requires a much greater effort,
not all of it monetary.
</P>
<P>
   A discouraging sign was the dozens of fires eating through
houses in a Serb and Gypsy neighborhood in Mitrovica. Albanians
looted jewelry, pots and pans, carpets. Mothers and children looted
together. Yet more homes were crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did the same to us,'' Nexhat Gjeloshi, 25, a Kosovo
Albanian, said as he walked unconcerned past the smoke. ``They did
worse to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
