<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0473 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-REPUBLICANS27-C     06-26 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-REPUBLICANS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young Republicans gather in Ohio
 &HT;    By Meggen Lindsay
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ They came to campaign. They came to network. They
came to hear their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And over four days they've drawn an impressive speaking list:
Charlton Heston and GOP presidential hopefuls John Kasich and Lamar
Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   The approximate 650 ``young'' Republicans, mostly white, many in
their 30s, converged at the Regal Hotel in Cincinnati this week to
elect officers, pass resolutions and meet politicians during the
four-day Young Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a lobbyist, I'm an accountant. I don't have a
political agenda,'' said California delegate Mark Szulc, 37, a
former national executive director of the Young Republican National
Federation. ``As cheesy as it may sound, I come to meet the future
leaders of our country. It's nice to be able to meet these people
on an informal basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization, which requires members to be between 18 and
40, approved a platform, elected its national officers, rallied
support for conservative causes _ and did its share of partying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to do the business and have as much fun as
possible in the process,'' said J. Mance Bowden III, executive
director of the Young Republican National Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Heston, the Oscar-award winning actor and president of the
National Rifle Association addressed the convention Thursday
afternoon. Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander spoke Friday
afternoon, while Ohio Congressman John Kasich will speak tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander was encouraged by the number and dedication of the
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the future of our party,'' he said. ``They are always
a big help on campaigns. I'm here trying to earn their support _
they make up a whole new generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander spoke during a luncheon, initially taking cracks at
Democratic candidate Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country doesn't need a president whose chief
accomplishment is being the number one cheerleader in Clinton's pep
rally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring parents, kids and schools to be the most important
campaign issues, Alexander urged giving parents tax breaks and more
flexible working schedules, but emphasized that the responsibility
for children lies with the parents, not the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is not at Washington, D.C., the answer is at
home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the Republican campaign, he warned about deciding
the GOP candidate too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we make a mistake on nominating the best candidate, we will
have 16 years of Clinton and Gore,'' he said. ``We'll be better off
if we have a contest within the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiming that the Republicans can't beat Gore without a strong
debate, Alexander suggested having monthly debates among the GOP
candidates to ensure his party's readiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election is too important to be bought and it ought not to
be inherited,'' he said. ``A sure fire way not to have the
best-prepared candidate is to anoint him or her without a
contest.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about GOP opponent George W. Bush, Alexander replied,
``He's not tested, he's not seasoned. He's good in the Texas
league, but he hasn't played in the national league.''
</P>
<P>
   The speeches seemed to energize the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are opportunities you just don't get on a regular
basis,'' said national committee woman Janie Wolfe, 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Young Republicans were also there for the nightlife.
</P>
<P>
   The co-chairman of Illinois' delegates, Gary Mendenhall, joked
that the best benefit about the convention was ``drinking beer.''
He later rephrased the fun as ``a state-to-state camaraderie.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention, which was hosted by the Ohio League of Young
Republican Clubs and the Blue Chip Republicans, took a little over
a year to coordinate. Cincinnati won the bid from a sight selection
committee, who came to the Queen City for a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It provides a great opportunity to show off a great time in
Ohio,'' said Bob Bennett, Ohio Republican Party Chairman. ``We have
a strong and active YR organization in Ohio, and this is another
way to energize young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
