<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0474 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRSTREAM27-COX     06-26 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRSTREAM27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Airstream still riding high
 &HT;    By Angela Townsend
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON CENTER, Ohio _ Audrey Farley of Florida had just
finished touring Airstream Inc.'s main assembly plant Thursday when
she and other curious members of the Wally Byam Caravan Club
International found their way to one of the company's latest motor
homes, the 39-foot Land Yacht XL.
</P>
<P>
   Farley, owner of an Airstream trailer for 20 years, peeked in
the bedroom, admired the wood kitchen cabinets and leather couches
and stopped with a look of wonderment in her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she was doing some comparison shopping, Farley laughed
and said, ``No, honey. I'm just wishing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The object of Farley's affection is a $220,000, top-of-the-line
motor home complete with television, stereo system, microwave and
queen-sized bed. About a dozen of these swank homes on wheels will
be available for sale by end of August.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 50 years the Airstream name has been synonymous
with quality and comfort. To many, Airstreams are the Cadillacs of
RVs.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin and Michael Collins were quarantined
in an Airstream trailer upon returning from their mission to the
moon in 1969. Today, space shuttle astronauts are driven to the
launch pad in an Airstream motor home.
</P>
<P>
   While a long-time favorite of well-heeled retirees, in more
recent years Airstreams have also become revered by younger
consumers and celebrities. Actors Anthony Edwards and Tom Hanks are
among the more famous Airstream owners who use them as dressing
rooms or to get to and from movie sets.
</P>
<P>
   The only place in the world where Airstream trailers and motor
homes are built is in Jackson Center, population 1,400, a rural
community about 60 miles north of Dayton in Shelby County.
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure why Airstream founder Wally Byam picked Jackson
Center to open a plant in 1952. Byam started building them in
California in the early 1930s, but was forced to stop production
during World War II after the aluminum alloy he was using was
classified as a critical war material.
</P>
<P>
   Byam, for whom the Wally Byam Caravan Club International is
named, resumed production in 1947. He started building Airstreams
in Jackson Center, most long-time employees believe, because he
wanted to improve Airstream's distribution in the Eastern United
States and received economic incentives from the village, said Mark
Wahl, Airstream's vice president of manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Byam died in 1962. But the Airstream product lives on as
American icon.
</P>
<P>
   Each afternoon at 2 o'clock, employees conduct tours for a few
dozen people, mostly Airstream owners and potential owners who want
to see how the product is made.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two weeks, with the Wally Byam rally taking place
in Fairborn, those tours have become larger and more frequent.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with Wahl. ``We think it's important for people to
see how their products are built,'' he said, adding that some come
specifically for the chance to see their own trailer or motor home
being built.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Uyematsu of California took a tour Thursday morning with 40
other early arrivals for this year's Wally Byam rally. Uyematsu
became an Airstream convert in 1968 for one simple reason: ``It was
easier to tow than the one I had,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is overwhelming for me,'' said Eileen Stadler of Oregon,
as she toured the plant with her husband, Bill. Both retirees, the
Stadlers are spending their entire summer in their 3-year-old
Airstream motor home. Next on the travel itinerary is a road trip
to Stadler's native Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
   It's this type of loyalty that helped Airstream weather the
tough times, such as the late 1970s when gasoline availability was
at an all-time low. That blow severely curtailed production and
prompted the company to lay off three-quarters of employees, shut
down facilities in Versailles, Ohio and Cerritos, Calif., and merge
all its operations into Jackson Center.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Airstream has more than 400 employees who work out of
Airstream's eight facilities in Jackson Center. They make 11 motor
homes and 12 trailers each week. The current manufacturing cycle
for a trailer is about eight days, while motor homes taken an
average 13 days to complete. Wahl estimates it takes about 300 work
hours to assemble some of the longer trailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've improved on efficiency, but the units are much more
complex today,'' Wahl said.
</P>
<P>
   The main assembly plant feels more like an overgrown garage than
the well-oiled manufacturing center it is.
</P>
<P>
   There's no assembly line; rather, teams of workers perform
various tasks in different buildings. One team assembles the
trailers' famous rounded shells out of large sections of aluminum
and aluminum alloy, while other employees build the chassis that
are later mated with the shells.
</P>
<P>
   Following assembly, finished units are inspected and tested for
leaks in a booth that simulates strong winds and torrential rain.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year marriage of Jackson Center and Airstream seems
solid.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been a very good business partner. We are really
blessed to have them here,'' said Jackson Center Mayor Scott
Klopfenstein, a former employee in Airstream's engineering
department and mayor for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Airstream generates significant income for the
village. But Klopfenstein also is proud of the other things
Airstream has provided the community, such as the two new village
welcome signs erected earlier this month and the new generator for
the village fire department.
</P>
<P>
   Airstream is equally enamored with Jackson Center. Airstream
plans to expand its 249,000-square-feet of manufacturing space to
accommodate larger models of trailers and motor homes with even
more amenities, and all of that expansion will take place in
Jackson Center, Wahl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've developed some strong roots in the community,'' he said.
``There's a great work ethic here. It just makes sense to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
