<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0476 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-LAWSUITS-REVIE     06-26 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-LAWSUITS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COURTS VS. SCIENTIFIC CERTAINTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(DW) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During years of fighting liability suits, makers of silicone
breast implants paid out more than $7 billion in verdicts and
settlements to women claiming injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last week, came a correction of sorts. An independent
scientific panel issued a report suggesting the courts had been
wrong; implants, the scientists said, didn't cause serious diseases
after all.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing earlier panels, the Institute of Medicine of the
National Academy of Sciences said silicone implants can cause
localized problems. But the report said there was no persuasive
evidence that the implants caused the more serious ailments that
some juries had blamed on them, like lupus and rheumatoid
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   The report, far too late to retrieve the $7 billion, made the
courts look foolish, hoodwinked by scientific speculation. It
highlighted sharp differences between legal and scientific
approaches to the search for truth, and increased the growing
pressure on the legal system to move away from its tradition of
letting juries sort out conflicting claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Science has become so sophisticated, and it is involved in so
many lawsuits, that the courts are having to come to terms with how
they are going to deal with it,'' said Paul R. Rice, a professor at
American University's Washington College of Law. ``And they are not
doing a very good job.''
</P>
<P>
   The struggle between scientific and legal approaches centers on
differing definitions of certainty. The two systems have different
goals, which often come into conflict in courtroom battles.
</P>
<P>
   Science, which never stops searching for answers, has a high
threshold for reaching conclusions: 95 percent certainty, some
scientists say, is necessary to decide that one thing probably
caused another. But the law must stop its search at the conclusion
of each case. So juries in civil cases are told that a mere
preponderance of the evidence _ 51 percent _ is enough certainty to
render a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   While the breast implant report was regarded by many as
authoritative, the battle is far from over. Lawyers for plaintiffs
attacked the report as little more than a rehash of earlier
studies, some of which were financed by the manufacturers, and
suggested that scientific research would one day conclude that
there were serious problems with the implants.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years critics of the way the legal system uses
scientific evidence have been winning. For years, judges have been
defending themselves against accusations that they permitted ``junk
science'' guesswork to persuade juries to conclude that all sorts
of products were responsible for illnesses and injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the criticism that courts were letting juries be
misled with untested scientific theories and, sometimes, mere
speculation, the Supreme Court and lower courts across the country
have begun to make new rules limiting scientific and technical
evidence that is presented to before juries. In a series of cases
beginning in 1993, the Supreme Court has said trial judges should
be more vigilant ``gate keepers,'' assuring that ``scientific
testimony or evidence admitted is not only relevant but reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle over breast implants and similar cases in which the
courts appeared to have reached incorrect scientific decisions have
accelerated the trend, which has often meant judges restrict the
scientific evidence that can be presented to jurors.
</P>
<P>
   As legal cases have become increasingly technical, said Peter H.
Schuck, a Yale law professor, the different legal and scientific
approaches have clashed more openly than ever before. ``Science is
always gaining new information,'' Schuck said. ``The law is the
opposite. It has to make a decision so people can get on with their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal system long ago recognized that legal and scientific
determinations might contradict each other, he said. For decades,
for example, individual smokers have had difficulty winning damage
suits against tobacco companies despite the overwhelming scientific
consensus that tobacco is linked to disease.
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars say the inconsistencies are a small price to pay
for a legal system that does not have the luxury of waiting for
scientific certainty. ``People just have to get used to the idea
that the legal system is imperfect,'' said Saul Levmore, a
professor at the University of Chicago Law School.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics say the courts have used their lower standard
of proof to encourage big verdicts in liability cases that are
supported by little more than weak theories. ``It is bad for the
rule of law,'' said David Bernstein, a professor at George Mason
University Law School in Arlington, Va., ``because the tort system
is supposed to be based on the proposition that you only pay when
you actually cause injury.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to insist on more definite scientific evidence
began in the 1980s, Schuck said, when some judges grew skeptical of
some of the scientific claims in high-profile cases. Judges began
to insist that plaintiffs' lawyers present epidemiological
evidence, for example, to back up the claims of doctors and other
expert witnesses that the products at issue had caused injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Two huge cases brought such critiques from judges. They involved
the claims of Vietnam veterans who said they were harmed by the
defoliant Agent Orange, and the claims of people who believed birth
defects were caused by the morning-sickness drug Bendectin.
</P>
<P>
   Critics called the plaintiffs in those cases blackmailers who
were capitalizing on the sympathies jurors have for injured people.
Such cases began a momentum that will now be spurred further by the
report on the silicone breast implants.
</P>
<P>
   But Rice and some other legal experts say startling disclosures
about companies that are exonerated by science after paying
billions of dollars are only part of the story. ``What about all
the cases of people who are now dead,'' he asked, ``and the company
was responsible and never had to pay?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
