have begun to make new rules limiting scientific and technical
evidence that is presented to before juries. In a series of cases
beginning in 1993, the Supreme Court has said trial judges should
be more vigilant ``gate keepers,'' assuring that ``scientific
testimony or evidence admitted is not only relevant but reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle over breast implants and similar cases in which the
courts appeared to have reached incorrect scientific decisions have
accelerated the trend, which has often meant judges restrict the
scientific evidence that can be presented to jurors.
</P>
<P>
   As legal cases have become increasingly technical, said Peter H.
