<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0480 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATE-POLITICS-REVIEW     06-26 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS STATE LAWMAKERS' POWER INCREASES, SO DOES GRIDLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(DW) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ With its preference for crossfire over consensus,
harangues over handshakes, the New York Legislature has long
engaged in an us-vs.-them tribalism that influences everything _
from the favors it bestows on constituents to the allocation of
water coolers in the Statehouse. Now, though, the coarse political
customs here have become so entrenched that state leaders have been
all but unable to perform their most fundamental duties.
</P>
<P>
   The state budget is three months late, preventing school systems
and nonprofit groups from doing modest planning. Significant
health-care proposals lie virtually untouched and the Legislature
cannot even agree on minor criminal justice initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the current vitriol, Albany used to be considered
something of a parliamentary freak show. But gridlock fueled by New
York-style partisan passions is spreading to state capitals around
the country.
</P>
<P>
   This trend is emerging in part because Washington has been
transferring power to the states on matters like welfare, providing
lawmakers with more to wrangle over and drawing more interest
groups into the fray. State authority was further strengthened by
last week's Supreme Court decisions that placed curbs on Congress'
ability to make federal law binding on the states.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the transformation of federal-state relations,
the other root of the partisanship has been growing political
competition. After decades in which control of most state
legislatures was solidly in the hands of one party or the other,
perpetual losers have turned the tables. In the once-Democratic
South, Republicans have made steady inroads. In the Midwest, the
balance in many legislatures is so precarious it has repeatedly
shifted in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this doesn't breed an environment of mutual
respect, cooperation and good feeling,'' said Chuck Chvala, a
Democrat who is now majority leader of the Wisconsin Senate for the
second time in the 1990s, after serving as minority leader twice.
Just last week, a Republican state senator, Bob Welch, demanded an
ethics investigation of Chvala, contending that he had committed
the sin of working on the budget in private.
</P>
<P>
   Term limits, which affect elected officials in almost 20 states,
have also had an impact, casting out entrenched lawmakers and
making its easier for opposition parties to win seats. The
newcomers, knowing their stay is limited, have less incentive to
try to push them out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, these tensions are likely to escalate because
parties in control after the next election will be able to draw
district lines based on the 2000 census, helping them _ through the
wonders of gerrymandering _ to stay on top.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, partisanship is not necessarily bad, especially if it
shakes up legislatures where one-party supremacy led to stagnation.
Not every statehouse has turned unruly. Today's good fiscal times
can go a long way toward salving disputes. It may be that
constituents are content to let lawmakers bicker the months away.
Still, the new tone is evident in many capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the fights over seats, another factor has been the
evolving character of lawmaking. Once strictly a part-time vocation
_ practically a hobby _ the post of legislator has become very
time-consuming in many states, with legislatures taking on some of
the trappings, and political sensibilities, of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, legislative leaders are setting up centralized
committees to collect political contributions, largely from donors
with business before their legislatures. Through these committees,
the leaders can maintain discipline among the rank and file, which
is more beholden to them for campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   The most visible symbol of this new era may have been the
squabbling earlier this year in the Alabama Legislature between
newly emboldened Republicans and old-guard Democrats. The
lieutenant governor, the first Republican to win the position in
this century, hunkered down in the Senate chamber for a
round-the-clock session, refusing to take a bathroom break lest the
Democratic senators trump him in his absence.
</P>
<P>
   Other states have also seen more contentiousness. In North
Carolina and Indiana, control over the lower house has ricocheted
from one party to the other and back again, with the newly ousted
minority stewing in exile and plotting its return to power.
California has often witnessed turmoil this decade _ including
tardy budgets a la Albany _ in part because of term limits.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, in roughly 65 percent of the states either
major party has a reasonable chance of seizing control, an increase
from less than 50 percent two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you had a 90-to-10 percentage split, it was almost a
nonpartisan state; partisanship didn't mean much to anybody,'' said
Malcolm Jewell, an emeritus professor of political science at the
University of Kentucky. ``There wasn't any point in trying to stick
together. You didn't need party cohesion.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, New York is not one of the places where
legislative races are more competitive. Partisanship in Albany
stems largely from the rivalry between the two houses, and not the
feuding inside. There are no term limits, and the majorities _
Republicans in the Senate, Democrats in the Assembly _ have used
the rules to cement absolute dominance.
</P>
<P>
   That aside, the skirmishes around the nation leave the
impression that there has been a steady Albany-ization of state
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are much more partisan, looking toward the next
election,'' said Paul Mannweiler, a Republican who is minority
leader in the Indiana House but who has also been speaker. ``We are
in the minority now, but we have to get back to the majority. To do
that, you have to draw some partisan differences.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
