<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0494 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-BOOKS-2TAKES-NY     06-26 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BOOKS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW GRAY MARKET AS CHINA LOOSENS GRIP ON PUBLISHING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In the cramped basement offices of Alpha Book Co.,
metal desks are stacked with manuscripts and a large poster of a
chimp in a red blazer headed ``The Boss'' dominates the room.
</P>
<P>
   Here, two thirtysomething editors, both with American graduate
degrees, skirt a legion of rules and regulations in order to bring
out surprisingly provocative books in a country where, officially,
all publications are state owned and controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Their hottest seller _ a collaboration with a state publishing
house _ is a translation of Paul Fussell's 1983 ``Class: A Guide
Through the American Status System.'' And they recently were hosts
of a book party for one of their authors, Yu Jie, whose chatty
essays tackle topics like the importance of dissent and how China
has changed since the 1989 protests in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere has opened enough so that we can put out things
we are interested in,'' said Shi Tao, the managing director of
Alpha, which was founded last year. ``We do a lot of critical books
because people want to read them. And we want to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   So far 1999 has been a chilly political period, marked by
sensitive anniversaries, dissident arrests and the closing of
several liberal publications. But a growing stream of adventurous
books and magazines has been bubbling up from under the ice, many
courtesy of new private companies like Alpha Books.
</P>
<P>
   There is no free press, of course. But these new publications
discuss a wide range of issues from corruption to sex to the need
for democracy in China in a frank and lively way virtually unheard
of in China before the 1990s; a number have become best sellers,
extremely popular among educated urban Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   And at some level, China's government has accepted, if not
embraced, these publications _ which at any rate are now probably
too numerous to control easily. Officials mostly turned a blind eye
toward the heavy traffic through legal loopholes that brings most
progressive books and magazines to press. And many experts see the
publications as possible harbingers of greater official freedom in
a country where the government has previously assiduously regulated
the printed word.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment it is free market economics that is spawning
liberalization and eroding government control: Having lost their
once hefty subsidies in the move to a market economy, the state
publishers have become increasingly willing to print controversial
material, looking to make money by catering to consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that I'm now able to publish my books is entirely
thanks to the emerging marketplace,'' said Mo Luo, an essayist and
author of the recent ``Notes from a Loser: A Free Thinker's Life
Experiences.'' ``In the current consumer environment you can't
survive publishing books that are dull and boring. So the
liveliness of the publishing world has opened up; there is wider
space for speaking out.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, nonetheless, limits to that space, and newspapers in
particular remain under tight control of a government clearly
mindful of the broad reach of the daily press. But with intense
business competition and a growing variety of publishing options,
even quite sensitive books and articles now often see the light of
day _ although often through circuitous routes.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, for example, all 50,000 copies of the May issue of
Beijing Literature were destroyed after an official loosely
connected with the magazine objected to a historical essay
extolling democracy _ a blow for free speech. But weeks later, that
same essay is already scheduled to appear in the July issue of
another publication, one with a different government sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, even though the government suspended the publishing
license of a progressive magazine called Way in February, a host of
equally adventurous magazines have taken up the torch, publishing
essays that have variously condemned totalitarian states, sung the
merits of free speech and favored a trial for the former ruler of
Chile, Gen. Augusto Pinochet. Violators of human rights ``cannot
rest peacefully,'' an article says.
</P>
<P>
   The tactics in getting such controversial words into print are
legion: Independent book editors collaborate with struggling state
publishers, essentially subcontracting to provide both a manuscript
and marketing skills. Monthly magazines call themselves ``book
series,'' since periodicals are more tightly regulated than books.
Magazine editors ally with cash-strapped government agencies to
secure licenses to bring out magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Panorama Magazine, for example, is a new upscale magazine of
culture and social thought, whose soul (and editors) are in urbane
Shanghai. But it is officially put out by a distant textbook
publisher, the Liaoning Educational Publishing House, which wanted
to diversify and hoped that owning a lively magazine would attract
new book authors.
</P>
<P>
   Another increasingly popular method for bringing out books is
for independent book companies to purchase directly from a state
publisher a new ``book number'' _ the government license plate that
each new book carries to indicate it is legally published.
</P>
<P>
   All these arrangements give progressive intellectuals access to
printing presses, and give state publishers access to cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very complicated process and there are many
secrets,'' said Li Yu, a book agent and general manager of the
Beijing Blue Monsoon Culture Co., a book company.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's clear that the market economy can be seen as a way to
move toward intellectual freedom. And the government is itself to
an extent adjusting to the situation; you can see they're tacitly
accepting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Through these cracks have emerged a steady stream of popular
books that are testing the limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are massive numbers of publishers who are concerned with
economic gain, so I've been able to publish my books even though I
know there are senior officials who are very unhappy with the
content,'' said Yu, whose first book of essays, ``Fire and Ice,''
was a major hit last year.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of today's progressive authors, Yu said he had been
writing for many years but only recently started publishing his
essays, which, for example, poke fun at Mao's personality cult and
recall his own struggle to conform to life at the military college
where incoming college freshman were sent for political
indoctrination after the June 4, 1989, crackdown in Tiananmen
Square.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He notes with some satisfaction that although Hong Kong and
Taiwanese newspapers had predicted his books would be banned, he
published his fourth volume this spring, and has more requests than
he can handle from magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways the situation is very awkward, but at least now
someone like me is able to publish these kind of essays _ and
that's not bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Progressive magazines and book series have also continued to
expand.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue of Observe magazine, published early this year,
features a translation of ``Power of the Powerless,'' the 1978
essay by Vaclav Havel, who is now president of the Czech Republic,
which analyzed totalitarian regimes and the value of resisting
them. It is followed by a critique of post-totalitarian states that
must seem close to home to China's leaders. ``The powerholders have
no choice but to add a little law (but by no means rule of law),
consumerism is on the rise, and corruption grows steadily more
serious,'' reads the essay.
</P>
<P>
   Articles in Frontiers endorse the ``opening up of public
opinion,'' and criticize the country's death penalty; one in Reform
shows how government growth figures overstate actual economic
progress, and one in Panorama praises a gay version of ``Swan
Lake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is now willing to tolerate much more freedom in
the exchange of ideas,'' said Xiao Gongqin, a professor of modern
history and essayist in Shanghai. ``So long as you're not chanting
slogans like `Down With Jiang Zemin,' the atmosphere is much more
relaxed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Every author is aware of forbidden territory, however, even if
the acreage has shrunk over the years. Publishers and editors risk
official criticism and even their jobs if they aid and abet
projects that stray too far over the invisible and ever changing
line.
</P>
<P>
   In this sensitive year, editors and authors agree that limits
have contracted somewhat. Essays that last year might have been
reprinted in official newspapers now settle in obscure academic
journals, and state publishing houses have been more cautious in
selling their book licenses. And references to the Tiananmen
protests, difficult at the best of times, are this year out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a state publisher refused to put out a book
by a young intellectual until several passing references to the
1989 crackdown were removed, said Xu Xun, project director of Alpha
Books, which had invested in the book.
</P>
<P>
   But most editors said they were content to lay low for the
moment, since all hope that freedoms will expand once the
anniversaries pass. ``We're brand new and don't want to commit
suicide,'' said an editor of Panorama, who refused to be
identified. ``When circumstances allow, we'll say things that are
politically a bit more out of line or run pieces even more worthy
of being called spiritual pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been signs that at least some in the government favor
cutting the publishing industry loose, officially allowing private
publishers to operate. Last year, just before a major government
book fair, hundreds of independent publishers and agents were
allowed to organize a shadow fair in the same town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that last year will be the last gasp of official
efforts to strictly control books, newspapers and magazine,'' said
Yu, the writer. ``Now that economic reform in China has reached
this extent, it's hard to go back. Recent actions have been largely
symbolic acts to scare others.''
</P>
<P>
   But already, he and others said they have gained considerable
room for maneuver. ``With an increasing number of magazines, if I
can't publish something in Beijing, I can always go to Shanghai or
Wuhan,'' said Yu. ``And if a magazine gets shut down because the
government is not happy with its views, another will pop up.''
</P>
<P>
   A new book called the ``Fallen Temple,'' a fond recollection of
the underground avant-garde that existed during Mao's era, was
first rejected by two Beijing publishers and then taken by the
Xinjiang Young People's Publishing House, in far western China.
</P>
<P>
   It is an odd game of cat-and-mouse, where the mice are
multiplying and the old cat often seems not terribly hungry.
</P>
<P>
   When Way was very publicly closed down this spring, its founders
were told that they had strayed from their mandate: The magazine,
which covered a broad range of topics, came under the aegis of the
Beijing Committee on Science and Technology and should have stuck
to scientific matters, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief battle to save the magazine, the editors
scattered. But they did not fall into line. They are now working on
the start-up of a new newspaper featuring articles on culture and
leisure, the Chinese Cooperation News, this time sponsored by the
Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
