<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0496 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTRICITY-TRADING27     06-26 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRICITY-TRADING27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern foresees smoother trading
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Southern Co. is off to a smooth start this summer with
its electricity trading business, and executives do not foresee a
repeat of last year, when a sudden heat wave sent wholesale prices
soaring to crisis levels.
</P>
<P>
   At this time last year, Southern was dealing with an
unprecedented run-up in national wholesale electricity prices,
triggered when Midwesterners ramped up air conditioners all at
once.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the Midwest, the prices power companies paid for
wholesale electricity rose from $30 to $7,000 per megawatt hour,
and several smaller trading companies were unable to meet their
obligations. An average U.S. home uses 1 megawatt hour of
electricity per month.
</P>
<P>
   The city-owned utility of Springfield, Ill., defaulted on
contracts to sell power to several large utilities because of the
trading volatility. One of those agreements was to sell power to
Southern for $10 million _ much less than the wholesale market
value at the time.
</P>
<P>
   That dispute is still being litigated, though Southern
executives say the Atlanta-based company made more money than it
lost in the wholesale trading frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thrive on volatility. The key to commodity prices is supply
and demand,'' said Gary Morsches, chief operating officer of
Southern Company Energy Marketing, the company's energy trading
unit.
</P>
<P>
   Morsches said he does not expect a repeat of last year's
defaults, even if temperatures and prices skyrocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit controls have been strengthened throughout the
industry, and weaker players have left,'' he said. ``Poorly
capitalized entities are not being traded with.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Brian McGee, Southern's director of forward power
trading, wholesale markets have already seen a price spike this
year. Hourly prices in the Northeast rose from $40 to $1,000 per
megawatt hour during a June 7-8 heat wave but created no problems
for trading companies.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the market has been ``pretty quiet'' so far, he said.
The big question is whether unforeseen shortages are created if
power plants are shut down during the high-demand summer months, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Company Energy Marketing is 60 percent owned by
Southern and 40 percent by Houston-based Vastar Resources, a
natural gas company. The wholesale trading unit represents one of
Southern Co.'s moves into unregulated utility markets.
</P>
<P>
   Southern operates the unit and is due to raise its stake to 75
percent during the next three years. SCEM buys and sells
electricity across the country but is prohibited from sales inside
Southern's regulated service territory in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   SCEM operates a 24-hour electricity and natural gas trading
floor that can accommodate as many as 200 traders at Perimeter
Center. The operation will more than double in size when it moves
to new quarters in nearby Sandy Springs in December.
</P>
<P>
   Southern is on a crash program to purchase power plants around
the country to become less dependent on volatile electricity
sources for its wholesale business.
</P>
<P>
   Even after $1.3 billion in power plant purchases in California
and the East Coast, only 5 percent of the power sold will come from
Southern's own system.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
