<SLUG> BC-GOLF-DEPRIVATION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOLF OASIS FOR THE WEALTHY IS A DESERT FOR EVERYONE ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOHANSIC, N.Y. _ Almost every Saturday night, Ron Bucci, a
chiropractor from Tarrytown, kisses his wife and three children
goodbye and drives the family van up to Mohansic Golf Course, where
he sleeps in the parking lot with carloads of other men from
Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Bucci arrives around 8 p.m., early enough to tap a few
balls around Mohansic's putting green, down a bottle of beer or two
at the bar and engage in ritual male banter. Sleep is scarce, and
by 4 a.m., the groggy platoon of unshaven fathers, husbands and
boyfriends wanders into the cozy clubhouse to collect the holy
grail of public-access golf: a Sunday morning tee time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got mailmen up there sleeping, construction workers,
correction officers, cops, accountants,'' said Bucci, 40, a
seven-year veteran of the Mohansic sleepovers. ``If the manager of
the course wants to get an early spot, he's up there sleeping,'' he
said. ``I'm lucky. I have a van. Some guys sleep in the front seat
of their car.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that Westchester County, golf oasis for the
wealthy, is a golf desert for everyone else. Though the county is
peppered with 61 golf courses, only five are open to the free-range
duffer, that particular golf subspecies who cannot afford even a
mid-range private club's $150,000 membership fee and $10,000 in
annual dues.
</P>
<P>
   Long Island, by contrast, is home to 64 private and 50 public
courses. In southern Connecticut, many towns operate their own
public courses.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has become so bad in recent years that Westchester _
one of the most affluent counties in the nation _ is now among the
most golf-deprived, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: The county's five public courses, operating at
capacity, were host to 270,000 rounds of golf last year, meeting
less than 20 percent of the estimated demand for 1.5 million annual
rounds, according to a report by the National Golf Foundation. ``If
there was anywhere in the country that I would build a golf course,
it would be in Westchester County,'' said Angelo Palermo, the
Florida-based golf-course consultant who submitted the report to
county officials in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   County officials appear ready to take such advice to heart. By
the end of this week, County Executive Andrew J. Spano plans to
choose from among five multimillion-dollar bids, including one from
his own Parks Department, to build a public course on the grounds
of the defunct Hudson Hills Golf Club in New Castle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was ever a slam-dunk project,'' Palermo said, ``this
is it.''
</P>
<P>
   The new course is still at least two years from reality. Though
the county bought the 170-acre property from IBM in December 1997
for the bargain price of $3.5 million, officials have done little
with the land, which is dense with bramble, bogs and white-tailed
deer.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Schwartz, Spano's deputy, said constructing the course
would cost less than $10 million, a relative bargain. Nowadays,
with land scarce, and environmental regulations ever more complex,
even a starter golf course can cost $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they manage to get a tee time, Westchester golfers
face less-than-ideal conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public golf is nuts,'' said Frank Madalone, 33, a dentist from
Yonkers, swinging a 3-iron just off the first tee on a recent
Friday at Sprain Lake Golf Club, where 54,197 rounds were played
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play on the weekend, it's insanity. The fairways overlap,
balls flying everywhere,'' he said, shaking his head. ``It's like a
firing range out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' he added, taking the measure of the course before
him, ``even for $12, it's not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on weekdays, Westchester's public courses are crowded,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way: If you want a tee time at 3 o'clock in
the afternoon on a weekday, on a 95-degree day, you can probably
find one,'' said the county's parks commissioner, Salvatore
DeSantis.
</P>
<P>
   The dearth of public golf is not unique to Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no place that is undersupplied in golf as much as the
New York area,'' said David Leibowits, a golf course developer at
Centennial Golf Club, a 27-hole course in Putnam County that
charges $105 for a weekend round. ``People drive an hour and a half
to two hours for golf,'' he said. ``The demand is unlimited.''
</P>
<P>
   Many things have conspired to make that so.
</P>
<P>
   After an ebb in golf's popularity in the 1970s and 1980s, more
women and youths are playing than ever, industry analysts said.
That is especially true in Westchester, home of some of the most
exclusive private clubs in the country and a 32-year-old
professional tournament now known as the Buick Classic, at
Westchester Country Club in Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   The shift is evident at Ardsley High School, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf club used to be five kids,'' Henry Tina, the school's
golf coach, said at Mohansic's second hole on Saturday. ``I got 18
kids now. Where are they going to play?''
</P>
<P>
   Until a few years ago, he said, local private clubs allowed the
team to practice on their courses. Now they squeeze onto Sprain
Lake's course.
</P>
<P>
   Pro golf's marketing of its young, camera-ready stars like Tiger
Woods has also brought legions of young wannabes to public courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have so many guys wearing pink now,'' said Anthony
Federico, of Ardsley, waiting with Tina under a maple tree at
Mohansic's second hole.
</P>
<P>
   Money is also a factor: The economy's years-long boom has made a
decent set of clubs a less intimidating purchase, and a public
course's greens fee is often less expensive than a movie, soda and
popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence of the surge, however, the quality of the
public courses has dropped as they absorb more rounds from
inexperienced players. Last year, golfers played 30 million rounds
on New York state's 857 courses, industry statistics show, an
average of about 35,000 per course.
</P>
<P>
   But in Westchester County, Dunwoodie, the least active course,
clocked 48,884 rounds, according to the county's Parks Department.
Saxon Woods, in Scarsdale, crammed in 61,772 rounds. ``That's
seven-minute tee-time intervals,'' Palermo said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many local golfers leave.
</P>
<P>
   Federico and Madalone, the dentist, both said they drive up to
two hours to play more expensive golf in Dutchess County,
Connecticut or Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' Federico lamented. ``It seems like such a shame
that we're in such a wealthy county.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another, perhaps more disturbing trend that veteran
golfers say is sweeping Westchester County's public-access golf
courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more anger on the golf course,'' said John
Lewandowski, 52, a sales and marketing executive from South Salem,
after whacking a 150-yard drive past Mohansic's first hole one week
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, they don't care about anybody else. They don't rake the
bunkers. They don't wait for people to leave the green.''
</P>
<P>
   What really galls him is the flying balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll hit close to you to sort of move you along,''
Lewandowski said, leaning on his putter. ``That can be dangerous.
Golf balls hurt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
