<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AIRPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACEKEEPERS, AT LAST, REOPEN PRISTINA AIRPORT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SLATINA, Yugoslavia _ Two weeks after the first NATO
peacekeepers arrived in Kosovo, the first military aircraft landed
here Saturday at the province's main airport, which NATO commanders
said could soon open to regular flights.
</P>
<P>
   A hulking Russian cargo plane touched down at 1:19 p.m.,
followed moments later by a French C-130 in what was an
orchestrated effort to highlight the cooperation of Russian and
allied troops after the diplomatic standoff caused when a
contingent of Russians occupied the airport on June 12, hours
before NATO's forces started streaming into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's commander in Kosovo, Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, appeared
at the airport with his Russian counterpart, Col. Gen. Viktor
Zavarzin, and both pledged to work together toward peace in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said that once NATO ferries in the necessary radar and
other equipment to get the airport functioning over the next week,
regular military flights could begin, followed by relief flights
and, eventually, even commercial ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all part of bringing Kosovo back to normality,''
Jackson said outside the airport's terminal, whose windows were
blown out by NATO's repeated airstrikes against Yugoslav troops
based there.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the airport, located about 10 miles west of the
capital, Pristina, should help speed the deployment of sorely
needed troops, equipment and relief supplies. The peacekeeping
force has grown slowly as the NATO allies have had to amass troops
in Macedonia and then move them north along narrow roads,
increasingly crowded with refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, NATO's senior commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, said he
had called on the allies to move more quickly to build up their
forces in Kosovo, which has been wracked by violence and
retribution between the province's remaining Serbs and the
returning Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The reports of looting have continued, despite pledges by NATO
commanders to step up foot and vehicle patrols.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, gunshots echoed around Pristina. Late Friday, U.S.
marines at a checkpoint in Gnjilane were involved in another
firefight that left one Serb dead.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's spokesman, Lt. Col. Robin Clifford, said Saturday that
the gun battle appeared to have begun as a shootout between Serbs
and Albanians. He said that the dead man had been killed by a
bullet from an AK-47, the weapon of choice among armed Serbs and
Albanians, not an American M-16, issued to marines. Three Serbs and
two Albanians were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday about 200 Albanians demonstrated in Mitrovica, where
Serbs have cordoned part of the city. But the protesters were
persuaded by Hashim Thaci, the leader of the Kosovo Liberation
Army, not to provoke a confrontation. Jackson and Sergio Vieira de
Mello, the U.N. special representative for Kosovo, met with Serbs
in the city's hospital in an effort to calm tensions.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport, Jackson welcomed the arrival of 39 Russian
soldiers on the cargo plane Saturday, along with tons of equipment,
a day after Russia's Parliament approved the deployment of as many
as 3,600 troops in Kosovo. ``I'm very keen to get every soldier I
can at the moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The airport is opening under the terms of an agreement reached
in Finland a week ago between American and Russian ministers that
resolved the embarrassing impasse created when the Russians used
their de facto control of the airport as leverage in securing a
role for Russia in NATO's operation.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement itself reflects the lingering wariness between
NATO and Russia, which was evident when Russian troops refused for
a time to let British troops enter the airport to prepare for the
news conference. Under the agreement, the first 12 military flights
are evenly divided between NATO and Russian aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Zavarzin emphasized that Russia's participation would make the
peacekeeping force truly multinational, even though NATO troops
will still make up the overwhelming majority of the force, which
will eventually grow to nearly 60,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   The media controlled by the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic, in particular, have stressed Russian participation as
part of their message that Milosevic in fact kept control of
Kosovo, and the foreign force in the province consists partly of
fellow Orthodox Slavs, the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have witnessed are the latest steps to ensure a
multinational presence in Kosovo,'' Zavarzin said as the Russians
unloaded cargo from their aircraft. Russian troops will operate as
distinct units in the American, French and German sectors of
Kosovo. Some 700 will control the airport grounds, providing
security and maintenance, although NATO forces will have
responsibility for air traffic control. ``We have to fulfill this
mission together,'' Zavarzin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
