<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ Gov. George W. Bush airlifts his presidential dream to
California this week, a state rich with opportunity but fraught
with
</P>
<P>
   political peril. The opportunity for Bush lies in a vote-rich
Hispanic community he has targeted and a cash-rich high-tech
community that seems up for grabs. But for Bush, and all GOP
contenders, the California peril lies in a fractured state party
that is reeling from defeats. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-REPUBLICANS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ They came to campaign. They
came to network. They came to hear their leaders. And over four
days they've drawn an impressive speaking list: Charlton Heston and
GOP presidential hopefuls John Kasich and Lamar Alexander. The
approximate 650 ``young'' Republicans, mostly white, many in their
30s, converged at the Regal Hotel in Cincinnati this week to elect
officers, pass resolutions and meet politicians during the four-day
Young Republican National Convention. (Lindsay, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WARCRIMES _ IZBICA, Yugoslavia _ Churned earth has
replaced the neat rows of mounds that told the world a mass grave
was here. A few detached body parts may remain in the clods of
dirt, along with the errant shoe or muddy blanket once used to wrap
a body. But gone are the corpses, the most compelling evidence of a
heinous crime. The story of the Izbica (Is-BEE-tsa) massacre, in
which more than 140 people are said to have been executed, is one
of seven counts in the war crimes indictment against Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic. Here in Kosovo that justice will be
terribly difficult to attain even where there has not been
intentional evidence tampering. There is ample opportunity for
evidence to be ruined simply by the passage of time and intrusion
of innocent people to crime scenes that have no guard, no fences or
even any markings. Developing. (Kunstel, Cox News Service). 25.
WITH PHOTOS. MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WARCRIMES-BOX _ The seven counts against Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic. (Kunstel, Cox News Service). 10. MOVED
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY-PROFILE-COX _ SYDNEY, Australia _ Sydney 2000 backers
like kangaroos, but they'd rather you come to their country looking
for something a little more sophisticated. Discussing Sydney's
image while dining at Nick's, a harborside restaurant in the
Darling Harbour area of downtown Sydney, the worries seem
overblown: A monorail (bearing an advertisement of an Olympic
sponsor) and water ferries traverse the harbor ahead. Within
walking distance are shops, restaurants and the massive hall where
wrestling, judo and a host of other Olympic sports will be played.
This has the look, the feel and the amenities of one of THE
gathering spots during the Sydney Olympics, which start Sept. 15,
2000. And unlike Atlanta in 1996, Sydney's downtown gathering spot
already exists. ``That is one of the nice things: We've got this
great gathering spot that is already in place, waiting for the
Olympics,'' said Peter Christopher, a newspaper executive guiding a
visitor through the city. Although there are worries about the
Olympic bribery scandal affecting the organizers' ability to raise
the rest of the money to host the 2000 Olympics, venue construction
and other preparations are in good enough shape that supporters are
able to worry about things like image. (Reetz, Cox News Service)
WITH PHOTOS and MAP (3-column map of Sydney showing venues) MOVED
MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: This story will be made into a bonus CoxNet FOCUS page
that will move on Friday, June 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DROUGHT _ ZACATECAS, Mexico _ A late spring storm was
enough to bring out thirsty rattlesnakes in Mexico's high central
plains, but it didn't impress farmer Apolonio Hernandez. With a
face as parched and wrinkled as the land he tries to farm,
Hernandez sat impassively under a mesquite tree while clouds
spattered the ground several miles away. Once again, Central and
Northern Mexico is suffering from drought that's jeopardizing
everything from vegetables for export to beans for domestic
consumption. It's the kind of periodic episode in this central
Mexican state that puts people out out of business, communities in
crisis and sends desperate people searching for work in Mexico's
cities or in the United States. Even with rainfall, the governor
says, Mexico's water problems won't subside without a major
overhaul of agricultural policy. (Ferriss, Cox News Service). 30.
WITH PHOTOS and LOCATOR MAP INFORMATION.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Friday in (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
