<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GAY-ATLANTA _ ATLANTA _ The banners hanging all over downtown
and Midtown are simple. ``Celebrate,'' they say, over stripes of
different colors that look like a piece of a rainbow or a Life
Savers wrapper. For some, the banners, which are flying for the
first time in three decades of gay pride festival, represent the
growing acceptance and clout of Atlanta's gay community, one of the
country's largest. For others, the message is so simple it's
useless, a reminder, instead, of how far gays and lesbians have to
go before being fully accepted. (Croft/Crenshaw, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 50. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CEMENTPLANT _ BRANFORD, Fla. _ It's one of those simple,
Deep-South pleasures that country folk take for granted and city
folk may drive hours to enjoy: floating down an ice-cold,
spring-fed river in the heat of summer on a fat rubber tire tube.
Thousands flock each summer to North Florida's Ichetucknee Springs
State Park to do just that, drinking in the unspoiled natural
splendor of a crystal-clear river. But a proposal to build a large
cement plant a few miles away from the river has triggered a
controversy, splitting the small communities that dot the rural
countryside near the Ichetucknee. (MWilliams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OYSTERS _ ORANGE BEACH, Ala. _ Gulf Coast sea food dealers are
fighting a new round of accusations that raw oysters can kill you.
Ever since ``Good Morning America'' came to Mobile late last month
and reported on the growing dangers of the vibrio vulnificus
bacteria in Gulf waters, Alabama Sea Food Association leaders have
been trying to reassure the public that raw oysters are good for
people. A look at the controversy. (David, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution free-lancer; not for use by NYTNS clients)
</P>
