<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0514 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-POLICE-ART-840     06-26 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POLICE-ART-840(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENSNARED IN LOGISTICS, U.N. LAGS IN ASSERTING CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The lines of people standing outside
office buildings in Kosovo's capital show where they think the
power lies. Saturday, dozens of young people were filling out forms
applying for jobs at the new headquarters of the U.N. mission here.
</P>
<P>
   Another line of people waited outside the central NATO military
police station to report theft or damage to their property over the
last few months. By contrast, the Serbian government building, once
the bastion of local power, stands almost deserted, its windows
blown out and three British soldiers guarding the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   People know that the U.N. mission is to be the civilian
administration in Kosovo. As yet, however, its presence is barely
felt. A U.N. flag flies over the former Defense Ministry building
and a few white U.N. cars are parked outside. The offices are
largely empty and smell of new paint.
</P>
<P>
   The mission is still at the stage of recruiting people, the U.N.
secretary-general's special representative to Kosovo, Sergio Vieira
de Mello, acknowledges. He himself is only an interim chief and
does not know when a permanent representative will be appointed.
</P>
<P>
   He has yet to appoint his five civilian regional administrators
although last week he said he had selected three. One priority is
to appoint six local judges to deal with the dozens of suspects
arrested by the few military police who arrived with the NATO
forces on charges ranging from petty theft to multiple murder. That
has taken all week and the judges have yet to get to work.
</P>
<P>
   The most pressing need is for an international police force to
tackle the crime that has flourished with the exit of the Serbian
police and military forces and many Serbian civilians and the
return of over 300,000 Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   For these past two weeks, what little policing that has taken
place has been the work of NATO soldiers whose powers to stop every
incident of looting, burning, harassment or other violence have
been severely stretched.
</P>
<P>
   The first 40 police officers of a planned 3,000-strong
international police force will arrive on Tuesday, more than two
weeks after NATO arrived in Kosovo. The process of acquiring police
officers from member countries is so time-consuming that the 40
officers are borrowed from the U.N. mission in nearby Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials estimate that it will be three months before all
3,000 officers are in place. ``We don't enjoy what the armies
enjoy,'' said Fabricio Hochschild, special assistant to the acting
head of the mission. ``We're a cash-strapped, under-funded
organization. We don't have civil administrators and police who can
be put on planes and brought here in 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Vieira de Mello, a Brazilian diplomat who ran the U.N. mission
in Cambodia, pleaded for understanding. ``Governments would not
provide funds'' for Kosovo, before June 14, two days after NATO's
entry, ``when they got a Security Council resolution,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Staff will increase gradually, he said, and interpretation of
the United Nations' exact mission here and how to structure
civilian administration are only now being decided. ``We are
inventing right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mission is bogged down in technicalities, waiting for
headquarters to decide on key issues of international law, such as
how to structure immigration, customs and security at Kosovo's
border in a way that will ensure the still formally existing
sovereignty of Yugoslavia over this ruined province. Who will pay
pensions, social security and salaries of state employees is
another dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Vieira de Mello has been shuttling around trying to keep the
political scene free of strife, bringing together the leaders of
the Serbian and Albanian communities together to try to prevent an
increase in violence. ``If we let ourselves be discouraged by early
signs of intolerance, we will not succeed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has been sharply criticized over one of the most obvious
tasks, securing public buildings and records. U.N. officials did
move in to seal the district court building, and all the documents
still inside, shortly after arriving in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Executive Council, the main government building in the
city, and virtually every other official building were ignored.
Even when reports emerged of Serbian officials destroying documents
in the government building, the United Nations merely asked the
Serbian head of government, Zoran Andjelkovic, to desist.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after two days when reporters spotted government
workers loading up a truck full of paper material that the United
Nations took more determined action. A full 12 days after NATO
troops came into Kosovo, soldiers were posted in the government
building to prevent any further material being removed.
</P>
<P>
   Vieira de Mello said it had been his decision, since he had to
request the use of NATO soldiers and effectively take them away
from their job of restoring general security. ``I have to choose
between static tasks or the active tasks they are doing to secure
the environment,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A member of the mission criticized the U.N. stance on the
government building, saying it set a weak precedent in the crucial
early stages of the mission. He warned that the failure to act in
such instances could embolden the Kosovo Liberation Army, which in
the absence of any other authority has already assumed de facto
control in several towns and villages across the province.
</P>
<P>
   This process of shifting control has been illustrated all this
past week at Pristina hospital as Albanian doctors and medical
staff returned to take up their old jobs. Some had been laid off
just three months ago, some as long as 10 years ago, by a policy
that favored Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Their arrival, along with wounded soldiers of the KLA, raised
tensions to such a degree that the Serbian staff began to fall
away. Saturday, a young man in civilian clothes was guarding the
main door of the surgical ward. He readily admitted he was a member
of the KLA and said that there were no more Serbian personnel at
the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should they expect to keep their jobs, after they pushed
out all the Albanians?'' he said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   Along the street at the university faculty buildings, a convoy
of 50 cars of Serbian families was pulling out of the city, leaving
for Serbia or Montenegro. They were leaving modern, prosperous
looking homes. On the doors of each, in Albanian, were scratched
taunting messages. ``Jaha, don't touch,'' read one, as if an
Albanian had already marked it as his property.
</P>
<P>
   An engineer who gave his name only as Ivan said the KLA had
taken over the power station where he worked at Obilic, not far
from Pristina, and told the Serbian personnel to leave. Then, Ivan
said, he received threats on the telephone. ``That's what did it
for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Andjelkovic was there trying to persuade the Serbs not to leave.
But as the convoy drove off, he threw his hands up. ``No, I failed.
I couldn't persuade them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
