<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0516 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORCHESTRAS27-COX     06-26 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORCHESTRAS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playing, promoting new music tops orchestra league agenda
 &HT;    By Carol Simmons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ When more than 1,500 musicians, office staff, board
members and volunteers representing many of the nearly 900
orchestras affiliated with the American Symphony Orchestra League
congregated in the Windy City earlier this month for the league's
annual confab, they had one topic on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Music.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound obvious. But it ain't necessarily so.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1942 and chartered by Congress in 1962, the orchestra
league is the symphonic world's nonprofit trade organization. Soon
to move to New York City from its longtime base in Washington,
D.C., the ASOL's mission is ``to provide leadership and service to
American orchestras while communicating to the American public the
value and importance of orchestras and the music they perform.''
</P>
<P>
   But orchestras are in the business of making music, and it's the
business end that gets much of the ASOL focus and support.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, the focus has shifted.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the 21st century, the organization has launched a
five-year initiative dedicated to the performance of contemporary
American music. Dubbed ``Music for a New Millennium,'' the effort
involves more than encouraging the playing of new music; it's about
helping orchestras succeed in presenting works ``to the audiences
who want to hear it, though they may not know it yet,'' as Henry
Fogel, president of the Chicago Symphony Orchestra, put it to
conference delegates.
</P>
<P>
   How can orchestras identify compelling new music, perform it
with confidence, promote it effectively and get audiences to
embrace it?
</P>
<P>
   Those were the questions that propelled the three days of
conference activities, which also included performances by the
Chicago Symphony Orchestra, the Chicago Civic Orchestra and the
Chicago Youth Symphony and Concert orchestras. Panel discussions
featured a mix of contemporary composers, critics and orchestra
managers, while break-out sessions dealt with such in-the-trenches
staff concerns of education and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   There were no easy answers to the initial questions, and the
perpetual issues of accessibility and elitism wove through the
comments of many panelists.
</P>
<P>
   Does new music have to be difficult to be good?
</P>
<P>
   Does presenting ``accessible'' works _ as in music a lot of
people can take to easily _ qualify as pandering?
</P>
<P>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning composer Christopher Rouse said he
doesn't think accessible and good are necessarily incompatible.
``We've celebrated inaccessible too long,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said he sees a new trend in the music of young
composers that not only is increasingly melodic, but also
emphasizes the spiritual and emotional aspects of musical
expression over the often intellectual concerns of 20th century
modernism.
</P>
<P>
   Music is about communication, Rouse said, and ``any music is
accessible that engages the listener's senses and emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Borda, executive director of the New York Philharmonic,
was interested in communication as well, but that which occurs
around the performance experience. ``We have to discover new ways
of inviting people into our concerts,'' she said. She suggested
taking some cues from art museums and the ways they make events out
of new exhibitions. She also sees great potential in reaching new
listeners as well as ticket-buyers through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   John Rockwell, arts editor for the New York Times, raised a
provocative question: ``Is it wrong to segregate new music?'' he
asked, suggesting that while it's important to include some modern
and/or new music during the regular subscription season, it may
also be worth pursuing special programming. He also suggested
presenting new music in smaller performance halls as well as
providing concerts at cheaper prices. ``Make tickets affordable to
the people who want to go to hear those kinds of music,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed a given to most conference participants that
unfamiliarity with a new work or composer can hamper an audience's
understanding or enjoyment of the piece. But keynote speaker
Michael Steinberg, who writes the concert program notes for the New
York Philharmonic, said it's more important that the orchestra
musicians understand the music they're playing.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg quoted the modern composer Arnold Schoenberg, who
said: ``My music isn't modern, it's just badly performed.''
According to Steinberg, ``conviction'' on the part of the conductor
and the players was necessary to give life to a new piece of music.
</P>
<P>
   The ASOL's intent is to help make that happen. The ``Music for a
New Millennium'' initiative is both ``a celebration and an array of
activities,'' said the Chicago Symphony's Fogle.
</P>
<P>
   The means to the end include an interative Web site _
www.newmusicnow.org _ which was launched at the conclusion of the
conference; composer residencies; and performances, discussions and
special presentations at each conference over the five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that audiences often disliked much of the music of
the 20th century, the ASOL's membership is hoping to make the music
of new millennium a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
