</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0520 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-VIRTUAL-DRUGGISTS-A     06-26 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-VIRTUAL-DRUGGISTS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET TRADE IN PRESCRIPTION DRUGS RAISES LEGAL, ETHICAL
QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add art advisory and abridgment note.)   (Eds: An abridged version of this story will move by 3:15 p.m. ET,
slugged VIRTUAL-DRUGGISTS-SHORT.)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dr. Leandro Pasos, 68, was struggling to make a
living when, about a year ago, an unusual advertisement in a
Seattle newspaper caught his eye. Doctors with active licenses, the
ad said, could earn up to $10,000 a month doing ``fully automated
online medical reviews.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad was placed by Performance Drugs Inc., a fledging company
that had set up shop on the Internet to market Viagra, the
diamond-shaped blue pill that offers millions of men the hope of
better sex through chemistry. The company had lined up pharmacies
in Miami and Las Vegas to ship the pills to patients. But it needed
doctors to write the prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   As an orthopedic surgeon, Pasos specialized in ailments of the
bones and joints, not impotence. Still, he signed up with
Performance Drugs. For a salary of $5,000 a month, he agreed to
review questionnaires submitted electronically by prospective
Viagra patients, authorizing prescriptions as he saw fit. As he
later explained to investigators, ``I needed a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus did Pasos join the ranks of a growing breed of physicians:
cyberdoctors. His patients were strangers to him; his examinations
took place in the facelessness of cyberspace. That got Pasos into
trouble with the Washington Medical Quality Assurance Commission,
which in May cited him for unprofessional conduct for prescribing
drugs to people he had not physically examined, and fined him $500.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pasos declined to be interviewed, and his lawyer said
no patients had been harmed, the officials who put an end to his
career in online prescribing like to think his case will serve as a
warning. Yet their efforts have barely been noticed in the
flourishing electronic drug market, a new brand of commerce that is
raising questions of medical ethics and law.
</P>
<P>
   In cyberspace, pharmacies are shipping pills across state lines
without the requisite licenses. Doctors are writing prescriptions
for people they have never met, a practice the American Medical
Association says is unethical, but not illegal. And nobody _ not
Congress, not the American Medical Association, not various federal
and state agencies _ knows quite how to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is strictly the Wild West of drug dealing via the
Internet,'' said Rep. Ron Klink, D-Pa., who is pressing Congress to
hold hearings on the problem. Buyers, he warned, should beware:
``We don't know where these drugs are manufactured. We don't know
if the people taking them have conditions that should preclude
them. We know nothing and neither does the public. No one is
watching it.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind prescriptions is that certain drugs are
dangerous enough to warrant authorization from a doctor, a
``learned intermediary,'' in the lexicon of medicine. Typically,
once the Food and Drug Administration approves a drug for sale, it
is prescribed by doctors, who are licensed by state medical boards,
and dispensed by pharmacies licensed by state pharmaceutical
boards. But on the Internet, said William Hubbard, associate
commissioner for policy at the Food and Drug Administration, ``you
might as well just put drugs on the shelf down at the drugstore and
say, `Take your pick.'''
</P>
<P>
   Online prescribing is closely tied to another recent phenomenon:
the emergence of three new ``lifestyle drugs,'' medicines meant to
enhance quality of life, as opposed to curing disease. In addition
to Viagra, they are Propecia, the first pill to treat baldness, and
Xenical, a new diet pill. Yet other drugs are readily available
with a cyberdoctor's consultation. Among them are Celebrex, for
arthritis; Valtrex, for herpes; Claritin, for allergies, and Zyban,
an anti-smoking pill.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there is a burgeoning black market on the
Internet, driven primarily by foreign companies selling everything
from infertility pills to antidepressants without even the pretense
of a doctor's orders. But beyond having Customs inspectors stop
those foreign shipments at the border, there is little the
authorities can do. So they are focusing on companies like
Performance Drugs, though whether they can rein them in is a matter
of opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the politicians are going to be able to do
anything to us,'' said Bill Reeves, who runs Viapro.com, a
Phoenix-based Web site that sells Viagra. He reiterated a quote he
once heard: ``It's kind of like trying to nail Jell-O to a wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Just about anyone with a credit card can buy medicine from sites
like Viapro.com. For a fee that typically ranges from $35 to $85,
patients receive an online medical consultation, which consists of
filling out a health history questionnaire. If the doctor approves,
the pills arrive in the mail, shipped either by a pharmacy or the
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how much business these sites do. But Reeves and
others say they have no shortage of customers, drawn by low prices,
convenience and, in the case of Viagra, the promise of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, apparently, is there any shortage of doctors. ``I probably
have 5,000 names of doctors who want to participate,'' said Bill
Stallknecht, co-owner of ThePillbox.com, based in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Patients learn who their doctors are when the medication arrives
in the mail. State licensing investigators learn the same way.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Pasos, the few doctors who have been disciplined
include an Illinois psychiatrist who runs a holistic health center
and a Colorado doctor who supervises a cosmetic surgery clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Why they do it is anybody's guess. The Colorado doctor, Benjamin
Johnson, 32, said he thought the work was legitimate until
regulators disciplined him for unprofessional conduct. ``Maybe,''
he said, ``I got caught up in the excitement of being involved in
something cutting edge.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Leandro Pasos was not trying to be cutting edge, just hoping to
earn some extra cash. A 1954 graduate of Tulane University's
medical school, Pasos had practiced medicine for more than 40
years, both in this country and his native Nicaragua, when he
spotted the Performance Drugs ad. He was working just two hours a
week, documents from the Washington Medical Quality Assurance
Commission show, treating patients for lower-back pain at a
Seattle-area clinic.
</P>
<P>
   He sent in his resume, showed up for an interview and was hired
on June 16, 1998. His one-page contract made the work sound simple.
``Our automated review system,'' said the job description,
``enables the physician to review several patient charts at a
glance.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement was short-lived. That summer, an investigator
for the Louisiana medical licensing authority bought Viagra by mail
from Performance Drugs, and tipped off the Washington Medical
Quality Assurance Commission when the pills came with Pasos' name
on the label.
</P>
<P>
   About that time, an investigator for the Kansas Board of Healing
Arts bought Viagra over the Internet from Performance Drugs. This
bottle, too, carried Pasos' name. The board obtained a court
injunction against the doctor, accusing him of practicing medicine
without a license in Kansas, and called its counterpart in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Pasos' career in Internet prescribing came to an end on Sept.
17, said his lawyer, Robert Beckerman. That was the day after the
commission wrote a letter to the doctor, asking him to meet with
its investigators. Not long afterward, Performance Drugs went out
of business, although its orders are now being handled by a new
company, Lifestyle USA, which operates out of the same office, a
fifth-floor suite in a building on the edge of downtown Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators met Pasos on Oct. 8, in Beckerman's office.
``I have never signed a prescription for Viagra, ever,'' Pasos
insisted at the outset, according to a transcript of the session.
Technically, that was correct. According to Pasos' contract, there
was no need to, because the dispensing pharmacy kept a copy of the
doctor's medical license on file. ``Orders are assumed approved,''
the contract said, ``unless otherwise notified by the physician.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Pasos said he used discretion in considering the
medical questionnaires. Patients with heart conditions were
rejected for Viagra because it might be dangerous. As to how he
knew patients were telling the truth, he replied: ``I have to
assume you are telling the truth. Even if you come to my office,
you can tell me anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Pasos did not know much about Performance Drugs. He told
investigators he did not know who wrote the medical questionnaire.
He did not know how many requests for prescriptions the company
handled. He did not know the names of the drugstores filling the
prescriptions. He did not talk to pharmacists with questions. ``I
would refer the calls to the company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you comfortable doing this kind of work?'' the
investigators finally asked. ``Not so much,'' Pasos replied. ``I
had no choice. Without a job, I would be going on welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   But the job did not turn out to be as lucrative as Pasos had
hoped. In the end, he said, he collected only $2,500 from
Performance Drugs, half a month's pay for three months of work.
</P>
<P>
   If the world of the cyberdoctor is perilous, so too is that of
the Internet pharmacist. Bill Stallknecht has managed to survive
it, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   At 52, Stallknecht is a devoted Libertarian, and his political
philosophy informs his views about conducting medicine in
cyberspace. (Last year, he ran for Congress in Texas under the
party's banner, garnering 1 percent of the vote, he said.) He is
also a pharmacist, and has owned the Pill Box Pharmacy, a group of
five drugstores in the San Antonio area, since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he took his business online, at the behest of a
brother-in-law who prepares Web sites. The idea at first was simply
to advertise. The pharmacy specializes in compounding, creating
special formulations of drugs not readily available. Among its
products, in that pre-Viagra era, was an injection therapy for
erectile dysfunction, a remedy Stallknecht promoted on his Web
site. By the time Viagra was approved, in March 1998, he was
swamped with requests for the drug. By last August, he was filling
100 to 200 electronic orders for Viagra a day. Around that time, he
said, he also established another Web site, Medicalcenter.net, to
recruit doctors willing to prescribe Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   He views with disdain the paternalism of the medical
establishment, which he says has an interest in trying to put
people like him out of business. ``Have you heard any patients
being unhappy?'' Stallknecht asks. ``All the power bases say, `We
don't want them cutting into our sacred cow.'''
</P>
<P>
   Today, ThePillbox.com sells four prescription drugs: Viagra;
Propecia, the baldness pill; Xenical, the diet drug; and Claritin,
the antihistamine. Each, Stallknecht maintains, is safe enough to
prescribe without a physical examination, a view the Food and Drug
Administration does not share.
</P>
<P>
   Other drugstores also operate online. CVS Corp., for instance,
recently purchased Soma.com, an online pharmacy that does not use
cyberdoctors. It verifies prescriptions with patients' doctors by
telephone, and is licensed in every state it ships drugs to.
ThePillbox.com, in contrast, is licensed only in Texas;
Stallknecht's position is that when patients visit his Internet
site, they ``actually come to Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   And the company fills only prescriptions written by Texas
doctors. Stallknecht would not say why, but if Texas doctors are
writing prescriptions for a Texas pharmacy, there is less chance of
running afoul of regulators in another state.
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds as if Stallknecht is just one step ahead of the
law, he says, he is. He keeps meticulous records of every
prescription he fills, and comes to work every day expecting
investigators to walk through the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm under scrutiny all the time,'' he said. ``I tickle 50
states all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It does not take much to build an electronic drugstore: just a
valid doctor's license, a relationship with a drug wholesaler, and
an American Express card.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, has been the experience of Eric Thom, vice
president of Confimed.com, an online pharmacy based in Seattle.
Confimed was founded last July, at the height of the Viagra craze,
by an obstetrician-gynecologist whom Thom described as ``an
entrepreneur.'' The company vice president agreed to describe the
process, but without using the name of the founding doctor.
</P>
<P>
   At Confimed, the doctor and drugstore are rolled into one;
Washington, like some other states, permits doctors to dispense
medicine. The doctor began, Thom said, by hiring a Web site
designer. Then, Thom said, ``he called his pharmaceutical
representative, gave them his American Express number, ordered
about 200 pills and started listing his site on some search
engines.''
</P>
<P>
   Thom sees nothing unethical in this. Confimed, he said, is not
gouging patients; its price for Viagra is $9.50 for a 50-milligram
pill and $11 for 100 milligrams. ``You would likely pay right in
that range at the neighborhood drugstore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Confimed site offered complete information about
Viagra's side effects and about who should not take the drug. And
Thom said he took great pains to design a patient questionnaire
that would be more thorough than any doctor's visit, using his
marketing experience to construct the questions in such a way that
patients would be forced to read them. ``We've taken precautions
every step of the way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, officials in Washington state have not taken any action
against Confimed, said the company's lawyer, Jeffrey Johnson.
Kansas, which has moved aggressively against Internet pharmacies,
has obtained a court order preventing Confimed from doing business
there. Johnson said the company would seek to overturn the order in
court. Both he and Thom said they believed strongly that Confimed's
business is legitimate. ``We are trying to be the standard of
cyberconsultation,'' Thom said.
</P>
<P>
   The standard of cyberconsultation, said Dr. Nancy Dickey,
president of the American Medical Association, is an oxymoron;
there can be no standard, she maintains, when patient and doctor
are strangers. At its convention in Chicago on Thursday, the AMA
voted to develop model state legislation to limit Internet
prescribing, and urged that cyberdoctors be disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not ethical,'' Dr. Dickey said. ``It is not good
quality medicine, and it would appear to be driven largely by a
desire to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Boards of Pharmacy, which represents
state pharmaceutical licensing authorities, goes one step further.
``Any site that uses a questionnaire without a legitimate
patient-physician relationship, we consider illegal,'' said Carmen
Catizone, the board's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   He explained: Pharmacies can fill only valid prescriptions.
Prescriptions written by cyberdoctors, he says, are not valid.
Therefore, Catizone reasons, it is illegal for druggists to fill
them.
</P>
<P>
   To help guide consumers, the pharmacy association recently
developed its own seal of approval. Earlier this month, the group
began accepting applications from Internet drugstores that want to
carry the seal. So far, about a dozen have applied.
</P>
<P>
   But Klink, the Pennsylvania congressman, is skeptical. ``That
seal can be replicated and counterfeited,'' he said. ``Are they
willing to take responsibility for each and every product sold over
the Internet that they put their seal on?''
</P>
<P>
   Klink has asked the General Accounting Office to study Internet
drug sales, and is hoping Congress will hold hearings soon.
Meanwhile, federal and state regulators are trying to determine
their authority. In April, the Food and Drug Administration
convened a meeting of interested agencies. ``Nobody,'' Hubbard
said, ``has explicit total authority to take over this problem and
solve it.''
</P>
<P>
   The FDA, which regulates drug manufacturing, has no jurisdiction
over how doctors prescribe the medicines it approves. The Drug
Enforcement Agency has control over the sale of narcotics. The
Federal Trade Commission, which can regulate advertising, might
play a role, but only if it can document deceptive or unfair trade
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, Pfizer, the manufacturer of Viagra, filed a
complaint with the commission alleging that cyberdoctors are
deceiving consumers by ignoring the advice on the drug's label to
physically examine patients. Richard Cleland, an FTC lawyer, would
not say whether an investigation was under way.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves understaffed state licensing authorities, who say
that Web sites are elusive targets. Cyberdoctors can be tracked
only in one way: by ordering drugs and seeing whose name is on the
prescription. Web sites appear and disappear overnight. And the
Internet is hardly a medium that can be reined in one state at a
time; even if every cyberdoctor in the United States were put out
of business, drugs would still be available from Web sites
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever try, as a kid, to take the sand and make a dike
to hold the ocean back?'' asked Mark Stafford, the lawyer for the
Kansas Board of Healing Arts who handled the civil suit against
Pasos. ``That's kind of what it's like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
