<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0524 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-YUGO-TV-2TAKES     06-26 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-YUGO-TV-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVE, IN BELGRADE, NEWS AS GOVERNMENT SEES IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Call it the Big Lie show.
</P>
<P>
   This summer season, it's about how Serbs have not lost control
of Kosovo, how the once-vilified NATO forces are merely carrying
out Slobodan Milosevic's policy of protecting Serbs from Albanian
terrorists, and how, despite the odd hiccup, things are going
pretty darned well in the Yugoslav province that Serbs regard as
their holy land.
</P>
<P>
   On the state-controlled television that Milosevic has used so
masterfully in the last decade, the evening news last week showed a
tranquil Serbian village in Kosovo where contented, secure farm
families were surrounded by lush crops, tidy haystacks and
trustworthy British soldiers, one of whom sweetly petted a village
dog.
</P>
<P>
   That same evening there was horrifying counterprogramming, but
only for the affluent sliver of the Serbian population that has
access to CNN and BBC on satellite television. Pictures of burning
Serbian villages in Kosovo, torched by vengeful Albanians, were
broadcast along with accounts of Serbs being shot to death and
fleeing by the tens of thousands from Kosovo into what is left of
Milosevic's Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The production values shaping the show on Belgrade television go
back 12 years to the town of Kosovo Polje, where Milosevic, then an
obscure Communist bureaucrat, found his nationalist legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yugoslavia does not exist without Kosovo! Yugoslavia would
disintegrate without Kosovo! Yugoslavia and Serbia are not going to
give up Kosovo!'' Milosevic declared in a speech that he made sure
was broadcast on television. That speech launched both his career
as a top politician and the cycle of violence that would obliterate
multiethnic Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Since reality, in the form of 21,000 heavily armed, NATO-led
troops who have effectively turned Kosovo into a foreign country,
has betrayed Milosevic's best-remembered and most fundamental
promise as a Serb leader, it appears to have been decided at the
highest levels in Belgrade that reality is not in the national
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo episodes of this season's Big Lie, like previous ``news''
programming during the Bosnian war about how mendacious Muslims in
Sarajevo were laying siege to themselves to get world sympathy, are
part of a pattern of mass deception that has characterized a decade
of Milosevic's nationalist wars.
</P>
<P>
   It is a strategy that sells defeat as victory, ignores the
periodic floods of Serbian refugees flowing into Serbia from lost
war zones and leaves millions of Serbs in ignorance or confused
denial of human-rights atrocities committed in their name by
Milosevic's security forces.
</P>
<P>
   Grisly evidence of Serbian atrocities in Kosovo that has been
broadcast around the world in the last two weeks has not reached
the majority of Serbs whose main source of information is state
television.
</P>
<P>
   Even for the privileged few who, thanks to satellite dishes,
have seen the pictures of rotting corpses being pulled from wells
or shallow graves, the images seem to prompt what Westerners regard
as counterintuitive reactions, somehow confirming that Serbs are
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a little strange and proud people, and my opinion is
that nobody likes Serbs,'' said Angelina Arbutina, 32, a
well-traveled Belgrade basketball player who has starred on the
Yugoslav national team in the Olympics and European championships.
She says she flips back and forth in the evening between local and
satellite television, finding the truth somewhere in between.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is war, what happened in Kosovo,'' Ms. Arbutina said.
``If we killed Albanians, I'm sure the Albanians killed Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a poll published in Nin, a Belgrade newsmagazine,
about two-thirds of Serbs do not believe Western news accounts of
Serbian atrocities in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Another poll, by Medium, a private firm, paints a picture of
Serbian public opinion that is nationalistic and misinformed. This
poll of 800 urban and rural Serbs, conducted in personal interviews
to avoid the demographic distortion that comes from telephone polls
in this poor country, found that nearly four out of five Serbs
support the peace agreement that ended the 10-week war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It also found, though, that only 14 percent support the
withdrawal of nearly all Serbian armed forces from Kosovo, and 80
percent said turning the province over to NATO peacekeepers was
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story is very old in our public opinion polls,'' said
Srbobran Brankovic, polling director for Medium, referring to
popular misunderstanding about how lost wars in Croatia and Bosnia
were packaged for Serbs on state television. ``The pattern in state
media is to tell the people just those details that are convenient.
Our television says that we managed to keep Kosovo inside Serbia.
They never say how many Serb fighters were withdrawn or how many
Serbian refugees have fled. They just say that their security is
being secured by United Nations and Russian forces.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said on Friday that Serbs ``are going to have
to come out of denial'' about atrocities in Kosovo. He said that in
order to receive aid they would have to ``decide whether they think
it's OK that all those tens of thousands of people were killed, and
all those hundreds of thousands of people were run out of their
homes, and all those little girls were raped and all those little
boys were murdered.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about such Western demands, Brankovic said that, for
Serbs, they always backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't know about the atrocities, and those who do
know are not feeling guilty,'' he said. ``Everything we get from
the West is pressure, pressure, pressure. It makes the people
homogenized. We have some growing anti-West feeling in Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   This postwar season, though, as the pace of misleading images on
state television accelerates, there are a number of indications
that the credibility of Milosevic's television programming is
beginning to slide.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Belgrade television's coverage of the conflicts in
Croatia and Bosnia, in which all the violence, destruction and
death occurred somewhere else, coverage of Milosevic's lost war
with NATO has to compete with what many Serbs can see and hear for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian leader's euphonious promises about quickly
rebuilding war-damaged bridges and factories do not square with the
hard-scrabble lives of many people, who are struggling with
gasoline shortages, soaring unemployment and collapsing foreign
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television shows government ministers going throughout Serbia
talking about reconstruction, but everyone can see it is a joke and
that there is no money,'' said Ognjen Pribicevic, a senior research
fellow at the Institute of Social Sciences in Belgrade and a
political adviser to the opposition leader Vuk Draskovic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the matter of the 50,000 Serb refugees that
Yugoslav aid officials estimate have fled Kosovo and traveled north
to Serbia, a number that has never been mentioned on state
television. It reports, instead, that conditions are good for Serbs
to return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent refugees from coming to the Serbian capital and
becoming a highly visible contradiction of state television news,
the police are stopping Kosovo's fleeing Serbs on the main highway
about 18 miles south of Belgrade. They direct them to smaller towns
in central Serbia. A similar diversion occurred when more than
250,000 Serbs fled Croatia in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The state's lack of money, too, is becoming increasingly hard to
hide. In recent days, hundreds of Yugoslav soldiers, some armed and
drunk, have blocked roads in central Serbia, demanding unpaid wages
and cursing Milosevic's government.
</P>
<P>
   No details of these protests, which have reportedly blocked
roads near two major towns in central Serbia, have been mentioned
on state television. The police confiscated videotape used at the
barricades by local television in the town of Kraljevo.
</P>
<P>
   What television news focused on recently, instead, was how the
peace agreement in Kosovo had succeeded in fulfilling Milosevic's
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put up heroic resistance, and we have risen above the
aggressor in every aspect of the struggle,'' Gorica Gajevic,
general secretary of the ruling Socialist People's Party, said in a
speech in the federal Parliament broadcast on the evening news.
Similarly, Momir Bulatovic, the Yugoslav prime minister, announced
on television that ``our country's territorial integrity and
sovereignty have been defended.''
</P>
<P>
   By claiming that Kosovo has not been lost, it appears that state
television has ventured beyond mendacious news broadcasting into a
realm of bad comedy. More than a dozen Serbs who were asked in
Belgrade last week about the claim smiled wanly and shook their
heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard that on TV,'' Branislav Nakic, 36, a printer, said,
rolling his eyes. ``But nobody believes it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
