<HEADER>
A0526 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-26 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BEACH BLANKET LINGO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There must have been something interesting in that
Clinton yakathon. But every time the president was asked at his
Friday press conference why he is so polarizing, whether he is
responsible for coarsening the culture or if it bugs him to be
trashed by his vice president, he vanished into a nattering nimbus
of positivism.
</P>
<P>
   So let's not talk about Bill Clinton. He is SO over. Let's talk
about dirty magazines.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not referring to Penthouse and Playboy. I have in mind the
wildly popular new macho men's magazines. One that is popular here,
Maxim, originated in Britain, where such magazines are known as
``laddie books.'' They are the kinds of magazines you used to see,
oil-stained, around your mechanic's shop.
</P>
<P>
   They are about cheesy babes, beer, bathroom humor and scoring
tips. Guys snap them up.
</P>
<P>
   What do men really want? Since Freud didn't ask this question,
it's left to me, in this season of beach reading, to pursue the
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Art Cooper, editor of the stylish GQ, is bemused by what the
dumbed-down laddie books reveal about the state of mind of American
men at the turn of the century. Cooper edited Penthouse in the
mid-'70s, but never thought he'd see the mainstreaming of the
flesh-peddling two decades later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a reaction against political correctness,''
Cooper says. ``It's a reaction against the women's movement. It's
for guys who really want to be 14 again.''
</P>
<P>
   This is, after all, the age of Adam Sandler and Mike Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Dennis, publisher of the raunchy Maxim, which recently had
a cover story on ``Squealers: what women say the morning after,''
says he wants to ``do for men what Cosmo has done for women. ...
It's own-up time for guys; it's OK to be a guy.''
</P>
<P>
   He says his circulation, after only two years, is 950,000, which
is 225,000 more than the most popular upmarket men's magazine, GQ.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our core beliefs is that men are incapable of talking
to other men unless they are making jokes,'' the 52-year-old Dennis
says. ``Most men don't know how to react to women. The tide of
political correctness has reached proportions that are almost
sickening. Yesterday I held a door open for a woman. She turned to
me and asked if I could see she had arms. I told her, `You have
more arms than manners.'''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Dennis tell it, these new skin rags are an expression of
deep principle. But the truth is messier. The male-magazine buying
public seems eager to embrace simple-minded gender stereotypes.
Maxim's manifesto on the Web instructs women: ``If we see you in
the morning and at night, why call us at work?''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't really make sense that these frat-boy mags are
thriving because men are confused and threatened by feminism, since
the women's mags have all gone retro and tarty too, preaching the
low-cut, high-heeled Cosmo girl attitude about trapping a man.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is a new magazine called Cosmo Girl! intended to
train even younger girls in man-trapping techniques. The premier
edition of the magazine for girls 12 to 17 features Ben Affleck
stickers, articles like ``Reel Him In ... Learn How to Set Your
Bait'' and, naturally, the latest on alleged nude pictures of Leo.
</P>
<P>
   With formerly innocent women's magazines like Mademoiselle
filled with stories like ``Guys &AMP; Sex, What They Think About
Foreplay, Experienced Women and Lust vs. Love,'' both sides of the
drugstore aisle seem sex-addled.
</P>
<P>
   Maxim is already so popular it has spawned its own spinoff
called Stuff. The cover this month screams, ``Fast cars, hot sex,
cold beer.'' Of its Czech cover girl, the magazine drools, ``In or
out of her swimsuit, Daniela Pestova has the world's heat-seeking
missiles trained once again on the Eastern bloc.'' Among the
revelations in ``50 Things Women Don't Want You to Know'' is No.
46: ``If she tries to kill herself, she will probably botch the
job.''
</P>
<P>
   Penthouse's Bob Guccione Jr. has gotten into the laddie-book act
_ surprise! _ with Gear. It features a sexily scowling Carrie Otis
in a bikini this month and redundantly proclaims itself ``The Sex
Issue.'' It offers stories like ``O Come, All Ye Unfaithful: why it
might actually be impossible for a man to be monogamous.''
</P>
<P>
   Vive la difference, but this is ridiculous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
