<HEADER>
A0529 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-26 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AMERICA IS READY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the introduction to his book ``Making a Killing _
the Business of Guns in America,'' Tom Diaz writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1960, more than three-quarter of a million Americans
have died in firearm suicides, homicides, and unintentional
injuries. In 1995 alone, 35,957 Americans died by gunfire: 18,503
in firearm suicides, 15,835 in firearm homicides, 1,225 in
unintentional shootings, and 394 in firearm deaths of unknown
intent.''
</P>
<P>
   Multiply those ghastly figures by three and you get the
approximate number of people treated in emergency rooms for
nonfatal gun wounds. Gun violence is one of the great American
pastimes. Children are far more familiar with its rituals than they
are with, say, the rules of baseball or football.
</P>
<P>
   A week and a half ago the House of Representatives, acting in
the wake of the tragedy in Littleton, had a chance to take a tiny
step toward reversing the pervasive slaughter of Americans by guns.
But the Republican majority, led by the likes of Tom DeLay, made
sure that didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay contends that ``guns have little or nothing to do with
juvenile violence.''
</P>
<P>
   What did pass the House was a patently unconstitutional measure
allowing public schools to post the Ten Commandments on classroom
walls. No wonder someone cried out during the gun debate, ``This
House is in a state of denial.''
</P>
<P>
   A better idea was offered by Bill Bradley, the former senator
who is running a quixotic campaign for president. Bradley said that
if he makes it to the White House he will seek approval of a series
of gun-control measures that go beyond anything the House
considered in its debate.
</P>
<P>
   He called for a complete ban on the manufacture, sale,
distribution and possession of the cheap handguns known as
Saturday-night specials. He called for all handguns to be
registered and said potential gun owners should first be required
to pass a safety course and obtain a license. He said all gun
dealers should be banned from residential neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   More than 750,000 Americans have been killed by guns since 1960,
and yet these common-sense proposals, long sought by staunch
advocates of gun control, are considered so radical they have no
chance of getting a serious hearing in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Ten Commandments yes, gun control no.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley denounced the National Rifle Association and the members
of the House who refused to consider meaningful gun-control
legislation. He suggested they were out of step with the majority
of Americans, especially those mothers who fear that their children
are endangered by the ``unregulated flow'' of guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think it's about time to stand up to the NRA,'' said
Bradley. ``What I'm hearing out there is that there is this shift.
People think that regulating who can own a gun, and that means no
children and no felons, and regulating what guns are available, and
that means no assault weapons or Saturday-night specials, are
reasonable steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he also supports proposals to limit the purchase of
handguns by any one person anywhere in the country to one a month,
to require background checks at gun shows, to require trigger locks
on handguns and to substantially increase the license fees for gun
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the front-runner for the Democratic
presidential nomination, is also a strong gun-control advocate,
although his proposals have not as yet been as far-reaching as
Bradley's. A spokesman for the vice president said a strong
pro-gun-control position would be spelled out by Gore this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, in a speech he delivered in California this month,
discussed the very real fear of violence that millions of American
students feel each day when they go to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``A graduating (high school) senior today is less likely to have
tried drugs and alcohol than 20 years ago,'' he said. ``Today's
senior is less likely to get pregnant while still a teen and more
likely to believe in God. Our children are basically good children.
... So why is it so difficult in this country to have a rational
dialogue about reducing gun violence?''
</P>
<P>
   Ask the leaders of the NRA. And their stooges in the majority
party in Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1459EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0531 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-ATLANTA27-COX     06-26 1723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-ATLANTA27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's gay pride festivities reveal openness, resistance
 &HT;    By Jay Croft and Holly Crenshaw
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The banners hanging in downtown and Midtown are
simple: ``Celebrate,'' they proclaim over a rainbow of colors.
</P>
<P>
   But celebrate what?
</P>
<P>
   In their first appearance, the banners meant to promote this
weekend's gay pride events also illustrate for some a key
contradiction of gay life in metro Atlanta, ``the city too busy to
hate'' in the heart of the Bible Belt: 300 flags fly, but not one
states what is being celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The banners are a step in the right direction, but I wish they
mentioned `gay' or `lesbian' pride,'' said fitness trainer Warren
Thompson. ``I don't want to call it a cop-out, but I perceive it as
a way to not offend.''
</P>
<P>
   And that unintended dual message _ a recognition of what has
been achieved and the hurdles that remain _ will be drawn into
focus during Atlanta's pride festivities, which are expected to
draw 300,000 homosexuals and their supporters from around the
region. Even as they enjoy relative acceptance in one of the
nation's gay meccas, gay Atlantans face an unyielding resistance to
anything more than superficial progress, many activists say.
</P>
<P>
   Some estimates list Atlanta as having the third-highest
concentration of gays in the nation, behind only New York and San
Francisco. Although numbers and rankings are impossible to verify,
the gay and lesbian presence here is obvious. Homosexuals support
their own shops, bars and restaurants, visit gay doctors and auto
mechanics, exercise at gay gyms, worship openly in churches and
temples, read their own newspaper, and enjoy the neighborhoods they
helped revitalize _ most notably Midtown, as close to a ``gay
community'' as can be found anywhere in America.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 30 years into the gay rights movement, some community
leaders question whether pride events remain relevant or necessary,
especially in gay strongholds such as Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.) says the festivities are
politically pointless in gay-friendly big cities but can still be
valuable in smaller towns like Tulsa, Okla., where he was grand
marshal for its first pride parade this month.
</P>
<P>
   But gays in Georgia can still be denied housing, lose custody of
their children or be fired from jobs simply because they are gay.
</P>
<P>
   And so, even in an accepting environment such as Atlanta, there
are major hurdles for gays and lesbians:
</P>
<P>
   _ The city of Atlanta has tried since 1993 to offer domestic
partner benefits for employees, but the state continues to fight
such a change in court.
</P>
<P>
   _ A bomb exploded at a lesbian nightclub two years ago, injuring
five people, and gays still fear violence and harassment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia remains one of 10 states without a hate-crime law.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anti-gay sentiment is often evident, from Cobb County's 1993
resolution condemning homosexuality to a Kirkwood minister's fear
last year of a ``homosexual takeover'' to the Southern Baptist
Convention's statements this month reasserting its opposition to
homosexuality. The convention also condemned President Clinton for
designating June as Gay Pride Month.
</P>
<P>
   All of these obstacles, and others, are good reasons to come
together in big numbers, some activists say. Glen Paul Freedman,
co-chairman of the Atlanta Pride Committee, emphasizes that pride
events create an atmosphere of solidarity and support, which can
inspire gays and lesbians to further political action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody takes little steps (toward coming out), and
attending pride helps them make those first steps,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movement is about more than recognition that we exist,''
added Jane Morrison, an attorney with the Lambda Legal Defense and
Education Fund. ``It's about equality, and that is why we need to
keep on marching.''
</P>
<P>
   And so today, spectators and supporters will flock to Peachtree
Street to watch the parade into Piedmont Park, and TV crews will be
poised to shoot footage for tonight's newscasts. About 170 groups
will ride on floats or march, including early gay rights pioneers
and the Parents and Friends of Lesbians and Gays, who usually
garner the most applause. Perfectly sculpted gym boys will give way
to people of all shapes, sizes and colors, and to flamboyant drag
queens, leathermen and ``Dykes on Bikes.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always so.
</P>
<P>
   About 125 people marched in the city's first gay-rights rally in
June 1970, with no media notice. That year, gays in five other U.S.
cities held similar events to mark the first anniversary of the
birth of the modern gay-rights movement, when police raided a
Greenwich Village, N.Y., gay bar called the Stonewall Inn and the
patrons _ tired of repeated, longtime harassment _ fought back,
igniting four days of riots and a new resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Salo, a graphic designer, was at some of Atlanta's earliest
gatherings, including the 1976 parade where he ``came out'' as a
homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even back then, Atlanta was one of the places that people were
saying to go to if you were gay,'' said Salo, 47. ``Before, you
could easily move about in the gay subculture, but I had never seen
such an assembled, visible presence.''
</P>
<P>
   As early as May 1978, a story in The Atlanta Constitution noted
the impact of the city's growing gay population on ``almost every
facet of society _ politics, education, business, the media, the
arts.'' Still, some of the people quoted were afraid to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   The newly visible gay community began to feel more assailed
starting in the late '70s _ by Anita Bryant, then AIDS, then the
religious right. As a result, more gays felt it necessary to come
out.
</P>
<P>
   Today, some gay leaders say their objectives have become so
diverse that it's no longer possible to concentrate on one goal.
Instead, activists are channeling energy into ensuring workplace
equality, the right to marry, insurance availability and other
everyday concerns that heterosexuals often take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very full plate of issues for people to deal with,''
said New York historian and author Eric Marcus. ``We've got a huge
menu.''
</P>
<P>
   Through all the gains and setbacks, pride events have grown _
often serving as a barometer of their time. Some years the events
were angry, others somber, and some were little more than
freewheeling street parties.
</P>
<P>
   Dilia Loe moved to Atlanta from Fort Lauderdale, Fla., last year
to run the Atlanta office of the Gay &AMP; Lesbian Alliance Against
Defamation, one of three national gay organizations with offices
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta's pride celebration gives us a chance to celebrate our
culture and our civic milestones here,'' Loe said. ``But there will
be thousands of people who absolutely will not want to be in front
of the camera, and for some people, it takes all the courage they
can muster to attend.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, gay men and women have been drawn to big cities
such as Atlanta for jobs and cultural opportunities, and to seek
the anonymity of a large gay population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, gay people have migrated here as a way of escaping
the scrutiny of small towns,'' said Atlanta City Councilwoman Cathy
Woolard, the first openly gay elected official in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the entire country, there may be some places
for gay people that are more comfortable than Atlanta,'' she said.
``But in the scheme of things, Atlanta rates right up there _ which
is not to say that we don't suffer prejudice in Atlanta or other
gay-friendly places, because it still exists everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even I, as an openly gay city councilperson, feel it on a
somewhat regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   As with other urban centers, Atlanta's gay development was a
byproduct of its broader, post-war growth _ with gays and lesbians
swept up in the general population boom.
</P>
<P>
   Dana White, an Emory University professor of Urban Studies, said
Atlanta's appeal to gays and lesbians also was accelerated by the
construction of Hartsfield International Airport, business leaders'
focus on economic expansion and positive public relations, the
city's civil rights legacy, and the counterculture of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a town that was developing, where you could make your
mark,'' said Phil McDonald, special assistant to Mayor Bill
Campbell. ``The city leadership created this climate where gay
people felt not like they would be accepted, but where they would
have an opportunity to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, the doubled-sided nature of gay life in Atlanta
is played out in the political arena, with city officials often
taking a more progressive stance than state leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council voted in 1986 to ban discrimination among its
workers, and in 1993 the city instituted a domestic-partner
registry _ but it is largely symbolic and carries no legal weight.
Campbell has appointed a 12-member advisory panel on gay issues,
and he signed an executive order requiring companies that do
business with the city to prohibit discrimination based on sexual
orientation. But enforcement requires someone to complain before a
company can lose a contract or have to begin diversity training _
neither of which has happened, McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we take two steps forward and then slide back,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the starkest example is the city's 6-year-old attempt to
grant its employees domestic partner insurance benefits. The state
Supreme Court struck down the ordinance, then accepted a revised
version. But state Insurance Commissioner John Oxendine refuses to
allow the city to change its policies to allow the coverage, saying
it would encourage illegal sexual relationships. All employers in
Georgia must gain Oxendine's approval, except those large enough to
self-insure.
</P>
<P>
   The city sued Oxendine over his ruling, and the case is ongoing
in Fulton County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects the Pride festival or parade to change Oxendine's
_ or anyone else's _ mind about homosexuality or to put an end to
job discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the parade still pushes the envelope a little more,'' said
Thompson, the fitness trainer. ``It reminds straight people of the
sheer numbers. On the other hand, on some of the real big, serious
things, we still have a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
