<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-BANDWAGON-NYT &LR;      06-26 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BANDWAGON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH IS ON EASY STREET EARLY IN HIS CAMPAIGN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Two weeks have now passed since Gov. George W. Bush
first hit the campaign trail. His poll numbers keep getting better,
the crowds keep on coming, and the money keeps on rolling in.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot go on this way forever for the frontrunner for the
Republican nomination for president in 2000, or so conventional
wisdom holds. But for ``W,'' the trail moniker the governor of
Texas has picked up, it has been nothing but smooth sailing so far
in these first two weeks of his official candidacy, as he has
traveled to nine states, from the Midwest to New England to here in
Florida, to pitch his campaign message of ``compassionate
conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm some kind of fired up!'' Bush blurted on Friday at a
fund-raiser here on his first campaign stop in Florida, where his
younger brother, Jeb Bush, is the governor. In most of the polls
conducted after his first 10 days on the road, the Texas governor
continues to lead Vice President Al Gore by close to 15 percentage
points and has increased his lead over his nearest Republican
rival, Elizabeth Dole, to a formidable 50 points.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, polls indicate he now has more support among
GOP voters than all 11 of his Republican primary rivals have
combined. His opponents have been taking pot shots at him, calling
his ``compassionate conservatism'' a fuzzy, ill-defined notion that
tries to be too many things to too many people. But he continues to
pitch it, as he did here, telling a crowd of 500 or so supporters
in Miami:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a conservative mind and a compassionate heart. It is
conservative to cut tax rates and compassionate to help families
still left struggling. It is conservative to set high education
standards and hold kids to them and it is compassionate to see that
not one kid gets left behind. It is conservative to expect people
on welfare to find work but compassionate to encourage charity and
help those who really can't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   To Jeffrey Manchester, a Miami business management consultant
who contributed $1,000 to hear the governor and pick at finger
food, that approach bespoke Republican moderation as much as
anything and had ``just the right balance,'' Manchester said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says that education is just about the most important
issue facing this country today, and it pleases me no end that the
governor touched on that at the very start and then kept returning
to it,'' Manchester said. ``I liked what I heard. I have no problem
with being conservative and compassionate at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor had finished speaking and was working the crowd,
slapping backs, embracing and being embraced, now winking, now
posing for a souvenir picture, now whispering earnestly in an ear.
He had been introduced by his brother, Jeb, and the two of them had
mugged a bit at the podium about the family thing, the political
dynasty thing, as in Kennedys and Roosevelts.
</P>
<P>
   Would George W. get Manchester's vote? ``Let's see how he does
further down the road,'' Manchester said. ``Don't they all run into
some challenging difficulty sooner or later? I'll be watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Celinda Lake, one of the most respected Democratic pollsters,
said last week after running still another Bush survey that she was
``startled'' at how strongly Bush was suddenly running among women
and Hispanic voters, normally Democratic-leaning constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive, too, is the number of Republican leaders who have
now climbed aboard the Bush bandwagon, many of them over the past
two weeks. He now has over half of the party's governors, senators
and members of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the money thing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is so far ahead in fund raising _ he expects to top the $20
million mark by the end of this month and double that by primary
season next spring _ that he may forgo accepting federal matching
funds and the spending limits that come attached.
</P>
<P>
   In one day, on his sweep through Florida on Friday, in which he
touched down at Fort Myers, Tampa, Fort Lauderdale and Miami, he
collected $2.5 million, campaign aides said. That is more money
than some of his rivals have collected in a full year of fund
raising. Randy Enwright, a Republican consultant who once was
executive director of the Florida Republican Party, predicted that
before Election 2000 is over, Bush will have raised more money in
Florida than all his rivals will combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll take some of Al Gore's money, too,'' Enwright said,
suggesting that potential Gore donors might turn to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's campaign pitch has now settled into a predictable
format and rhythm, as usually happens with candidates. He offers
standard hot-button lines, well-tested jokes and themes centered
for the most part on tax cuts, better schools, a stronger military,
personal responsibility and stronger families and communities.
</P>
<P>
   But the themes are only broadly sketched. He promises details
later, once the themes are set, a promise that does not satisfy his
critics, who accuse him of on-the-one-hand/on-the-other-hand
waffling. What the Bush stump speech does not include are
hard-edged, head-on attacks on Gore, President Clinton and
Republican rivals. Sensitive and divisive issues like abortion and
affirmative action are relegated to the background, though Bush
says he is opposed to both, generally.
</P>
<P>
   Among his top priorities, Bush says, are tax cuts and an
increase in military spending. The cuts, he argues, would spur the
economy to even greater heights. The extra military spending is
needed, he says, because of the spread of international terrorism
and because more and more countries are developing missile
capabilities. He does not touch much on the Clinton-Lewinsky
scandal. But when he does, by indirection, saying he would never
disgrace the dignity of the Oval Office, he draws his biggest
applause. One of his biggest laughs comes when he takes a sideswipe
at Gore for claiming to have helped invent the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore no more invented our current prosperity than I
invented the Internet,'' Bush says.
</P>
<P>
   As for his own gaffes out on the trail, he has thus far
committed only a few of the kind that reporters and opponents
pounce on early in a campaign as indications that a candidate has a
lot to learn or may not be up to the job.
</P>
<P>
   There was that moment in the first day or so on the road when he
committed what is generally classified a political no-no. He
declared flatly that he would win the first big contest of Election
2000, the straw poll that Iowa's Republican Party has scheduled for
Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Having set the bar, he now must clear it.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was that interview in which he referred to the people
of Timor as ``Timoreans'' _ they are Timorese _ and that remark in
Richmond, Va., in which he confused Slovakia and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly fatal stuff. Yet it forced him to confess that ``this is
a big world, and I've got a lot to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But should I be fortunate to be elected,'' he quickly added,
``I'll be ready. I'll be ready to assume the office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
