<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0543 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH27-COX     06-26 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fractured GOP in California poses challenges for Bush
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush airlifts his presidential
dream to California this week, a state rich with opportunity but
fraught with political peril.
</P>
<P>
   Long before anyone casts a vote, California _ with more than 10
percent of the delegates needed to win the GOP presidential
nomination and about 20 percent of electoral votes needed to win
the White House _ is shaping up as a key 2000 battleground.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity for Bush lies in a vote-rich Hispanic community
he has targeted and a cash-rich high-tech community that seems up
for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   But for Bush, and all GOP contenders, the California peril lies
in a fractured state party that is reeling from defeats. In the
nation's most populous state, Bush lacks the support of a
Republican governor. That's because last year, for the first time
in 16 years, Californians put a Democrat in their governor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to turn this party around,'' said California GOP
Chairman John McGraw. ``We got a drubbing last year.''
</P>
<P>
   McGraw, who is remaining neutral in the presidential primary,
says Bush could be the guy to do it. At many of his campaign stops
in the past two weeks, Bush has claimed he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a uniter, not a divider,'' he says frequently.
</P>
<P>
   In California, where Republicans appear to have done about
everything they could to drive away Hispanic votes in recent years,
Bush backers are sure the Texas governor is the man to turn it
around. A recent Los Angeles Times poll showed him running away
from the GOP field, garnering support from 50 percent of those
surveyed. Elizabeth Dole was second at 13 percent. No other
Republican was in double digits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because everybody thinks he is the one. He's
going to lead us out of the desert,'' said Bush backer Allan
Peters, who has had no trouble attracting people and their
checkbooks to a Bush fund-raiser in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising, at least this week, will not be a problem for Bush
anywhere in California. He will raise about $2 million at seven
fund-raisers, a total that could push him over $20 million for the
first six months of the year, a record.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is an incredibly important state,'' Bush said. ``I
intend to take it very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to collecting money, Bush hopes to collect a lot of
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to begin to introduce Governor Bush to
California,'' said Gerry Parsky, his California campaign manager.
``It's a huge state with a lot of diverse interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The March 7 California primary (which, thanks to efforts last
week by Bush backers, is a winner-take-all event) will be a battle
to lure voters aligned with a party in turmoil. GOP gubernatorial
nominee Dan Lungren, then the state's attorney general, was
trounced by Democrat Gray Davis by 20 points in November, ending 16
years of Republican governors in Reagan country.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP also lost legislative seats in a bad year blamed, in
part, on ex-Gov. Pete Wilson, who dried up the party's appeal to
moderates and Hispanics by backing ballot initiatives that cut off
welfare benefits for illegal immigrants and ended affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies part of the reason some Republicans see Bush, a
Spanish-speaking governor who shuns immigrant bashing (though fuzzy
on affirmative action and bilingual education), as the savior,
according to Peters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't anybody else who supposedly can bring these
different people together. If they don't do that, you might as well
chalk up another loss for Republicans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parsky says the mission for Bush, in the wake of the GOP wipeout
in California last year, is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters of California viewed the Republican candidates as
extreme and as not inclusive and as not willing to reach out to
people and be concerned,'' he said, convinced that Bush has the
message to erase that image.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also wants to persuade Californians that he understands
what Parsky calls ``the new economy,'' lingo for the high-tech
industry. Vice President Al Gore, the front-runner for the
Democratic nomination, was back in California last week trying to
tap into that sector. Gore has made 57 trips to California since
taking office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   On one of those trips earlier this year, he was greeted by a
newspaper ad from high-tech leaders urging Bush to run for
president. Bush will cash in on that sentiment Thursday with a
fund-raising breakfast in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not the only GOP contender courting Californians. Five
showed up at the state GOP convention. Arizona Sen. John McCain,
who last week peeled off eight South Carolina lawmakers who had
urged Bush to run, currently is contacting GOP leaders, including
some who have signed on with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, already running ads on cable TV, will probably be
the only other Republican candidate with the money it takes to make
contact with California voters. If New Hampshire and Iowa are
retail states where voters expect hand-to-hand, eye-to-eye contact,
California is a wholesale state where politics, for many, is played
out on TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be watching,'' Tony Hammond, Forbes' California campaign
manager, said when asked if the billionaire publisher will begin an
ad blitz soon.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes last week previewed his angle of attack on Bush,
challenging Bush's claim to be a tax-cutter. The Texas governor
frequently tells audiences that he presided over the two largest
tax cuts in Texas history.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is trotting out the list of 75 taxes Bush wanted to
increase as part of his 1997 property tax cut plan. The package,
which did not win legislative approval, included property tax cuts
which would have outweighed the increases.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush winds up with the nomination, he then must find a way to
carry a state that has strayed from the GOP side in presidential
races. The elder George Bush narrowly carried California in 1988,
but was trounced in California by Bill Clinton in 1992, picking up
only 33 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Clinton throttled challenger Bob Dole in California by
51 percent to 38 percent, including a whopping 71 percent to 28
percent among Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   With that defeat, coupled with the loss of the 1998
gubernatorial race, the California GOP has been suffering through
infighting. The conservatives prevailed, electing Santa Clara
businessman McGraw as chairman at a contentious February
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of you know that I have very strong convictions,'' McGraw
said in his victory speech. ``That does not mean and will not mean
in this party any intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   A month earlier, McGraw raised some concerns that he might not
offer the inclusive voice for which the party is looking.
</P>
<P>
   He told a Catholic newspaper that ``killing our babies (is the)
issue of the century. Compared to that, cutting taxes or any other
issue pales in comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   But McGraw now insists that is a personal message, not one he
wants the party to pitch. He understands what's at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very diverse state. Whomever the nominee is is going
to have to relate to very broad and diverse communities in
California,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a community we want to revitalize here in
California,'' he said of Hispanics, targeting Bush as the man to do
it. ``He speaks Spanish. That's huge, huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
