<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      06-26 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME ISSUE PAYS IN CRUCIAL GOVERNOR'S RACE IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ One week before gubernatorial elections in
Mexico's most populous state, several opinion polls indicate that
Arturo Montiel, the candidate of Mexico's governing party, has a
modest lead over his rivals in a race considered the final testing
ground before a presidential vote next year.
</P>
<P>
   The July 4 elections in the state of Mexico are being closely
watched because the state, which nearly surrounds Mexico City, has
11 million inhabitants and the country's most important
manufacturing center. And the central campaign issue _ crime and
how to combat it _ is one that is likely to define the presidential
race.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Gimenez, the pollster for the Mexico City magazine
Milenio, said that the three main parties are competing fiercely
because the state is the last major electoral test before the 2000
presidential elections. ``This is about momentum,'' he said. ``It's
the last election before the balloting next year in which the
parties can change the electoral status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Montiel, who resigned as party president to become the candidate
of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the
PRI, was backed by 43 percent of potential voters in a poll
published on Friday in the Mexico City newspaper Reforma. The
candidate in second place, with 34 percent, was Jose Luis Duran,
who took a leave as the mayor of Naucalpan, a large Mexico City
suburb, to become the candidate of the center-right National Action
Party, the Reforma poll said.
</P>
<P>
   Higinio Martinez, the candidate of the center-left Party of the
Democratic Revolution, was in third place with 23 percent,
according to the Reforma poll.
</P>
<P>
   But Gimenez said he would publish a survey on Sunday showing
that the governing party and National Action candidates were tied,
with each backed by 39 percent of voters. The Democratic Revolution
candidate was backed by 22 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Campos, director of a Consulta, S.A., a polling firm that
will conduct a survey of voters leaving polling places on the day
of the vote for the Televisa television network, said he has
studied dozens of recent surveys in the state. He estimated that
Montiel had a steady lead of about six percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Mexico is one of the country's most diverse,
including a ring of vast, impoverished settlements like
Nezahualcoyotl, a bedroom suburb of Mexico City with a population
of nearly two million maids, bodyguards and other service workers.
It also holds extensive rural areas where farmers tend sheep and
cultivate corn and wheat.
</P>
<P>
   The governing party has always controlled the state government,
but the two opposition parties have made rapid recent gains.
</P>
<P>
   All three candidates have sought to capitalize on public
distress over crime and police corruption, which are rampant
nationwide and which no party has battled successfully. Montiel, in
particular, has portrayed himself as a strongman who will crack
down on crime.
</P>
<P>
   But Daniel M. Lund, director of Market and Opinion Research
International, a polling firm , said the governing party's main
strategy is to hand out gifts, including government benefits, to
persuade voters to back Montiel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody comes around and gives a family a bag of groceries or
milk, in the context of a commitment to vote,''Lund said. ``The PRI
also uses its control over state housing, street paving,
agricultural subsidies and scholarships, to leverage votes,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent poll, Lund said, 38 percent of those surveyed said
they had accepted gifts or economic support in exchange for their
vote. Of the 34 percent who said they intended to vote for the
governing party, half said they would do so because of the economic
support, Lund said. The other half said they would vote for the
party even without the economic support, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
