<HEADER>
A0557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICIAN-NOVEL-ART-     06-26 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICIAN-NOVEL-ART-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN'S NOVEL IS BOON TO SELF-PROMOTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Every politician is a relentless self-salesman
every day in this city, reglossing the product even as it tarnishes
in the cutthroat marketplace of candidacy. Which is why Rep. Peter
King had a certain merry smile last week when he returned to the
House floor fresh from a high-profile radio interview about his
latest entry in the political hopper: a novel, not a bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go through here only once,'' King said, eyeing the buzzing
scene for fresh opportunity. ``These guys who focus-group
everything are missing a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, some would say slyly, the Republican from Nassau
County, N.Y., has become a leading contrarian in the House
marketplace, notably withstanding the fury of Rep. Tom DeLay, the
Republican whip, to rise as one of only four Republicans who voted
against all four impeachment articles brought against President
Clinton by the GOP leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, King, as an Irish-American contrarian of sorts,
became the chief Republican point man at the side of Clinton in
shepherding Northern Irish nationalist politicians to full
partnership in the new Irish peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always feel with this stuff you can't get hurt,'' King said
of American politics, describing DeLay as plenty tough but hardly
as lethal as the Irish political assassins he came to know, and now
to novelize, from his visits to the Troubles as a young politician.
``I mean, no one is shooting real bullets in this business on our
side of the Atlantic.''
</P>
<P>
   At the core of this observation rests King's novel _ ``Terrible
Beauty'' (Roberts Rinehart), a narrative of the violent years of
politics in Belfast, Northern Ireland _ as well as still another
contrarian initiative.
</P>
<P>
   This is his self-promotion as a possible added candidate in the
Senate race shaping up in New York between Hillary Rodham Clinton
and New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. The many doubters of
King's chances in such a contest have nevertheless heard him
discussing it lately in book-show interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great: two championship fights, center stage,''
King said enthusiastically at the idea of challenging the first
lady after a primary run at Giuliani, whom he first encountered
over three decades ago when both were young lawyers in Richard
Nixon's Wall Street law firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy was a Democrat back then, and very liberal to the point
of admiring Rap Brown and Stokely Carmichael,'' King said, grinning
as he imagined what he might make of those ``black power''
agitators among conservative voters in the Senate primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a lot of what shows today _ Rudy's dark side _ was clear
then, too. He'd suddenly erupt at lunch with the guys over
something casual someone said about baseball or something. It was
`You're a liar!' and making the guy back down.''
</P>
<P>
   King thinks he knows how to get under the skin of Giuliani well
enough to win. Then he would challenge Mrs. Clinton as ``too
liberal for New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd run slightly right of center for the working middle-class
vote,'' he said. ``You know, people who don't sit around and
complain about their psychological hangups or the fact that they
may have had a father who drank,'' added the 55-year-old
conservative, dedicated to stamping out from politics all talk of
``reform'' and ``victimization.''
</P>
<P>
   He will decide about a Senate bid by mid-August, King said,
fully mindful that he would have to raise several million dollars
as ante to compete next year in the primary. ``I'd pretty much have
to turn into a cash register.''
</P>
<P>
   But the beauty for him right now, King acknowledges, is that,
precisely as he hoped, the Senate talk, with all his anecdotes of
Rudy the young radical, is galvanizing his book-flacking interviews
on radio and television. ``About a third of my National Public
Radio interview was about the Senate race,'' the congressman said
gratefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``A confluence of two great endeavors,'' King declared, laughing
at the varied ways a politician can feed the beast of
self-promotion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The book promotion has crimped King's treasured evening meals at
The Dubliner, a pub near the Capitol. But he is uncomplaining about
being saluted at the Irish Embassy on Monday night as a novelist
and statesman. He says the fact that he worked the Belfast crowds
with Clinton and came to admire the president as a stand-up
politician on the Irish issue was not a factor in his vote against
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I hated the guy, I thought these charges were not
impeachable,'' the congressman said. ``The fact that I had seen him
up close making tough decisions helped me keep my perspective.
We're talking about a person who is not all bad or all good _ a
real human being.''
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment was not the first time King resisted the
Republican marching drum. At St. Francis College in New York, he
wrote a thesis defending the record of Mayor Jimmy Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably did everything he was accused of,'' he said of the
corruption charges at Walker's City Hall. ``But nothing was ever
actually proven. There was no malice in the guy, and he kept the
city's spirits moving during the Depression,'' said King, who grew
up as the son of a police detective in New York City before joining
the Irish-American diaspora to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``How lucky it is to be here in Congress,'' said King, happily
flogging book and candidacy, exulting all the while in the daily
demands of political self-salesmanship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
