<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, June 27, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A very humid air mass will stifle the Deep South, Middle
Atlantic and Ohio Valley states on Sunday, providing ample moisture
to fuel clusters of showers and thunderstorms. Though thunderstorms
are possible anywhere within this region, there will be several
favored areas for storms to erupt.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms with locally heavy rains will flare across parts
of the Ohio Valley and central Appalachians as a slow-moving
jet-stream disturbance lifts increasingly humid air near the
surface. Thunderstorms will also rumble across parts of Virginia
and the eastern Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, clusters of thunderstorms, some with heavy rain,
will develop from the southern Appalachians to Mississippi, where
very humid Gulf air is forced to rise on the southern flank of the
Ohio Valley disturbance. Meanwhile, clusters of heavy thunderstorms
will erupt near the sultry Gulf Coast from Texas to Florida as the
leading edge of developing sea breezes wedges under and lifts humid
air over land.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms, some with heavy rain and
a few with severe weather, will erupt from the central Plains to
the upper Mississippi Valley as a jet-stream disturbance emerging
from the Rockies lifts humid air streaming north from the Gulf of
Mexico. Later Sunday, isolated severe storms are also possible from
southeast Wyoming and eastern Colorado to the high plains of west
Texas and eastern New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Patchy fog will dull parts of southeast New England and Long
Island, N.Y., on Sunday morning before yielding to sunny, warm and
humid weather.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Hit or Miss
</P>
<P>
   The nature of showers and thunderstorms in the summer is hit or
miss. Whether forecasters use words such as ``isolated'' or
``scattered,'' the message is clear: Some areas will receive rain
and some will not. The general lack of expansive areas of rain in
summer is a consequence of a dearth of expansive low-pressure
systems, which owe their wet girth to the large north-south
temperature contrasts of late autumn, winter and early spring. In
summer, the heating power of the sun lessens these contrasts,
setting the stage for a random bubbling up of hit-or-miss showers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1630EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0564 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-CAMP27-COX     06-26 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-CAMP27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-Hawk continues basketball camp for hearing impaired
 &HT;    By Carlos Frias
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ask Mike Glenn what it means to be a hero, and he can
answer with one name, ``Mildred Nelson.''
</P>
<P>
   As an athletic teen-ager, Nelson made a 5-year-old Glenn want to
grow up to be pro basketball player. That she was deaf only
inspired him more. Glenn, a former NBA player and current Hawks
telecaster, recalls working with his father, Charles, girls
basketball coach for 18 years at the Georgia School for the Deaf in
Cave Spring. With the city's population less than 2,000 at the
time, everyone in town had some link to the school.
</P>
<P>
   When his father's players weren't pinching his cheeks, Glenn
would watch his father develop the team into one of the nation's
top squads of deaf players, and Nelson into one of the top female
deaf players ever.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson soon made Glenn her favorite. She taught him to dribble
and shoot, which became his strengths in the NBA, including four
years with the Hawks. But first, she taught him to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was 6, Glenn was fluent in American Sign Language and
able to cheer for his favorite player by raising his arms and
shaking his hands, the sign language equivalent of clapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was my first hero,'' he said smiling, remembering her
shooting prowess and brilliant smile. ``She kinda started teaching
me, and I'd sit down during the games and clap for her. I, like
everybody else, was clapping and like, `Give the ball to Mildred.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the hook that got me into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, one can ask any of the 81 children who attended last
week's 20th annual Mike Glenn Basketball Camp for the Hearing
Impaired and many can point to Glenn as their hero.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, 43, still puts on the weeklong, nonprofit camp he started
while he was with the Knicks in 1980 and has continued in Atlanta
for the past 18 years. It has become one of the foremost camps for
youths of high school age with hearing disabilities, and the only
free one. Sponsors provide everything.
</P>
<P>
   This year's camp finished Friday with 12 of the top boys and
girls playing against Atlanta all-star teams of nondeaf children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw (deaf) kids, when they got to other camps, they felt
left out, and I wanted to let them feel included,'' he said. ``It
greatly improves a kid's self-esteem, and it overall helps bridge
the gap that has existed so long.''
</P>
<P>
   When he visited the Millnech School for the Deaf in New York in
1980, many of the kids in the stands expected Glenn, a player for
the Knicks at the time, just to smile and wave. Then, he started
signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started signing, and the place was just a silent hush; their
eyes were wide open, their mouths were hanging down,'' he
remembers. ``They just embraced me after that.''
</P>
<P>
   That summer, with his own money, he put on the first camp at
Millnech. It started as a six-hour day camp with 35 players _ and a
team of coaches that consisted of Glenn and former teammates Marvin
Webster, Joe Meriweather and Micheal Ray Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it was repaying a debt of gratitude, and this camp is
an extension of what is comfortable for me, of what is happiness
for me,'' Glenn said. ``It's so connected to me, that it's almost
inseparable.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, professionals like Hawks guard Steve Smith and
Vancouver Grizzlies forward Shareef Abdur-Rahim have visited the
camp. A handful of volunteer coaches, who use a week's worth of
their vacation time in the summer, have run the camp since its
inception 18 years ago and work to keep the sponsorships and a
group of 80 to 100 kids coming each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to it every year; it's like a family reunion,''
said Reggie Johnson, 38, Glenn's oldest friend from Cave Spring,
who helped start the camp. ``We've worked hard, real hard, but it's
all been so rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   The real reward goes to the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I grew up around hearing people, I felt I had to prove
myself all the time,'' Nathaniel LaRue, of the Katzenbach (N.J.)
School for the Deaf, said through an interpreter. ``Here, we're all
equal, so you have to prove yourself athletically, but you don't
have to prove yourself that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Glenn introduced ``reverse mainstreaming,'' in
which eight to 10 nondeaf players are invited. They learn quickly
that many of their deaf teammates are talented ball players who act
just like other teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the deaf an opportunity to experience challenges with
kids from different states and with some hearing kids,'' said
Willie Brown, a Georgia State graduate and the program's greatest
success as the first deaf basketball player with a Division I
scholarship. ``At the same time, the hearing kid gets to see a deaf
kid compete at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn looks forward to the day when a second-generation camper
comes through the program and plays alongside his son, Michael
Justin, 6, who once knew more signs than spoken words. Maybe, Glenn
hopes, his son already has a hero, like the one his father did
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so proud when I see him sign; he's so comfortable, and I
see he's learned some of those lessons,'' Glenn said. ``I like the
mission that this camp has accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
