<HEADER>
A0565 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-NBADRAFT27-COX     06-26 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-NBADRAFT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA draft casualties join earlier
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NBA and superagent David Falk have been
adversaries at times, allies at others. Underclassmen bolting
college to the NBA is one issue they agree on: Something must be
done to prevent the mass defection of underdeveloped talent to a
man's league.
</P>
<P>
   The way Falk sees it, much of the problem can be solved by
executing laws already in effect. Nearly half the states in the
nation have some sort of law regulating what agents can do with
college or high school kids, Falk says. In North Carolina, it's a
felony for an agent to have contact with a student-athlete without
first giving written notification to the applicable college
athletics director or high school principal, the Charlotte Observer
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   But the laws almost never are enforced. And so, athletes that
still have college eligibility are receiving and heeding misguided
advice, according to Falk. ``Economic suicide'' is what Falk calls
the players who skip to the NBA too soon. Falk represents many
players who left school early, including Duke's Elton Brand. But he
insists that he never recommends they leave before their
eligibility is up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players are getting such poor advice,'' Falk says. ``We
all watched (high school player) Rashard Lewis sit at the draft
last year and cry as he slid into the second round.... I doubt
anyone advised him he'd go in the second round. Or Al Harrington,
who went 25th to Indiana. Had he gone to school for one year he
probably would have been top 10 this year. That decision might cost
him $5 million to $10 million'' over his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, we need more disasters,'' he says, ``because no one
wants to acknowledge that advising players is a specialized
business. You need disasters to warn players this is a very serious
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has seen its product decline in recent years because of
the influx of players coming into the league who have not been
refined in the game. Flash is up, scoring down. And commissioner
David Stern has put it on his agenda to somehow put an age
requirement on potential draftees. That would all but eliminate the
high school player but not prevent athletes from playing one season
before bolting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the right to set an age limit in the
collective-bargaining agreement,'' Stern said. ``I believe we can
work together to come up with something that is legally correct and
will withstand legal challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island sophomore star Lamar Odom, who declared himself
eligible for Wednesday's draft and hired an agent, does not seem to
have much legal ground in his attempt to return to the school.
Odom, 19, fired lawyer Jeff Klein and decided he did not want to go
pro yet, but he relinquished his amateur status when he hired
Klein.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has not filed a formal appeal, Odom wants the NCAA
to allow him to retain his two years of eligibility. Meanwhile, NBA
Players Association executive director Billy Hunter contended that
Odom should be allowed to return to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be unfortunate if this young man was compelled to
begin his NBA career before he believes he is ready,'' Hunter said.
``If, indeed, Lamar has determined that it is in his best interest
to continue to mature as an individual and as an athlete in a
college environment, we sincerely hope he will have that
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The draft had 38 early-entry players, going into the weekend.
Most NBA personnel officials say they think that fewer than half of
them will get drafted. The Philadelphia Daily News did a study that
pointed out almost none of the undrafted players go back to
college. And in the last five years, only 81 of 148 hopefuls were
drafted, and just 51 of the 81 who were drafted are still in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kinds of numbers will continue to be that way with the
way things are going,'' Vancouver president Stu Jackson said.
``It's a cycle that we have to do something about.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
