<HEADER>
A0567 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-CALLAWAY27-COX     06-26 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CALLAWAY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Callaway led golf's charge out of the woods
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While newcomers to golf probably will not believe it,
there really was a time when woods were wood. It was a period of
great ugliness in the game. Imagine, a club face with all the
explosiveness of an end table, a mis-hit ball that barely went
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Feel fortunate you weren't a part of such hackdom.
</P>
<P>
   LaGrange native Ely Callaway changed all that, of course. His
company, Callaway Golf, wasn't the first to manufacture a metal
wood, but it definitely began the high-tech, oversized driver
explosion _ from $22 million in sales in 1990 to $842 million in
1997 _ and remains king of the market today.
</P>
<P>
   Big Bertha to Great Big Bertha to Biggest Big Bertha. Golf was
never the same after this charming but feisty man, now 80 years
old, began what became the oversized titanium driver revolution. It
has grown to include fairway woods and irons, but the love affair
with the longest club started with Big Bertha in 1991. Named after
a World War I cannon, the club, despite its expense, became the
``gotta-have-it'' item for millions of worldwide amateurs and pros.
Although Callaway's share of the market has been reduced by the
avalanche of competitors who followed him into the market, the Big
Bertha driver has become the golfer's friendliest item since the
beverage cart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's graduated from being the least popular club in the bag to
being the most popular for most golfers,'' Callaway said in a
recent telephone interview. ``We do feel very proud of that, and
we're very glad that it has happened, because it fundamentally
changed an attitude toward a golf club.''
</P>
<P>
   A man who believes that loyalty and character are nearly as
vital as one's heart and lungs, Callaway left Burlington Industries
after nearly 30 years in the textile business in a dispute about a
chairmanship he thought should have been his.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship he establishes with both employees and those
who endorse his clubs is as special as the feel of high-tech metal
meeting balata. At the Carlsbad, Calif., manufacturing and testing
facility, everyone eats in the same dining room, whether it's
Callaway, Big Bertha design guru Dick Helmstetter or the workers
who pull the molten, metal molds from the furnace.
</P>
<P>
   The man's energy and optimism are inspiring. But what would you
expect from a fellow who turned a small-market company called
Hickory Stick, which made specialty wedges and putters, into the
golf's all-time equipment story? Larry Dorman, who was hired to
write a book on Callaway when Dorman was golf writer for the New
York Times, was so intrigued by the man that he left journalism to
serve as Callaway's vice president of advertising, press and public
relations. Smitten by Dorman's personality, professional skills and
contacts, Callaway made him an offer he couldn't refuse, tripling
his newspaper salary.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Azinger, who won a PGA Championship in 1993, then fought
for his life against cancer, won't forget that Callaway paid him in
full during the entire year he was unable to play while undergoing
chemotherapy and radiation treatments. When Callaway took on
troublesome John Daly in 1997, who was dropped by Wilson after his
alcohol-related problems, it absorbed several hundred thousand
dollars of Daly's gambling debts.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Azinger attended Callaway's 75th birthday party,
despite being ``as bald-headed as a cue ball, with the bandana and
a coat and tie.'' Callaway also made a large donation to the
American Cancer Society in Azinger's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves me and I love him,'' Azinger said. ``I think the
world of the guy. I feel a tremendous amount of loyalty to Callaway
Golf because of `Mr. C.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although Callaway hasn't lived in Georgia regularly since
graduating from Emory University in 1940, he returns to the area
frequently and has made a major impact on Atlanta _ and not just
from area tee boxes. In 1993, he gave Emory Callaway stock worth
more than $5.8 million that was used to renovate the university's
physics building, since renamed The Loula Walker and Ely Reeves
Callaway Sr. Memorial Center, in honor of his parents. Among his
other regular contributions to Emory is a percentage of sales from
the Bobby Jones commemorative clubs in the form of a Robert T.
Jones Jr. Scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and father taught me that it's better to give than
receive,'' Callaway said. ``And if you've got it and can be
helpful, that's nice. I think it's a whole lot to enjoy giving
while you're alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Callaway is a distant cousin of Jones; they share a common
great-grandparent. He likes to imagine what might have transpired
had a Great Big Bertha been available for the legendary player from
East Lake Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have made him perfect,'' Callaway says, chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   His delightful accent always will connect him to the South, even
if the miles and the workload since reclaiming his CEO position
last year do not allow it. He was back at Callaway Gardens in Pine
Mountain this spring for a dedication of the Callaway Brothers
Azalea Bowl at the resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still connected there, but the connections are becoming
fewer by the month, because time is passing, and people move on and
sometimes even die,'' Callaway said. ``But I have many cousins
there on the side of Cason and Fuller Callaway (the brothers who
founded the Callaway Gardens resort). I hope they still admit I'm
one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   A former chairman of the National United Negro College Fund
Corporate Campaign, Callaway on one occasion in 1970 would not
allow impending surgery to interrupt his plans. Just before a major
fund-raising luncheon in Atlanta, he was stricken with an illness.
Vernon Jordan, then the executive director of the UNCF, said ``In
excruciating pain, he was rushed to the emergency room of a local
hospital. During the preparation for surgery, Ely arranged to tape
his speech to the luncheon.... We raised the largest amount in the
history of the UNCF that year _ $10 million.''
</P>
<P>
   A 3-handicap player in his 40s _ Azinger still calls him ``a
beautiful swinger of the golf club'' _ Callaway basically has
sacrificed his own game while lowering America's handicaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play much because I don't have time,'' he says.
``Generally, I spend my time hitting the ball (on the test range),
evaluating new clubs instead of trying to get ball in the cup,
which is too difficult.... I spend my time trying to put myself in
the place of the average hacker and see how they will react to our
new woods and irons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Bertha was a steel-headed driver (War Bird model) before
going titanium, but popular from the start, even at $250. The
company's unique, bore-through design difference was Helmstetter's
S2H2 (Short Straight Hollow Hosel). When titanium became the rage
and the Great Big Bertha opened at $500, some critics thought it
marketing suicide, but rival Taylor Made immediately introduced its
equally pricey weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Although the equipment market has stagnated the last couple of
years, with Callaway sales dropping slightly in 1998, net sales for
the first quarter of 1999 were $185.7 million _ up 5 percent. Of
that dollar amount, $81.6 million came from titanium metal woods. A
Callaway golfball is due out in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never started out in a business with the ultimate
long-term goals in mind,'' Callaway says. ``I take one step at a
time and let things evolve. We hadn't the faintest idea that when
we got into the golf-club business by buying that little company
that we would become a large-scale, worldwide golf company. We
didn't even think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, chances are remote of standing on the first tee with your
weekly foursome and not seeing at least one Big Bertha driver
emerge from under a head cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job now is to come out with a new driver that's going to
be much more rewarding in some way than the current Great Big
Bertha Hawk Eye is,'' Callaway said. ``We intend to do that, and
we're going to do it. I can't tell you when, but if we use our
brains properly and work hard enough, we'll come up with another
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubters, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
