<HEADER>
A0568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-WAR27-COX     06-26 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WAR27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Club maker fights to protect name
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A year ago, the fight was with the United States Golf
Association, which threatened the unthinkable _ a ban on oversized,
titanium drivers. It took full-page advertisements in publications
all over the world for Ely Callaway to state his case.
</P>
<P>
   Now, things basically are back to normal for the energetic
octogenarian from LaGrange who heads Callaway Golf. He has returned
to arm-wrestling with his competitors.
</P>
<P>
   If Callaway, 80, isn't suing rival Orlimar for what he thinks is
patent infringement and unfair advertising, he is raising his blood
pressure about other things he thinks are deceptive to the American
public. In other words, if a golf fan sees a Callaway cap on a
player, it means that he is playing Callaway clubs _ and in just
about all cases, at least 10 clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We happen to think that good ethics is good business,''
Callaway said in a recent phone interview, ``and we hear some of
our competitors don't feel that way at all. They say, `Oh, well,
it's only business.'... We think when most people watch from the
gallery or on TV and they see a Callaway bag with Colin
Montgomerie, many of the people assume Colin Montgomerie is playing
Callaway clubs; and that one of the reasons he's playing well and
winning is because the clubs are Callaway. That's what it says when
we put our name on the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Callaway, who sued Orlimar Golf during the winter, claiming that
its new irons copied their own patented design process, fumed when
Orlimar advertised Ted Tryba as one of its own after he shot a 61
at the Nissan Open. Tryba wore an Orlimar cap without playing any
of the company's clubs, Callaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway ended up embarrassed recently when staff member Paul
Stankowski was caught playing last month with a Callaway bag and
his old Ping irons inside. All Stankowski had to do, Callaway said,
was inform the company that he wanted to switch back to his old
irons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would understand,'' he said. ``We just would have told him
not to use the bag the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Azinger, another Callaway staff member, this year acted on
an option in his contract and requested to return to his old
MacGregor blade irons, because he was having difficulty with the
amount of offset in the Callaway X-12 irons. The company sent him a
new bag, which just said ``Callaway Big Bertha Metal Woods'' on it.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit filed by Callaway against Orlimar remains in the
courts, with Callaway recently having filed an amended complaint.
Orlimar president and CEO Jesse Ortiz said, ``We have demonstrated
that Orlimar TriMetal technology is superior, and Callaway's
lawsuit cannot change that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the USGA, the people there testing clubs for abnormal
``spring-like effect'' have quieted down but haven't gone away.
Callaway continues to wonder about their agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still in the frame of mind we were this time a year
ago,'' Callaway said, ``and that is that extra distance off the tee
is good for golf. Their feeling is that extra distance off the tee
is bad for golf.... By good for golf, we mean good for millions of
golfers who play and who indeed know that, even with a lot of extra
distance that they can get today, they're no threat to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
