<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-ROYALTIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERIOR REGULATIONS BECOME MIRED IN A DEBATE ON ETHICS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After Mobil Oil settled a lawsuit last year
charging that it had underpaid the government for drilling rights,
one of the public interest groups that filed the suit shared its
award with two federal employees who had long complained about oil
company royalty payments.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Interior Department has been trying to force the
industry to pay higher royalty fees to the government, but
congressional critics are now using questions about the unusual
rewards to the federal officials to delay any new regulations. The
Justice Department is also investigating the propriety of the
payments of $350,000 each to the two federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   The reverberations from the payments have produced a peculiarly
Washingtonian tale of ethics, lobbying and the intensity of policy
debates when vast amounts of money are on the table.
</P>
<P>
   The latest events were set in motion last August, when the
interest group, Project on Government Oversight, received nearly
$1.2 million for its part in bringing a successful lawsuit against
Mobil for paying about $40 million less than it owed the U.S.
Treasury for drilling on federal lands.
</P>
<P>
   The board of the group, based in Washington, decided in November
to share the money with the two officials, one of them at Interior
and the other at the Energy Department, because they had been
campaigning and complaining for years that the oil companies were
not paying their fair share.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Department has since drafted regulations that would
force the oil companies to pay more in royalties, regulations that
are expected to cost the oil companies several billion dollars over
the next decade. But members of Congress who oppose the regulations
say that the rules are tainted because the two officials who
received the payments may have had a role in preparing the
measures.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has opened an investigation into the
payments, one made to an official still employed by the Interior
Department, Robert Berman, and the other to Robert A. Speir, who
recently retired from the Energy Department. The Justice
Department's Public Integrity section is looking into whether the
payments violated any of the laws that prohibit payments to
government employees because they might constitute a bribe, illegal
gratuity or improper outside income.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Brian, the executive director of the public interest
group, which goes by the acronym POGO, said in an interview that
the decision to share the award from the lawsuit was an effort to
reward two employees who had acted for years as whistle-blowers and
had been ignored by their superiors.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have been saying the system is filled with problems
since 1986,'' Ms. Brian said. ``We felt it was the fair thing to do
to reward them. What's really going on here is that the oil
industry has been caught underpaying the government and they're
trying to do anything to divert attention from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brian's organization has been responsible over the years for
disclosing embarrassing cost overruns and government purchases,
particularly in the military, including things like a $400 hammer
and $76 screws.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, and a staunch ally of the oil
industry, said in an interview that the payments should not have
been made under any circumstances. ``It really puts the agency
people up for sale,'' he said. ``If we're going to give out rewards
to public officials for policies someone outside the government
likes, the oil companies have plenty of money.''
</P>
<P>
   POGO, Berman and Speir have been battling with their Republican
adversaries in Congress over what role they played in drafting the
regulations being proposed. The Interior Department issued a
statement saying Berman and Speir had only ``inconsequential''
roles in the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Republican staff aides on the Energy Committee say they have
memorandums and computer messages from the two officials showing
that they played some role in drafting the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``This all casts a cloud over the Interior regulations,'' said
Young, who is helping to block the rules from taking effect. ``How
can they implement the regulations when this matter is under
investigation by the department?''
</P>
<P>
   The payments were first disclosed by Platt's Oilgram News, a
trade daily that covers the energy industry. But the complaints
about their propriety have been propagated widely by Poe Leggette,
a Washington lawyer and lobbyist and former Interior Department
official who has represented several major oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some sort of delay is warranted until the Justice
Department completes its investigation,'' Leggette said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit against Mobil and several similar actions were
brought under the Federal False Claims Act, a Civil War-era statute
that was given new life in 1986 when it was revised by Congress.
Under the law, private citizens may bring lawsuits against anyone
they think has defrauded the government. If the lawsuits are
successful, the outside party may collect anywhere from 10 percent
to 30 percent of the award as a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Prof. Evan Caminker of the law school at the University of
California at Los Angeles, an authority on these kinds of lawsuits,
said that courts had generally held that public officials may be
part of a group that brings such lawsuits but not in any matter on
which they were involved as a government assignment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
