<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CRENSHAW'S APPROACH SHOT IS GENTLE BUT TOUGH
ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ He's known as Gentle Ben, and he is. That's why
some people are wondering if Ben Crenshaw is too nice to be the
Ryder Cup captain. He disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not too nice,'' he said. ``If I have something in my mind,
I stick to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Over a quarter of a century on the PGA Tour, Ben Crenshaw had
winning in his mind, and he stuck to it with his tenacious Texan
toughness. Stuck to it to win 19 tournaments, including two
Masters, and over $7 million in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   Now the something stuck in his mind is regaining the Ryder Cup
from the European pros in the Sept. 24-26 matches at the Country
Club in Brookline, Mass., and he's definitely tough enough to be
the captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very competitive, very traditional,'' Crenshaw said. ``I
believe in the Ryder Cup and what it stands for. But I've got to be
myself. If I go completely out of myself and rant and rave, that
won't be me. My job is to get these guys team-oriented for the
matches.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 12 pros on the U.S. team, the top 10 finishers in the
Ryder Cup standing will be automatic choices. The current top 10
are David Duval, Tiger Woods, Payne Stewart, Davis Love III, Mark
O'Meara, Hal Sutton, Jim Furyk, Phil Mickelson, Jeff Maggert and
Steve Stricker.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw will complete the team with two captain's choices from
a group that is likely to include John Huston, Steve Pate, Fred
Couples, Lee Janzen, Justin Leonard and Tom Lehman, if not Maggert
and Stricker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of tournaments for guys to increase their
Ryder Cup points,'' Crenshaw said. ``With the guys already sure to
make it, I want them to play practice rounds together at
tournaments, chip and putt together, eat together, feel like
teammates, because they are.''
</P>
<P>
   The team won't be completed until Aug. 16, after the PGA
Championship at Medinah outside Chicago. Two weeks later, the day
after the World Golf Championship NEC Invitational in Akron, Ohio,
the team will arrive at the Country Club for a practice round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not knowing the course at Valderrama was a problem when we
didn't win in Spain two years ago,'' Crenshaw said. ``And the young
guys on the team have never played the Country Club. The only ones
who have are the older guys who played there in the 1988 United
States Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw, who missed the 36-hole cut at the Buick Classic, was
sitting on the bench at his Westchester Country Club locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Country Club is a placement course, especially on your
approach shots,'' he said. ``The greens are small. But with that
one practice round, when they get there the Tuesday before the
matches, they'll know where they are. They won't waste that Tuesday
getting to know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at a nearby locker, Tom Kite, the 1997 captain,
couldn't help but overhear Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``That practice round will be important,'' Kite said. ``Two
years ago I asked all our guys to stop at Valderrama for a practice
round on the way to the British Open, but the only guys who did
were Tiger, Mark O'Meara and Davis Love. I also had a private jet
coming down there from Scotland and six guys were supposed to be on
it, but only one guy got off _ Payne Stewart.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, it turned out, wasn't on that 1997 team, but as the
reigning U.S. Open champion, he's a lock this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne will be a tremendous asset to our team,'' Crenshaw said.
``He'll help keep the other guys loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Kite said: ``You need somebody with a sense of humor to relax
everybody. Somebody like Payne, Peter Jacobsen, Paul Azinger. In
1993 at the Belfry, Paul brought a crazy little game called, `Pass
the Pig,' a dice game with the dice shaped like a pig. Playing that
game, guys relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   The American team retained the cup, 15-13, in England that year,
but lost it to the Europeans at Oak Hill outside Rochester in 1995.
During the loss to the Europeans at Valderrama, long rain delays on
both Friday and Saturday prevented the American team from hanging
out together.
</P>
<P>
   ``No dead time at night,'' Kite said. ``The players were so
tired when they got back to the hotel after playing 36 holes, they
just crashed.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the American hopes of regaining the cup that the
Europeans had snatched at Oak Hill when Nick Faldo holed an
8-footer on the 18th green to defeat Curtis Strange, 1-up, in the
decisive singles.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Crenshaw knows how it feels to win and lose the Ryder Cup.
He helped hold the cup in 1981 and 1983, but he was on that losing
team at Oak Hill and also on the losing 1987 team at Muirfield
Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Muirfield Village, the Europeans beat us in the short game,
getting it up and down, making a big putt,'' the captain said. ``At
Oak Hill, I had an inability to hole putts. I don't feel like I did
my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Crenshaw doesn't want to feel that way at the Country Club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
