<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROTATING ROTATION  
 HUNDLEY TRIES TO REGROUP  
 BAD START I, BAD START II  
 ORIOLES GLAD BELLE IS MAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Try to follow the bouncing baseball as it has caromed around the
Boston Red Sox starting rotation:
</P>
<P>
   Juan Pena is summoned from the minor leagues to take the spot of
Bret Saberhagen, who goes on the disabled list with a strained
right shoulder. Brian Rose is called up to take Pena's place when
he is put on the disabled list with a sore right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen returns and bumps Pat Rapp to the bullpen. Rapp
quickly returns to the rotation when Mark Portugal leaves the club
and considers retirement. Portugal comes back and replaces
Saberhagen, who moves to the disabled list a second time with a cut
left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Jin Ho Cho, yet another rookie, is promoted from the minors to
replace Tim Wakefield, who becomes the closer when Tom Gordon goes
on the disabled list. Saberhagen returns but bumps no one to the
bullpen because Manager Jimy Williams decides to keep all six
pitchers in the rotation for one cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The rookies Pena, Rose and Cho have started a total of 12 games.
Their collective record is 8-0; the Red Sox have won 11 of their 12
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley Tries to Regroup
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers are suffering the most disappointing
first half in the majors, and no one feels sorry for them. In fact,
more people in baseball are probably delighted with their stunning
failure than with any other development. That's because they let
everyone know last winter how they were going to ride Rupert
Murdoch's money to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers are collapsing under the weight of their own
boasts, and one of the reasons is the inability of Todd Hundley to
recapture the catching and hitting ability he possessed with the
New York Mets before his elbow operation. Desperate to get
themselves moving forward, the Dodgers decided to take a step
backward with Hundley. They benched him for a week and a half _ he
sat out eight consecutive games _ while he worked on his throwing
mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody keeps screaming that he's not healthy,'' Rick
Dempsey, a Dodgers coach and former catcher, said. ``I'm screaming
that he is healthy. There are no problems with his arm from a
physical standpoint. He's gotten into so many bad habits since he
came back from the operation it's hard to pinpoint any one of them.
The bottom line is he's not throwing any runners out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley had thrown out only seven of 60 runners who tried to
steal, a dreadful 12 percent success ratio. He was hitting .230.
``I think his offense was bothering his defense more than vice
versa,'' Dempsey said.
</P>
<P>
   At manager Davey Johnson's request, Dempsey conducted an
in-season spring training camp for Hundley, overseeing daily 3 p.m.
workouts. His aim was to shorten Hundley's stride and throwing
motion when he tried to throw out base stealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitchers are as much to blame because they don't give him an
opportunity to throw out runners,'' Dempsey said. ``He rushed, and
it turned into something ugly. Ten days to two weeks may not be
enough time, but we have to get him back in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, whose outfield experiment with the Mets last season
contributed to a change in his throwing style, threw, threw and
threw some more. He worked with live batters and base runners,
shortening his stride and his motion and speeding up his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw a lot,'' Dempsey said. ``We broke him down so we
could build him back up. He's laying on the ground gasping, saying
his legs just can't take it. A catcher needs his legs for throwing
so we have him on a running program to build up his endurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dempsey liked the improvement he said Hundley made during their
training camp. ``I know it's all going to work out,'' the coach
said. ``We absolutely need him. I'll work with him as long as he
needs it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad Start I, Bad Start II
</P>
<P>
   Ben Grieve of Oakland, the American League rookie of the year
last season, struggled at bat for the first two months of this
season. Every time he looked at the scoreboard and his batting
average was posted, it began with a 1. But a two-hit game June 9 at
San Diego lifted him above .200 (31-154, .201) for the first time
since opening day, and, collecting 22 hits in 61 at-bats (.361) in
that game and the next 15 games, he reached a season-high .242
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Rivera of San Diego, whom the Yankees sent west for Hideki
Irabu, was slightly above .200 in the early days of the season,
then quickly fell below and did not get back over that mark until
June 18 (34-168, .202). Unlike Grieve, Rivera has not taken off. He
slipped back to .198 Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles Glad Belle Is Mad
</P>
<P>
   When Albert Belle played for the Cleveland Indians, his
teammates felt that the angrier he was, the better he hit, so they
supposedly set out to do things that made him angry. His current
team now has reason to believe in the Indians' method.
</P>
<P>
   When Baltimore manager Ray Miller sat Belle down for a game
after he did not run out a grounder, Belle was hitting .244 and had
socked 10 home runs and driven in 35 runs in 58 games. Since
getting back into the lineup the next game, Angry Albert, entering
Saturday's game, was hitting .370 with five home runs and 10 RBIs
in 13 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0585 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-2NDT     06-26 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: tell us.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But Congress is cautious, and the reason can be summarized in
one word: cost.
</P>
<P>
   From 1992 to 1997, national spending on prescription drugs grew
by an average of 11 percent a year, which is more than double the 5
percent rate for health care spending overall. The increase
reflects the development of new, more expensive, more effective
drug therapies and greater use of prescription drugs, driven in
part by more aggressive marketing aimed directly at consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers and health maintenance organizations report that drugs
are their fastest-growing cost.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid, the federal-state program for poor families, does
cover prescription drugs, and even though it gets substantial
discounts from manufacturers, Medicaid now spends more on drugs
than on doctors' services.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Concannon, the commissioner of human services in Maine,
said the state's Medicaid program spent $140 million a year on
prescription drugs, compared with $40 million on doctors' services.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen deMontmollin, vice president of AvMed Health Plan, a
large nonprofit HMO in Florida, said drug spending for his members
rose 33 percent last year, to $115 million.
</P>
<P>
   At a congressional hearing last week, Republican senators like
William Roth Jr. of Delaware, Charles Grassley of Iowa and John
Chafee of Rhode Island expressed support for Medicare coverage of
drugs, but said it should be provided first to the neediest
beneficiaries. Moderate Democratic senators like John Breaux of
Louisiana and Max Baucus of Montana agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley, the chairman of the Senate Special Committee on Aging,
expressed the view of the Republican majority. He cautioned against
``any rich new benefit'' and said, ``A targeted approach, focusing
on low-income seniors, is the best solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux was chairman of a 17-member commission that was supposed
to advise Congress and the president on the future of Medicare. The
panel did not agree on much, but did provide authoritative
bipartisan backing for the view that Medicare is antiquated because
it does not cover prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux proposed drug coverage for 3 million low-income
beneficiaries, and he said it would cost the government $60 billion
over 10 years. The White House rejected the proposal as
``inadequate and inefficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Democrats, led by Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts
and Reps. Henry Waxman and Pete Stark of California, agree with
Clinton that drug coverage should be available to all
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare beneficiaries now pay a premium of $45.50 a month.
Under current law, with no change in benefits, the monthly premium
is expected to double in a decade, to $101 in 2009. Any premium for
prescription drug coverage would be added to that.
</P>
<P>
   John Podesta, the White House chief of staff, said the poorest
people would not have to pay the full premium for drug coverage
under Clinton's plan. ``Some people will get help with the premium
at the lower end of the scale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a consumer
group, said, ``It makes sense for seniors to pay a significant part
of the cost through a premium.'' But, he said, it is ``absolutely
essential'' for the government to pay the premiums for Medicare
beneficiaries with incomes as much as 35 percent above the poverty
level (up to $14,931 for a couple).
</P>
<P>
   ``Administration officials told me they were willing to pay the
full premium on the drug benefit for people with incomes up to 120
percent of the poverty level,'' Pollack said. ``I urged them to do
better than that, to go to 135 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Low-income beneficiaries are already eligible for federal
assistance in paying their basic Medicare premiums. But in studies
going back to 1991, Pollack has repeatedly documented the failure
of the federal government and the states to locate the people
eligible for such subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare officials have told the White House that if Medicare
begins to cover prescription drugs, many more low-income people
would have an incentive to step forward and claim the federal
subsidies to which they are entitled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
