<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOUTING FOR PLUS FACTORS AMONG COSTA RICA'S NEW ARRIVALS FROM
CUBA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Venezuela, Dominican Republic, Costa Rica, Cuba)   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Desperate to find talent in any corner of the earth, more than a
dozen teams, including the Yankees and the Mets, had scouts in
Costa Rica the past few days scrutinizing the latest catch from
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Six players _ two pitchers, two catchers, two outfielders _
defected in the last year and now seek their personal pot of
baseball gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no talent to rave about,'' one scout said after
watching the catchers and the outfielders work out last Thursday,
``but that doesn't mean the guys won't get a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a shrinking lode of good amateur players in North
America, teams have fanned out all over the world pursuing nuggets
they hope will grow to be major-league gems.
</P>
<P>
   In their frenzied quest, however, they are not always as
discriminating as they were when talent in this country was
abundant.
</P>
<P>
   Guillermo Quiroz is a Venezuelan catcher who at the age of 16
last year worked out in Florida for interested clubs. ``He's
well-developed for his age, he's a well-below-average runner, has
below-average arm strength, shows power in batting practice,'' an
official of one team said at the time after watching Quiroz. ``But
the way the business operates, he will probably command a decent
bonus. In that kind of atmosphere you create a competition where
somebody is going to want to beat somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Blue Jays did just that, signing Quiroz last
September for a $1 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have executed more than their share of expensive
signings of foreign players: Hideki Irabu, Orlando Hernandez,
Jackson Melian, Ricardo Aramboles and Alfonso Soriano, for example.
The latest was Willi Mo Pena, an outfielder from the Dominican
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets initially signed Pena for the 1999 season last July,
giving him a $6,000 bonus. But the commissioner's office
subsequently declared him a free agent after it was learned that
the Mets signed him illegally. It seems that the scout who signed
the 16-year-old Pena signed his father's name to the contract,
without knowing that his father could not write and signed his name
with three X's.
</P>
<P>
   With Don Nomura, who represents Irabu, as his agent, Pena, now
all of 17 years old, proceeded to sign with the Yankees last April
for just a bit more than the bonus the Mets gave him: the Yankees
awarded Pena a $2.4 million signing bonus and a total package of
$3.7 million for five years. But that wasn't all. They also put him
on the major-league 40-man roster, a status seldom accorded to a
player signing his first contract.
</P>
<P>
   Under a major-league contract, Pena's salary is covered by the
maximum 20 percent cut rule, and the sizable bonus becomes part of
the salary. His contractual status also affects the number of years
the Yankees can have him under reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to sign Pena to a major-league contract was made by
George Steinbrenner, who sided with his minor league office in
Tampa over his major-league office in New York. One of the reasons
the major-league office was opposed to the signing was that the
contract's $740,000 average annual value raised the team's payroll
for luxury tax purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Another Pena, Brayan, is among the Cuban contingent in Costa
Rica. The profile sent to major-league clubs by the agent for the
players, Gus Dominguez of Beverly Hills, Calif., said the
17-year-old catcher was ``considered by most knowledgeable sources
to be the best prospect in Cuban baseball outside of National Team
(`A') and considered by many to be the best overall prospect in
Cuban baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The scout who attended the workouts said that Brayan Pena, who
defected in Venezuela before a tournament in April, did not
demonstrate a ``plus'' tool, using scouting terminology.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have a plus arm, he's not a plus runner and he
didn't show plus power,'' the scout said. Furthermore, he said,
scouts were disappointed because Pena was ``a little bit
overweight.''
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive player of the group, the scout added after a
Friday game, was a pitcher, Miguel Perez, a 23-year-old
right-hander. But, he said, Perez is ``not in the class of Livan
and El Duque,'' referring to the half-brothers Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   The players cannot negotiate or sign with anyone until they gain
residency status in Costa Rica. Dominguez, their agent, said they
have temporary residency and are awaiting notification on their
request for permanent status.
</P>
<P>
   At best, the scout said, the players have ``average type of
ability,'' then quickly added, ``That doesn't mean they're not
going to get a lot of money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
