<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GOING IN THE WIND TO SYDNEY IS A TEEN-AGER'S GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELTER ISLAND, N.Y. _ This is Amanda Clark's downwind summer,
probably her last chance to improve without pressure, to find out
without penalty how far she can push before she flips. She is 17
years old, your basic amateur. She buys her own shoes.
</P>
<P>
   There are no college scholarships in her sport. No agents call.
On money raised from friends and neighbors, her mother and father
will take turns accompanying her to Finland, England, the
Netherlands, Canada, as Amanda works her way through the fleet
toward next April's Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   In this time of ferocious tennis parents and personal Little
League coaches and sneaker-company summer camps, Amanda Clark's
``Sailing to Sydney'' campaign seems quaint, although it is being
conducted on a Web site as well as on yacht-club lawns.
</P>
<P>
   On a particular breezy weekend morning, she admits being torn
between writing a few more of the thank-you notes to the 338 people
who have contributed $37,283 or taking a spin on the bay. Her face
changes, actually brightens, when she talks about sailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like wind,'' she said, sitting in the living room, her eyes
flicking toward a curtain moving in an open window. ``I liked it
right away. From the start, I felt free when I was sailing. I could
go wherever I wanted. I never got tired. I could go fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was genes. Her grandfather, Albertus ``Toots'' Clark,
sailed on Vanderbilt yachts and became a professional captain.
Maybe it was upbringing. Her father, Dennis Clark, a painting
contractor, put his three children on his boat as soon as they were
heavy enough to be ballast.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just knew right away where to sit in a boat to not be in
the way, to not get hit on the head,'' said Clark, one of the few
locals here to join the 113-year-old Shelter Island Yacht Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was never afraid,'' said her mother, Ellen Clark, who runs
a recruitment company for pharmaceutical scientists. ``When Amanda
was 7, she went out by herself. She just has a way on the water.''
</P>
<P>
   In the youth sailboats called Optimists, Amanda quickly
established herself as competitive, tireless, willing to ``sail her
hours'' on her own after school, on weekends and in cold weather,
and to bounce back from mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   When she was 12, the family made the first major decision to
support her passion. She joined the sail maker Dev Colie's Jersey
Shore Optimist team. Denny Clark and Amanda made the 6 a.m. ferry
so she could be at Point Pleasant by 9. He would drive back to
work, and then he or Ellen would make another round trip late in
the day to pick her up. They remember the car rides fondly, a
chance to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda was good enough soon enough to need even longer rides, to
regattas in Florida, then California, Hawaii, Ireland, South
Africa, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weighed it so many times,'' said Ellen. ``Is this worth it?
We have two other children, Greg and Rebecca, both older. And we
saw other parents spending thousands of dollars, pushing kids who
really didn't want to sail, who'd be out there crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Amanda laughed. ``I'd be out there crying, too. `What am I doing
wrong?' Sometimes even `What am I doing here?' But that never
lasted long.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the Clarks say they saw youngsters with more
innate talent than Amanda _ a better sense of race tactics, for
example, an ability to read the wind shift faster _ but few who
seemed as determined, as ready to move on from a defeat, to learn
from it, to just work harder. They became absorbed in the extended
family of sailing families.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Amanda was the top woman at the Optimist Nationals. A
year later, she was ranked third on the U.S. sailing team in the
Europe class. Her competitors now were older, more experienced
sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, her old friends stopped calling to ask: Wanna hang
out?
</P>
<P>
   How could they understand the esoteric nature of her concerns?
Should she give up the hiking pads that are strapped around thighs
to give support and protection while the sailor hangs out over the
rail? As a child, she had considered them the epitome of
sophisticated sailing and longed for the day she would wear them.
But now, she is wondering if bruises are an acceptable price to pay
for the better fluidity of movement without them, the enhanced
connection to the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Wanna hang out?
</P>
<P>
   While she can't remember exactly when she discovered that the
tiller was really gripping her, she recalls a revelatory moment
last June, in an Optimist with a coach, Courtnay Becker-Dey. Then,
she said: ``Everything clicked. The boat just felt so good. I
wasn't fighting the helm, the shape of the sail was right, nothing
twisted, no big wrinkles, and I felt the power of the boat and I
felt in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going downwind, I knew my limits and I sailed that line,
just how far I could push the boat without flipping over. I had it.
I knew it was time to move on.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This is her moving-on summer, a chance to improve, no pressure
for rankings. With a Danish coach, Ken Andreasen, she will work on
upwind sailing, on thinking not only about what she is doing while
powering the boat but what is going on in the race. ``If I can hang
with the girls upwind _ I'm smaller than most of them _ I can use
my downwind skills to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   A high school senior, she will start looking at colleges in the
fall _ somewhere close to water _ and start lifting again. She is 5
feet 3 inches tall, and would like to add 10 pounds of muscle. ``I
haven't had time to get to 140,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The curtain is moving more insistently now and Amanda makes a
decision. She will write two dozen thank-you notes, and then get
into the wind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
