<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-U.S.-830(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO YOU WANT TO BE A WORLD SOCCER STAR
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the United States entered the first Women's World
Cup in 1991, midfielder Julie Foudy had to convince her father that
the trip to China was worthwhile. When the victorious Americans
returned home, about the only people to greet them at the airport
were baggage handlers.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, the Women's World Cup is being played in the
United States, and an unprecedented buzz has been created around
the national team, which has been sought out by news media outlets
from ``The Late Show with David Letterman'' and ``Hard Copy'' to
Sports Illustrated and Mademoiselle.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, Mia Hamm held a soccer ball in one hand and
signed a child's jersey with the other, while shouldering a
cellular phone to her ear and answering questions on a Chicago
sports-talk radio show. Earlier that day, several hundred children
ringed the practice field in suburban Chicago to watch the American
women train. When the national soccer team began in 1985, it was
lucky to get several hundred spectators at a game.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, the Americans drew 78,972 for the World Cup
opener against Denmark at Giants Stadium. It was the largest
audience ever to see a women's sporting event in this country. A
second sellout followed on Thursday, when the United States
defeated Nigeria, 7-1, before 65,080, at Soldier Field in Chicago.
A crowd of 50,000 is expected for Sunday's final round-robin match
against North Korea in Foxboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Individual female athletes like Billie Jean King and Jackie
Joyner-Kersee have become household names, but never has a women's
team sport been played on such a grand stage, on its own, free from
having to share attention with other events under the Olympic
umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are seeing a cultural shift in the sporting
landscape,'' said Donna de Varona, the chairwoman of the Women's
World Cup who is also an Olympic swimming champion and a longtime
booster of women's sports. ``There is room to embrace another sport
in the great stadiums of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the sport is gender-blind in this country, women don't
suffer by comparison, as they do in Italy or Brazil. Soccer has
been the No. 1 weekend attraction in this country for a long time.
We just had to give them the big event. Families are looking for
clean, wholesome, affordable fun and role models their kids can
identify with.''
</P>
<P>
   While television ratings have been unexceptional, organizers
expect them to grow as the tournament builds. They also hope to
sell out the 92,000-seat Rose Bowl if the Americans reach the final
on July 10. It should not be difficult for suburban America to
identify with players who are college-educated, smart, funny,
athletic, successful and attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman played host to Brandi Chastain, a defender, on one of
his recent shows, and the players responded by sending him a team
picture in which they appeared to be wearing nothing but ``Late
Show'' T-shirts. ``This may come out wrong,'' he said on the air,
``but the U.S. women's team is Babe City.''
</P>
<P>
   Adolescent girls squeal for the players with a high-pitched
shriek rarely heard among mammals outside the dolphin family.
``It's the Spice Girls meet Tigerbeat,'' Chastain said.
</P>
<P>
   To the rest of America, the players were virtually unknown until
two weeks ago. Now, moviegoers recognize them standing in line and
point them out to friends. For the American players, wearing soccer
gear to the mall is a no-no, the equivalent of a deer wearing a
bull's-eye in the woods. At the team hotels, youngsters ride the
elevators and call the players' rooms for autographs. The players
have begun checking in under assumed names.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michelle Akers used `Pig Farmer,' but had to change it,'' said
Aaron Heifetz, the team spokesman, ``which should not be seen as a
sign of disrespect for the pork industry.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has fielded inquiries about the team from every
magazine from The New Yorker to Muscle and Fitness. ``Christie
Pearce is a seamstress, and she made her own prom dress, so I keep
waiting on a call from American Quilt to do a profile,'' Heifetz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of this has been welcomed. Professional autograph
collectors have descended on the Women's World Cup, stalking
players at the team hotel. ``Heavy breathers,'' defender Kate
Sobrero calls them. Akers, the first American star who is playing
in her third World Cup, said that youngsters now follow her into
bathrooms in public places, seeking autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this attention better than no attention?'' Akers said.
``That's a good question. I wonder how Michael Jordan would answer
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But, most of the time, the players cheerily accept the
distractions. For most of their careers, they couldn't have been
any more anonymous if they had been in the witness-protection
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have one without the other,'' Foudy said. ``You
can't want to promote your sport and gain notoriety and be
financially successful without having those kinds of obligations
and distractions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even with the new visibility and the success of having won a
world championship and an Olympic gold medal, however, the American
women are still reminded frequently about the disparity between the
men's game and the women's.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday at Giants Stadium, the female referee insisted
that the American players remove all their jewelry, including
wedding rings. It was an officious request, considering that male
players wear more jewelry than QVC models. Carla Overbeck, the
American captain, refused to remove her wedding band, saying
``These don't come off,'' and the referee relented.
</P>
<P>
   The American women would each receive a bonus of $12,500 for
winning the World Cup, compared to the $380,000 that the American
men would have received had they won the 1998 World Cup in France.
The women, who went on strike over a salary dispute in 1995, have
chosen not to make an issue of the bonus disparity, feeling they
can eventually ease the incongruity by winning the 1999 World Cup
and generating a viable professional league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we're worth, but we have gone way beyond
what is expected of players to promote our sport,'' Chastain said.
``I think it's going to come around. I'm trusting that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain said she found it liberating to pose nude _ wearing
only cleats and holding a strategically placed soccer ball _ for
Gear magazine. It showed, she said, that female athletes are
``powerful, strong, athletic and we shouldn't be ashamed.'' It is
quite a bit more than fans are likely to see of her teammates, who
should continue appearing, fully clothed, at stadiums from coast to
coast in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This event is catching on in mainstream America,'' said Tony
DiCicco, coach of the women's national team. ``It's a look at
women's athletics in the future. Seldom has a women's team sport
had this type of global event. If we continue to win, I think
America will develop an Olympic aura, like we're trying to win a
gold medal, and I think everyone will be watching the team.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
