u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DRAFT-NYT &LR;      06-26 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS   TRADE SUNDSTROM, CLOUTIER TO DRAFT CZECH WING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On a draft day filled with a furious flurry of deals,
the Rangers moved up twice in the picking order, the Islanders
played a pat but full hand among the top 10 and the Devils took a
late selection.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers paid quite a price to get what they wanted. In
order to select Pavel Brendl with the fourth pick overall in what
is thought to be a strong draft, the Rangers traded Niklas
Sundstrom, a regular forward for four seasons, and Dan Cloutier, a
goalie who was thought to be one of their best future prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Those two players went, along with a first-round draft choice in
2000 and a third-round pick in 2000, to Tampa Bay. Sundstrom and
Cloutier were two of the few first-round draft choices who worked
out well for the Rangers in recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Later Sunday, the Rangers traded center Marc Savard to Tampa Bay
so that they could choose another center with the ninth selection.
They took Jamie Lundmark, from the Moose Jaw Warriors of the
Western Canadian junior league.
</P>
<P>
   Brendl, a 6-foot, 204-pound right wing, is from the Czech
Republic but played last season with the Calgary Hitmen of the
Western League, one of three major-junior circuits in Canada. In 68
games, he scored 73 goals and 61 assists.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's Central Scouting Bureau report rated Brendl ``a
powerful skater with a wide stride'' who has ``deceptive speed that
often results in breakaway opportunities.'' Although just 18 years
old, Brendl predicted he could play next season in New York,
possibly alongside center Petr Nedved, already a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I will,'' he said. ``I'm sure I can. I'm not scared
that I can't score in the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Brendl tried out last season with Las Vegas of the International
Hockey League, a minor professional circuit. One of his teammates
there, briefly, was Nedved, then a holdout with Pittsburgh, later
traded to New York from the Penguins. Nedved, Brendl said, urged
Brendl to play in juniors in Canada to get the experience, as
Nedved had done at the same age.
</P>
<P>
   The scouting report also called Brendl ``extremely accurate with
shooting and passing and almost always hits his target. Shows great
ability to find the open man in traffic. Has good lateral movement
when handling the puck and exhibits exceptional balance and
strength when fending off checking opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   The day began with a series of trades that re-arranged the order
of the first few picks of the first round. Vancouver, originally
scheduled to pick third, ended up with both the second and third
choices and chose Daniel and Henrik Sedin, twin brothers from
Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion team in Atlanta, scheduled to take the second pick
overall, moved up to first, replacing Tampa Bay, and took Patrik
Stefan, a native of the Czech Republic who played for Long Beach of
the IHL last season. Stefan, a 6-foot-1-inch, 205-pound center,
played only 33 games because of post-concussion syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, with three picks in the top 10, took center Tim
Connolly with the fifth pick overall, left wing Taylor Pyatt with
the eighth choice and defenseman Branislav Mezei with the 10th
choice. The Rangers, who were supposed to choose 11th in the first
round with their original pick, traded Savard to Calgary and
switched picks with the Flames, who were to choose ninth. With the
ninth overall choice, the Rangers took Lundmark and got another
player from Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   With their first pick, the 27th overall, the Devils chose Ari
Ahonen, a goalie from Finland.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' draft history in recent seasons has been spotty.
Last season's top pick was Manny Malhotra, who made the roster and
showed promise as a third- and fourth-line center.
</P>
<P>
   For various reasons, others have had less success. The 1997 top
pick was Stefan Cherneski, the 1996 pick was Jeff Brown and the
1995 pick (in the second round) was Christian Dube. The top choices
of 1994 and 1993 were Cloutier and Sundstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Cloutier was the backup goalie and Sundstrom, after a
disappointing season, was mentioned in trade talks, along Todd
Harvey, in a proposed deal with the Islanders for Zigmund Palffy
that fell through. The top pick in 1992 was Peter Ferraro, now with
Boston. The top pick in 1991, Alexsei Kovalev, was traded to
Pittsburgh last season for Nedved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
