<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BECKER ROLLS ALONG INTO WIMBLEDON'S ROUND OF 16  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Australia, Sweden, France, Spain, The Netherlands,
Calif., Pa.)   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Boris Becker's Wimbledon swan song is
showing signs of becoming an aria. The 31-year-old German, a decade
removed from the last of his three Wimbledon championships,
continued to turn back the clock and take control of Center Court
like a playground bully. It's not just his adoring fans, a legion
of flag-waving, face-painted zealots; his opponents seem caught up
in the spell as well.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Becker, the oldest warrior left on the men's side,
used his intimidation tactics to achieve the desired effect against
the youngest man in the draw, Australia's 18-year-old Lleyton
Hewitt, the ponytailed prospect from Down Under who predicted ``it
would be a buzz'' to share Becker's turf.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hewitt spent the day being buzzed by his idol's serve
while nervously missing his own targets. Hewitt's backhand passing
shots were of little threat to Becker as he stood sentry at the net
from start to finish and ultimately soldiered into the Round of 16,
a 6-1, 6-4, 7-6 (7-5). He next plays second-seeded Patrick Rafter,
who defeated Thomas Enqvist of Sweden, 7-6 (7-5), 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hewitt, Becker treated him like an unwelcome house
guest on the Center Court. ``I think Boris sort of walks around
like he basically owns that court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Becker called his progress here somewhat flabbergasting but
infinitely rewarding. ``I have no explanation for it; I'm just
going out there trying to play great tennis, and it all happened,''
said Becker, who reneged on his 1997 retirement from Grand Slam
play because he decided that he remains, after all, ``one of the
five, six players who really know how to play'' on grass. ``Things
are looking very good for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Things stopped looking good for the 1996 champion, Richard
Krajicek, who was ambushed on Court Two, the Graveyard Court, by
the 196th-ranked Swiss qualifier Lorenzo Manta, 6-3, 7-6 (7-5),
4-6, 4-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, I was surprised at how well he played,'' said
Krajicek. ``I expected him to get a little nervous but he kept
playing better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-seeded Dutchman, Krajicek, was joined on the sidelines
by 14th-seeded Tommy Haas of Germany, a 7-6 (8-6), 7-6 (7-3), 7-6
(7-2) loser to Wayne Arthurs, a 163d-ranked Australian qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   Jelena Dokic, the 16-year-old Australian qualifier who bounced
top-seeded Martina Hingis from the first round, moved into the
Round of 16 with a 6-7 (7-9), 6-3, 6-4 comeback against Anne
Kremer. Dokic will play ninth-seeded Mary Pierce in the fourth
round.
</P>
<P>
   In the only upset on the women's side, Alexandra Stevenson, the
18-year-old powerhouse from San Diego who decided to turn
professional here, landed in the Round of 16 Saturday after
upsetting 11th-seeded Julie Halard-Decugis of France, 6-3, 6-3.
Stevenson pelted the Frenchwoman with 12 aces, saved all six break
points she faced, and advanced to her first fourth round of a Grand
Slam event.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager's opponent is an American better known for her
all-court doubles expertise, Lisa Raymond of Wayne, Pa. Raymond
upset Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, a two-time Wimbledon finalist, in
the second round, and Saturday she knocked out Conchita Martinez,
the Spaniard who won her only Slam title here in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson's coup lasted just 58 minutes, and afterwards she
explained that she was making good on a little game dreamed up by
her buddy, Serena Williams, back when both of them were among the
unseeded rank-and-file. Seeded players, explained Stevenson, were
viewed like sitting ducks in a shooting gallery: ``You wind up your
ducks and you take them out, you shoot them. It's fun to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun, too, said Stevenson, is breaking free of the junior ranks,
an emancipation that has, in her case, included the rejection of a
scholarship offer from UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a junior, it's the scarlet letter: you can't go
anywhere,'' said Stevenson, a 6-footer who prefers bigger arenas
and bigger opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Another unexpected 1999 Wimbledon force, Jim Courier, still has
his head cold but has shaken off a more serious condition, the
dehydration that briefly rendered him a hospital patient.
</P>
<P>
   Courier, whose four-hour, 24-minute third round epic against
Sjeng Schalken left him also suffering from heat exhaustion on
Friday evening, received intravenous treatment after the match at
Parkside Hospital in Wimbledon village. The 61st-ranked Courier was
released after a few hours of observation and Saturday pronounced
himself recovered and ready for Week Two, his first Week Two at
Wimbledon in six years.
</P>
<P>
   But Courier insisted that the trip to the hospital was
necessitated by a misjudgment by the tournament medical staff.
Courier said the All England Club's resident physician, Dr. Tudor
Miles, who had seen him earlier in the week to treat a bad cold,
hadn't felt his post-match cramping required on-site intravenous
correction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit sad that a tournament of this stature has a
sub-par medical performance; I just think it's antiquated,'' said
the 28-year-old Courier, who saved two match points and began
cramping the instant he picked up his gear bag to leave the court
after claiming the 97-minute fifth set 13-11.
</P>
<P>
   Courier said the most painful aspect of the victory was having
to fold himself into a car to get to the hospital instead of taking
treatment here: ``Getting into a car and sitting down when you're
cramping is the worst thing you can do,'' he said, ``it's like
you're in labor if you're a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on site at the practice courts Saturday, Courier bumped
into sixth-seeded Tim Henman, his opponent in Monday's Round of 16
and his victim in their last two encounters. Henman, under severe
pressure to deliver the host nation its first championship since
Fred Perry in 1936, joked that he'd been hoping for a much longer
hospital stay for the American.
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi reached the Round of 16 without dropping a set,
beating Spain's 63rd-ranked Alberto Martin Saturday, 6-2, 6-0, 2-6,
6-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
