<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COL-BOOKSTORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BOOKSELLER QUITS BATTLE WITH INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAMBERTVILLE , N.J. _ Lambertville has dozens of antiques stores
now, nearly as many upscale bistros offering the latest variation
on frothy milk and coffee, and a handful of pretty good
restaurants, too.
</P>
<P>
   But it has no bookstore, except for the antique kind, not since
Janet Holbrook added up the years and the dollars and found that
while the rewards of being a small bookseller are great, the
profits in the age of the Internet are evanescent.
</P>
<P>
   Now the store, Rivergate Books, on Lambert Street down by the
Delaware River, is closed. A thanks-for-10-wonderful-years note in
Mrs. Holbrook's rounded schoolteacher hand is taped to the window.
The rooms of shelves are bare except for a few titles _ George
Soros' ``Crisis of Global Capitalism,'' Scott Lasser's first
effort, ``Battle Creek'' _ awaiting the bulk buyer to haul what the
store could not move, even in its final going-out-of-business sale.
</P>
<P>
   Obituaries of small, family-owned bookstores seem to be
everywhere these days, and giant discounters like Barnes &AMP; Noble
and Borders usually get the blame. But Lambertville, a town of
about 5,000 in Hunterdon County, is 20 miles by back roads from the
nearest mall and superstore.
</P>
<P>
   And Rivergate Books seemed to be insulated from the lure of 20
percent off, thanks to its personal service, the roster of monthly
book-club meetings it sponsored, the children's hours it provided,
the storytellers it brought in and the art shows of children's
illustrators it spun off.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, however, defied distance and back roads and even
personal ties, Mrs. Holbrook found, as it brought a new competitor
into the very heart of her store.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Barnes &AMP; Noble came in, a few people were curious and
went to look and bought some books,'' said Mrs. Holbrook, who is a
retired high school English teacher. ``But they came back and said
they wanted to be able to find things more easily and have clerks
that had an idea of what their grandchildren might like to read,
and we held our own.''
</P>
<P>
   They also came for the book readings by writers Mrs. Holbrook
found, for the cookies and cider and a chance to get a book signed
by the author _ evenings that Rivergate was famous for. And it was
during one of those evenings that Mrs. Holbrook found that her
universe had shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out that Gerald Stern, who won the National Book Award
for Poetry, was a Lambertville man, and I asked him if he would
come and do a reading,'' Mrs. Holbrook said. ``He gave a wonderful
presentation, and we had a good turnout, but we sold very few
books, and then I overheard one of the women who were presenting a
book for his signature say that she had bought hers through
Amazon.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I thought we were bringing something special to the
town,'' Mrs. Holbrook said, finishing her story. ``But if people
are going to bring in books that they got from the Internet, then
we don't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Mrs. Holbrook suggested only paperbacks for her
reading groups, and offered a 20 percent discount to members,
people started buying their copies over the Internet, or borrowing
them from the library, said Aletta Goodwin, a member of the
Thursday afternoon group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her store was always so serene and beautiful, and she was
doing so much for the town,'' Mrs. Goodwin said. ``I think she
should have had a great send-off by bopping us all over the head
and throwing us out into the street for being ungrateful
wretches.''
</P>
<P>
   So Rivergate Books is closed, and its space will probably be
taken over by another antiques store of the kind that already
brackets it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet parts of Mrs. Holbrook's legacy will live, whatever the
competition from outside. The Thursday afternoon group that was
started at the store now meets at a women's club in town, and will
carry on there. The Tuesday evening group will move to the library,
where the children's story hours that took root at Rivergate now
flourish. Storytellers like Rebecca Kelly and Jane King have made
careers of the starts they got at Rivergate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started telling `Fish Tales' at Rivergate during the Shad
Festival,'' Ms. Kelly said, ``and I'm going to keep on telling
them, only at the library. Nothing is going to stop that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
