<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: EWING WAITS FOR HIS FLOAT IN THE PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first Knick to walk away from the celebrating San
Antonio Spurs was the man who had not had an opportunity to stop
them. Patrick Ewing came through the tunnel late Friday night at
Madison Square Garden, a 7-footer many years in the habit of gazing
upward to avoid eye contact in moments like these. Ewing turned
right, strode stiffly down the hall and into the locker room, where
he waited for the others to come and shake hands.
</P>
<P>
   Then the door opened and Ewing was at his dressing stall, where
he has been for 14 years without once experiencing what Tim Duncan
now had in year two. Sweat glistened on Ewing's forehead, as he
spoke of the pride he had in his team and the pain in not being
able to assist it when it desperately needed his size even more
than his experience and heart.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked if the New York Knicks could have beaten the Spurs
with him in the paint to battle Duncan and David Robinson, instead
of losing, 78-77, in game 5, and the championship series in five
games. Ewing couldn't say. No one could really say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would have been a better team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fate had cut him out of the final act of the wildest Knicks'
script, in what had been a most bizarre Knicks season that began
three months late and only after it looked as if there would be no
season at all.
</P>
<P>
   You may recall that the collective bargaining session that
spared these 1999 playoffs occurred without Ewing, the union
president who was adamant about not acquiescing to Commissioner
David Stern. The meeting proceeded with Ewing, in effect, benched
by Billy Hunter to help save the season that concluded with Ewing
on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were forced into something and we took a stand,'' Hunter,
the union director, said in the Knicks' locker room, after Ewing
had finished. ``One thing has nothing to do with another.
Providence is providence. The Knicks didn't get the ring because
Patrick wasn't part of it. I believe he's destined, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows how next year's playoff balls will bounce? It could be
that Ewing will have to wonder someday if he sabotaged himself, if
this whole drama was just another variation on the heartbreaking
theme of John Starks, game 7 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing's ties to the agent David Falk helped create a more
militant union that delayed the inevitable and, in the process,
kept Ewing out of shape for the jump-started season. With his coach
feeling jittery about his job, Ewing played too many minutes too
soon, with an unsurprising, if not altogether predictable, result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, my injuries will heal and I'll be back stronger,''
Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks do make it back to the finals, if they should win,
then history will be revised accordingly. The Achilles' injury that
hampered Ewing's season before finally ending it will ultimately be
remembered as a painful but necessary development. His disability
forced Jeff Van Gundy, however reluctantly, to redirect his team's
focus and style. It allowed other talent and an edgy collective
character to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The fiery Latrell Sprewell carried the Knicks with a playoff
career-high 35 points on Friday night. The calm and cool Allan
Houston had a playoff career-high 34 points in game 3, the one
Knick victory. When Marcus Camby finally played, he brought
interior athleticism unseen around these parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A young nucleus,'' Dave Checketts, the Garden president,
called the players acquired by Ernie Grunfeld, the former general
manager. ``I told Patrick, `Your best chance is going to be next
season.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the heat of a championship series slipping away,
controversies arise that are not worth the paper they are printed
on. Larry Johnson's silly remarks about ``rebellious slaves,'' for
one, would have been laughed off had they come from the mouth of
Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   The only relevant Knick issue is what's next? Sprewell and
Houston do play the same position and both have enhanced market
value. Do the Knicks explore a major trade if a Gary Payton is
dangled before them?
</P>
<P>
   Standing pat is its own predicament, if a healthy Ewing expects
to lumber back down into the post and have the offense resume
running through him. The first question Checketts should ask Van
Gundy when they sit down to break bread (presumably not at the
restaurant Checketts took Grunfeld to) is if he can objectively
deal with that scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy was hired to please Ewing, but he has cashed in now on
the talent of Houston, Sprewell and Camby. Next year belongs more
to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am looking forward to next year,'' Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
   He soon took a long walk down the hall, past the mobbed Spurs'
locker room, to the bowels of the Garden. He leaned against a wall,
biting his lower lip, waiting for the black Navigator in which he
would eventually drive away.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the television people came by to chat. Isiah Thomas gave
him a hug. There was a commotion from around the bend and Ewing
craned his neck to see. It was Duncan, the most valuable player of
the NBA finals, on his way to the interview room, news media
entourage in tow.
</P>
<P>
   The championship rings have always gone to the other stars. To
Bird. Magic. Isiah. Olajuwon. Jordan. Now, to Robinson, Ewing's
contemporary, and Duncan, this reserved dynamo from St. Croix. The
long wait continues. Is it, as Hunter said, Ewing's destiny to win?
Or is he fated to watch these parades pass by?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1740EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
