<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CHAMPIONSHIP-NYT &LR;      06-26 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CHAMPIONSHIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SPREWELL AND DUNCAN, THERE IS LIFE AFTER JORDAN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the end of this five-month sprint, Latrell
Sprewell had nowhere to go. Trapped underneath the basket with 2
seconds left, his man-to-man shootout with Tim Duncan would go down
to the buzzer. He took one dribble away from trouble only to find
more waiting for him on the left baseline, the awesome twin towers
from San Antonio closing in on the Knicks' swingman the way the
Spurs were closing in on a title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to get a layup,'' Sprewell said after his
last-second shot fell short in Game 5 of the finals late Friday
night. ``Charlie threw an excellent pass. I was just so far under
the basket. With their size coming down on me, I didn't have the
layup like we planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Catching the ball underneath the basket and trying to score is
an unbelievably tough task. On one hand, you're close enough to the
rim to touch it. On the other, you have no room to move.
</P>
<P>
   It's like playing a lockout-ruptured season without Michael
Jordan; you're damned if you do and damned if you don't. So you do
what you can to get off a shot and pray that it falls, knowing you
tried.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find solace in that, maybe you can remember the
scoring war you waged with the game's preeminent player, your 14
straight points to his 12 straight in the second half, your 35 over
all to Duncan's 31, a duel reminiscent of Dominique Wilkens and
Larry Bird in the 1988 Eastern Conference finals; how far the two
of you have come in a short amount of time, and how much the league
needed you both in these lean, post-Michael times.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Spurs won 20, lost 62 and wondered if David
Robinson would ever play basketball again. Eighteen months ago,
Sprewell was suspended from the game and Patrick Ewing's career was
in question after a freak wrist injury sidelined him for most of
the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   As franchises about to hit their nadirs in the 90s, the Knicks
and the Spurs were two of the most unlikely finalists at Madison
Square Garden. They were anchored by Sprewell and Duncan, two
players with nothing in common but their desire to take over a
game.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, an ending may have amounted to a beginning.
Suddenly, Life After Michael appears manageable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spree was just awesome,'' said Spurs Coach Gregg Popovich.
``He got on one of those rolls where it didn't matter if you were
playing up on him or not, he was making it. You just knew the way
he and Tim were playing, it was going down to the wire. I coached
Spree for two years, and when he gets on one of those kind of
rolls, you know it's going to be scary. He gets into a zone.''
</P>
<P>
   For two seasons Popovich has also coached Duncan, a player who
keeps growing with each possession.
</P>
<P>
   Days after the lockout ended in January, the disenchanted fan
had even more reason to loathe this game. Jordan's retirement on a
gray-slate day in Chicago not only created a domino effect for the
Bulls franchise, but it ushered in an era of uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing success aside, David Stern's hope for the millennium
did not look promising. Too many miles on the legs of Stockton &AMP;
Malone, Sir Charles, Reggie and Patrick forced the commissioner to
entrust the game's future to a sketchy, counterculture crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson lighting up anyone he wanted for 30 points or
more. Jason Williams and Chris Webber laughing and scowling in
Sacramento. When Rasheed Wallace and Isaiah Rider went farther in
the post-season than Kobe and Shaq, change was afoot.
</P>
<P>
   There was Sprewell, the most unlikely star of all in this
post-Jordan morality play. What use could the league possibly have
for him after choking his coach 18 months ago and setting off every
racial and political hot button in sport?
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, the NBA and its troubled souls became partners
in redemption. To bring people back, the league was prepared to
live with more tattoos, baggage and `tude.
</P>
<P>
   Perception not always equaling reality, did we mention that
Duncan has a pierced tongue to go along with a tattoo? If he could
blend his Generation X trinkets with an old-school game, the
thinking went, anyone can.
</P>
<P>
   At age 23, he gave the league a breathtaking look at its future
on Friday night at the Garden. Drop-stepping inside, throwing up
jump hooks from 15 feet out, Duncan was the consummate big man,
conserving his aggression and strength for the right moments and
helping one of the game's true ambassadors, teammate David
Robinson, win his first championship.
</P>
<P>
   In victory, the protagonists got their rings. In defeat, the
antagonist became almost a sympathetic character, a guy whom you
could not help but feel for as he tried to launch a shot over the
outstretched arms of the 7-foot sapling in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan and Sprewell, vying for Michael's title on the last night
of the season. The gentle giant from the Virgin Islands, governing
his passions in a very Caribbean way as he fought for position and
rose for his shots. The tenacious swingman, exiled from the game a
year ago, clutching his fist and punching the air, each made basket
eliciting an emotional release.
</P>
<P>
   They were nothing like each other and nothing like Jordan. As
the league's golden era ends and a new one begins, perhaps that is
how it is supposed to be. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1743EDT &QL; 
