<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-N     06-26 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL'S SEASON OF HITS AND MISSES ENDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the season after his exile, the private Latrell
Sprewell had rationed his deeper thoughts and guarded the personal
details of his life, the way the shell of an oyster hides a pearl.
</P>
<P>
   Pry, as you might, Sprewell resisted.
</P>
<P>
   But as the prime-time hour Friday night turned into early
Saturday morning, Sprewell finally let everyone in as he turned
Madison Square Garden into his own therapy session. He let it all
out, and he did not have to say a word.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he has a mean streak. It was on display as he sneered and
huffed like a bull when he dunked over the San Antonio Spurs'
helpless Jaren Jackson during the Knicks' third-quarter comeback in
Game 5 of the NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he longs for acceptance. After a horrific 3-for-12 start,
Sprewell fed on the crescendo of the crowd's raucous support as if
it were an intravenous tube pumping replenishment into his veins as
he charged into his 43d minute.
</P>
<P>
   To that point, he had been inhuman: spinning and popping
contorted jumpers, driving through a minefield for 7-footers, and
dunking with his limbs extended in a wild flex. But finally,
perhaps inevitably for the Miracle Knicks, he missed his 27th shot
attempt of the night at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he does feel remorse. As the Spurs scattered across the
Garden floor to celebrate their first National Basketball
Association title after edging the Knicks, 78-77, Sprewell stood
alone on the floor with one agonizing thought after scoring 35
points. ``All I wanted were those last 2,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell only wanted to win. This was an element of his
personality that seemed suspect in his earliest days as a Knick _
back when he seemed indifferent to outcomes _ but it turned out to
be his driving quality in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wanted to win so badly,'' Marcus Camby, Sprewell's
friend and teammate, said. ``You saw him leave his heart on the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as you get to understand someone a little better _ wouldn't
you know it? _ there is no guarantee that he will be back next
season. There are varying theories as to what will become of a
Knick team in 1999-2000 that leaped into the arms of destiny this
season and persevered under the most adverse of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   While Jeff Van Gundy has been assured of his return, Dave
Checketts, the Garden president, reiterated Friday night that there
will be many conversations in the next two weeks with his coach and
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stick to my guns and say that I look forward to
spending a lot of time with Jeff and all of the players,''
Checketts said. ``I'm pretty certain things will work themselves
out in a good way.''
</P>
<P>
   What that means, no one knows. There is an argument to be made
for the Knicks to search for a premier point guard. If that plan
exists, does Sprewell or Allan Houston go? It would seem like a
shame. It took a while, but they proved they can play on the same
floor together this year.
</P>
<P>
   When Houston sizzled to 34 points in Game 3 of the finals,
Sprewell applauded him and said, ``All I want to do is keep feeding
him the ball when he's that hot.'' In Game 5, Houston took only one
shot in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about what Allan didn't do,'' Van Gundy said. ``It's
more about what Latrell was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   At different moments, Sprewell and Houston were the only stars
the Knicks needed. If this team is anyone's team, maybe it's theirs
now. But as the injured Patrick Ewing stood in the locker room
after the game, he cast doubt on that premise. What was missing
against the Spurs? He was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would have been a better team,'' Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks had been 100 percent, if Ewing had been on the
floor, maybe they would not have run as much. Maybe Sprewell and
Houston would not have had the same chance to emerge as characters
of Garden lore for their playoff performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banged up, injured, we still had our shot to go out there and
win the series,'' Camby said. ``Healthy, it still remains to be
seen. We'll probably never get to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby, Sprewell and Houston have wondered what the Knicks will
be like when Ewing returns to health. Subtly and slowly, Van Gundy
did diminish Ewing's role this season when the uptempo Knicks
bolted off the bench. Van Gundy is loyal to a fault where Ewing is
concerned, but there were more times when Ewing was used as a
trailer on the fast break and came through with the kind of spot-up
jumpers that develop when an aggressive team can drive and kick the
ball out.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, Ewing's role changed out of necessity. His sore
Achilles' did not bode well for the pounding around in the paint,
which perhaps left him more willing to go along with the faster
flow. If robust and healthy, will Ewing want to revert to the
post-up style he thrives in? If so, Sprewell and Camby could find
themselves agitated on the bench again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess, I'll have to do whatever I have to do,'' said
Sprewell, who has one year remaining on his contract. ``I can do
either, start or play the other.''
</P>
<P>
   He says this, and he probably means it. But as recently as the
second round of the playoffs, Sprewell nearly jumped out of his
skin as he sat on the bench deep into the third quarter of a game
in Atlanta. Afterward, he bemoaned his sedentary life on the bench.
Even on Friday afternoon, when Sprewell was asked how Van Gundy had
handled his addition to the team, he gave a mixed review.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been much like the year for the entire team,'' he
said. ``It's been up and down. But we all came together as a unit
in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, everyone came to know Sprewell a little better as he
exposed his every emotion to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd has been great to me,'' Sprewell said. ``That's one
of the reasons why I want to be here next year.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
