<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-DRAFT-NYT &LR;      06-26 1392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENTER THE KIDDIE CORPS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Ill., R.I., Ga., Calif., Ohio, Wash. , N.Mex.,
Canada)   By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your class for the 1999 National Basketball Association draft
(if they had stayed in school): Kevin Garnett, Shareef Abdur-Rahim,
Vince Carter, Stephon Marbury, Ron Mercer, Paul Pierce and Jason
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy, yes. But not a bad start on the top 10. The reality is
that the league's early entry process is here to stay and college
underclassmen and high school seniors who have talent want to get
paid for it as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with a polished Tim Duncan emerging as the best player in
the game _ and serving as a blueprint for anyone willing to put in
four years of college _ it's confounding why more teen-aged phenoms
don't think twice about immediately going to work for the rest of
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of one of the greatest senior classes in college
history, we bring you the official '99 draft _ another kiddie corps
event to be held Wednesday at the MCI Center in Washington. It's
not awful from an overall talent standpoint. But you can count the
amount of impact players on one hand.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the Chicago Bulls begin rebuilding in earnest. With
the No. 1 pick, General Manager Jerry Krause appears to be leaning
toward the bruising Duke forward Elton Brand, who quieted skeptics
during workouts when he measured a full 6-feet-8-inches tall and
showed an arm extension the length of most 7-footers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it be Scottie Pippen or Toni Kukoc, Krause is enamored
with reach and athleticism. He may still try to trade the pick if
he can get two choices in the top 10, with an eye toward taking
Wally Sczerzbiak, the Miami of Ohio forward, with one of those
selections.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's on to the biggest question mark in the draft, Lamar
Odom. He is easily the most talented player, a 6-10 guard who can
pass, run the floor and hit the 3-pointer with aplomb. But the
Rhode Island freshman only worked out for one team, Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, flirting with the idea of returning to school, is said to
be as confused as the teams thinking about taking a gamble on him.
He did not even take the league's mandated physical in Chicago,
which has many teams concerned.
</P>
<P>
   His odyssey of the past two weeks has many league officials
directing their frustration at the National Collegiate Athletic
Association for not allowing Odom to return to Rhode Island once he
began wavering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a travesty that the NCAA did not aggressively try
to keep him in school,'' said Pete Babcock, the Atlanta general
manager. ``When Lamar Odom says, `I think I made a mistake,' and
they come back with, `You broke a rule by signing with an agent,
too bad,' it's just not right. They should suspend him for the
first game or dole out some penalty, but at least let him return to
school if he wants to. Instead, they just ignored him and turned
their backs.''
</P>
<P>
   After Brand and Odom, Maryland's Steve Francis, UCLA's Baron
Davis and Szcerzbiak may round out the top five. Charlotte has the
No. 3 pick, the Los Angeles Clippers select fourth and Toronto is
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's Corey Maggette, whom the Bulls were contemplating picking
No. 1 a month ago, did not impress scouts during his pre-draft camp
workouts and will most likely go in the second five.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe players like Duncan and Keith Van Horn, another four-year
senior, do have some influence. Twelve players withdrew their names
from the draft last week, leaving 27 underclassmen, high school and
foreign players eligible. Among the more notable names to pull out
were Weber State forward Harold Arceneaux and New Mexico guard
Lamont Long.
</P>
<P>
   Following in the footsteps of Garnett, Kobe Bryant and Tracy
McGrady, this year's high school wunderkind is Picayune (Miss.)
senior Jonathan Bender, a 6-10 rail who broke Michael Jordan's
scoring record in the McDonald's High School All-American Game.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a supply of talented players at one position in the
top 20, it's at point guard. Beyond Francis and Davis, Utah's Andre
Miller, Duke's William Avery and Arizona's Jason Terry may not be
far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Think the point-starved Knicks, with the No. 15 pick, are
salivating over one of these players ending up in New York?
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the multitude of underclassmen, many of whom may not pan
out, the draft has other problems. For one, the league's decision
to push the signing period to Aug. 1 from July 1 has some major
potential hangups.
</P>
<P>
   If, for example, a drafted player is included in a trade that
involved another player not yet under contract, the drafted player
may have to wait a month before he is moved to the team he will
begin his career with.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these kids are putting these hats on, and they have to
wait for a month to explain to somebody that they're with another
team,'' said one Western Conference team official, on condition of
anonymity. ``If we had another team pick for us with the idea we
were going to do a deal on Aug. 1, we sure would not want our new
player potentially getting hurt in a July summer league with the
team he's not even going to play on. It presents a lot of
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 1, teams are able to begin negotiating with free agents
and their draft picks. But they cannot sign deals until Aug. 1. The
month-long gap was installed mainly to give team and league
officials a clearer understanding of their salary-cap room before
they signed their players.
</P>
<P>
   But, like picking the first 10 players in a crapshoot of a
draft, it could lead to more confusion than clarity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STAYING A LAKER
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement released Friday from the offices of his
agent, Shaquille O'Neal, that good-natured and
committed-to-the-team center, said he decided to remain with the
Lakers rather than opting out of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaquille has decided to remain with the Lakers,'' said the
statement, released by the agent Leonard Armato. ``He will not
exercise his option to terminate his contract with the team and
will leave the remaining four-year term of the agreement in tact.
He is excited about the Lakers prospects for the future and is
looking forward to playing for new coach Phil Jackson.''
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, it was a sign that O'Neal is genuinely concerned
about living up to the expectations the city and the franchise have
for him. With so many players bailing out on their underachieving
teams instead of becoming a solution to the problem _ Shaq's former
teammate, Anfernee Hardaway, is a prime example _ O'Neal should be
commended.
</P>
<P>
   The truth? It's hardly news. The chance of O'Neal leaving the
Lakers was severely hurt when the new agreement between the players
and owners was signed in January _ an agreement that made it
impossible for another team to pay O'Neal more than the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Not to say O'Neal is just about money; it's up for debate how
much covert lobbying he and his agent did to make sure Jackson was
given serious consideration for the coaching job. But if he left
Los Angeles for anywhere but the Knicks, his marketing power base
would have been severely crippled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MISTER MANNERS
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the endless stream of press conferences, interviews and
finals madness last week was the message of a humble veteran
shooting guard whose team did not even make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In receiving the league's sportsmanship award, Hersey Hawkins
related the story of a Seattle game that got ugly this past season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played New Jersey at home, and they pounded us, beat us
real bad,'' he said. ``Everybody was upset, a lot of words being
exchanged out there on the floor among teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the game, we were going to get something to eat. My
oldest son says to me, `Dad, I like the way you play the game.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned back, I said, `What do you mean you like the way I
play?' He said, `When you get mad, you don't curse and you don't
yell at the other players.' And that right there told me how
important it is to conduct yourself in a good manner when you are
out there on the basketball floor. It really let me know that they
are watching everything I do.''
</P>
<P>
   In a post-season in which Damon Stoudamire complains about
minutes, everyone complains about calls and Larry Johnson cannot be
quiet for his own good, it's a message worth remembering. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
