<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0615 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-KC-KAN &LR;      06-26 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-KC-KAN </SLUG>
  
 POLL REFLECTS PROGRESS IN RACIAL EQUALITY IN kANSAS CITY  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN HOFFMANN and MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Human progress never rolls in on the wheels of inevitability;
it comes through the tireless efforts of men willing to be
co-workers with God, and without this hard work, time itself
becomes an ally of the forces of social stagnation.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Martin Luther King Jr.,
</P>
<P>
   Notes From a Birmingham Jail
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City did not rest these last 10 years, and human progress
_ at least in terms of racial equality _ rolled forward, however
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   A poll jointly conducted by The Kansas City Star and The Kansas
City Call reflects that. Conducted earlier this year, the poll
gauged area attitudes on race and racism.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with an identical one The Star did in 1989, the new
poll showed that, in many ways, black Kansas Citians today are more
optimistic than they were a decade ago, sometimes significantly so.
</P>
<P>
   According to the poll, more area African-Americans are:
</P>
<P>
   - Upbeat about their quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   - Convinced that race relations are getting better.
</P>
<P>
   - Confident that racism is not a significant problem in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   Given the last decade's high-profile racial issues, increased
diversity training in the workplace and economic growth in the
black community, few experts were surprised by the poll results.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have black people in positions of leadership like never
before,'' said former Mayor Emanuel Cleaver. ``Blacks are seeing
all of this. It not only made them feel good, it gave hope that
things can get better.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cleaver and others say the good news should be tempered, and
poll results show that.
</P>
<P>
   While black residents see racism declining, they still feel its
heavy presence. Six out of 10 black residents still see racism as a
significant problem; half or more expect to encounter bigotry when
they visit the Country Club Plaza, Johnson County or the Northland;
and four out of 10 still believe that race relations have either
stagnated or are getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that black people still encounter
discrimination on a daily basis, and to an extent that whites never
have and cannot understand,'' said Norman Yetman, a professor of
sociology at the University of Kansas. ``Sure, we've come a long,
long way in the fight against racism. But we've got a long, long
way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, black residents are likely to encounter a more subtle
racism than in the past, said Darryck Dean, associate executive
director of Kansas City Harmony, a nonprofit organization that
works to improve race relations.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Dean said, racism may come in the form of a
seemingly helpful store employee who actually is keeping a watchful
eye on a black customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our language has changed, what is politically correct has
changed, and people are forced to jump on the bandwagon,'' Dean
said. ``But there is still discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Price, president of the National Urban League, said he
still had three main concerns about race relations in the 1990s:
prevalence of police brutality against the black population; an
undercurrent message in the affirmative-action debate that suggests
black Americans are incapable of succeeding without government
help; and those who turn the welfare debate into an issue of black
inferiority.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such worries, experts and residents _ black and white _
are encouraged by the racial advances of the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a great deal of progress,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Real household income for black Americans (adjusted for
inflation) increased by about 9 percent between 1989 and 1997, the
last year for which U.S. Census Bureau figures were available. In
the same period, incomes for white Americans increased about 6
percent. Still, the per capita income for blacks in 1997 was
$12,351, compared with $20,425 for whites.
</P>
<P>
   In May, unemployment among black Americans fell to 7.5 percent,
the lowest level on record, although still above the overall rate
of 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And in a Newsweek poll published this month, blacks were more
optimistic than whites about prospects for their jobs, family
income and educational opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Price said it also was hard to ignore the successes of
African-Americans in finding their way into corporate boardrooms
and executive offices in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation moves forward in fits and starts,'' he said. ``We
do not move in a straight line....Sometimes, progress is
maddeningly slow. And we've got a long ways to go before we reach
equity. But we are moving inexorably forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Some figures from Kansas City mirror the national progress.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate for black residents of the metropolitan
area fell from 13.3 percent in 1993 to 8.6 percent in 1997. That's
the most recent year for which figures are available, but
economists say the rate is almost certainly lower now.
</P>
<P>
   Market research commissioned by The Star shows black Kansas
Citians today, compared with 10 years ago, are more likely to own a
home, have a college education, own color televisions and microwave
ovens, invest in mutual funds and travel for business or pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   A real-life example:
</P>
<P>
   When Beverly Saunders, now 60, graduated from high school, she
dreamed of working at a big downtown Kansas City bank. She had
typing and shorthand skills, and she had been a good student. She
also was black.
</P>
<P>
   Bank after bank turned her away, saying she wouldn't fit into
their offices and pointing her instead toward mail rooms or
companies that offered more physical labor.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years later, her daughter got an office job with
NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the job I dreamed about,'' Saunders said.
</P>
<P>
   Such progress has roots that reach back to about 1970, said
William Worley, a historian at the University of Missouri-Kansas
City. That's when area housing restrictions for minorities began
eroding, and job opportunities and general social acceptance began
increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Experts pointed to many other factors that spurred better
opportunities for black Kansas Citians in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   High on the list is a flourishing economy. Nationally, it's the
longest expansion ever during peacetime, and the local economy,
with its low unemployment, reflects that strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the economy is good, there is a lot less overt hostility
between the races,'' Cleaver said. ``When times are good, it's a
lot easier to talk about controversial and touchy subjects.''
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
