<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0617 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-KC(SECONDTAKE)-K     06-26 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-KC </SLUG>
 (SECOND TAKE)-KAN  
 POLL REFLECTS PROGRESS IN RACIAL EQUALITY IN kANSAS CITY  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN HOFFMANN and MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (touchy subjects)
</P>
<P>
   Others pointed to Cleaver, Kansas City's first black mayor, as a
reason for local progress. Cleaver was elected mayor with support
from white and black voters alike. And when he got into office, he
worked hard to improve race relations through such efforts as a
1996 task force, which involved people from throughout the
metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayor Cleaver had a significant impact,'' said the Rev. Kirk
Perucca, executive director of Project Equality. ``He's helped this
city deal with race issues in a much more direct and continual
way.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Cleaver fought to use public money to improve
blighted areas that house mostly minorities. From the $22 million
renovation of the 18th and Vine Historic District to the $3 million
Brush Creek Community Center on Cleveland Avenue, black residents
saw officials working to improve inner-city neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   And there were other efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Perucca credited work, throughout the '90s, of many neighborhood
groups and nonprofit organizations to improve race relations. When
a group such as Project Equality goes out to a business with 200
employees and teaches the importance of a diverse work force, many
employees take the concept home with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a ripple effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   C.C. Herbison, assistant professor of African and
African-American studies at the University of Kansas, noted that
pop culture now embraces black culture. Best-selling authors Toni
Morrison and Terry McMillan write about the experiences of black
women. Oprah Winfrey is an entertainment industry force. Michael
Jordan is, well, Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a society that is now more willing to accept
greatness, regardless of race, and that is a positive sign,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts believe the Star//Call poll reflects those real
changes and that the results are encouraging:
</P>
<P>
   - Half the black respondents said their quality of life was good
or excellent, compared with only a third in 1989. That response
held true even for those making less than $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   - The percentage of black respondents who think race relations
are getting better jumped from 6 percent in 1989 to 24 percent. A
third said race relations were somewhat better, the same as 10
years ago. Only 12 percent see relations getting worse, compared
with 20 percent in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   - While fewer blacks see racism as a significant problem now,
more whites do _ 51 percent, compared with 41 percent in 1989. But
experts see good news even in that number.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Smith, a longtime civil-rights activist and adjunct
professor at UMKC, says whites who don't socialize often with
blacks are less likely to believe life for African-Americans is
improving. They see media stories about racial issues and are left
thinking that the outlook is negative.
</P>
<P>
   Smith says whites also do not think about the role race plays as
much as blacks do. As the '90s fostered more discussion on the
issue, whites may have opened their eyes to the problem, while
blacks saw positives in the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Harmony's Dean said, the general public is more aware
of racial issues, and that means things should be getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like the Clarence Thomas issue and affirmative action
are keeping race relations on people's plates,'' he said. ``Whether
you agree or disagree, the issue is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, experts say the good news for blacks isn't good enough,
especially compared with whites' poll responses.
</P>
<P>
   For example, while half the blacks said their quality of life
was good or excellent, three-quarters of the whites did.
</P>
<P>
   And while the numbers of blacks who socialize with whites jumped
from 56 to 70 percent in the last 10 years, in many cases they may
be seeing the same whites _ only 55 percent of whites socialize
with blacks, compared with 54 percent in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Hershberger, executive director of Kansas City Harmony,
said the discussions on race relations she had heard had not all
been positive. Yes, there's improvement, she has heard. Still, too
many problems exist to be optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Young, executive director of the Black Chamber of Commerce
of Greater Kansas City, says African-Americans' lives have improved
little and Kansas City still is divided by race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things really aren't any better,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Cleaver, the man at the center of much that happened here
in the last decade, wonders whether the progress charted by the
poll will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change is not inevitable, and time is neutral,'' Cleaver
cautioned. ``I think the year 2009 will see Kansas City as a more
enlightened place. But we are existing in a hair-trigger society,
and anything _ a downturn in the economy, a race-related
catastrophe _ can set us off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
