<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHIMPANZEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHIMPANZEES WITH CULTURE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, June 27: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After examining the results of 151 years of chimpanzee research,
a team of primatologists recently concluded that certain behavioral
variations among groups of chimpanzees could only be called
cultural. That is, they have the ability to pass on the results of
observation and learning _ something that was believed to be a
solely human attribute.
</P>
<P>
   Now a group of sleep investigators, led by Dr. Charles Czeisler
at Harvard University, has published its finding that human
circadian rhythm _ the internal clock that regulates sleep and
waking _ does not, as was once believed, differ widely from the
circadian rhythms of other animals.
</P>
<P>
   They, in other words, are more like us than we care to believe,
and we are more like them than we like to let on. If this is not
the grand theme of modern life science, it is certainly one of its
sub-themes. By using investigative techniques that are uniquely
human, we seem to be gaining a clearer focus on the ways in which
humans are not unique.
</P>
<P>
   We have learned to live with the notion of the curvature of
space. It may be harder to learn to live with the curvature of
history, to grasp that our almost deific sense of difference from
the animal creation is a latent prejudice that obscures as much as
it explains.
</P>
<P>
   The case of the cultural chimpanzees is, for some people,
particularly troubling because it blurs a boundary that seemed
especially clear-cut, almost sacred. Whenever it is suggested that
evolution has played a critical part in shaping the details of
human behavior, controversy erupts. We like to believe instead that
culture _ the arena of our freedom _ is the main determinant of
human behavior. The faith that cultural variation is unique to
humans has perhaps softened the theory of evolution for some
because it seemed to suggest that humans were liberated in a
behavioral, if not a biological, sense from evolution's rigor.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no loss in learning that chimpanzees may indeed
enjoy cultural variation or in learning that humans do indeed feel
the influence, like all other animals, of living on a planet that
rotates once every 24 hours. The mystery of our kinship with the
rest of earth's species is far greater than the mystery of our
difference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
