<HEADER>
A0621 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-ELECTIONS-ABROAD     06-26 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ELECTIONS-ABROAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: UNDEMOCRATIC ELECTIONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, June 27: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is election season abroad. In the past few weeks, voters in
eight nations have chosen parliaments or presidents. In several
cases _ Israel, Nepal, Slovakia, South Africa _ citizens
enthusiastically participated in a democratic choice of new
leaders. In other places like Indonesia and Nigeria, elections
marked a step toward democracy but were not completely fair. In
Togo and Malawi, they were openly fraudulent. As the world is
increasingly discovering, not all elections are equal, and some
merely create the illusion of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Since the fall of communism, virtually any leader who wanted
foreign aid or diplomatic recognition such as membership in
regional organizations first had to hold an election that the
international community could call legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy activists realized years ago that while elections are
crucial, they are only a beginning and do not always guarantee the
development of democratic institutions and habits. Now, however,
the world is beginning to recognize that elections often do not
even accomplish the narrow mission they are there to perform _
allowing citizens to toss out rulers who govern badly.
</P>
<P>
   It seems paradoxical, but just because people can vote for their
leaders does not mean they can hold those leaders accountable.
Indonesians, for example, made their first post-Suharto elections
this month a celebration of their new choice between real
candidates. But the leader of the party that apparently won,
Megawati Sukarnoputri, may not become president. The president is
due to be chosen in November by a 700-member assembly. Voters
picked most of the members, but others will be appointed by the
military and other groups. This gives an unfair boost to the
incumbent, B.J. Habibie, Suharto's chosen successor.
</P>
<P>
   In countries with few democratic institutions, rulers have
near-dictatorial powers and can easily find ways to rig voting. For
Malawi's election on June 15, President Bakili Muluzi replaced a
respected election commissioner with his hacks, who obstructed
voter registration in areas thought to be pro-opposition. Rulers
can also block opponents' access to television, intimidate
opposition activists and raid the state treasury to pay for
campaigns or gifts for voters. Especially in small nations, many
elections receive little outside attention until just before
election day, when international observers arrive. That leads
incumbents to engage in pre- or post-election day fraud rather than
ballot stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   Sub-Saharan Africa _ aside from South Africa _ illustrates the
limits of the world's new emphasis on elections. From 1991 to 1993,
Africa did have a handful of truly democratic elections. But
democracy activists cannot think of a single case in the last six
years in which an incumbent ran and lost.
</P>
<P>
   Tragically, many autocratic leaders do not need to rig
elections. In Serbia, Slobodan Milosevic enjoys about the same
public support he did before the war, 20 percent. But that might be
enough to win re-election, as he has used the common strategy of
dividing his opponents by offering them political posts.
Particularly where politics is based on region or ethnicity, voters
often support a candidate from their own group no matter what his
record.
</P>
<P>
   Elections, while easily manipulated, are the only system that
offers any hope of holding leaders accountable. It is progress,
moreover, that the manipulators can find themselves outcasts. But
international election observers are still too narrowly focused on
election day itself. Members of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations were so eager to admit Cambodia that they seized on a clean
voting day and ignored major campaign fraud in parliamentary
elections last July.
</P>
<P>
   Well-meaning international observers need independent reports on
campaign fraud before they can make judgments about events they do
not witness. That is why the rise of local independent monitoring
groups needs to be encouraged. In the last few years, millions of
people have voted for the first time, peacefully and joyfully. In
too many cases, they have not been freely choosing their leaders.
They are doubly victimized when the world persists in calling these
rigged events democracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
