<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADIO-HOST-POLITICS-7     06-26 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-HOST-POLITICS-735&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 TALK-SHOW HOST PONDERS A SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As one of talk radio's original angry white males,
Bob Grant of WOR-AM has enjoyed considerable notoriety and won high
ratings by making inflammatory comments about the people who upset
him. They tend to be poor, politically liberal or black.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, however, Grant has been tormenting someone on
the other end of the political and economic spectrum: Gov. Christie
Whitman of New Jersey, a virtual paragon of establishment affluence
and Republican moderation.
</P>
<P>
   Grant has feuded with the governor since 1994, when she
chastised him for making racially offensive comments. Now he is
flirting with a run as an independent candidate next year for the
U.S. Senate seat that Whitman is seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts discount Grant's very public ruminations
as a stunt to boost ratings and make Whitman squirm. But because
Whitman has never won more than 49 percent of the vote in any
statewide election, it is widely acknowledged that an independent
candidacy by a well-known conservative like Grant, who lives in
Monmouth County, N.J., could hurt the governor in a close race.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman herself conceded that point earlier this month, when she
said she feared Grant would draw crucial conservative votes from
her. The tone of the governor's statement was generally
conciliatory, but she did utter the R-word _ race _ to describe
what she said was one of the few issues on which she and Grant
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   At WOR's studios in Manhattan, the governor's unexpected
comments about race sent a buzz through the halls, and as
technicians scurried to edit a tape of them in time for that
afternoon's show, Grant appeared triumphant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get the band ready,'' Grant said. ``John Philip Sousa.''
</P>
<P>
   David Bernstein, the program director, clapped his hands and
exclaimed, ``You're gonna get a lot of mileage out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   While verbal jousting with Whitman does make good radio drama,
Grant insists that his possible candidacy is actually a matter of
patriotic duty. After nearly 30 years as the self-appointed voice
of the Little Guy, Grant, 70, says the republic desperately needs a
populist antidote to what he calls professional office-seekers who
he says control American government.
</P>
<P>
   And Grant, a man who earns a handsome salary but still brings
coffee to work each day in a thermos, says he is just the man to
remind Capitol Hill about the concerns of his neighbors and
listeners who pay mortgages in Manalapan and get stranded in
traffic outside the Holland Tunnel to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   If elected, Grant said, he would try to replace the income-tax
system with a national sales tax. He would tighten immigration
laws, slash welfare and reduce what he describes as the labyrinth
of intrusive government regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Grant also insists he will contribute to the nation's political
discourse by talking plainly and honestly about race, an ambitious
claim given the furor he has ignited when discussing racial issues
and black public figures in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Grant was fired by WABC in 1996 for making disparaging remarks
about Ron Brown, the commerce secretary who died in a plane crash.
At various points in his career he has called Haitian refugees
``unwashed scum'' and black South Africans ``screaming savages,''
referred to the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. with an unprintable
slur, and labeled former New York City Mayor David Dinkins ``a
men's room attendant.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant now says he regrets his reference to King, but has no
apologies for his other statements. He points to the furor they
inspired as evidence of how, he says, the media and left-wing
special-interest groups have tried to stifle his speech.
</P>
<P>
   His public battle with Whitman began in 1994, when she said she
was offended by Grant's racial comments. The governor then appeared
on his show, chastised Grant and vowed that she would never return.
</P>
<P>
   Now that race is again New Jersey's most loaded issue, with the
governor having been criticized for failing to respond quickly
enough to complaints of racial bias by the state police, Grant says
he is eager to show voters how Whitman has repeatedly pandered to
minority leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was one of her biggest supporters, but she betrayed me back
then because she was caving to the black ministers,'' Grant said.
``She is still caving in to them today, and I think the voters are
going to make her pay for that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For all Grant's zeal about the issues however, he still seems
uncertain about embracing the rigors of a campaign, or stepping
away from the microphone after nearly 30 years on the air.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Whitman made her comments about Grant, for instance,
he said surprisingly little to capitalize on a potent political
opportunity. The program, broadcast during afternoon drive time,
started with a brass band's rendition of ``Hail to the Chief'' and
an emcee introducing ``the next senator from the great state of New
Jersey, Bob Grant.'' Next came sound bites from Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   When the red light flashed and Grant went on the air, he mused
about the governor's comments briefly. Within five minutes though,
he was warning listeners that Democrats in Congress ``aren't
interested in gun control, they're interested in gun
con-FIS-CATION!''
</P>
<P>
   In the WOR control room, the show's producer, Roy Fredriks, was
baffled by the abrupt change of topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's he beating up on Clinton for?'' Fredriks asked the
engineer. ``We can get a whole show out of Whitman.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant's callers were not as easily distracted from the Senate
race.
</P>
<P>
   Cary from the Bronx said he thought it was high time someone
like Grant went to Washington to fight for the common man. Steve in
the Car called on his cellular phone to warn Grant that the
governor would relentlessly try to portray him as a bigot if he
continued his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that your people are going to combat that,'' Cary
said, ``by showing that you've called so many people savages over
the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant seemed buoyed by his listeners' loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do attack me,'' he said of his potential opponents,
``it will ensure my victory because people will rally to my side,''
Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   Off the air, where Grant's demeanor is far more genial than his
on-air persona, he said he was inspired to run by the unlikely
victory of Jesse Ventura, the professional wrestler who last year
was elected governor of Minnesota. Grant also dismisses suggestions
that his candidacy is a publicity stunt designed to reverse a
slight drop in his ratings in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what happened in Minnesota, I only need 35 to
37 percent of the vote to win,'' he said. ``That's a real
possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Under federal rules, Grant would have to either give up his show
or provide his opponents equal time on the air if he officially
declares his candidacy. Until he does, such bold predictions will
do little to sway people who suspect that Grant is simply enjoying
the chance to cause grief for Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were someone else, I'd probably think that, too,'' he
said. ``But this has nothing to do with Christie Whitman. At my
age, this is probably my last chance to do something like this. So
if I'm ever going to make a difference, now is the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
