<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0626 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BUSH-NY     06-26 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: GEORGE W. BUSH CRAMS FOR THE WHITE HOUSE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN R. WEISMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When meeting with his policy experts, many of them
alumni of his father's presidency, George W. Bush is said to
project an air of confidence if not entitlement. ``I am going to be
the next president,'' he declares, according to one adviser. ``I
need your help, not to become president, but to be a good
president.'' By all accounts, the Texas governor who studied at
Yale and Harvard is not only running hard for the White House. He
is also cramming for it like someone facing the ultimate final
exam.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the faculty of George Bush University is just getting
to know its prized student. But one thing is already clear. Though
there are many Bush veterans, they are of a different cast from
those who advised his father: more conservative in foreign policy
and more moderate domestically than Republican leaders in Congress,
a fact that has begun to alarm many on the right.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign policy team assembled by Bush is headed by
Condoleezza Rice, the departing provost of Stanford University and
a specialist on the Soviet Union on President Bush's national
security staff. In what almost seems like a generational revolt by
the governor, the team conspicuously lacks the main players
surrounding President Bush, like former Secretaries of State James
Baker and Lawrence Eagleburger, and Brent Scowcroft, the Bush
national security aide.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when you talk to the governor's people about foreign policy,
there is a tone of restoration that comes through, as if they aim
to get back to the values of strength and firmness of the
Republican White Houses of old. The governor's foreign policy
people say Bush will be more skeptical than his father toward the
United Nations and other multinational organizations and more
willing to embrace explicitly the idea of American global
supremacy. He is said to favor a tougher stance toward rogue states
like North Korea and Iraq, and to see China and Russia more as
rivals than partners, another contrast with his father.
</P>
<P>
   It is not, most Bush aides hasten to say, that the governor is
repudiating the teachings of his father. Rather, they say, times
have changed and the glow of friendship and cooperation in the
aftermath of the cold war is gone. But those looking for a
generational grudge match might find it in Bush's particular
disdain for Strobe Talbott, President Clinton's deputy secretary of
state, who is the administration's apostle of establishing a
working relationship with Russia and Boris Yeltsin. ``Strobe
Talbott has been wrong for 30 years,'' an adviser quoted the young
Bush as saying. ``I knew him at Yale.''
</P>
<P>
   President Bush seemed to love nothing more than meeting with
heads of state. Gov. Bush has hardly met any, at least by himself.
On domestic affairs, he is said to have strong views, and they are
distinctly more moderate than the ones heard in Congress these
days. Lawrence Lindsey, the former Federal Reserve Board member who
is his chief economic adviser, and Mayor Stephen Goldsmith of
Indianapolis reflect that attitude. On tax cuts, Lindsey talks of
cutting the marginal rates, but emphasizes the importance of tax
cuts for the lower end of the economic spectrum. Asked by The
Weekly Standard whether he embraced the traditional conservative
position of lowering or eliminating the capital gains tax, Lindsey
said: ``Maybe it's the populist in me, but capital should be
taxed.''
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, the Republican leadership has almost nothing good
to say about the role of government in public life. But at his
inaugural speech as governor last January, Bush said: ``government
can't solve all our problems. Economic growth can't solve all our
problems. In fact, we're now putting too much hope in economics,
just as we once put too much hope in government.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush favors more government spending for schools and, to help
people get off welfare, for day care. Contrast that with the recent
speech by Tom DeLay, the Republican whip, citing day care as a
factor in the decline of American values.
</P>
<P>
   The difference with Congress is so great that Bush had to
reassure Republicans in Washington last week that he would not, as
some fear, run against them in the election. Those words could be
put to the test if Congress proceeds with punitive budget cuts in
coming weeks. At the photo session Bush did not appear with the two
Texans most associated with hard-line conservatism, DeLay and Dick
Armey, the House majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush moves to flesh out what he means by ``compassionate
conservatism,'' a phrase that both the left and the right find
condescending, his views may rankle people in some unlikely
quarters _ the believers in global interdependence who surrounded
his father and the believers in less government at all costs who
now dominate the party in Congress. It could turn out to be a much
more interesting campaign than even the Republicans have bargained
for.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
