<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 06/26/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) MOHANSIC, N.Y. -- June 26, 1999 -- GOLF-DEPRIVATION-2,
6-26 -- Ron Bucci, a chiropractor from Tarrytown, N.Y., waiting
overnight in his van for a Sunday morning tee time at the Mohansic
Golf Course, one of Westchester County's few public courses. Though
Westchester County is peppered with 61 golf courses, only five are
open to the free-range duffer, that particular golf subspecies who
cannot afford even a mid-range private club's $150,000 membership
fee and $10,000 in annual dues. (Susan B. Markisz/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MOHANSIC, N.Y. -- June 26, 1999 -- GOLF-DEPRIVATION-1,
6-26 -- Jeff Miller set to play at Mohansic Golf Course at 5:45
a.m., one of Westchester County's few public courses. Though
Westchester County is peppered with 61 golf courses, only five are
open to the free-range duffer, that particular golf subspecies who
cannot afford even a mid-range private club's $150,000 membership
fee and $10,000 in annual dues. The problem has become so bad in
recent years that Westchester -- one of the most affluent counties
in the nation -- is now among the most golf-deprived. (Susan B.
Markisz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 26, 1999 -- BKN-SPURS-TITLE, 6-26 -- The
San Antonio Spurs twin towers David Robinson, left, and Tim Duncan
and teammate Jaren Jackson celebrate during the grandeur that
surrounded winning the team's first National Basketball Association
championship in the Spurs' 26-year history. The Spurs defeated the
New York Knicks 78-77 on Friday night to win the finals, four games
to one. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- June 26, 1999 -- POLITICIAN-NOVEL, 6-26 --
Rep. Peter T. King, R-N.Y., relaxes in his office with copies of
his novel ``Terrible Beauty'' (Roberts Rinehart), a narrative of
the violent years of politics in Belfast, Northern Ireland. Some
recent book interviews have focused on King's possible entry into
the New York Senate race run already shaping up between Hillary
Rodham Clinton and New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. ``I'd run
slightly right of center,'' says King. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- June 26, 1999 -- KOSOVO-POLICE,
6-26 -- A French NATO soldier searches an Albanian suspected of
looting in Mitrovica. The most pressing need in Kosovar cities like
Mitrovica is for an international police force to tackle the crime
and handle the raised tension -- looting, burning and harassment --
that has flourished with the exit of the Serbian police and
military forces and many Serbian civilians and the return of over
300,000 Albanian refugees. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SPECTACLE ISLAND, Mass. -- June 26, 1999 --
MASS-ISLAND-REVIVAL, 6-26 -- A view from the top of a hill on the
cleaned-up Spectacle Island, looking south over the island and
beyond it, to Boston Harbor. Spectacle Island, once considered one
of the dirtiest areas of landfill in the United States, will now
receive a $1 million grant to make it a futuristic land of
zero-emission power. (Jared Leeds/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PEC, Yugoslavia -- June 26, 1999 -- KOSOVO-DESTRUCTION-3,
6-26 -- Cars carfully cross a bridge partially destroyed by a NATO
bomb near Pec. Many of the bridges were camouflaged with paint or
covered with trees and branches during NATO airstrikes. After the
massive bombing campaign by NATO to halt the Serbian campaign of
destruction, the long-term reconstruction of Yugoslavia will
require great effort, not all of it monetary. (Tyler Hicks/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BELA CRKVA, Yugoslavia -- June 26, 1999 --
KOSOVO-DESTRUCTION-2, 6-26 -- Safet Popaj, 60, leads his family
through the burned ruins of their house in Bela Crkva in southwest
Kosovo. Albanian villagers here say 64 people, many of them the
young men who were the town's future, were massacred by Serbs. In
addition to the house, Popaj says he lost about 11,000 pounds of
wheat, 6,600 pounds of corn and all seven of his cows. ``We have
had enough killing here,'' says Popaj. ``But, you know, economic
casualties -- that's 100 percent of us.'' (Tyler Hicks/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PEC, Yugoslavia -- June 26, 1999 -- KOSOVO-DESTRUCTION-1,
6-26 --Kosovo Albanians walk through a ruined section of Pec. Most
of the damage was inflicted by the Yugoslavs, but there is also
damage from the NATO air campaign. In March, with the onset of
NATO's bombing campaign, the Serbs took their campaign of
destruction to cities like Pec and Djakovica in the west and
Mitrovica in the north, acting apparently out of pure revenge, and
a desire to drive the Albanians away for good. (Tyler Hicks/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAN ANTONIO -- June 26, 1999 -- VIRTUAL-DRUGGISTS, 6-26
-- Bill Stallknecht, 52, a San Antonio pharmacist who runs
ThePillbox.com, says he is constantly under the scrutiny of state
regulators. He views with disdain the paternalism of the medical
establishment, which he says has an interest in trying to put
people like him out of business. ``Have you heard any patients
being unhappy?'' Stallknecht asks. ``All the power bases say, 'We
don't want them cutting into our sacred cow.''' (Edward Ornelas/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- June 26, 1999 --
MRS.CLINTON-BANKRUPTCY-LAW, 6-26 -- Hillary Rodham Clinton, who has
been battling proposed bankruptcy legislation, is concerned about
the impact on women and children. Mrs. Clinton says that those who
can repay their debts should, and she says ``the credit industry
should be held accountable for making credit too easily available
to people who cannot pay their bills.'' She also views the
legislation as making it harder for women to receive alimony and
child support if their former husbands file for bankruptcy. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
