<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SNOQUALMIE-DEVELOPMEN     06-26 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNOQUALMIE-DEVELOPMENT-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: DEVELOPMENT COMES TO LOGGING TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By HARRIET KING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SNOQUALMIE, Wash._ Once dependent on the logging industry, this
blue-collar city in the Cascade Mountain foothills 30 miles east of
Seattle is moving toward a higher-end image as the timberland owner
begins developing a huge and expensive new housing complex.
</P>
<P>
   Crews are now grading large tracts on 1,343 acres that follow
the hillsides and plateaus in the Weyerhaeuser Real Estate Co.'s
Snoqualmie Ridge development, which will eventually have 2,000
housing units, a 100-acre industrial park and a 10-acre shopping
center.
</P>
<P>
   The 160 ridge-top residences built so far command views of the
town in the valley below, the nearby 4,124-foot Mount Si and a sea
of mountain peaks to the east.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 units _ detached houses, town houses and two-family
houses _ will go up this year, priced from $220,000 to more than $1
million for some along the Jack Nicklaus PGA golf course, where
initiation fees are $45,000 for residents and $55,000 for
nonresidents.
</P>
<P>
   Both pay monthly dues of $300. Last month, the Optiva Corp.,
which makes electric toothbrushes, opened the first industrial
plant in the complex and is now in operation with 500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   City officials have fought to make sure that Snoqualmie Ridge
will not be an exclusive enclave of perhaps 5,000 people closed to
the city's 1,500 residents. ``We want to be one community, not two
divided,'' says Mayor Randy Fletcher, who works 40 hours a week as
a machinist and won his post a year-and-a-half ago by campaigning
on a platform of controlled growth.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who rides a Harley-Davidson, has at times knocked on
the doors of new residents ``to welcome them to our town one
household at a time.'' Ten years ago residents bitterly opposed the
Weyerhaeuser project out of fears that urban sprawl and traffic
would destroy the rural valley with its farms and horse pastures,
as has happened to neighboring communities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But City Administrator Kim Wilde believes the success of the
project will assure a better future for the 101-year-old
Snoqualmie. The city estimates that in five years it will start
receiving $3 million a year in revenues from the development. Just
a few years ago the town was so poor that its waste water treatment
system was failing and, Wilde said, ``the streets were practically
dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Snoqualmie annexed the ridge property in 1990 as a vehicle for
growth because the Snoqualmie River regularly floods the town. New
King County zoning laws restrict construction in a flood plain and
it has been years since new homes were built within city limits.
</P>
<P>
   The historic, two-block-long downtown on Railroad Avenue is
lined on one side with a grocery, hardware, barber and beauty
shops, a pharmacy, an ice cream store and a bowling alley. Across
the street is a railroad yard brimming with rusting antique train
cars, a depot built in 1890, a rose garden and Smokey Joe's Tavern.
The town and a scenic railroad cater to the 1.5-million tourists
who visit the 268-foot high Snoqualmie Falls a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   The Weyerhaeuser Corp. of Federal Way, Wash., has been a
presence in the valley since 1917 when it built its first of a
series of sawmills and was the valley's largest employer. But with
the demise of large old-growth timber, its only operations here are
a lumber-drying kiln and a wood-planing plant. The company employs
215 people locally, including those working in 120,000 acres of
timberlands in its Snoqualmie Tree Forest. Snoqualmie Ridge is the
third planned community that the company is developing in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council negotiated long and hard with Weyerhaeuser
before approving the project. ``People do not recognize the courage
it took for the City Council to stand up to a developer of this
magnitude,'' said Wilde. ``The city by no means rolled over and
played dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The most hotly contested issue was Weyerhaeuser's plan to
construct hundreds of expensive homes overlooking the scenic
Snoqualmie Falls. The company backed off, so the wilderness view
from the falls will be unobstructed. Only a corner of the 12th tee
of the golf course is visible.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the company has invested $150 million in Snoqualmie
Ridge, mostly in streets, utilities infrastructure, landscaping and
planning. Nine builders are constructing the residences, including
Weyerhaeuser's Quadrant Homes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy was to position our development close to
Interstate 90 because Puget Sound is a very large market of
potential buyers and people can get to work in Seattle within 30
minutes,'' says Edwin Vetter, general manager of the Snoqualmie
Ridge project.
</P>
<P>
   To keep traffic of 5,000 new residents from overrunning the
downtown, Weyerhaeuser spent $30-million to build a 3.5-mile
parkway off I-90 through the development. The road then swings down
the ridge and ends a few blocks north of the downtown. The company
will turn the parkway over to the city.
</P>
<P>
   In a ``shortfall'' agreement, Weyerhaeuser is picking up the tab
for expenses created by the development until Snoqualmie has a cash
flow from tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The company is now paying the salaries of 17 new city employees,
such as police officers, firemen, parks and administrative staff to
deal with an influx of residents. The city is also pursuing grants
and so far has garnered $10 million for major street, sidewalk,
storm sewer and parks improvements, and money to elevate 40
chronically flooded homes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of the grants, $2 million came from the Federal Emergency
Management Administration to elevate homes in the flood plain so
they would not be inundated in the next flood. An additional
$500,000 came from the State Transportation Improvement Board to
improve streets.
</P>
<P>
   Vetter said his company had constructed a storm-drainage system
and a new wastewater treatment plant to replace the failing system,
and had expanded the water supply to serve the entire town. In
addition, the developer dedicated land for three schools and 40
percent of the development's acreage, or 538 acres, will remain in
open space or parks, including the 222-acre golf course.
</P>
<P>
   The big plum for the city is the new tax base. ``We anticipate
having a revenue surplus from the project around 2005,'' said
Wilde. Funds will go toward a new community center on the ridge,
where Weyerhaeuser has reserved a site and will donate $750,000
toward overall costs of $5 million. And a new city hall and park
are planned downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers at Snoqualmie Ridge are a mix of empty-nesters, young
couples and large families who mostly are relocating from elsewhere
in the Puget Sound area. They work at companies such as Boeing and
Microsoft, said Scott Estes, a salesman at a model built by William
Buchan Homes.
</P>
<P>
   Detached homes sell for $220,000 for 1,400 square feet with
three bedrooms, $430,000 for 3,200 square feet with three bedrooms,
$619,000 for 3,600 square feet with four bedrooms. If situated on a
golf course fairway, they start at $700,000 for custom-built homes
with 4,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Two-family houses, each unit with three bedrooms, will range
from 1,683 square feet to 1,841 square feet per unit and cost from
$254,000 to $320,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the impact downtown has been positive. At the Coast to
Coast hardware store, Robert Squibb, a salesman said, ``People say
they'd rather give us the business than go elsewhere. We've sold a
lot of lawn mowers, wheelbarrows and barbecues.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Weyerhaeuser would like to expand into 800 acres adjoining
Snoqualmie Ridge and a local subsidiary of the Puget Sound Energy
electric utility, Puget Western, is proposing a development of 300
homes with a shopping center near the falls. Both proposals are
delicate issues for city officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't stop all growth,'' said Mayor Fletcher, ``but we can
get up front and steer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
