<HEADER>
A0643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSCLINTON-PRESS-SECR     06-26 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-PRESS-SECRETARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESS AIDE FOR EXPLORATORY COMMITTEE IS APPOINTED BY FIRST LADY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the verge of starting a summer of nearly nonstop
travel across New York state, Hillary Rodham Clinton announced
Saturday that she had hired a press secretary for her Senate
exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   It is her first high-profile campaign appointment and a clear
sign that Mrs. Clinton is shifting her attention from being first
lady to laying the foundation for a prospective Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton selected Howard Wolfson, who is now the chief of
staff to Rep. Nita M. Lowey, the Westchester Democrat who had
planned to run for the Senate seat if Mrs. Clinton did not. Wolfson
also served as communications director for Charles Schumer's
successful Senate campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson's appointment was announced three days after Mrs.
Clinton returned to Washington from a trip to Europe with President
Clinton. The announcement Saturday morning, combined with other
signs of activity in Mrs. Clinton's camp, suggests that her
political efforts are shifting into a new and more intensive phase.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's associates said Saturday that she is on the verge
of signing a lease for a campaign headquarters near Madison Square
Garden in midtown Manhattan. She and Clinton have been looking at
videotapes and pictures of houses where they might live, including
one in North Salem.
</P>
<P>
   And next Wednesday, Mrs. Clinton will travel to the upstate home
of Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the Democratic senator who is retiring
at the end of 2000, to begin a three-day swing through upstate New
York. It is during that trip that she is expected to formally
announce the creation of her exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's aides said Saturday that they hope the
appointment of Wolfson, who has extensive experience in both New
York and Washington politics, will bring some order to what has
been the rather haphazard public face of Mrs. Clinton's putative
campaign. Until now, a number of Mrs. Clinton's associates and
friends have been speaking on behalf of the first lady's political
plans, some with knowledge, and some without.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson, 32, was among a number of candidates Mrs. Clinton
considered for the position of press secretary. She had met
earlier, and was close to appointing, Dick Riley, a former press
secretary to former New York City Mayor Edward Koch, to the
position. However, when Ms. Lowey announced that she was not
running for the Senate seat in early June, Mrs. Clinton's senior
political adviser, Harold M. Ickes, arranged a meeting between
Wolfson and Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson brings a number of potential advantages to Mrs. Clinton.
For one thing, he grew up in New York _ he was born in Middletown,
and grew up in Yonkers and Mount Vernon _ which is particularly
significant because one of Mrs. Clinton's potential Republican
opponents, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, has been trying to
discredit her as a carpetbagger.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson also worked in a senior position in the last successful
statewide Democratic campaign, when Schumer was elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``His winning experience, both with Nita Lowey and Chuck
Schumer, and his knowledge of New York will be invaluable as I
consider a run for the Senate,'' the first lady said in a
statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
