<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0645 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-1STL     06-26 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PLANS TO CUT LONG-TERM COST OF MEDICARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to clarify poverty level in 2nd-to-last graf of 1st take.)  (mk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will try to reconcile two
seemingly contradictory goals this week when he unveils a plan to
cut the long-term cost of Medicare while expanding the program to
cover prescription drugs, administration officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   His plan would make structural changes in Medicare to encourage
competition and efficiency in the care of the elderly and the
disabled. It would also require major new infusions of cash from
the federal treasury, said officials who are putting final details
of the plan in place.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said Clinton would insist that the government
offer drug coverage to all 39 million Medicare beneficiaries. Drug
coverage should be ``universal, voluntary and heavily subsidized,''
a White House official said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Republicans and some Democrats in Congress want to
start gradually, by covering medicines for the lower-income
beneficiaries who most need assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens to his proposal, Clinton will reshape
the debate simply by demanding that coverage of prescription drugs
be made available to all Americans over the age of 64 and to those
of any age who are severely disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saying that the benefit has to be universal is a major
contribution to the debate,'' said Martin Corry, director of
federal affairs at the American Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   Though often lost in the hubbub over new benefits, the original
reason for trying to redesign Medicare was to avert a financial
crisis. Administration officials said the president's plan would
keep Medicare solvent in these ways:
</P>
<P>
   _ The federal government would steer Medicare patients to
certain hospitals that promise to give the government a deep
discount on complicated, expensive procedures like heart bypass
surgery and hip replacement operations. Many studies have found a
higher quality of care at hospitals that perform a large number of
such procedures.
</P>
<P>
   _ Medicare would use competitive bidding to buy a wide range of
goods and services, including hospital beds, wheelchairs and other
medical equipment. The government would also try to negotiate
prices far below those set in existing fee schedules.
</P>
<P>
   _ Medicare would get a huge infusion of cash from the treasury:
$700 billion, representing 15 percent of federal budget surpluses
anticipated over the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable transformation seems to have occurred in the last
year. The question now is not whether Medicare should cover
prescription drugs, but how.
</P>
<P>
   Disagreements over that question, including the sheer complexity
of designing a benefit affordable to both elderly people and to the
treasury, could easily stymie efforts to provide drug coverage in
this Congress. But the issue will become more urgent as 76 million
baby boomers qualify for Medicare over the next three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jennings, the president's health policy coordinator, said:
``The desired outcome is to cover prescription drugs for everybody.
That's the approach we're contemplating. Large numbers of middle-
and upper-income Medicare beneficiaries have little or no drug
coverage, but high out-of-pocket drug costs. If you target the
solution to low-income people, you're not taking care of the
problem at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beneficiaries have paid for Medicare throughout their working
careers,'' Jennings said. ``If you say that certain people on
Medicare can have drug coverage and others don't, you will
undermine the broad support that exists for the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will depict drug coverage as one element in a
comprehensive plan to shore up Medicare, White House officials
said. But health policy experts and politicians doubt that Medicare
can be ``fixed'' by the passage of one bill, however comprehensive.
In the next two decades, they predict, Congress will continually
tinker with the program, searching for ways to enhance benefits
while trimming payments to hospitals, doctors and other health care
providers.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every type of health care provider is pleading with
Congress to restore Medicare money cut just two years ago by the
Balanced Budget Act. Thus, beneficiaries, eager for drug coverage,
and health care providers have competing claims to the same pot of
money.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they were ready to portray the
coming debate over Medicare as a struggle between needy
beneficiaries and a greedy health care industry. So far, they said,
the 1997 cuts appear to have done more harm to the financial
condition of the industry than to the health of beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Nursing homes, home care agencies and health maintenance
organizations have been complaining bitterly about the cuts. But
Corry of the AARP said, ``There has not been a spontaneous outcry
among beneficiaries, or an upsurge in complaints about denial of
access to home care, nursing homes or hospitals.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton describes affordable prescription drugs as ``the
greatest growing need of seniors.'' And he notes that drugs have
become an integral, indispensable part of modern medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Elderly people use one-third of all prescription drugs sold in
the United States. On average, each Medicare beneficiary has more
than 18 prescriptions filled each year.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House says that 15.5 million Medicare
beneficiaries have no insurance for prescription drugs, and 6
million of those beneficiaries have incomes more than twice the
official poverty level. The poverty level this year is $8,240 for
an individual and $11,060 for a couple.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every member of Congress has heard pleas from
constituents unable to afford medicines they need. ``The public in
America is getting gouged,'' said Sen. Richard Bryan, D-Nev.
``That's what our constituents tell us.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Congress is cautious, and the reason can be summarized in
one word: cost.
</P>
<P>
   From 1992 to 1997, national spending on prescription drugs grew
by an average of 11 percent a year, which is more than double the 5
percent rate for health care spending overall. The increase
reflects the development of new, more expensive, more effective
drug therapies and greater use of prescription drugs, driven in
part by more aggressive marketing aimed directly at consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers and health maintenance organizations report that drugs
are their fastest-growing cost.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid, the federal-state program for poor families, does
cover prescription drugs, and even though it gets substantial
discounts from manufacturers, Medicaid now spends more on drugs
than on doctors' services.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Concannon, the commissioner of human services in Maine,
said the state's Medicaid program spent $140 million a year on
prescription drugs, compared with $40 million on doctors' services.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen deMontmollin, vice president of AvMed Health Plan, a
large nonprofit HMO in Florida, said drug spending for his members
rose 33 percent last year, to $115 million.
</P>
<P>
   At a congressional hearing last week, Republican senators like
William Roth Jr. of Delaware, Charles Grassley of Iowa and John
Chafee of Rhode Island expressed support for Medicare coverage of
drugs, but said it should be provided first to the neediest
beneficiaries. Moderate Democratic senators like John Breaux of
Louisiana and Max Baucus of Montana agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Grassley, the chairman of the Senate Special Committee on Aging,
expressed the view of the Republican majority. He cautioned against
``any rich new benefit'' and said, ``A targeted approach, focusing
on low-income seniors, is the best solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux was chairman of a 17-member commission that was supposed
to advise Congress and the president on the future of Medicare. The
panel did not agree on much, but did provide authoritative
bipartisan backing for the view that Medicare is antiquated because
it does not cover prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux proposed drug coverage for 3 million low-income
beneficiaries, and he said it would cost the government $60 billion
over 10 years. The White House rejected the proposal as
``inadequate and inefficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Democrats, led by Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts
and Reps. Henry Waxman and Pete Stark of California, agree with
Clinton that drug coverage should be available to all
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare beneficiaries now pay a premium of $45.50 a month.
Under current law, with no change in benefits, the monthly premium
is expected to double in a decade, to $101 in 2009. Any premium for
prescription drug coverage would be added to that.
</P>
<P>
   John Podesta, the White House chief of staff, said the poorest
people would not have to pay the full premium for drug coverage
under Clinton's plan. ``Some people will get help with the premium
at the lower end of the scale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a consumer
group, said, ``It makes sense for seniors to pay a significant part
of the cost through a premium.'' But, he said, it is ``absolutely
essential'' for the government to pay the premiums for Medicare
beneficiaries with incomes as much as 35 percent above the poverty
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Administration officials told me they were willing to pay the
full premium on the drug benefit for people with incomes up to 120
percent of the poverty level,'' Pollack said. ``I urged them to do
better than that, to go to 135 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Low-income beneficiaries are already eligible for federal
assistance in paying their basic Medicare premiums. But in studies
going back to 1991, Pollack has repeatedly documented the failure
of the federal government and the states to locate the people
eligible for such subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare officials have told the White House that if Medicare
begins to cover prescription drugs, many more low-income people
would have an incentive to step forward and claim the federal
subsidies to which they are entitled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
