<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-FLATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: MYSTERY ON THE SALTWATER FLATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETE BODO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. _ David Blinken stood high above the water
line in Napeague Bay, on the poling platform rising above the
outboard engine of his 20-foot flats skiff. Balancing himself with
a 20-foot-long black pole, he braced his thick legs as a mild swell
rolled the boat, causing the platform _ a panel of white fiberglass
hardly larger than your typical bathmat _ to tilt. It was a stunt
worthy of a circus, and I imagined that Blinken was a 1,000-pound
baby elephant, dressed in a pink tutu. Blinken's excited voice
quickly dispelled the fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, fish ahead,'' he barked. ``Gimme a throw, 50 feet, at two
o'clock.''
</P>
<P>
   I cast from the bow, futilely trying to spot the fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go right,'' Blinken called, judging the length and direction
of my cast. ``A little more line. Go right. OK, drop it. Drop it
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The fly, a brown and green concoction with a tiny dumbbell tied
in at the front for eyes, hit the water with a plop. The coaching
resumed, in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strip hard,'' Blinken repeated. ``Slow. Twitch it, stop. Short
strip, let it drop, he's on it, come on _ eat it, eat it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the last moment, the big striped bass decided to pass on the
morsel. I tried to imagine what it must be like to refrain from
grabbing, say, a deviled egg drifting past my own nose, and
realized that there really is a reason why so many people watch
television shows like ``The X Files.'' If you're going to
sight-fish on the saltwater flats, make room in your life for a
little mystery. And prepare to accept rejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``See those stones?'' Blinken said, as he leaned into his
push-pole and slid us along in about 20 inches of water, along a
stretch of beach between Napeague and Gardiners Bay. ``They were
ground up and dumped there by glaciers.''
</P>
<P>
   The cobbled bottom below the boat was more like the floor of a
trout stream than a tidal flat. The colors were autumnal, with
patches of pine-green kelp and red slipgut scattered among amber
and brown stones polished to the consistency of dinner rolls. If
the appeal of blue water stems from our age-old fascination with
the unseen _ Gee, I wonder what's down there? _ the beauty of the
flats lies in things observed.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing the flats _ the ``skinny water'' in anglers' language _
is a time-honored art among bonefish and tarpon anglers in southern
Florida and the Caribbean. But it is a relatively new practice in
the Northeast. Blinken, 38, whose operation is called North Flats
Guiding, is one of a handful of guides who have successfully
adapted the gear and techniques developed in the south to the quest
for stripers and blues in the labyrinth of bays, estuaries and
flats of the east end of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   A flat is any significant expanse of shallow water from a few
inches to 2 feet deep, with an even bottom. To many people, a flat
appears to be an utterly useless place, since you can't swim,
Jet-Ski or surf in it. But for the flyfisher there's nothing
socially unacceptable about being on the bay side of the Hamptons'
sandy beaches, because the flats are essentially critical, wetland
environments where life is manufactured from two of its main
ingredients: light and water. The fertility of a flat makes it an
ideal nursery for small fish and crustaceans, and that in turn
makes a flat the ideal stomping ground for big, predatory gamefish
when the tide, light, wind direction and water temperature invite
marauding.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:30 p.m., at peak heat on an already hot day, Blinken poled
along a place he calls Dead-Tree Flat. We were, as he likes to say,
``looking for shadows'' _ the ghostly gray forms of striped bass
searching for pods of the baitfish called sand eels, or crabs.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to spot fish before they spot you is a critical and
challenging component in sight fishing, for a couple of reasons.
For one, the medium of water dramatically shrinks anything in it,
to the extent that even in only 2 feet of water, a 36-inch fish
looks hardly larger than a loaf of bread.
</P>
<P>
   For another, unlike a loaf of bread, a fish is packaged to blend
into rather than stand out from its surroundings. And, as any
veteran angler will tell you, the notion that water is transparent
is myth. Water can be as opaque as a slab of obsidian, or as
translucent as air. It all depends on the angle and availability of
the light.
</P>
<P>
   I stripped the fly fast, getting it in front of the bass, and
upon command I let it drop. We saw the inside of the bass' great
mouth, dazzling white and large enough to inhale a softball. In a
moment I was tight on the fish, and it shattered the stillness on
the flat with its first, angry thrashing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
