<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK 5-ALARM FIRE LEAVES FAMILIES HOMELESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A five-alarm fire that began Saturday morning in the
storage yard of a plastics factory in the Astoria section of Queens
destroyed at least eight nearby apartments and may leave as many as
32 families temporarily homeless.
</P>
<P>
   No residents were injured, but at least three of the 225
firefighters battling the blaze were sent to local hospitals, one
to be treated for burns, two others for dehydration, according to
William Feehan, first deputy commissioner of the New York Fire
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters were on the scene by 11:08 a.m., within five
minutes of the first alarm, Feehan said, but more than two hours
and 52 engines later, there were still flames shooting from beneath
the fallen tin roof of a shed in the storage yard of the company,
Pop Display.
</P>
<P>
   Among the manufacturing materials stored in the factory were
drums of motor oil and hydraulic fuel, cases of styrene plastics
and propane cylinders, which caused several explosions as they
caught fire, Feehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Shane, 52, who has lived in the apartment building next to
the factory for 28 years, said: ``It felt like something blowing
up. I didn't think anything of it. Then a couple of minutes later I
heard another boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Shane, who was watching television at the time, said her
brother-in-law alerted her to the fire by telephone, and she and
several other residents of the four-story building fled as the
first engines were arriving.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters evacuated other families as flames reached all
eight apartments facing the factory yard, as well as the building's
roof.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelia Snedeker, a resident, said she had fed the stray cats
in the factory yard Saturday morning around 9:30 as usual, then
returned to her apartment to eat breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just smelled smoke,'' she said. ``They knocked on the door _
the police. I saw the smoke. I heard a lot of explosions.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of area residents swarmed on the sidewalks surrounding
the burned buildings as the black smoke in the sky blocked the sun.
Maria Cardenas, 38, a mother of two, was at the supermarket with
her 4-year-old son, Jesse, then returned around 11:30 a.m. to see
her apartment building in flames, with many of its windows
shattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `My son, where is my son?''' Mrs. Cardenas
said in Spanish, referring to her older boy, Johnny, 15. She found
him with neighbors about five minutes later. ``I feel desperate. I
don't have an apartment. My things are destroyed. I don't know what
will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross arrived by 12:30 p.m., and offered shelter to
displaced residents.
</P>
<P>
   Feehan said investigators had not established the cause of the
fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
