u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIANS-BOS     06-26 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW MORE RUSSIANS ARRIVE IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT 
c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ A detachment of Russian troops flew into
the airport here Saturday, defusing a potentially explosive rift
with NATO peacekeeping forces and offering reassurance to Serbs
losing faith in NATO's ability to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   The 39 paratroopers and technical specialists who arrived in the
capital city of Kosovo province were the first of an expected 3,600
Russian troops expected to arrive over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   They will be grafted on to the 22,000 soldiers of the NATO-led
KFOR peacekeeping force patrolling the streets of a province still
simmering with tension, as returning Albanians take sometimes
deadly revenge on Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Kosovo's Serb minority, meanwhile, continued to flee
in steady numbers.
</P>
<P>
   NATO hopes the Russians, who have a historic kinship with Serbs,
will help stem the flight of Serbs who feel threatened by the
majority ethnic Albanians. The Albanian refugees have returned with
stunning swiftness after being driven from their homes to refugee
camps in Albania, Macedonia, and the Yugoslav republic of
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian and French transports were the vanguard of a dozen
flights _ half of them Russian and half NATO _ expected over the
next 10 days. They will bring crews and equipment to make the
airport fully operational for military and humanitarian flights.
</P>
<P>
   The precise role of Russian troops in the KFOR mission remained
the subject of tortuous negotiations between Moscow and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   British Lieutenant General Sir Michael Jackson, commander of the
peacekeeping force, joined Russian Colonel General Viktor Zavarzin
at a press conference, and both stressed that they were now
cooperating.
</P>
<P>
   As they spoke, British and Russian troops mingled on the tarmac.
On the terminal building, a Russian flag and the flag of Russian
airborne forces flew side by side, with a British flag off to one
side.
</P>
<P>
   The military leaders stood side-by-side and said reopening the
airport was a crucial step in international efforts to rebuild
Kosovo, which suffered widespread devastation both from the Serb
campaign against the province's ethnic Albanian majority and from
NATO's air campaign to halt the Serb action.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said any diplomatic rifts that developed over the
incident had been healed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very pleased to get every soldier I can at the moment,''
Jackson said, referring to NATO's attempt to keep control of the
situation in Kosovo by accelerating deployment of an eventual
55,000 peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Ilyushin-76 troop transport and an almost
simultaneous French flight were the first aircraft to arrive at
Pristina's Slatina Airport since a dispute between Russia and NATO
over control of the strategic facility threatened the Kosovo peace
mission.
</P>
<P>
   It also marked the end of a standoff that began June 12 when 200
Russian soldiers from Bosnia occupied the airport, catching NATO by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the presence of thousands of peacekeepers, a climate of
lawlessness continued in the province. On Friday, 14 Serb civilians
were reportedly killed in the space of 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   One flash point between Serbs and ethnic Albanians was the
northern town of Mitrovica, where the leader of the ethnic Albanian
Kosovo Liberation Army arrived Saturday to defuse mounting
tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Hashim Thaci told ethnic Albanians in the town, where a bridge
over the River Ibar has become a dividing line of barbed wire,
tanks, and shouting between the communities, that Serbs should be
allowed to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should realise that everyone who wants to live in Kosovo
should live in Kosovo,'' he told a crowd of supporters.
</P>
<P>
   With the flood of returning refugees cresting in recent days,
the office of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees said it would
begin a full-scale operation Monday to provide transportation and
aid to returning families.
</P>
<P>
   Many families are returning to burned-out homes and chilling
evidence of the murderous campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' carried
out by Serb forces. Thousands have ignored pleas by UN officials
and even President Clinton, during his tour of a refugee camp in
Macedonia this week, that they wait in the camps until land mines,
littered throughout the countryside, could be identified and
clearing begun.
</P>
<P>
   More than 330,000 have returned in the two weeks since NATO's
11-week air war against Yugoslavia ended. About 800,000 Kosovo
Albanians had fled Serb terror to Macedonia, Albania, and
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern town of Lipljan, British soldiers arrested a
member of the Serbian Interior Ministry whom they accused of
involvement in as many as 56 deaths in Kosovo, a British forces
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   British Lieutenant Colonel Robin Hodges did not identify the
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Material from the Associated Press was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
