<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox standing by slumping Perez
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves are prepared to be patient with 21-year-old
fifth starter Odalis Perez, and losses in his last three starts
don't change that. Perez lost the series opener to the Mets after
throwing a season-high nine strikeouts before allowing three runs
in the sixth inning to fall to 4-5 with a 5.42 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's learning up here in a very difficult situation,'' manager
Bobby Cox. ``He's holding his own. As bad as it may seem, it's not
that bad. Winning is everything with this team right now, but I
like him. I think we can bring him along.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Braves have been able to develop their
fifth starter in the minorleagues, pitchers like Terrell Wade and
Jason Schmidt, but in this case, with Denny Neagle traded away and
Kevin Millwood in the No. 4 spot, the Braves are prepared to train
Perez on the job and deal with the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put him in there and left him in there,'' Cox said.
``He's more than holding his own.''
</P>
<P>
   In his loss in Houston, Perez was hurt by seven walks. In
Arizona, he got beat on eight hits, including two home runs. On
Friday night he hung a couple of 0-2 pitches at bad times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble with him is he has three above-average pitches, he
falls in love with one and not the other one,'' Cox said. ``It gets
him in trouble once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Leo Mazzone said after Perez gave up a home run
to Benny Agbayani he came off the field saying he'd taken too much
off his changeup, which is just what Mazzone had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of the maturation process,'' Mazzone said.
``He's very sincere in wanting to be successful. He's hard on
himself, sometimes too hard on himself.... I've got a lot of
confidence in him. He's got some quality pitches. For the fifth
hole, he's great, no drop-off in stuff.... If he ends up the year
at .500 that's pretty darn good. A lot of staffs don't have a
(third starter) at .500.''
</P>
<P>
   Speier struggles
</P>
<P>
   Justin Speier has watched his ERA soar from 2.86 to 5.65 in his
last three outings after giving up six runs in a 22-1 loss to the
Orioles and five runs against the Mets on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cox attributed it to rustiness for Speier, who hadn't pitched in
six days and showed it by walking a season-high four batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually I pound the strike zone,'' Speier said. ``Last night,
I didn't get ahead. If you don't get ahead and throw mediocre
pitches, you're going to get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox also knows it's a tough situation to come in and hold it
when the team is losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to gear up, knowing the manager is mopping up with
you,'' Cox said. ``It's hard. He's got a great attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Speier said he doesn't mind being the last reliever out of the
bullpen and the stretches between outings it entails.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's no big deal,'' Speier said. ``I'm just happy to be a
part of this team, getting a chance to pitch at the big-league
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   The MRI exam scheduled for Randall Simon's left knee was
postponed until after the Braves' upcoming road trip to Montreal
and New York. Simon has felt some stiffness in his knee after
sliding on it or landing hard on it in games, but otherwise has
been able to play since he first injured it sliding home in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something we're worried about because it's not going
to keep me out for a month,'' Simon said. ``They just want to be
sure what we're dealing with. Right now everything is fine.''...
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss was still out of the lineup on Saturday night because
of his sore quadriceps. ``He's still feeling it,'' Cox said. Weiss
may have to look ahead to the Mets series at Shea Stadium July 2-4,
because the Expos play on artificial turf....
</P>
<P>
   Cox said Saturday the Braves do anticipate Javy Lopez will be
ready to play when he comes off the disabled list July 6. Trainers
are having a special brace made for him to wear on his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
