<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0676 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLDRAFT27-COX     06-26 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLDRAFT27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Right fit for Atlanta
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On a few occasions since being named the architect of a
hockey team last year, Don Waddell has joked that the NHL
guarantees little more than a place in the standings for an $80
million franchise fee. The construction was up to the general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the NHL executive with the most bloodshot set of eyes
continued attacking his project with the same aggression he wants
from his players. One day after spinning eight trades following the
expansion draft, the Thrashers were part of a 12-hour, four-team
trade that enabled the team to move up from second to the first
overall pick and select Czech center Patrik Stefan.
</P>
<P>
   In Stefan, the Thrashers not only landed the centerpiece of
their future but an 18-year-old who already has played two seasons
with a pro team (Long Beach of the IHL) and can step right into the
team's lineup _ a rarity for an NHL draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very big day for our franchise,'' Waddell said.
``We've made it no secret how we feel about Patrik and what kind of
player he is. But to be able to bring in a player who can play
immediately is a big positive for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The duration of the Thrashers' euphoria is linked directly to
how long Stefan remains lucid. Most questions directed at him in
recent months have centered on the two or three concussions he had
this season that limited him to 35 games (of an 82-game season)
with Long Beach. Waddell maintained he made this pick without
seeing Stefan's most recent medical records. But he does not
believe he is taking any gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten the needed information verbally (from Stefan's
agent) that we were comfortable with to make this decision,''
Waddell said. ``I have not seen the medical information. But I'm
very confident everything is fine. ... We're 100 percent sure. It's
not an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell believes that if Rich Winter, Stefan's agent, had made
the medical records public, ``We might not have gotten him. Tampa
might not have made the trade and would've taken him first. But it
also seems rather obvious that (Winter) didn't want Patrik to go to
Tampa (which has a surplus of centers). Maybe that's why he did
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefan reassured all _ again _ about his health, saying,
``Everybody talks about my health, my concussions. But I feel very,
very well. That is all behind me now. I just want to think about
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed doubtful that future was in Atlanta. But the dominoes
began to fall around midnight Friday when Vancouver general manager
Brian Burke (holding the third overall pick) phoned Waddell and
said he had acquired Chicago's first pick (fourth overall) for
defenseman Bryan McCabe and a No. 1 in 2000 or 2001. Burke was
trying to angle to draft Swedish twins Daniel and Henrik Sedin and
he wanted assurances that they would fall that far. Waddell
couldn't guarantee anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were talks until about 3 in the morning,'' Waddell said.
``When I unplugged my phone at 3, I didn't think it would happen.
There were too many `ifs' because everything was contingent on
Vancouver getting Tampa's pick to trade to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks resumed at 6 a.m. ``I thought it might get done, but then
between 8 and 11 I thought it was dead again.'' At about 11:30,
Burke closed a deal with Tampa, landing the Lightning's first pick
for the fourth pick and two third-rounders. The Canucks then dealt
that No. 1 to the Thrashers, who gave Vancouver a third-rounder in
2000 to move up one spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finished it on the floor about 10 minutes before we went on
the air,'' said Burke, alluding to the draft broadcast at noon.
</P>
<P>
   Burke got what he wanted most: both Sedins. The Thrashers got
Stefan. And new Tampa president Rick Dudley continued to make a
flurry of trades, dealing the fourth pick to the New York Rangers
for goalie Dan Cloutier, forward Niklas Sundstrom and first- and
third-rounders next year.
</P>
<P>
   Given Dudley's uncertainty about Stefan, there's a chance the
Thrashers might have been able to swing a late trade with the
Lightning. But that wasn't necessary. And nobody was happier about
the result than Stefan, who had 35 points (11 goals) in 33 games
with Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know anything until they said it on the stage,'' he
said. ``I was surprised. But it's great. Atlanta is an expansion
team but it can be a great team and I can be a part of this future.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
