<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS BEAT BALTIMNOR E, 7-4  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The humidity here Saturday made breathing feel as if
you were leaning nose-first into the spray of a boiling tea kettle,
and the Yankees' players reminded themselves to drink water and
retreat to their air conditioned clubhouse whenever possible. About
90 minutes before Saturday's game, however, David Cone flopped onto
the dugout bench, legs splayed in front of him, as if he were
happily relaxing at poolside.
</P>
<P>
   Cone loves the heat, preferring it since he had surgery to
repair an aneurysm below his right armpit three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He can sweat in the heat, keep his pitching arm loose in the
heat and, best of all, win in the heat. He stifled the Orioles for
eight innings Saturday, as the Yankees won, 7-4, their fifth
consecutive victory and the Orioles' fourth straight loss.
</P>
<P>
   The steamy conditions did take their toll on the Yankees
(44-28). Derek Jeter got a cramp in his left hamstring while
running to first base in the eighth inning. Jeter, who was removed
for a pinch-runner, said he had not felt the injury before that
play, but it should be noted that Jeter is strategically deceptive
while discussing his injuries. Teammates said Jeter's hamstring was
bothering him earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the exact nature of the injury, and whenever Jeter
first felt the cramping, Manager Joe Torre indicated that he
thought Jeter would play on Sunday, when the Yankees try to
complete a sweep of this six-game trip. At the very least, Torre is
confident Jeter's injury is not serious.
</P>
<P>
   Cone had never won in Camden Yards, going 0-4 with a 5.40 earned
run average in six previous starts, probably owing to the park's
dollhouse dimensions and the power of the Baltimore lineup in
recent years. But for once, the conditions here suited Cone, the
88-degree temperature, the thick air.
</P>
<P>
   The humidity, said first baseman Tino Martinez, made it ``hard
to breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer, the left fielder who homered for the second
consecutive day, estimated he drank 10 bottles of water before the
game, ``almost to the point where I felt bloated.'' Between
innings, Spencer removed his spikes on the bench, ``to let my feet
breathe.'' The players, taking a direct hit from the sun while on
the field, would stretch, bend over and do whatever they could to
cope with the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Cone made his adjustment. He often throws fastballs early in the
game and early in counts, establishing this pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday Cone pitched backward: rather than simply fire
fastballs _ the fastball is a high-effort pitch _ Cone threw his
split-fingered fastball, slider and curve early in counts in the
first few innings, and he threw them for strikes. The first time
through the Baltimore lineup, Cone required three or fewer pitches
with eight of the nine hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Cone usually averages about 17 pitches an inning, and by
controlling his off-speed pitches against the Orioles he was able
to get through the first three innings with 37 pitches, or 12.3 an
inning.
</P>
<P>
   To Hideki Irabu, watching from the Yankees' bench, this was a
very subtle and smart way to conserve energy on the hot and humid
day. The Orioles had one hit in the first five innings, a bloop
single over short that Jeter lost in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``On as hot a day as it was, to be as effective as he was _
that's as good as he's been all year,'' Torre said of Cone.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's Jason Johnson was able to shut out the Yankees
through four innings, but Spencer slugged his home run leading off
the fifth inning. Scott Brosius doubled, and scored when Chuck
Knoblauch doubled, and after Martinez's two-run, two-base hit
highlighted a four-run burst in the eighth, the Yankees were in
command, 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   Cone wanted to finish the game, and he threw only 89 pitches in
the first seven innings, striking out six _ five of those on
two-strike sliders so good that the Orioles' hitters, like Brady
Anderson, Mike Bordick and B.J. Surhoff, could only watch.
</P>
<P>
   But the sun began to feel particularly hot in the eighth inning,
several Yankees said, and Torre could see players on both teams
sagging.
</P>
<P>
   Cone gave up a one-out double to Bordick and a two-out walk to
Albert Belle, and Torre jogged to the mound to ask Cone if he was
spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got one hitter left,'' Cone told him. Torre jogged back
to the dugout and Cone pitched to Harold Baines, who grounded out
sharply to Martinez to end the inning. Cone (8-3) allowed only five
hits and a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera closed out a belated Baltimore uprising in the
eighth, and when the Yankees' position players returned to the
clubhouse, they sprawled on the couches in the players' lounge,
exhausted. ``I can tell you this, I'm going to sleep well,'' said
Joe Girardi, who, as Cone's catcher, had two reasons to dream
peacefully Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   CAL RIPKEN, Baltimore's third baseman, had two hits, including
his 10th homer of the year. Ripken needs 64 hits to reach 3,000 in
his career, and 6 home runs for 400. ... MARIANO RIVERA faced one
hitter in the bottom of the ninth inning, striking out B.J. SURHOFF
for his 20th save in 21 chances. Rivera has made 29 appearances
this year, and retired the first hitter he faced in 28 of those.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
