<SLUG> BC-CT-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HAVEN FESTIVAL GROWS INTO A `MINI-WORLD'S FAIR'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Md., N.Y.)  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Inspired by the success of the Special
Olympics World Games here in 1995, Anne Tyler Calabresi had a
vision she believed could help start a cultural and economic
renaissance in this troubled Ivy League city.
</P>
<P>
   She thought the heart of the downtown, with its 350-year-old
green, and the cozy, historic courtyards of Yale University, would
be the perfect place for an international festival that could
``showcase the city's vast cultural treasures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't another city this size that can boast having an
Ivy League university and internationally renowned art museums and
theaters and a world-class symphony orchestra,'' said Mrs.
Calabresi, who in 1992 founded an academic and social enrichment
program for inner-city children. ``I wanted to create an event to
bring people together who know about the depth of the arts in New
Haven, and at the same time showcase the city's museums, theaters,
restaurants and both visual and performing artists, for people who
have no idea what is here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Calabresi, whose husband, Guido Calabresi, is a federal
judge and former dean of Yale Law School, said she had no idea the
International Festival of Arts and Ideas would grow so quickly to
become one of the largest in the country. The festival, now in its
fourth year, is in the midst of a 16-day run that ends July 3.
</P>
<P>
   With symposiums covering social issues like ``Can Our Schools Be
Better'' and ``War and Peace,'' and performances by internationally
renowned entertainers, festival organizers say they are striving to
take the event to a level rarely achieved in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say they want to make the festival _ modeled after
European festivals that combine the arts, science and in-depth
discussions of ideas _ a tourist attraction that will draw people
to New Haven throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The festival provides this extraordinary vehicle that we
believe can bring people to New Haven during the event, but also
sparks an awareness of the city so they will want to come other
times as well,'' said Paul Collard, the festival's director.
</P>
<P>
   Collard said more than 150,000 people are expected to spend
about $2.5 million in the city during the festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intangible impact this festival is having on New Haven
cannot be overstated,'' said City Planner Karyn Gilvarg, ``both in
psychological and real economic terms. We know it is providing a
tremendous showcase for our museums, restaurants and other
businesses that we could not have dreamed possible a few years
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival blends mostly free science and art exhibits and
musical performances for adults and children, as well as plays
performed by the Royal Shakespeare Theater Co.
</P>
<P>
   Collard, who organized festivals in England, moved from London
two years ago with his wife and four children to direct the
festival here. He said its growth has been extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   The festival has a budget of $2.4 million, contributed by
sponsors like Fleet Bank, the Mashantucket Pequot Tribal Nation,
Sikorsky Aircraft, Southern New England Telephone and the Bayer
Corp. This year, advertising supplements were distributed in
newspapers throughout Connecticut and in New York and
Massachusetts, Collard said. Marketing research has shown that the
supplements help draw people to the city not only during the
festival but throughout the year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year or two, the goal was to reach people in the
immediate New Haven area,'' he said, ``but now we want to begin
drawing people from around Connecticut and throughout the East
Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Phillips, passing through Connecticut on her way home to
Baltimore from a Cape Cod vacation, stopped at the festival with
her three children. She said it was unlike anything she had ever
seen in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more like a mini-World's Fair,'' Ms. Phillips said.
``I've seen festivals like this in Europe, but never before in this
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
