<HEADER>
A0682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-FUTURE-ART-     06-26 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-FUTURE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS' PLACE IN HISTORY MAY REST ON A REPEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The quiet and composed Sean Elliott wanted to bask in the
moment. He wanted to be consumed by the grandeur that surrounded
winning the first National Basketball Association championship in
the San Antonio Spurs' 26-year history. He wanted to savor the
jubilation, the sense of accomplishment, the squirting of the
champagne.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, the NBA is as much about the future as it is
about the present. When Pat Riley coached the Los Angeles Lakers in
the 1980s, he predicted in the midst of their title celebration
that his club would become the first team to repeat as champion in
nearly 20 years. When Michael Jordan won his fifth title with the
Chicago Bulls in 1997, he strutted along the makeshift platform at
midcourt, holding up six fingers to signify that he would be back
to claim one more crown.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no surprise that the questions being asked of the
Spurs early Saturday morning, after they defeated the Knicks by
78-77 to win the finals, four games to one, had nearly as much to
do with next season as with the one San Antonio just finished
dominating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want to talk about that right now,'' Elliott said
when asked about the Spurs' chances of repeating.
</P>
<P>
   But sitting next to him was a more outspoken teammate, the
rambunctious Mario Elie, and he did not mind fast-forwarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to catch Magic Johnson,'' said Elie, who won titles
with the Houston Rockets in 1994 and 1995 before joining the Spurs
this season. ``I'm trying to catch Larry Bird and Michael Jordan.
With this team, we can go right back next year if we keep the same
unit. If we stay healthy, man, I don't see why we can't do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   While there was a time when winning one NBA championship was
enough, the mark of greatness nowadays is the ability to do it
again. Since 1988, when Riley's Lakers became the first team since
Bill Russell's 1969 Boston Celtics to win back-to-back titles, no
champion has done less.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Pistons won their first title in 1989, then repeated
the next year. Jordan led the Bulls to three straight championships
before retiring in 1993. And then Houston held the crown for two
years until Jordan returned to reclaim it from 1996-98.
</P>
<P>
   With such tough acts to follow, the difference between the Spurs
being remembered as a solid club that capitalized on an abnormal
lockout-shortened season or something special hinges on their
ability to seize a second title immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won one championship, but you really can't measure a lot
on that,'' said Will Perdue, the Spurs reserve who played on
Chicago's first three title teams. ``Good teams win championships.
Great teams continue to win championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the aforementioned champions, the Spurs have what seem to
be the ingredients for winning consecutive titles: two superstars
and a solid cast of role players. Tim Duncan, who averaged 27.5
points and 14 rebounds in earning the finals' most valuable player
award, is now widely regarded as the league's top player. And
33-year-old David Robinson, Duncan's 7-foot ``twin tower,'' should
have two or three excellent seasons left in him, particularly with
Duncan's presence reducing his nightly demands.
</P>
<P>
   While the series with the Knicks highlighted the inadequacies of
San Antonio's supporting cast, as long as Duncan and Robinson are
aboard, the Spurs should have enough to contend for the Western
Conference championship. Duncan will definitely wear the Spurs'
black and silver next season, but his long-term future with the
franchise is in question.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Holt, the Spurs' chairman, hopes to put the public
financing of a new arena on city ballots by next January. If the
vote fails, there is every indication that the team will move to
another city, perhaps Baltimore, San Diego, New Orleans or Anaheim,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan said that he hopes to stay with the Spurs for the rest of
his career, but that he will not sign a contract extension with the
club until its future location is determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love San Antonio,'' Duncan said. ``It's a great place. I
would love to be there the rest of my career. However it works out,
it works out. I think everybody with the Spurs knows what it's all
about. We just have to get it done. I think we will get it done.
We've given them a good reason to keep us there.''
</P>
<P>
   With the championship trophy in tote, the Spurs' love affair
with San Antonio seems likely to continue. The phrase ``Go Spurs
Go'' was plastered all over town during the finals, and about
250,000 fans are expected to attend a flotilla parade to honor the
team along the city's Riverwalk Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Some things may change in the West next season: The Spurs may
make minor changes to Duncan and Robinson's complementary cast, and
the Lakers should be better with Phil Jackson as their coach. But
Duncan sees no reason why Sunday night's celebration on the water
cannot be the first of many such coronations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be ready to go next year,'' Duncan said. ``There will be
a lot tougher teams in the West that are going to challenge us for
it, but we'll be right back up there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
