<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUSPECT-INS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
IMMIGRATION OFFICIALS REVIEWING HOW SUSPECTED SERIAL KILLER PASSED
OUT OF THEIR CUSTODY
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JO ANN ZUIGA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The release of a suspected serial killer from
Immigration and Naturalization Service custody earlier this month
illustrates how the latest technology has not quite caught up to
criminals, federal and state officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Resendez-Ramirez slipped through the cracks after he was
taken into custody on June 1 by Border Patrol agents although his
fingerprints were on file both with the National Crime Information
Center and the Texas Crime Information Center, officials confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials in Texas said they were unsure what procedural
changes would be made to prevent a similar occurrence in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   They said Friday that Resendez-Ramirez's arrest as an illegal
immigrant on June 2 at Sunland Park, N.M., was processed the same
as about 1.5 million others made each year by the Border Patrol
along the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time he was apprehended, we had no idea that he was
wanted by the FBI. He was operating under another alias,'' said INS
spokesman Tomas Zuniga at the agency's regional office in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   He was processed at the Santa Teresa INS border station, where
his photo and fingerprints were taken under the INS system known as
IDENT.
</P>
<P>
   A computerized fingerprint identification system, IDENT allows
agents to track how many other times the detainee tried previous
illegal crossings.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a detainee gives a false name, the fingerprint will tie
him or her to any previous attempted crossings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We processed him as we do about 1.5 million apprehensions a
year. We don't ask IDENT for additional checks unless we have a
query or a reason to believe we should put a run on someone,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   IDENT is not cross-referenced to any other state or federal
fingerprinting system without additional checking.
</P>
<P>
   However, if at that point, Resendez-Ramirez's fingerprints had
been run through NCIC or TCIC, officials would have been alerted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both NCIC and TCIC had his fingerprints on file and warrants
out for his arrest at that time,'' said Texas Department of Public
Safety spokeswoman Tela Mange.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the arrest occurred before the FBI had set up its
multiagency task force, Operation Train Stop, on June 8 and gained
nationwide publicity, FBI officials pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   So instead Resendez-Ramirez was released a little after midnight
June 2. He was placed in an INS van and driven halfway across an
international bridge and released back into Mexico, Zuniga said.
</P>
<P>
   A query by INS to NCIC or TCIC can take 45 minutes to an hour
and requires additional costs for manpower and time, Zuniga said.
``But when a human life is at risk, that time means nothing,'' he
acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   A pilot program by the FBI with DPS that uses a Livescan
computer to fingerprint people rather than ink and paper could help
prevent such slips in the future, DPS spokeswoman Mange said.
</P>
<P>
   On that system, a search of databases is done automatically. But
now they're on separate systems and agencies have to scan in the
fingerprints, upload and then wait for a match as the computer goes
through millions of fingerprints, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez has a history of slipping into the United
States illegally since 1976, has served state prison time in New
Mexico and Florida and had been deported previously at least four
times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
