<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0696 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN     06-26 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA CHECKS ITS ODOM-ETER READING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The phone lines are burning as every NBA team worries about
whether to make a deal in Wednesday's draft.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the confusion is that the one player most teams
thought was the most talented, Rhode Island's Lamar Odom,
reportedly still wants to go back to college and blew off more
workouts last week.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago, Vancouver and Charlotte are all fielding offers for the
top three picks, so here's some of the latest:
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are supposedly offering Glen Rice to Vancouver so
they can draft Baron Davis before the Charlotte Hornets take him at
No.3.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder if the Grizzlies could be gullible enough to believe Rice
would re-sign with them.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets have a small dilemma. Davis has not warmed to them,
and is represented by Arn Tellem, who helped get Kobe Bryant to the
Lakers after Charlotte drafted him.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Hornets, agents don't call the shots
anymore. They'll be happy to take Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver is also getting plenty of calls with Philadelphia
(Theo Ratliff), Miami (P.J. Brown) and Indiana (Dale Davis)
interested in acquiring a point guard.
</P>
<P>
   But the Grizzlies might be leaning toward keeping their pick.
They are the only team Odom worked out for and also are intrigued
with adding Elton Brand, now that he actually measured 6-foot-8\ at
a pre-draft camp.
</P>
<P>
   The trade rumors are especially rampant in Chicago. The Bulls
have the No.1 pick, but Toronto is hammering away at Chicago GM
Jerry Krause.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that a deal could be coming, Maryland point guard
Steve Francis worked out for the Raptors last week, reneging on his
promise to only work out for the top three teams in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto has offered its two first-round selections (Nos.5 and
12), but the Bulls want the No.5 and Tracy McGrady or Doug
Christie.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls have also ignored Charlotte's offer of David Wesley
and Anthony Mason, which seems awfully low. Not to mention the
added benefit of getting to deal with Mason.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando is trying to shop guard Nick Anderson for any of the top
five picks, but no one really wants his $24.5 million over the next
four years.
</P>
<P>
   Revised top 10: Barring the barrage of trades, here's another
look at the top-10 picks.
</P>
<P>
   1. Chicago: Francis; 2. Vancouver: Brand; 3. Charlotte: Davis;
4. Clippers: Wally Szczerbiak; 5. Toronto: Odom; 6. Minnesota:
Richard Hamilton; 7. Washington: Andre Miller; 8. Cleveland: Jason
Terry; 9. Phoenix, Jonathan Bender; 10. Golden State: William
Avery.
</P>
<P>
   Back in L.A.: It might sound farfetched, but word out of Detroit
is that the Lakers are showing interest in acquiring problem-child
Bison Dele, who used to be known as Brian Williams when he played
for the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Whither the Worm? Dennis Rodman's agent has sent letters to
warm-weather NBA teams saying he is interested in playing next
season.
</P>
<P>
   But Miami coach Pat Riley has his own theory about Rodman's next
destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he will end up in L.A. with his `father' there,''
Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget, Riley and Jackson are less than cordial, meaning
Lakers-Heat games should at least be interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Cowens in Cleveland: The Cavaliers might name Dave Cowens as
their coach this week. He has had two interviews and met team owner
Gordon Gund last week.
</P>
<P>
   Who's the boss? What do Danny Ainge and Crespi High have in
common? Last week, plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge was at Mater Dei High last weekend to watch his son,
Austin, play for Highland of Gilbert, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   With Ainge watching in the stands as he waited for his son's
game to begin, coach Gary McKnight yanked his Mater Dei team off
the court before the end of the first half. McKnight was upset at
the officiating during the Monarchs contest.
</P>
<P>
   McKnight then decided to bring his team back and resume the
game, just before Crespi and Highland players were ready to begin
playing an impromptu pickup game.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge was among the angry Highland parents in the stands.
According to sources, Ainge was so upset he followed the coach into
Mater Dei's locker room and yelled at McKnight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0697 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT     06-26 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARON LANDSCAPE IS FERTILE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baron Davis may be another guy who has the answer, but evidence
suggests the corresponding question was multiple choice.
</P>
<P>
   Amen.
</P>
<P>
   So put your hands on the remote control, feel the spirit moving
you into the embrace of TNT, and wait for Baron to be picked in
Wednesday's NBA Draft.
</P>
<P>
   You won't have to wait long.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, sisters and brothers and hoop-junkie cousins to be named
later, we have seen the ex-UCLA star within the last three days and
he remains an exclamation point guard. He's the truth, but his
pre-draft story is becoming stranger than fiction.
</P>
<P>
   What's the skinny on Baron's change of direction, his lateral
agility? Without equivocation, we can tell you his, ahem, crossover
is still murder.
</P>
<P>
   And the infamous left knee he injured 15 months ago seems to be
just fine, too.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa, preacher. We'd better return to that crossover reference.
</P>
<P>
   OK, this crossover has nothing to do with Baron's ability to
break ankles and take names. No, we're here to determine if Davis
expected to shake hands with the commish before the fifth pick is
called has had a change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   Let's rewind to May.
</P>
<P>
   As if by rote, Davis responded to preferred-draft-destination
inquiries by saying he'd like to stay home and play in L.A. a Laker
jersey would be great, but helping to lift the Clippers, was a
challenge he'd also love to accept.
</P>
<P>
   However, Wednesday's San Francisco Chronicle published a Davis
quote that urged the Warriors to trade up ahead of the Clippers and
draft him.
</P>
<P>
   We believe Davis said it, but realize the draft countdown
includes more unfulfilled posturing than a skirmish between bantam
computer nerds.
</P>
<P>
   And we are not extending the quoted ``out of context'' option,
leaving us with this response:
</P>
<P>
   What gives?
</P>
<P>
   His agent, Arn Tellem, has been unavailable for comment. Davis
was
</P>
<P>
   available for comment Thursday, but wasn't asked to do so
because we weren't aware of the Chronicle story. (Editor's note:
``Duh.'')
</P>
<P>
   Now let's present the puzzle. Davis turned his ankle during
Tuesday's Warrior workout, but insisted on keeping Thursday
afternoon's encore workout date with the Clippers. If he doesn't
want the Clips to draft him, why would he show up?
</P>
<P>
   Team Davis has refused to visit the point-guard hungry Charlotte
Hornets, who hold the draft's third pick and would like an
audition.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he's planning to make a quick trip to North
Carolina, Davis said, ``I'm not sure,'' which must be UCLA-speak
for ``Gee, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Tellem, according to word around the NBA campfire, may be using
whatever juice he can squeeze to keep his client out of Charlotte,
where the marketing opportunities (sneaker deal, baby) are limited.
If successful, such leveraging could further validate an agent's
superiority to the slotted-contract attention of a mere attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant also is represented by Tellem, and their noisy
dissatisfaction with Charlotte's selection of young Kobe in the
1996 draft led to a quick deal with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Hornets have bestowed their head-coaching
responsibilies upon Paul Silas, who worked with Tellem in the
Clippers' San Diego days.
</P>
<P>
   Would Charlotte draft Davis without a workout? Vancouver drafted
Mike Bibby last year, even though agent David Falk limited Bibby's
visits to one (Clippers). Could Charlotte be scared off by Baron's
knee? Possibly, but remember that Hornets GM Bob Bass is the guy
who drafted Sean Elliott in San Antonio when Elliott's surgically
repaired knee was an issue in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hop over to our own bottom line. Will the Clippers draft
Davis if he's still on the board at four? They may not wait that
long. They could offer free-agent power forward Lorenzen Wright
(sign-and-trade bait) and that fourth pick for Vancouver's spot at
No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Our below-the-bottom line is that the 199 NBA Draft will be as
tough to predict as your sister's meat loaf.
</P>
<P>
   MORE BARON LANDSCAPE
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no Baron Davis chatter is complete without a trip
down Laker Street.
</P>
<P>
   Davis worked out for L.A.'s other team a few days ago, and is
said to be coveted by Jerry West, the team's VP of basketball ops.
</P>
<P>
   We can dig it, but NBA misinformation does grow on trees in
June. Anyway, for Davis to become a Laker, West as the popular
script has it would chat with Phil Jackson and decide if shipping
Glen Rice to Miami is the thing to do. If they agree, the Heat, in
turn, would send P.J. Brown to power forward-challenged Vancouver,
and the Grizzles would surrender their second pick to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Another Tellem client to work out for the Lakers is 6-foot-11
Jonathan Bender, the lean-and-gifted Mississippi high school kid
who's projected to disappear from the draft board shortly before
the 10th pick is made.
</P>
<P>
   TOUGH TRIP FOR `RIP'
</P>
<P>
   NBA smarties love the way Richard ``Rip'' Hamilton can get to
the basket, but the UConn shooting guard had a tough time making it
to Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The trip included a nice drive from Seattle to the Canadian
border, where Rip remembered the one thing he'd forgotten to pack a
passport. But he eventually made it in time for his Grizzles
workout. Don't get happy. His return flight was canceled, so the
star of the 1999 NCAA Tournament had an eight-hour wait at the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the travel miseries, Hamilton who worked out for the
Clippers on Thursday morning is having fun as a traveling salesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enjoying myself, but you can't half-step during this
process,'' he said. ``It's a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to show
what you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Who would Rip prefer to work for?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' said Hamilton, who seems to be a good fit for
Minnesota at No. 6. ``I just want a hat.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Immediately after a player is drafted, an NBA
operative hands him a baseball cap with appropriate logo.
</P>
<P>
   SHOT-CLOCK VIOLATIONS
</P>
<P>
   The NBA fiction department includes a recent report that the
Clippers aren't exactly thrilled with the progress of Michael
Olowokandi, last year's No. 1 overall pick. But Coach Chris Ford
said the 7-foot center, who had minor surgery on his left knee the
week after the regular-season ended, has been sort of thrilling
during recent on-court workouts. Chicago talent capo Jerry Krause
thinks enough of the Kandi Man to make the Clippers another offer
they easily refused. ... The list of early entry draft prospects
returning to college does not include Georgia Tech shooting guard
Dion Glover. Glover, who missed his sophomore season with a knee
injury, still can't work out, but could be selected just past the
midway point of round one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 2103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990626.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0702 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-AL-NOTES-LADN     06-26 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL IT BE INDIAN WELLS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just because Toronto left-hander David Wells signed a two-year,
$16 million contract extension this past week doesn't mean he is
off the trade market.
</P>
<P>
   With Indians owner Dick Jacobs trying to sell the team, Wells
would be a good fit for someone determined to go out a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the extension makes him even more tradeable than he
was before,'' said agent Greg Clifton, who negotiated the
extension. ``Now teams are dealing with a known quantity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians like Wells, who was routed 11-4 by Tampa Bay on
Friday, because they need a left-hander, he's playoff-tested and it
would be great theater to watch him pitch in Yankee Stadium in
October. The downside? He won't come cheaply, and he's capable of
demanding a trade at the end of the season. &QL; 
CAN YOU THROW?
</P>
<P>
   Having recorded saves in three straight games last weekend, Red
Sox interim closer Tim Wakefield said he was ready to face
Baltimore the next game.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox never got to him, but this raised a question. How
many consecutive days can a knuckleballer pitch in relief? ``The
rest of the season,'' teammate Mike Stanley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, uncertain about the future of closer Tom Gordon,
thought Wakefield, 6 for 6 in save opportunities, got stronger each
time out.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as throwing one inning and 13-15 pitches,'' pitching
coach Joe Kerrigan said, ``I think he can do it five, six, seven
days in a row.'' &QL; 
FLYING OR GROUNDED?
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles won 11 of 13 after the Albert Belle/Ray Miller
dugout blowout, but the biggest test of their credibility might be
coming this weekend when they dropped the first two games to the
Yankees. They had drawn within four games of .500 before dropping
back-to-back 2-1 games to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Belle's play had been crucial in the turnaround. He had four
home runs during the two-week roll, but the really big gun has been
B.J. Surhoff, whose 21-game hitting streak finally ended Tuesday.
Surhoff had five homers since June 9, when the Orioles started to
play better. But if the Birds go south again, he could be sent to
the Braves before the July 31 trade deadline. &QL; 
NOT ON THE RESUME
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Manto was expected to be outrighted Friday when the Indians
activated third baseman Travis Fryman. Manto has been sent down 11
times by the Indians over the years.... Twins right-hander Rob
Radlosky was demoted Thursday after giving up seven homers in 81/3
innings _ an average of one every 22 pitches. He was 0-1 with a
12.46 ERA, and opponents were hitting .375 against him. Minnesota
wasn't sure who was headed out. One-time Dodger Gary Rath stayed
despite an 0-1 record and an 11.57 ERA. &QL; 
GOOD NEWS, BAD NEWS
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay Devils Rays had their largest crowds since opening
day when the Yankees came to town. Sadly, most of them were Yankees
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take fans for whatever reason,'' said Rays manager Larry
Rothschild. ``I don't really care. Someday, we've got to get beyond
that, for whatever reason, and get fans out here to watch us
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't just a bad team. It's the location of the
ballpark in St. Petersburg. There is an eight-mile bridge between
Tampa and St. Pete which has eliminated the sizable Orlando market.
Fans don't want to cross Tampa and that bridge at rush hour. &QL; 
ANYTHING YOU CAN DO...
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars won the NHL Stanley Cup, which may put some
pressure on the AL West-leading Texas Rangers. Tom Hicks owns both
teams and Jim Lites is president over both. But the Stanley Cup
also reinforces the Rangers' belief that Hicks will do what it
takes to get them over the top, having signed big-name free agents
Ed Belfour and Brett Hull to reinforce the Stars lineup. ``There's
a feeling that if it comes down to making moves at the right time,
Mr. Hicks will do it,'' Rusty Greer said. ``But I don't think
there's any more pressure that could be added by any outside person
than what the 25 guys in this clubhouse put on themselves.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
