<HEADLINE>
STOTTLEMYRE PLAYS CATCH-UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona right-hander Todd Stottlemyre played catch Tuesday, his
first time throwing a ball in five weeks since discovering he had
tears in his right rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks are reluctant to set a return date, but are
hopeful he can be back in a month. Despite leading the West,
Arizona will need Stottlemyre, who was 4-1 with a 3.59 ERA before
going on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was rewarded with a huge contract last winter and there's
nothing more disappointing than being on the shelf,'' said
Stottlemyre, who signed a four-year, $32 million contract. ``That's
part of what's eaten at me the last five weeks. It's a big part of
what motivated me to get back. I feel a great need to have to do my
part.'' &QL; 
LOOKING FOR HELP
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are pushing the Braves in the East and Atlanta is
expected to go after another hitter before the July 31 trading
deadline, probably an outfielder/leadoff hitter such as Milwaukee's
Marquis Grissom.
</P>
<P>
   Grissom, who played in Atlanta from 1995-96, the last two times
the Braves were in the World Series, would be a comfortable fit,
though he would have to shift from center to left. The Brewers want
to dump his $5 million salary and the Braves desperately need a
leadoff hitter so Walt Weiss can move back to No.8. &QL; 
RICH MAN, POOR MAN
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee Brewers have two big-time pitchers playing for a
pittance, but only one is earning his money. Hideo Nomo, 5-1 with a
3.68 ERA in his first nine starts, is making $250,000. Former Angel
Jim Abbott, trying to make the transition from hard thrower to
soft-tossing finesse pitcher, is making $400,000 and is 1-6 with a
6.82 ERA after 14 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been difficult,'' Abbott said. ``There's a mind-set you
have to change, especially when there comes a certain point in the
game when you want to rear back and throw the ball as hard as you
can. When you can't do that, you have to be smarter and pitch with
less emotion, maybe take your foot off the accelerator a little
bit.'' &QL; 
BAD TASTE
</P>
<P>
   If you think giving up chewing tobacco is easier than
cigarettes, think again. Phillies right-hander Curt Schilling, who
said he had quit for life last March 18 when a lesion was
discovered on his lower lip, is dipping again.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, who won his 10th game Thursday, was told at that time
by doctors that if he did not quit using smokeless tobacco he was a
prime candidate for mouth cancer. Doctors also said the lesion is
gone and a total reversal of the condition could occur if he quit
for good. &QL; 
NEXT TO GO
</P>
<P>
   Florida officials confirmed this past week that 1997 World
Series MVP Livan Hernandez could be made available in a trade and
that teams have called to express interest. Hernandez, 3-7 with a
4.66 ERA after losing Thursday to the Mets, doesn't want to go.
</P>
<P>
   He is making $800,000 this season, the last of a four-year
contract. Since Hernandez won't have enough service time to be
eligible for arbitration, he can be signed for about the same
amount next year _ so teams would get a bargain on a 24-year-old
pitcher who could produce at least 200 innings a year. &QL; 
TIME FOR BEN
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres put an end to catcher Ben Davis' 23-game
hitting streak Wednesday. And in the process, they made his
big-league dream come true. Davis, 22, was promoted from Triple-A
Las Vegas on Tuesday when Jim Leyritz went on the DL after getting
hit Tuesday night at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The second overall pick in the 1995 draft behind the Angels'
Darin Erstad, Davis made his major-league debut last year during a
September call-up but had just one at-bat. He went 0 for 4 against
the Dodgers on Thursday but already is considered a superb handler
of pitchers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
