<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
11 PLAYERS ARE WITHIN 3 STROKES OF THE LEAD  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ It was hot on the golf course. It was crowded
on the leader board. And when the third round of the Buick Classic
concluded Saturday, the outcome of the final round was difficult to
predict.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven players ended the day within three shots of the lead,
setting up a final round at Westchester Country Club that could
rank among the tournament's historical best. Some of the contenders
have never won on the PGA Tour, like Jim Carter, who shared the
lead with Duffy Waldorf. Others have won majors, like Lee Janzen
and Justin Leonard, who were tied for third place, two strokes off
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, a lot of players will arrive at the
first tee Sunday feeling nervous and excited.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a five-under-par 66, and keeping himself in position to
win his first tour event, Carter was at eight under par for the
tournament (205), tied with Waldorf, who shot a 68.
</P>
<P>
   Five players were tied for third place at six under par.
</P>
<P>
   --Janzen, a two-time United States Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   --Leonard, who won the 1997 British Open.
</P>
<P>
   --Steve Flesch, last year's tour rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   --Chris Perry, who started Saturday tied for first.
</P>
<P>
   --David Sutherland, another player looking for his first victory
on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be surprising to see Janzen and Leonard rise to the
top, as they are two players who have been in this position many
times and won. But it would also be dangerous to overlook the
determination of Carter, a 38-year-old tour veteran who feels he is
long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to learn how to handle it,'' Carter said, speaking
of entering the final round with the lead. ``The more you can get
there, the more comfortable you get. It's nice to be the
third-round leader, but that is not what we are shooting for.
Obviously, it's going to be a great thrill when I break through. I
think it's going to happen sooner or later.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heat, Corey Pavin (tied for 17th) shot a 65, five
players shot 66, and there were birdies to be had if you could
drive the ball in the fairway. Waldorf shot a 68, and he made
birdies on four of his last six holes. Waldorf's last tour victory
came in 1995, so while he has not waited as long as Carter, he is
also eager to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would mean that I still have game enough to compete out
here,'' said Waldorf, who is 36. ``That's kind of the doubt you
have as you get a little bit up there in years and you see young
guys coming on and hitting it longer than you, making more putts
and chipping great. You wonder if you are ever going to get that
game back where you know you can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, who shot a 66 Saturday, does not have those worries,
but he is still looking for his first victory this year, and he is
also looking for Ryder Cup points. Currently 15th in the Ryder Cup
standings, Leonard needs a good summer to insure that he will be on
the United States team that will face Europe in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am on the wrong side of that bubble,'' Leonard said of his
Ryder Cup position. ``That is my motivation. That is a big reason
why I am here this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been a little frustrating for me, because I have
had so many 12th- through 25th-place finishes. But what I take away
is that my game is not very far off. A shot or two here or there is
nothing to drive myself crazy about.''
</P>
<P>
   Janzen, who shot a 69, was relieved to have last weekend behind
him, when he finished tied for 46th at the U.S. Open and failed to
defend his championship. Like Leonard, Janzen is making a summer
push for the Ryder Cup team, and he is 21st in the points standing.
Janzen won the Buick Classic in 1994, and this would be an
opportune time to win it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``A win would put me in great position, move me up the points
list quite a bit,'' Janzen said. ``It can be stressful. I remember
in 1995, I was pressing very hard to make the team, and I got too
disappointed each time I didn't finish in the top 10 of a
tournament. If I don't worry too much, I seem to play better. It
has taken me 10 years to realize that, and it may take me another
10 to accomplish it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still a lot of possibilities for this tournament.
Somebody out of the pack playing early could shoot a good score. I
would expect, though, that somebody on the leader board now will
win the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Maggert, who started the day tied for first place, stumbled
to a 77, including a 42 on the back nine, and finished the day tied
for 38th place.
</P>
</TEXT>
