<HEADLINE>
THREE RING FRACTURES SKULL IN PADDOCK AND IS DESTROYED  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ In a shattering accident in the paddock at
Belmont Park Saturday, Three Ring, one of the country's most
accomplished fillies, was euthanized after she reared while being
saddled, flipped and fractured her skull.
</P>
<P>
   The accident happened in front of about 100 owners, trainers and
jockeys and hundreds of racing fans watching from the steps of the
amphitheater that surrounds the saddling ring behind the clubhouse.
Three Ring, a 3-year-old who ran in the Kentucky Derby last month,
was being equipped with blinkers when she reared and pitched over
backward, striking her head against the wooden pole on the wall
separating her from the filly in the next stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hit her head on the ground initially,'' said Dr. Anthony
Verderosa, the attending veterinarian, ``and while struggling to
get up, hit her head on the pole. The impact fractured her skull.
It was not something that she could survive.''
</P>
<P>
   An oilskin shield was quickly raised to block the scene from
view, and Verderosa gave the filly an injection to end her agony.
But the gruesome scene stunned the onlookers, as well as the rest
of the 8,846 spectators at Belmont, who then watched the 3-5
favorite Dreams Gallore win the Mother Goose Stakes by 7{ lengths.
</P>
<P>
   The accident happened just three weeks after a record Belmont
throng of 85,818 saw Charismatic, winner of the Kentucky Derby and
the Preakness, break down at the finish line of the Belmont Stakes
with a fractured foreleg. Three Ring, after running last in the
Derby with a slipped saddle, won the Acorn Stakes last month and
was aiming for the Mother Goose, the middle race in New York's
Triple Tiara for fillies.
</P>
<P>
   She was bought in Ocala, Fla., for $70,000 last year by Barry K.
Schwartz, the chief executive officer for Calvin Klein and a
trustee of the New York Racing Association. She won three of her
five starts last year at 2 and ran third behind the top fillies
Silverbulletday and Excellent Meeting in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile
Fillies.
</P>
<P>
   She came back strongly this year, ran second in the Forward Gal
at Gulfstream Park in January and then dominated the Davona Dale
and the Bonnie Miss by a combined total of 20 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Three Ring's trainer, Eddie Plesa Jr., was supervising the
saddling of Three Ring 15 minutes before the Mother Goose when the
filly suddenly reared. She fell back down, struck her head on the
ground, thrashed and tried to get up again but hit her head against
the pole. As she lay bleeding on the ground, Verderosa determined
that she was beyond help.
</P>
<P>
   A stunned Plesa shook his head and said, ``No, no.'' Schwartz
was too distraught to comment, and later left the trustees' room in
tears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-99 2211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
