<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RUN OF LUCK HELPS GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for a season-best fourth consecutive victory this
afternoon against the Tampa Bay Mutiny at Raymond James Stadium,
Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid has slept well this week.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid was still living off the excitement of last week's 2-1
victory over D.C. United, a win that came in the waning seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there was a little controversy around the last
goal, I'm just happy that we won it,'' admitted Schmid. ``A win
like that certainly helps our team from a confidence standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thought that came to Schmid after United's Brian
Kamler notched the game 1-1 in the 83rd minute was, ``not again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbus did that same thing to us a few weeks ago,'' said
Schmid. ``We're up 1-0 late, they tie the game and win it in a
shootout. You just start wondering when the luck is going to even
out.''
</P>
<P>
   With six seconds left, it did. Galaxy defender Greg Vanney was
hacked from behind just a few yards outside the penalty area,
setting up a Mauricio Cienfuegos free kick. It looked as though
time would run out, but the referee stopped the clock because
United defenders were standing over the ball.
</P>
<P>
   On the re-start, Cienfuegos bent a right-footed shot over the
wall into the left netting for a 2-1 victory. That gave the Galaxy
back-to-back victories over last year's MLS finalists, Chicago and
D.C., stretching its winning streak to three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, in the time that I have been with this team we have
been on the other end of this type of game before,'' Schmid said.
``I thought they probably had more of the game than we did, but we
scored that goal in the first half and got one late. Sometimes you
just don't ask why, you just walk away and say thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy (8-6, 18 points, fourth place) has piled up nine
consecutive points to pull within five of Western Conference-leader
Colorado (9-3, 22 points), and Schmid hopes to add more before the
July 17 All-Star Game in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting closer to where we want to be,'' Schmid said.
``We just have to continue to win and get the maximum points out of
these next three games. Nine points would be brilliant, but seven
would be good, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid feels it's only a matter of time before this team reaches
its potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team we're defending well,'' Schmid said, ``but we need
to get a little tighter on defense in the middle part of the field
to create more turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also looking for a better understanding between Roy
(Myers), Carlos (Hermosillo) and Cobi (Jones), but when you think
of it, last week's game was the first time all three of them played
together. With each game, that understanding is going to get
better, and with it, so will this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Today the Galaxy faces a Tampa team (6-7, 12 points) that has
lost two straight and three of its last four. The Mutiny beat the
Galaxy for the first time at the Rose Bowl on May 15, coming away
with a 1-0 shootout victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
