</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, June 27. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
DROUGHT _ The five rain gauges on the Parsons ranch in central
Arizona are measuring dust, not water. They haven't collected more
than a trace of moisture on the rangeland near since mid-July last
year. More than 1,400 wildfires have broken out across the state so
far this year and the number of cattle on the Arizona range is down
by more than 20 percent compared with 1992. By KATHLEEN INGLEY.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LAS VEGAS _ To anyone outside Nevada, the idea that Oscar Goodman,
a millionaire lawyer who works for reputed mobsters could be
elected mayor of Las Vegas might not seem so strange. But to
image-conscious business and tourism leaders who want desperately
to reinvent this desert gambling town as a sophisticated
international resort destination, his election is a source of
potentially disastrous publicity. What power brokers failed to
count on was how Goodman reinvented himself. By SHAUN MCKINNON.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
