<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-26 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0918 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DROUGHT-AZR &LR;      06-26 1908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANCHERS DUMP LIVESTOCK AS ARIZONA HOPES FOR RAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The five rain gauges on the Parsons ranch are measuring dust,
not water. They haven't collected more than a trace of moisture on
the rangeland near Picacho Peak since mid-July last year.
</P>
<P>
   The family has lived in Arizona since 1968, Joe Parsons said,
``and it's the first time we haven't had winter rains.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials don't want to alarm anyone, but it's hard to avoid the
``D'' word.
</P>
<P>
   Drought.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter was one of the driest on record for Arizona, the
third worst since 1895. Reservoir levels are as low as they've been
in two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley's rainfall is only half of normal this year.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,400 wildfires have broken out across the state so
far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The number of cattle on the Arizona range is down by more than
20 percent compared with 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull declared a drought emergency last week so
ranchers can qualify for tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   And the worst may be yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a cool spell in early June, this summer is expected to
be hotter and drier than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as bad as I've seen in my lifetime, and I've lived in
Arizona since 1940,'' said Joe Lane, associate director of the
state Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Arizona is in severe drought, according to the most
common measure, the Palmer Drought Severity Index. The only
exceptions are the northeast, with moderate drought, and the
southwest, where conditions are about normal.
</P>
<P>
   Rain patterns in Arizona are fickle. No one knows whether the
state could be gripped by a drought as severe as the one in Mexico,
which has lasted five years in some places.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, this is the desert. Extremes of heat and dryness are
no surprise in much of the state.
</P>
<P>
   So far, said Michael Austin, director of the state Division of
Emergency Management, ``the drought we're experiencing now is
fairly typical and occurs fairly frequently in Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hardship, but it's not as bad as it could be,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Supplies of drinking water aren't likely to run low, except in a
few rural communities that have perpetual water problems.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest worries right now are cattle and fires.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers are selling off part of their herds because range
conditions are so bad. The state is lining up extra firefighting
muscle to keep forest blazes from getting out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Blame La Nina, a weather pattern caused by unusually cool water
off western South America.
</P>
<P>
   It brings dry winters to the Southwest; just the opposite of the
drenching winter rains caused by the better-known El Nino, a
warming of the eastern Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   What no one knows is whether the dry weather will continue,
delaying or reducing the summer monsoon season. In fact, there are
plenty of unknowns about Arizona's late summer period of violent
thunderstorms and high humidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really understand what makes the monsoon work, why
it's different from one year to the next,'' said Randy Cerveny, a
climatology professor at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   But judging from conditions on the Mexican coast, where the
storms build up before moving into Arizona, the Valley monsoon will
be delayed until at least mid-July, two weeks later than the usual
start. &QL; 
Range-land blues
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers are feeling the dry weather more than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Cracked shingles of dry mud stretch across the empty pond on the
Parsons ranch, next to Picacho Peak between Phoenix and Tucson. The
pond, known as a stock tank in the cattle business, is fed by
runoff from the rugged nearby peaks; and in a normal year, it would
be 8 to 10 feet deep in water.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Parsons pointed to the mesquite trees that ring the stock
tank. They should be heavy with mesquite beans, full of moisture
and protein for cattle, but bean pods are scarce.
</P>
<P>
   The family is running 200 head of cattle, a third less than
usual. To feed the herd, the family had to plant its irrigated
fields in forage instead of a cash crop like cotton.
</P>
<P>
   The dry weather is boosting volume at the family's auction
business in nearby Marana, which is handling 20-25 percent more
animals than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of cattle are selling that really shouldn't be,'' Parsons
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ranchers are sending calves to auction now, at half the weight
the animals would have in another four months. They're forced to
cut into their producing herd, cows that give birth to the calves
they sell.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout would be even worse, but many ranchers haven't
rebuilt their herds since a drought in 1996. The number of beef
cows in Arizona dropped from 279,000 in 1992 to 218,000 last
January.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions are poor or very poor on a third of the state's range
and pasture land.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us recognize that if it doesn't rain in July and
August, we are in real trouble,'' said Lane, of the Agriculture
Department.
</P>
<P>
   However, the lack of rain has had relatively little effect on
Arizona's field crops and fruit, which are fed by irrigation.
</P>
<P>
   Yuma, with some of the state's most productive farmland,
averages less than 3 inches of rain a year, while its citrus trees
drink 90 inches. Cotton requires 65 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Rain is actually bad news in Yuma because it generally damages
some crops, said Ken Evans, president of the Arizona Farm Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's been worried this month to see the humidity plummet
below 3 percent at times, the lowest level he can measure on his
farm outside Yuma.
</P>
<P>
   ``That feels good for people,'' he said, ``but it's horrible for
plants.''
</P>
<P>
   So he's had to irrigate more than usual, raising his costs. &QL; 
Danger in the woods
</P>
<P>
   Ray Larsen looked out the window at the fire station by
Christopher Creek and saw a scene that should come in September,
not June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yellow and brown leaves on the trees,'' he lamented. ``There's
even a little bit of reddish tint on them because they're so dry.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaves and pine needles on the forest floor here, about 90
minutes northeast of Phoenix, hold so little moisture that ``when
you walk in the woods right now, it's like walking on Rice
Krispies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As fire chief for the Christopher-Kohl's Fire District, Larsen
is worried about getting enough water to battle a big blaze.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the ponds, where firefighters install temporary pumps
or dip water with helicopters, are dried up this year.
</P>
<P>
   An ``April Fool's'' snowfall and unexpected rain in early June
dampened the threat of wildfires for a while this year, but the
break was brief. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   The fire danger in Arizona's forests is now high to extreme in
most of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Wildfires have already burned more than 37,000 acres this year.
The worst came in mid-June when a fire charred 4,000 acres and
destroyed 17 homes on the mountainous Fort Apache Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   When the forest is dry and the humidity is low, a passing car
can start a blaze with sparks from a dragging chain or a faulty
exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   Special fire-prevention teams, with rotating members from state
and federal agencies, are set up whenever a part of the country has
extreme potential for wildfires. Arizona got a team this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The state Land Department, which handles wild-land fires on 22
million acres of private and state land, has tapped a special
account to move key people and equipment closer to the expected hot
spots.
</P>
<P>
   It pays to line up planes ahead of time. When Texas and Florida
suffered severe fires last year, aircraft was tied up across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It left this state in the lurch,'' said Michael Anable, head
of the Land Department. ``Luckily we didn't have a bad fire
year.'' &QL; 
Why cities have water
</P>
<P>
   Although forests and range lands are parched, Arizona's major
cities aren't likely to go thirsty this year.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean there aren't some water problems. The Valley
has received an inch and a half of rain this year, barely
half-normal.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, the mountains have had little snow, which melts and
fills a series of reservoirs. Last winter was the eighth-driest for
water runoff in a century of records.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt River Project's reservoir system, which supplies much
of the Valley's water, is 30 percent below normal for this time of
year.
</P>
<P>
   But don't worry about getting air instead of water out of your
faucets, said Dallas Reigle, senior hydrologist at the SRP.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to heavy snow in the Rockies, there's extra water in the
Colorado River system this year. Good news, because part of the
Valley's water comes from the Colorado River by way of the Central
Arizona Project Canal.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that's the beauty of the water supply for the Phoenix
area. The way the storm patterns shift, if the Rockies aren't
getting much snow, then the mountains of Arizona are blanketed, and
vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk for a drought in Arizona and on the Colorado at the
same time is minute,'' said Darrell Jordan, assistant director of
the state Department of Water Resources.
</P>
<P>
   To make up for the scant supply in reservoirs, the SRP is buying
an additional 75,000 acre-feet of Colorado River water, the
equivalent of Saguaro Lake.
</P>
<P>
   It also plans to pump 300,000 acre-feet from wells, supplying
about a third of the total for the year, although state law
discourages using groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   But although the SRP doesn't expect to run short, Reigle still
has a message: ``I don't think we do enough in this state to
conserve water; it is a desert, and we need to be more mindful.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucson has traditionally paid more attention to conservation
than the Valley has. And with good reason. That city relies almost
entirely on wells, drawing on an ever-sinking water table. Tucson
voters passed an initiative that virtually prohibits use of
Colorado River water, which had caused problems in older plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   With the prospect that above-normal temperatures will boost
water use, Tucson has twin worries: that demand will outstrip the
capacity of its pumps and that city reservoirs will get too low for
adequate pressure and firefighting needs.
</P>
<P>
   So, Tucson is stepping up an audit program that sends out
specialists to hunt down leaks and give conservation tips to
homewners. This year, businesses and all city offices are included
in the program, with a special educational program for city
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, Hull has called together a drought task force to keep
tabs on the dry weather and come up with options for dealing with
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have different assessments of how bad it is and how bad
it's going to be,'' said Francie Noyes, Hull's spokeswoman. ``Our
approach is: Let's do the planning; let's be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   In the dry summer of 1996, the state paid to truck water to
communities that were running short.
</P>
<P>
   There's a predictable list of places that hit shortages of
drinking water even in a good year.
</P>
<P>
   They include Strawberry and Pine, where the water table is
relatively shallow. But so far, the wells in those places haven't
run dry.
</P>
<P>
   At the federal level, Arizona's congressional delegation helped
save San Carlos Lake, which was in danger of being sucked dry to
meet commitments to deliver water. An appropriation of $1.5 million
is buying Colorado River water for those obligations.
</P>
<P>
   The lake will shrink, with some fish kill likely.
</P>
<P>
   What the lake and the state need most, though, is the drought
relief that comes from Mother Nature.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
